B040C001V001	40	1	1	The Genealogy of Jesus Christ, the son of David, the son of Abraham.
B040C001V002	40	1	2	Abraham was the father of Isaac; Isaac of Jacob; Jacob of Judah and his brothers.
B040C001V003	40	1	3	Judah was the father (by Tamar) of Perez and Zerah; Perez of Hezron; Hezron of Ram;
B040C001V004	40	1	4	Ram of Amminadab; Amminadab of Nahshon; Nahshon of Salmon;
B040C001V005	40	1	5	Salmon (by Rahab) of Boaz; Boaz (by Ruth) of Obed; Obed of Jesse;
B040C001V006	40	1	6	Jesse of David–the King. David (by Uriah's widow) was the father of Solomon;
B040C001V007	40	1	7	Solomon of Rehoboam; Rehoboam of Abijah; Abijah of Asa;
B040C001V008	40	1	8	Asa of Jehoshaphat; Jehoshaphat of Jehoram; Jehoram of Uzziah;
B040C001V009	40	1	9	Uzziah of Jotham; Jotham of Ahaz; Ahaz of Hezekiah;
B040C001V010	40	1	10	Hezekiah of Manasseh; Manasseh of Amon; Amon of Josiah;
B040C001V011	40	1	11	Josiah of Jeconiah and his brothers at the period of the Removal to Babylon.
B040C001V012	40	1	12	After the Removal to Babylon Jeconiah had a son Shealtiel; Shealtiel was the father of Zerubbabel;
B040C001V013	40	1	13	Zerubbabel of Abiud; Abiud of Eliakim; Eliakim of Azor;
B040C001V014	40	1	14	Azor of Zadok; Zadok of Achim; Achim of Eliud;
B040C001V015	40	1	15	Eliud of Eleazar; Eleazar of Matthan; Matthan of Jacob;
B040C001V016	40	1	16	and Jacob of Joseph the husband of Mary, who was the mother of JESUS who is called CHRIST.
B040C001V017	40	1	17	There are therefore, in all, fourteen generations from Abraham to David; fourteen from David to the Removal to Babylon; and fourteen from the Removal to Babylon to the Christ.
B040C001V018	40	1	18	The circumstances of the birth of Jesus Christ were these. After his mother Mary was betrothed to Joseph, before they were united in marriage, she was found to be with child through the Holy Spirit.
B040C001V019	40	1	19	But Joseph her husband, being a kind-hearted man and unwilling publicly to disgrace her, had determined to release her privately from the betrothal.
B040C001V020	40	1	20	But while he was contemplating this step, an angel of the Lord appeared to him in a dream and said, »Joseph, son of David, do not be afraid to bring home your wife Mary, for she is with child through the Holy Spirit.
B040C001V021	40	1	21	She will give birth to a Son, and you are to call His name JESUS for He it is who will save His People from their sins.«
B040C001V022	40	1	22	All this took place in fulfilment of what the Lord had spoken through the Prophet,
B040C001V023	40	1	23	
        
B040C001V024	40	1	24	When Joseph awoke, he did as the angel of the Lord had commanded, and brought home his wife,
B040C001V025	40	1	25	but did not live with her until she had given birth to a son. The child's name he called JESUS.
B040C002V001	40	2	1	Now after the birth of Jesus, which took place at Bethlehem in Judaea in the reign of King Herod, excitement was produced in Jerusalem by the arrival of certain Magi from the east,
B040C002V002	40	2	2	inquiring, »Where is the newly born king of the Jews? For we have seen his Star in the east, and have come here to do him homage.«
B040C002V003	40	2	3	Reports of this soon reached the king, and greatly agitated not only him but all the people of Jerusalem.
B040C002V004	40	2	4	So he assembled all the High Priests and Scribes of the people, and anxiously asked them where the Christ was to be born.
B040C002V005	40	2	5	»At Bethlehem in Judaea,« they replied; »for so it stands written in the words of the Prophet,
B040C002V006	40	2	6	
        
B040C002V007	40	2	7	Thereupon Herod sent privately for the Magi and ascertained from them the exact time of the star's appearing.
B040C002V008	40	2	8	He then directed them to go to Bethlehem, adding, »Go and make careful inquiry about the child, and when you have found him, bring me word, that I too may come and do him homage.«
B040C002V009	40	2	9	After hearing what the king said, they went to Bethlehem, while, strange to say, the star they had seen in the east led them on until it came and stood over the place where the babe was.
B040C002V010	40	2	10	When they saw the star, the sight filled them with intense joy.
B040C002V011	40	2	11	So they entered the house; and when they saw the babe with His mother Mary, they prostrated themselves and did Him homage, and opening their treasure-chests offered gifts to Him–gold, frankincense, and myrrh.
B040C002V012	40	2	12	But being forbidden by God in a dream to return to Herod, they went back to their own country by a different route.
B040C002V013	40	2	13	When they were gone, and angel of the Lord appeared to Joseph in a dream and said, »Rise: take the babe and His mother and escape to Egypt, and remain there till I bring you word. For Herod is about to make search for the child in order to destroy Him.«
B040C002V014	40	2	14	So Joseph roused himself and took the babe and His mother by night and departed into Egypt.
B040C002V015	40	2	15	There he remained till Herod's death, that what the Lord had said through the Prophet might be fulfilled, 
B040C002V016	40	2	16	Then Herod, finding that the Magi had trifled with him, was furious, and sent and massacred all the boys under two years of age, in Bethlehem and all its neighbourhood, according to the date he had so carefully ascertained from the Magi.
B040C002V017	40	2	17	Then were these words, spoken by the Prophet Jeremiah, fulfilled,
B040C002V018	40	2	18	
        
B040C002V019	40	2	19	But after Herod's death an angel of the Lord appeared in a dream to Joseph in Egypt, and said to him,
B040C002V020	40	2	20	»Rise from sleep, and take the child and His mother, and go into the land of Israel, for those who were seeking the child's life are dead.«
B040C002V021	40	2	21	So he roused himself and took the child and His mother and came into the land of Israel.
B040C002V022	40	2	22	But hearing that Archelaus had succeeded his father Herod on the throne of Judaea, he was afraid to go there; and being instructed by God in a dream he withdrew into Galilee,
B040C002V023	40	2	23	and went and settled in a town called Nazareth, in order that these words spoken through the Prophets might be fulfilled, 
B040C003V001	40	3	1	About this time John the Baptist made his appearance, preaching in the Desert of Judaea.
B040C003V002	40	3	2	»Repent,« he said, »for the Kingdom of the Heavens is now close at hand.«
B040C003V003	40	3	3	He it is who was spoken of through the Prophet Isaiah when he said, 
B040C003V004	40	3	4	This man John wore a garment of camel's hair, and a loincloth of leather; and he lived upon locusts and wild honey.
B040C003V005	40	3	5	Then large numbers of people went out to him –people from Jerusalem and from all Judaea, and from the whole of the Jordan valley–
B040C003V006	40	3	6	and were baptized by him in the Jordan, making full confession of their sins.
B040C003V007	40	3	7	But when he saw many of the Pharisees and Sadducees coming for baptism, he exclaimed, `O vipers' brood, who has warned you to flee from the coming wrath?
B040C003V008	40	3	8	Therefore let your lives prove your change of heart;
B040C003V009	40	3	9	and do not imagine that you can say to yourselves, `We have Abraham as our forefather,' for I tell you that God can raise up descendants for Abraham from these stones.
B040C003V010	40	3	10	And already the axe is lying at the root of the trees, so that every tree which does not produce good fruit will quickly be hewn down and thrown into the fire.
B040C003V011	40	3	11	I indeed am baptizing you in water on a profession of repentance; but He who is coming after me is mightier than I: His sandals I am not worthy to carry for a moment; He will baptize you in the Holy Spirit and in fire.
B040C003V012	40	3	12	His winnowing-shovel is in His hand, and He will make a thorough clearance of His threshing-floor, gathering His wheat into the storehouse, but burning up the chaff in unquenchable fire.«
B040C003V013	40	3	13	Just at that time Jesus, coming from Galilee to the Jordan, presents Himself to John to be baptized by him.
B040C003V014	40	3	14	John protested. »It is I,« he said, »who have need to be baptized by you, and do you come to me?«
B040C003V015	40	3	15	»Let it be so on this occasion,« Jesus replied; »for so we ought to fulfil every religious duty.« Then he consented;
B040C003V016	40	3	16	and Jesus was baptized, and immediately went up from the water. At that moment the heavens opened, and he saw the Spirit of God descending like a dove and alighting upon Him,
B040C003V017	40	3	17	while a voice came from Heaven, saying, »This is My Son, the dearly loved, in whom is My delight.«
B040C004V001	40	4	1	At that time Jesus was led up by the Spirit into the Desert in order to be tempted by the Devil.
B040C004V002	40	4	2	There He fasted for forty days and nights; and after that He suffered from hunger.
B040C004V003	40	4	3	So the Tempter came and said, »If you are the Son of God, command these stones to turn into loaves.«
B040C004V004	40	4	4	»It is written,« replied Jesus, 
B040C004V005	40	4	5	Then the Devil took Him to the Holy City and caused Him to stand on the roof of the Temple,
B040C004V006	40	4	6	and said, »If you are God's Son, throw yourself down; for it is written, 
B040C004V007	40	4	7	»Again it is written,« replied Jesus, 
B040C004V008	40	4	8	Then the Devil took Him to the top of an exceedingly lofty mountain, from which he caused Him to see all the Kingdoms of the world and their splendour,
B040C004V009	40	4	9	and said to Him, »All this I will give you, if you will kneel down and do me homage.«
B040C004V010	40	4	10	»Begone, Satan!« Jesus replied; »for it is written, 
B040C004V011	40	4	11	Thereupon the Devil left Him, and angels at once came and ministered to Him.
B040C004V012	40	4	12	Now when Jesus heard that John was thrown into prison, He withdrew into Galilee,
B040C004V013	40	4	13	and leaving Nazareth He went and settled at Capernaum, a town by the Lake on the frontiers of Zebulun and Naphtali,
B040C004V014	40	4	14	in order that these words, spoken through the Prophet Isaiah, might be fulfilled,
B040C004V015	40	4	15	
        
B040C004V016	40	4	16	
        
B040C004V017	40	4	17	From that time Jesus began to preach. »Repent,« He said, »for the Kingdom of the Heavens is now close at hand.«
B040C004V018	40	4	18	And walking along the shore of the Lake of Galilee He saw two brothers –Simon called Peter and his brother Andrew– throwing a drag-net into the Lake; for they were fishers.
B040C004V019	40	4	19	And He said to them, »Come and follow me, and I will make you fishers of men.«
B040C004V020	40	4	20	So they immediately left their nets and followed Him. As He went further on,
B040C004V021	40	4	21	He saw two other brothers, James the son of Zabdi and his brother John, in the boat with their father Zabdi mending their nets; and He called them.
B040C004V022	40	4	22	And they at once left the boat and their father, and followed Him.
B040C004V023	40	4	23	Then Jesus travelled through all Galilee, teaching in their synagogues and proclaiming the Good News of the Kingdom, and curing every kind of disease and infirmity among the people.
B040C004V024	40	4	24	Thus His fame spread through all Syria; and they brought all the sick to Him, the people who were suffering from various diseases and pains–demoniacs, epileptics, paralytics; and He cured them.
B040C004V025	40	4	25	And great crowds followed Him, coming from Galilee, from the Ten Towns, from Jerusalem, and from beyond the district on the other side of the Jordan.
B040C005V001	40	5	1	Seeing the multitude of people, Jesus went up the Hill. There He seated Himself, and when His disciples came to Him,
B040C005V002	40	5	2	He proceeded to teach them, and said:
B040C005V003	40	5	3	»Blessed are the poor in spirit, for to them belongs the Kingdom of the Heavens.«
B040C005V004	40	5	4	»Blessed are the mourners, for they shall be comforted.«
B040C005V005	40	5	5	»Blessed are the meek, for they as heirs shall obtain possession of the earth.«
B040C005V006	40	5	6	»Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they shall be completely satisfied.«
B040C005V007	40	5	7	»Blessed are the compassionate, for they shall receive compassion.«
B040C005V008	40	5	8	»Blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God.«
B040C005V009	40	5	9	»Blessed are the peacemakers, for it is they who will be recognized as sons of God.«
B040C005V010	40	5	10	»Blessed are those who have borne persecution in the cause of Righteousness, for to them belongs the Kingdom of the Heavens.«
B040C005V011	40	5	11	»Blessed are you when they have insulted and persecuted you, and have said every cruel thing about you falsely for my sake.
B040C005V012	40	5	12	Be joyful and triumphant, because your reward is great in the Heavens; for so were the Prophets before you persecuted.«
B040C005V013	40	5	13	
        
B040C005V014	40	5	14	
        
B040C005V015	40	5	15	Nor is a lamp lighted to be put under a bushel, but on the lampstand; and then it gives light to all in the house.
B040C005V016	40	5	16	Just so let your light shine before all men, in order that they may see your holy lives and may give glory to your Father who is in Heaven.
B040C005V017	40	5	17	»Do not for a moment suppose that I have come to abrogate the Law or the Prophets: I have not come to abrogate them but to give them their completion.«
B040C005V018	40	5	18	Solemnly I tell you that until Heaven and earth pass away, not one iota or smallest detail will pass away from the Law until all has taken place.
B040C005V019	40	5	19	Whoever therefore breaks one of these least commandments and teaches others to break them, will be called the least in the Kingdom of the Heavens; but whoever practises them and teaches them, he will be acknowledged as great in the Kingdom of the Heavens.
B040C005V020	40	5	20	For I assure you that unless your righteousness greatly surpasses that of the Scribes and the Pharisees, you will certainly not find entrance into the Kingdom of the Heavens.
B040C005V021	40	5	21	»You have heard that it was said to the ancients, 
B040C005V022	40	5	22	But I say to you that every one who becomes angry with his brother shall be answerable to the magistrate; that whoever says to his brother `Raca,' shall be answerable to the Sanhedrin; and that whoever says, `You fool!' shall be liable to the Gehenna of Fire.
B040C005V023	40	5	23	If therefore when you are offering your gift upon the altar, you remember that your brother has a grievance against you,
B040C005V024	40	5	24	leave your gift there before the altar, and go and make friends with your brother first, and then return and proceed to offer your gift.
B040C005V025	40	5	25	Come to terms without delay with your opponent while you are yet with him on the way to the court; for fear he should obtain judgement from the magistrate against you, and the magistrate should give you in custody to the officer and you be thrown into prison.
B040C005V026	40	5	26	I solemnly tell you that you will certainly not be released till you have paid the very last farthing.
B040C005V027	40	5	27	»You have heard that it was said, 
B040C005V028	40	5	28	But I tell you that whoever looks at a woman and cherishes lustful thoughts has already in his heart become guilty with regard to her.
B040C005V029	40	5	29	If therefore your eye, even the right eye, is a snare to you, tear it out and away with it; it is better for you that one member should be destroyed rather than that your whole body should be thrown into Gehenna.
B040C005V030	40	5	30	And if your right hand is a snare to you, cut it off and away with it; it is better for you that one member should be destroyed rather than that your whole body should go into Gehenna.
B040C005V031	40	5	31	»It was also said, 
B040C005V032	40	5	32	But I tell you that every man who puts away his wife except on the ground of unfaithfulness causes her to commit adultery, and whoever marries her when so divorced commits adultery.
B040C005V033	40	5	33	»Again, you have heard that it was said to the ancients, 
B040C005V034	40	5	34	But I tell you not to swear at all; neither by Heaven, for it is God's throne;
B040C005V035	40	5	35	nor by the earth, for it is the footstool under His feet; nor by Jerusalem, for it is the City of the Great King.
B040C005V036	40	5	36	And do not swear by your head, for you cannot make one hair white or black.
B040C005V037	40	5	37	But let your language be, `Yes, yes,' or `No, no.' Anything in excess of this comes from the Evil one.
B040C005V038	40	5	38	»You have heard that it was said, 
B040C005V039	40	5	39	But I tell you not to resist a wicked man, but if any one strikes you on the right cheek, turn the other to him as well.
B040C005V040	40	5	40	If any one wishes to go to law with you and to deprive you of your under garment, let him take your outer one also.
B040C005V041	40	5	41	And whoever shall compel you to convey his goods one mile, go with him two.
B040C005V042	40	5	42	To him who asks, give: from him who would borrow, turn not away.
B040C005V043	40	5	43	»You have heard that it was said, 
B040C005V044	40	5	44	But I command you all, love your enemies, and pray for your persecutors;
B040C005V045	40	5	45	that so you may become true sons of your Father in Heaven; for He causes His sun to rise on the wicked as well as the good, and sends rain upon those who do right and those who do wrong.
B040C005V046	40	5	46	For if you love only those who love you, what reward have you earned? Do not even the tax-gatherers do that?
B040C005V047	40	5	47	And if you salute only your near relatives, what praise is due to you? Do not even the Gentiles do the same?
B040C005V048	40	5	48	You however are to be complete in goodness, as your Heavenly Father is complete.
B040C006V001	40	6	1	»But beware of doing your good actions in the sight of men, in order to attract their gaze; if you do, there is no reward for you with your Father who is in Heaven.«
B040C006V002	40	6	2	`When you give in charity, never blow a trumpet before you as the hypocrites do in the synagogues and streets in order that their praises may be sung by men. I solemnly tell you that they already have their reward.
B040C006V003	40	6	3	But when you are giving in charity, let not your left hand perceive what your right hand is doing,
B040C006V004	40	6	4	that your charities may be in secret; and then your Father –He who sees in secret– will recompense you.
B040C006V005	40	6	5	»And when praying, you must not be like the hypocrites. They are fond of standing and praying in the synagogues or at the corners of the wider streets, in order that men may see them. I solemnly tell you that they already have their reward.«
B040C006V006	40	6	6	But you, whenever you pray, go into your own room and shut the door: then pray to your Father who is in secret, and your Father –He who sees in secret– will recompense you.
B040C006V007	40	6	7	»And when praying, do not use needless repetitions as the Gentiles do, for they expect to be listened to because of their multitude of words.«
B040C006V008	40	6	8	Do not, however, imitate them; for your Father knows what things you need before ever you ask Him.
B040C006V009	40	6	9	»In this manner therefore pray: `Our Father who art in Heaven, may Thy name be kept holy;«
B040C006V010	40	6	10	let Thy kingdom come; let Thy will be done, as in Heaven so on earth;
B040C006V011	40	6	11	give us to-day our bread for the day;
B040C006V012	40	6	12	and forgive us our shortcomings, as we also have forgiven those who have failed in their duty towards us;
B040C006V013	40	6	13	and bring us not into temptation, but rescue us from the Evil one.'
B040C006V014	40	6	14	»For if you forgive others their offences, your Heavenly Father will forgive you also;«
B040C006V015	40	6	15	but if you do not forgive others their offences, neither will your Father forgive yours.
B040C006V016	40	6	16	»When any of you fast, never assume gloomy looks as the hypocrites do; for they disfigure their faces in order that it may be evident to men that they are fasting. I solemnly tell you that they already have their reward.«
B040C006V017	40	6	17	But, whenever you fast, pour perfume on your hair and wash your face,
B040C006V018	40	6	18	that it may not be apparent to men that you are fasting, but to your Father who is in secret; and your Father –He who sees in secret– will recompense you.
B040C006V019	40	6	19	»Do not lay up stores of wealth for yourselves on earth, where the moth and wear-and-tear destroy, and where thieves break in and steal.«
B040C006V020	40	6	20	But amass wealth for yourselves in Heaven, where neither the moth nor wear-and-tear destroys, and where thieves do not break in and steal.
B040C006V021	40	6	21	For where your wealth is, there also will your heart be.
B040C006V022	40	6	22	»The eye is the lamp of the body. If then your eyesight is good, your whole body will be well lighted;«
B040C006V023	40	6	23	but if your eyesight is bad, your whole body will be dark. If however the very light within you is darkness, how dense must the darkness be!
B040C006V024	40	6	24	»No man can be the bondservant of two masters; for either he will dislike one and like the other, or he will attach himself to one and think slightingly of the other. You cannot be the bondservants both of God and of gold.«
B040C006V025	40	6	25	For this reason I charge you not to be over-anxious about your lives, inquiring what you are to eat or what you are to drink, nor yet about your bodies, inquiring what clothes you are to put on. Is not the life more precious than its food, and the body than its clothing?
B040C006V026	40	6	26	Look at the birds which fly in the air: they do not sow or reap or store up in barns, but your Heavenly Father feeds them: are not you of much greater value than they?
B040C006V027	40	6	27	Which of you by being over-anxious can add a single foot to his height?
B040C006V028	40	6	28	And why be anxious about clothing? Learn a lesson from the wild lilies. Watch their growth. They neither toil nor spin,
B040C006V029	40	6	29	and yet I tell you that not even Solomon in all his magnificence could array himself like one of these.
B040C006V030	40	6	30	And if God so clothes the wild herbage which to-day flourishes and to-morrow is thrown into the oven, is it not much more certain that He will clothe you, you men of little faith?
B040C006V031	40	6	31	Do not be over-anxious, therefore, asking `What shall we eat?' or `What shall we drink?' or `What shall we wear?'
B040C006V032	40	6	32	For all these are questions that Gentiles are always asking; but your Heavenly Father knows that you need these things–all of them.
B040C006V033	40	6	33	But make His Kingdom and righteousness your chief aim, and then these things shall all be given you in addition.
B040C006V034	40	6	34	Do not be over-anxious, therefore, about to-morrow, for to-morrow will bring its own cares. Enough for each day are its own troubles.
B040C007V001	40	7	1	»Judge not, that you may not be judged;«
B040C007V002	40	7	2	for your own judgement will be dealt –and your own measure meted– to yourselves.
B040C007V003	40	7	3	And why do you look at the splinter in your brother's eye, and not notice the beam which is in your own eye?
B040C007V004	40	7	4	Or how say to your brother, `Allow me to take the splinter out of your eye,' while the beam is in your own eye?
B040C007V005	40	7	5	Hypocrite, first take the beam out of your own eye, and then you will see clearly how to remove the splinter from your brother's eye.
B040C007V006	40	7	6	»Give not that which is holy to the dogs, nor throw your pearls to the swine; otherwise they will trample them under their feet and then turn and attack you.«
B040C007V007	40	7	7	»Ask, and it will be given to you; seek, and you will find; knock, and the door will be opened to you.«
B040C007V008	40	7	8	For it is always he who asks that receives, he who seeks that finds, and he who knocks that has the door opened to him.
B040C007V009	40	7	9	What man is there among you, who if his son shall ask him for bread will offer him a stone?
B040C007V010	40	7	10	Or if the son shall ask him for a fish will offer him a snake?
B040C007V011	40	7	11	If you then, imperfect as you are, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your Father in Heaven give good things to those who ask Him!
B040C007V012	40	7	12	Everything, therefore, be it what it may, that you would have men do to you, do you also the same to them; for in this the Law and the Prophets are summed up.
B040C007V013	40	7	13	»Enter by the narrow gate; for wide is the gate and broad the road which leads to ruin, and many there are who enter by it;«
B040C007V014	40	7	14	because narrow is the gate and contracted the road which leads to Life, and few are those who find it.
B040C007V015	40	7	15	»Beware of the false teachers–men who come to you in sheep's fleeces, but beneath that disguise they are ravenous wolves.«
B040C007V016	40	7	16	By their fruits you will easily recognize them. Are grapes gathered from thorns or figs from brambles?
B040C007V017	40	7	17	Just so every good tree produces good fruit, but a poisonous tree produces bad fruit.
B040C007V018	40	7	18	A good tree cannot bear bad fruit, nor a poisonous tree good fruit.
B040C007V019	40	7	19	Every tree which does not yield good fruit is cut down and thrown aside for burning.
B040C007V020	40	7	20	So by their fruits at any rate, you will easily recognize them.
B040C007V021	40	7	21	»Not every one who says to me, `Master, Master,' will enter the Kingdom of the Heavens, but only those who are obedient to my Father who is in Heaven.«
B040C007V022	40	7	22	Many will say to me on that day, »`Master, Master, have we not prophesied in Thy name, and in Thy name expelled demons, and in Thy name performed many mighty works?'
B040C007V023	40	7	23	And then I will tell them plainly, »`I never knew you: begone from me, you doers of wickedness.'
B040C007V024	40	7	24	»Every one who hears these my teachings and acts upon them will be found to resemble a wise man who builds his house upon rock;«
B040C007V025	40	7	25	and the heavy rain falls, the swollen torrents come, and the winds blow and beat against the house; yet it does not fall, for its foundation is on rock.
B040C007V026	40	7	26	And every one who hears these my teachings and does not act upon them will be found to resemble a fool who builds his house upon sand.
B040C007V027	40	7	27	The heavy rain descends, the swollen torrents come, and the winds blow and burst upon the house, and it falls; and disastrous is the fall.«
B040C007V028	40	7	28	When Jesus had concluded this discourse, the crowds were filled with amazement at His teaching,
B040C007V029	40	7	29	for He had been teaching them as one who had authority, and not as their Scribes taught.
B040C008V001	40	8	1	Upon descending from the hill country He was followed by immense crowds.
B040C008V002	40	8	2	And a leper came to Him, and throwing himself at His feet, said, »Sir, if only you are willing you are able to cleanse me.«
B040C008V003	40	8	3	So Jesus put out His hand and touched him, and said, »I am willing: be cleansed.« Instantly he was cleansed from his leprosy;
B040C008V004	40	8	4	and Jesus said to him, »Be careful to tell no one, but go and show yourself to the priest, and offer the gift which Moses appointed as evidence for them.«
B040C008V005	40	8	5	After His entry into Capernaum a Captain came to Him, and entreated Him.
B040C008V006	40	8	6	»Sir,« he said, »my servant at home is lying ill with paralysis, and is suffering great pain.«
B040C008V007	40	8	7	»I will come and cure him,« said Jesus.
B040C008V008	40	8	8	»Sir,« replied the Captain, »I am not a fit person to receive you under my roof: merely say the word, and my servant will be cured.
B040C008V009	40	8	9	For I myself am also under authority, and have soldiers under me. To one I say `Go,' and he goes, to another `Come,' and he comes, and to my slave `Do this or that,' and he does it.«
B040C008V010	40	8	10	Jesus listened to this reply, and was astonished, and said to the people following Him, »I solemnly tell you that in no Israelite have I found faith as great as this.
B040C008V011	40	8	11	And I tell you that many will come from the east and from the west and will recline at table with Abraham, Isaac and Jacob in the Kingdom of the Heavens,
B040C008V012	40	8	12	while the natural heirs of the Kingdom will be driven out into the darkness outside: there will be the weeping aloud and the gnashing of teeth.«
B040C008V013	40	8	13	And Jesus said to the Captain, »Go, and just as you have believed, so be it for you.« And the servant recovered precisely at that time.
B040C008V014	40	8	14	After this Jesus went to the house of Peter, whose mother-in-law he found ill in bed with fever.
B040C008V015	40	8	15	He touched her hand and the fever left her: and then she rose and waited upon Him.
B040C008V016	40	8	16	In the evening many demoniacs were brought to Him, and with a word He expelled the demons; and He cured all the sick,
B040C008V017	40	8	17	in order that this prediction of the Prophet Isaiah might be fulfilled, 
B040C008V018	40	8	18	Seeing great crowds about Him Jesus had given directions to cross to the other side of the Lake,
B040C008V019	40	8	19	when a Scribe came and said to Him, »Teacher, I will follow you wherever you go.«
B040C008V020	40	8	20	»Foxes have holes,« replied Jesus, »and birds have nests; but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay His head.«
B040C008V021	40	8	21	Another of the disciples said to Him, »Sir, allow me first to go and bury my father.«
B040C008V022	40	8	22	»Follow me,« said Jesus, »and leave the dead to bury their own dead.«
B040C008V023	40	8	23	Then He went on board a fishing-boat, and His disciples followed Him.
B040C008V024	40	8	24	But suddenly there arose a great storm on the Lake, so that the waves threatened to engulf the boat; but He was asleep.
B040C008V025	40	8	25	So they came and woke Him, crying, »Master, save us, we are drowning!«
B040C008V026	40	8	26	»Why are you so easily frightened,« He replied, »you men of little faith?« Then He rose and reproved the winds and the waves, and there was a perfect calm;
B040C008V027	40	8	27	and the men, filled with amazement, exclaimed, »What kind of man is this? for the very winds and waves obey him!«
B040C008V028	40	8	28	On His arrival at the other side, in the country of the Gadarenes, there met Him two men possessed by demons, coming from among the tombs: they were so dangerously fierce that no one was able to pass that way.
B040C008V029	40	8	29	They cried aloud, »What hast Thou to do with us, Thou Son of God? Hast Thou come here to torment us before the time?«
B040C008V030	40	8	30	Now at some distance from them a vast herd of swine were feeding.
B040C008V031	40	8	31	So the demons entreated Him. »If Thou drivest us out,« they said, »send us into the herd of swine.«
B040C008V032	40	8	32	»Go,« He replied. Then they came out from the men and went into the swine, whereupon the entire herd instantly rushed down the cliff into the Lake and perished in the water.
B040C008V033	40	8	33	The swineherds fled, and went and told the whole story in the town, including what had happened to the demoniacs.
B040C008V034	40	8	34	So at once the whole population came out to meet Jesus; and when they saw Him, they besought Him to leave their country.
B040C009V001	40	9	1	Accordingly He went on board, and crossing over came to His own town.
B040C009V002	40	9	2	Here they brought to Him a paralytic lying on a bed. Seeing their faith Jesus said to the paralytic, »Take courage, my child; your sins are pardoned.«
B040C009V003	40	9	3	»Such language is impious,« said some of the Scribes among themselves.
B040C009V004	40	9	4	Knowing their thoughts Jesus said, »Why are you cherishing evil thoughts in your hearts?
B040C009V005	40	9	5	Why, which is easier? –to say, `Your sins are pardoned,' or to say `Rise up and walk'?
B040C009V006	40	9	6	But, to prove to you that the Son of Man has authority on earth to pardon sins« –He then says to the paralytic, »Rise, and take up your bed and go home.«
B040C009V007	40	9	7	And he got up, and went off home.
B040C009V008	40	9	8	And the crowds were awe-struck when they saw it, and ascribed the glory to God who had entrusted such power to a man.
