B040C012V031	40	12	31	This is why I tell you that men may find forgiveness for every other sin and impious word, but that for impious speaking against the Holy Spirit they shall find no forgiveness.
B040C012V032	40	12	32	And whoever shall speak against the Son of Man may obtain forgiveness; but whoever speaks against the Holy Spirit, neither in this nor in the coming age shall he obtain forgiveness.«
B040C012V033	40	12	33	»Either grant the tree to be wholesome and its fruit wholesome, or the tree poisonous and its fruit poisonous; for the tree is known by its fruit.
B040C012V034	40	12	34	O vipers' brood, how can you speak what is good when you are evil? For it is from the overflow of the heart that the mouth speaks.
B040C012V035	40	12	35	A good man from his good store produces good things, and a bad man from his bad store produces bad things.
B040C012V036	40	12	36	But I tell you that for every careless word that men shall speak they will be held accountable on the day of Judgement.
B040C012V037	40	12	37	For each of you by his words shall be justified, or by his words shall be condemned.«
B040C012V038	40	12	38	Then He was accosted by some of the Scribes and of the Pharisees who said, »Teacher, we wish to see a sign given by you.«
B040C012V039	40	12	39	»Wicked and faithless generation!« He replied, »they clamour for a sign, but none shall be given to them except the sign of the Prophet Jonah.
B040C012V040	40	12	40	For just as 
B040C012V041	40	12	41	There will stand up men of Nineveh at the Judgement together with the present generation, and will condemn it; because they repented at the preaching of Jonah, and mark! there is One greater than Jonah here.
B040C012V042	40	12	42	The Queen of the south will awake at the Judgement together with the present generation, and will condemn it; because she came from the ends of the earth to hear the wisdom of Solomon, and mark! there is One greater than Solomon here.
B040C012V043	40	12	43	»No sooner however has the foul spirit gone out of the man, then he roams about in places where there is no water, seeking rest but finding none.
B040C012V044	40	12	44	Then he says, `I will return to my house that I left;' and he comes and finds it unoccupied, swept clean, and in good order.
B040C012V045	40	12	45	Then he goes and brings back with him seven other spirits more wicked than himself, and they come in and dwell there; and in the end that man's condition becomes worse than it was at first. So will it be also with the present wicked generation.«
B040C012V046	40	12	46	While He was still addressing the people His mother and His brothers were standing on the edge of the crowd desiring to speak to Him.
B040C012V047	40	12	47	So some one told Him, »Your mother and your brothers are standing outside, and desire to speak to you.«
B040C012V048	40	12	48	»Who is my mother?« He said to the man; »and who are my brothers?«
B040C012V049	40	12	49	And pointing to His disciples He added, »See here are my mother and my brothers.
B040C012V050	40	12	50	To obey my Father who is in Heaven–that is to be my brother and my sister and my mother.«
B040C013V001	40	13	1	That same day Jesus had left the house and was sitting on the shore of the Lake,
B040C013V002	40	13	2	when a vast multitude of people crowded round Him. He therefore went on board a boat and sat there, while all the people stood on the shore.
B040C013V003	40	13	3	He then spoke many things to them in figurative language. »The sower goes out,« He said, »to sow.
B040C013V004	40	13	4	As he sows, some of the seed falls by the way-side, and the birds come and peck it up.
B040C013V005	40	13	5	Some falls on rocky ground, where it has but scanty soil. It quickly shows itself above ground, because it has no depth of earth;
B040C013V006	40	13	6	but when the sun is risen, it is scorched by the heat, and through having no root it withers up.
B040C013V007	40	13	7	Some falls among the thorns; but the thorns spring up and stifle it.
B040C013V008	40	13	8	But a portion falls upon good ground, and gives a return, some a hundred for one, some sixty, some thirty.
B040C013V009	40	13	9	Listen, every one who has ears!«
B040C013V010	40	13	10	(And His disciples came and asked Him, »Why do you speak to them in figurative language?«
B040C013V011	40	13	11	»Because,« He replied, »while to you it is granted to know the secrets of the Kingdom of the Heavens, to them it is not.
B040C013V012	40	13	12	For whoever has, to him more shall be given, and he shall have abundance; but whoever has not, from him even what he has shall be taken away.
B040C013V013	40	13	13	I speak to them in figurative language for this reason, that while looking they do not see, and while hearing they neither hear nor understand.
B040C013V014	40	13	14	And in regard to them the prophecy of Isaiah is receiving signal fulfilment: 
B040C013V015	40	13	15	
        
B040C013V016	40	13	16	»But as for you, blessed are your eyes, for they see, and your ears, for they hear.«
B040C013V017	40	13	17	For I solemnly tell you that many Prophets and holy men have longed to see the sights you see, and have not seen them, and to hear the words you hear, and have not heard them.
B040C013V018	40	13	18	»To you then I will explain the parable of the Sower.«
B040C013V019	40	13	19	When a man hears the Message concerning the Kingdom and does not understand it, the Evil one comes and catches away what has been sown in his heart. This is he who has received the seed by the road-side.
B040C013V020	40	13	20	He who has received the seed on the rocky ground is the man who hears the Message and immediately receives it with joy.
B040C013V021	40	13	21	It has struck no root, however, within him. He continues for a time, but when suffering comes, or persecution, because of the Message, he at once stumbles and falls.
B040C013V022	40	13	22	He who has received the seed among the thorns is the man who hears the Message, but the cares of the present age and the delusions of riches quite stifle the Message, and it becomes unfruitful.
B040C013V023	40	13	23	But he who has received the seed on good ground is he who hears and understands. Such hearers give a return, and yield one a hundred for one, another sixty, another thirty.
B040C013V024	40	13	24	Another parable He put before them. »The Kingdom of the Heavens,« He said, »may be compared to a man who has sown good seed in his field,
B040C013V025	40	13	25	but during the night his enemy comes, and over the first seed he sows darnel among the wheat, and goes away.
B040C013V026	40	13	26	But when the blade shoots up and the grain is formed, then appears the darnel also.
B040C013V027	40	13	27	So the farmer's men come and ask him, »`Sir, was it not good seed that you sowed on your land? Where then does the darnel come from?'
B040C013V028	40	13	28	`Some enemy has done this,' he said. »`Shall we go, and collect it?' the men inquire.
B040C013V029	40	13	29	»`No,' he replied, `for fear that while collecting the darnel you should at the same time root up the wheat with it.
B040C013V030	40	13	30	Leave both to grow together until the harvest, and at harvest-time I will direct the reapers, Collect the darnel first, and make it up into bundles to burn it, but bring all the wheat into my barn.'«
B040C013V031	40	13	31	Another parable He put before them. »The Kingdom of the Heavens,« He said, »is like a mustard-seed, which a man takes and sows in his ground.
B040C013V032	40	13	32	It is the smallest of all seeds, and yet when full-grown it is larger than any herb and forms a tree, so that the birds come and build in its branches.«
B040C013V033	40	13	33	Another parable He spoke to them. »The Kingdom of the Heavens,« He said, »is like yeast which a woman takes and buries in a bushel of flour, for it to work there till the whole mass has risen.«
B040C013V034	40	13	34	All this Jesus spoke to the people in figurative language, and except in figurative language He spoke nothing to them,
B040C013V035	40	13	35	in fulfilment of the saying of the Prophet, 
B040C013V036	40	13	36	When He had dismissed the people and had returned to the house, His disciples came to Him with the request, »Explain to us the parable of the darnel sown in the field.«
B040C013V037	40	13	37	»The sower of the good seed,« He replied, »is the Son of Man;
B040C013V038	40	13	38	the field is the world; the good seed–these are the sons of the Kingdom; the darnel, the sons of the Evil one.
B040C013V039	40	13	39	The enemy who sows the darnel is 
B040C013V040	40	13	40	As then the darnel is collected together and burnt up with fire, so will it be at the Close of the Age.
B040C013V041	40	13	41	The Son of Man will commission His angels, and they will gather out of His Kingdom all causes of sin and all who violate His laws;
B040C013V042	40	13	42	and these they will throw into the fiery furnace. There will be the weeping aloud and the gnashing of teeth.
B040C013V043	40	13	43	Then will the righteous shine out like the sun in their Father's Kingdom. Listen, every one who has ears!
B040C013V044	40	13	44	»The Kingdom of the Heavens is like treasure buried in the open country, which a man finds, but buries again, and, in his joy about it, goes and sells all he has and buys that piece of ground.«
B040C013V045	40	13	45	»Again the Kingdom of the Heavens is like a jewel merchant who is in quest of choice pearls.«
B040C013V046	40	13	46	He finds one most costly pearl; he goes away; and though it costs all he has, he buys it.
B040C013V047	40	13	47	»Again the Kingdom of the Heavens is like a draw-net let down into the sea, which encloses fish of all sorts.«
B040C013V048	40	13	48	When full, they haul it up on the beach, and sit down and collect the good fish in baskets, while the worthless they throw away.
B040C013V049	40	13	49	So will it be at the Close of the Age. The angels will go forth and separate the wicked from among the righteous,
B040C013V050	40	13	50	and will throw them into the fiery furnace. There will be the weeping aloud and the gnashing of teeth.«
B040C013V051	40	13	51	»Have you understood all this?« He asked. »Yes,« they said.
B040C013V052	40	13	52	»Therefore,« He said, »remember that every Scribe well trained for the Kingdom of the Heavens is like a householder who brings out of his storehouse new things and old.«
B040C013V053	40	13	53	Jesus concluded this series of parables and then departed.
B040C013V054	40	13	54	And He came into His own country and proceeded to teach in their synagogue, so that they were filled with astonishment and exclaimed, »Where did he obtain such wisdom, and these wondrous powers?
B040C013V055	40	13	55	Is not this the carpenter's son? Is not his mother called Mary? And are not his brothers, James, Joseph, Simon and Judah?
B040C013V056	40	13	56	And his sisters–are they not all living here among us? Where then did he get all this?«
B040C013V057	40	13	57	So they turned angrily away from Him. But Jesus said to them, »There is no prophet left without honour except in his own country and among his own family.«
B040C013V058	40	13	58	And He performed but few mighty deeds there because of their want of faith.
B040C014V001	40	14	1	About that time Herod the Tetrarch heard of the fame of Jesus,
B040C014V002	40	14	2	and he said to his courtiers, »This is John the Baptist: he has come back to life–and that is why these miraculous Powers are working in him.«
B040C014V003	40	14	3	For Herod had arrested John, and had put him in chains, and imprisoned him, for the sake of Herodias his brother Philip's wife,
B040C014V004	40	14	4	because John had persistently said to him, »It is not lawful for you to have her.«
B040C014V005	40	14	5	And he would have liked to put him to death, but was afraid of the people, because they regarded John as a Prophet.
B040C014V006	40	14	6	But when Herod's birthday came, the daughter of Herodias danced before all the company, and so pleased Herod
B040C014V007	40	14	7	that with an oath he promised to give her whatever she asked.
B040C014V008	40	14	8	So she, instigated by her mother, said, »Give me here on a dish the head of John the Baptist.«
B040C014V009	40	14	9	The king was deeply vexed, yet because of his repeated oath and of the guests at his table he ordered it to be given her,
B040C014V010	40	14	10	and he sent and beheaded John in the prison.
B040C014V011	40	14	11	The head was brought on a dish and given to the young girl, and she took it to her mother.
B040C014V012	40	14	12	Then John's disciples went and removed the body and buried it, and came and informed Jesus.
B040C014V013	40	14	13	Upon receiving these tidings, Jesus went away by boat to an uninhabited and secluded district; but the people heard of it and followed Him in crowds from the towns by land.
B040C014V014	40	14	14	So Jesus went out and saw an immense multitude, and felt compassion for them, and cured those of them who were out of health.
B040C014V015	40	14	15	But when evening was come, the disciples came to Him and said, »This is an uninhabited place, and the best of the day is now gone; send the people away to go into the villages and buy something to eat.«
B040C014V016	40	14	16	»They need not go away,« replied Jesus; »you yourselves must give them something to eat.«
B040C014V017	40	14	17	»We have nothing here,« they said, »but five loaves and a couple of fish.«
B040C014V018	40	14	18	»Bring them here to me,« He said,
B040C014V019	40	14	19	and He told all the people to sit down on the grass. Then He took the five loaves and the two fish, and after looking up to heaven and blessing them, He broke up the loaves and gave them to the disciples, and the disciples distributed them to the people.
B040C014V020	40	14	20	So all ate, and were fully satisfied. The broken portions that remained over they gathered up, filling twelve baskets.
B040C014V021	40	14	21	Those who had eaten were about 5,000 adult men, without reckoning women and children.
B040C014V022	40	14	22	Immediately afterwards He made the disciples go on board the boat and cross to the opposite shore, leaving Him to dismiss the people.
B040C014V023	40	14	23	When He had done this, He climbed the hill to pray in solitude. Night came on, and he was there alone.
B040C014V024	40	14	24	Meanwhile the boat was far out on the Lake, buffeted and tossed by the waves, the wind being adverse.
B040C014V025	40	14	25	But towards daybreak He went to them, walking over the waves.
B040C014V026	40	14	26	When the disciples saw Him walking on the waves, they were greatly alarmed. »It is a spirit,« they exclaimed, and they cried out with terror.
B040C014V027	40	14	27	But instantly Jesus spoke to them, and said, »There is no danger; it is I; do not be afraid.«
B040C014V028	40	14	28	»Master,« answered Peter, »if it is you, bid me come to you upon the water.«
B040C014V029	40	14	29	»Come,« said Jesus. Then Peter climbed down from the boat and walked upon the water to go to Him.
B040C014V030	40	14	30	But when he felt the wind he grew frightened, and beginning to sink he cried out, »Master, save me.«
B040C014V031	40	14	31	Instantly Jesus stretched out His hand and caught hold of him, saying to him, »O little faith, why did you doubt?«
B040C014V032	40	14	32	So they climbed into the boat, and the wind lulled;
B040C014V033	40	14	33	and the men on board fell down before him and said, »You are indeed God's Son.«
B040C014V034	40	14	34	When they had quite crossed over, they put ashore at Gennesaret;
B040C014V035	40	14	35	and the men of the place, recognizing Him, sent word into all the country round. So they brought all the sick to Him,
B040C014V036	40	14	36	and they entreated Him that they might but touch the tassel of His outer garment; and all who did so were restored to perfect health.
B040C015V001	40	15	1	Then there came to Jesus a party of Pharisees and Scribes from Jerusalem, who inquired,
B040C015V002	40	15	2	»Why do your disciples transgress the tradition of the Elders by not washing their hands before meals?«
B040C015V003	40	15	3	»Why do you, too,« He retorted, »transgress God's commands for the sake of your tradition?
B040C015V004	40	15	4	For God said, 
B040C015V005	40	15	5	but you –this is what you say: `If a man says to his father or mother, That is consecrated, whatever it is, which otherwise you should have received from me–
B040C015V006	40	15	6	he shall be absolved from honouring his father'; and so you have abrogated God's Word for the sake of your tradition.
B040C015V007	40	15	7	Hypocrites! well did Isaiah prophesy of you,
B040C015V008	40	15	8	
        
B040C015V009	40	15	9	
        
B040C015V010	40	15	10	Then, when He had called the people to Him, Jesus said, »Hear and understand.
B040C015V011	40	15	11	It is not what goes into a man's mouth that defiles him; but it is what comes out of his mouth–
B040C015V012	40	15	12	Then His disciples came and said to Him, »Do you know that the Pharisees were greatly shocked when they heard those words?«
B040C015V013	40	15	13	»Every plant,« He replied, »which my Heavenly Father has not planted will be rooted up.
B040C015V014	40	15	14	Leave them alone. They are blind guides of the blind; and if a blind man leads a blind man, both will fall into some pit.«
B040C015V015	40	15	15	»Explain to us this figurative language,« said Peter.
B040C015V016	40	15	16	»Are even you,« He answered, »still without intellingence?
B040C015V017	40	15	17	Do you not understand that whatever enters the mouth passes into the stomach and is afterwards ejected from the body?
B040C015V018	40	15	18	But the things that come out of the mouth proceed from the heart, and it is these that defile the man.
B040C015V019	40	15	19	For out of the heart proceed wicked thoughts, murder, adultery, fornication, theft, perjury, impiety of speech.
B040C015V020	40	15	20	These are the things which defile the man; but eating with unwashed hands does not defile.«
B040C015V021	40	15	21	Leaving that place, Jesus withdrew into the vicinity of Tyre and Sidon.
B040C015V022	40	15	22	Here a Canaanitish woman of the district came out and persistently cried out, »Sir, Son of David, pity me; my daughter is cruelly harassed by a demon.«
B040C015V023	40	15	23	But He answered her not a word. Then the disciples interposed, and begged Him, saying, »Send her away because she keeps crying behind us.«
B040C015V024	40	15	24	»I have only been sent to the lost sheep of the house of Israel,« He replied.
B040C015V025	40	15	25	Then she came and threw herself at His feet and entreated Him. »O Sir, help me,« she said.
B040C015V026	40	15	26	»It is not right,« He said, »to take the children's bread and throw it to the dogs.«
B040C015V027	40	15	27	»Be it so, Sir,« she said, »for even the dogs eat the scraps which fall from their masters' tables.«
B040C015V028	40	15	28	»O woman,« replied Jesus, »great is your faith: be it done to you as you desire.« And from that moment her daughter was restored to health.
B040C015V029	40	15	29	Again, moving thence, Jesus went along by the Lake of Galilee; and ascending the hill, He sat down there.
B040C015V030	40	15	30	Soon great crowds came to Him, bringing with them those who were crippled in feet or hands, blind or dumb, and many besides, and they hastened to lay them at His feet. And He cured them,
B040C015V031	40	15	31	so that the people were amazed to see the dumb speaking, the maimed with their hands perfect, the lame walking, and the blind seeing; and they gave the glory to the God of Israel.
B040C015V032	40	15	32	But Jesus called His disciples to Him and said, »My heart yearns over this mass of people, for it is now the third day that they have been with me and they have nothing to eat. I am unwilling to send them away hungry, lest they should faint on the road.«
B040C015V033	40	15	33	»Where can we,« asked the disciples, »get bread enough in this remote place to satisfy so vast a multitude?«
B040C015V034	40	15	34	»How many loaves have you?« Jesus asked. »Seven,« they said, »and a few small fish.«
B040C015V035	40	15	35	So He bade all the people sit down on the ground,
B040C015V036	40	15	36	and He took the seven loaves and the fish, and after giving thanks He broke them up and then distributed them to the disciples, and they to the people.
B040C015V037	40	15	37	And they all ate and were satisfied. The broken portions that remained over they took up–seven full hampers.
B040C015V038	40	15	38	Those who ate were 4,000 adult men, without reckoning women and children.
B040C015V039	40	15	39	He then dismissed the people, went on board the boat, and came into the district of Magadan.
B040C016V001	40	16	1	Here the Pharisees and Sadducees came to Him; and, to make trial of Him, they asked Him to show them a sign in the sky.
B040C016V002	40	16	2	He replied, »In the evening you say, `It will be fine weather, for the sky is red;'
B040C016V003	40	16	3	and in the morning, `It will be rough weather to-day, for the sky is red and murky.' You learn how to distinguish the aspect of the heavens, but the signs of the times you cannot.
B040C016V004	40	16	4	A wicked and faithless generation are eager for a sign; but none shall be given to them except the sign of Jonah.« and He left them and went away.
B040C016V005	40	16	5	When the disciples arrived at the other side of the Lake, they found that they had forgotten to bring any bread;
B040C016V006	40	16	6	and when Jesus said to them, »See to it: beware of the yeast of the Pharisees and Sadducees,«
B040C016V007	40	16	7	they reasoned among themselves, saying, »It is because we have not brought any bread.«
B040C016V008	40	16	8	Jesus perceived this and said, »Why are you reasoning among yourselves, you men of little faith, because you have no bread?
B040C016V009	40	16	9	Do you not yet understand? nor even remember the 5,000 and the five loaves, and how many basketfuls you carried away,
B040C016V010	40	16	10	nor the 4,000 and the seven loaves, and how many hampers you carried away?
B040C016V011	40	16	11	How is it you do not understand that it was not about bread that I spoke to you? But beware of the yeast of the Pharisees and Sadducees.«
B040C016V012	40	16	12	Then they perceived that He had not warned them against bread-yeast, but against the teaching of the Pharisees and Sadducees.
B040C016V013	40	16	13	When He arrived in the neighbourhood of Caesarea Philippi, Jesus questioned His disciples. »Who do people say that the Son of Man is?« He asked.
B040C016V014	40	16	14	»Some say John the Baptist,« they replied; »others Elijah; others Jeremiah or one of the Prophets.«
B040C016V015	40	16	15	»But you, who do you say that I am?« He asked again.
B040C016V016	40	16	16	»You,« replied Simon Peter, »are the Christ, the Son of the ever-living God.«
B040C016V017	40	16	17	»Blessed are you, Simon Bar-jonah,« said Jesus; »for mere human nature has not revealed this to you, but my Father in Heaven.
B040C016V018	40	16	18	And I declare to you that you are Peter, and that upon this Rock I will build my Church, and the might of Hades shall not triumph over it.
B040C016V019	40	16	19	I will give you the keys of the Kingdom of the Heavens; and whatever you bind on earth shall remain bound in Heaven, and whatever you loose on earth shall remain loosed in Heaven.«
B040C016V020	40	16	20	Then He urged His disciples to tell no one that He was the Christ.
B040C016V021	40	16	21	From this time Jesus began to explain to His disciples that He must go to Jerusalem, and suffer much cruelty from the Elders and the High Priests and the Scribes, and be put to death, and on the third day be raised to life again.
B040C016V022	40	16	22	Then Peter took Him aside and began taking Him to task. »Master,« he said, »God forbid; this will not be your lot.«
B040C016V023	40	16	23	But He turned and said to Peter, »Get behind me, Adversary; you are a hindrance to me, because your thoughts are not God's thoughts, but men's.«
B040C016V024	40	16	24	Then Jesus said to His disciples, »If any one desires to follow me, let him renounce self and take up his cross, and so be my follower.
B040C016V025	40	16	25	For whoever desires to save his life shall lose it, and whoever loses his life for my sake shall find it.
B040C016V026	40	16	26	Why, what benefit will it be to a man if he gains the whole world but forfeits his life? Or what shall a man give to buy back his life?
B040C016V027	40	16	27	For the Son of Man is soon to come in the glory of the Father with His angels, and then will He requite every man according to his actions.
B040C016V028	40	16	28	I solemnly tell you that some of those who are standing here will certainly not taste death till they have seen the Son of Man coming in His Kingdom.«
B040C017V001	40	17	1	Six day later, Jesus took with Him Peter and the brothers James and John, and brought them up a high mountain to a solitary place.
B040C017V002	40	17	2	There in their presence His form underwent a change; His face shone like the sun, and His raiment became as white as the light.
B040C017V003	40	17	3	And suddenly Moses and Elijah appeared to them conversing with Him.
B040C017V004	40	17	4	Then Peter said to Jesus, »Master, we are thankful to you that we are here. If you approve, I will put up three tents here, one for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah.«
B040C017V005	40	17	5	He was still speaking when a luminous cloud spread over them; and a voice was heard from within the cloud, which said, »This is My Son dearly beloved, in whom is My delight. Listen to Him.«
B040C017V006	40	17	6	On hearing this voice, the disciples fell on their faces and were filled with terror.
B040C017V007	40	17	7	But Jesus came and touched them, and said, »Rouse yourselves and have no fear.«
B040C017V008	40	17	8	So they looked up, and saw no one but Jesus.
B040C017V009	40	17	9	As they were descending the mountain, Jesus laid a command upon them. »Tell no one,« He said, »of the sight you have seen till the Son of Man has risen from among the dead.«
B040C017V010	40	17	10	»Why then,« asked the disciples, »do the Scribes say that Elijah must first come?«
B040C017V011	40	17	11	»Elijah was indeed to come,« He replied, »and would reform everything.
B040C017V012	40	17	12	But I tell you that he has already come, and they did not recognize him, but dealt with him as they chose. And before long the Son of Man will be treated by them in a similar way.«
B040C017V013	40	17	13	Then it dawned upon the disciples that it was John the Baptist about whom He had spoken to them.
