B040C026V043	40	26	43	He came and again found them asleep, for they were very tired.
B040C026V044	40	26	44	So He left them, and went away once more and prayed a third time, again using the same words.
B040C026V045	40	26	45	Then He came to the disciples and said, »Sleep on and rest. See, the moment is close at hand when the Son of Man is to be betrayed into the hands of sinful men.
B040C026V046	40	26	46	Rouse yourselves. Let us be going. My betrayer is close at hand.«
B040C026V047	40	26	47	He had scarcely finished speaking when Judas came –one of the Twelve– accompanied by a great crowd of men armed with swords and bludgeons, sent by the High Priests and Elders of the People.
B040C026V048	40	26	48	Now the betrayer had agreed upon a sign with them, to direct them. He had said, »The one whom I kiss is the man: lay hold of him.«
B040C026V049	40	26	49	So he went straight to Jesus and said, »Peace to you, Rabbi!« And he kissed Him eagerly.
B040C026V050	40	26	50	»Friend,« said Jesus, »carry out your intention.« Then they came and laid their hands on Jesus and seized Him firmly.
B040C026V051	40	26	51	But one of those with Jesus drew his sword and struck the High Priest's servant, cutting off his ear.
B040C026V052	40	26	52	»Put back your sword again,« said Jesus, »for all who draw the sword shall perish by the sword.
B040C026V053	40	26	53	Or do you suppose I cannot entreat my Father and He would instantly send to my help more than twelve legions of angels?
B040C026V054	40	26	54	In that case how are the Scriptures to be fulfilled which declare that thus it must be?«
B040C026V055	40	26	55	Then said Jesus to the crowds, »Have you come out as if to fight with a robber, with swords and bludgeons to apprehend me? Day after day I have been sitting teaching in the Temple, and you did not arrest me.
B040C026V056	40	26	56	But all this has taken place in order that the writings of the Prophets may be fulfilled.« At this point the disciples all left Him and fled.
B040C026V057	40	26	57	But the officers who had laid hold of Jesus led Him away to Caiaphas the High Priest, at whose house the Scribes and the Elders had assembled.
B040C026V058	40	26	58	And Peter kept following Him at a distance, till he came even to the court of the High Priest's palace, where he entered and sat down among the officers to see the issue.
B040C026V059	40	26	59	Meanwhile the High Priests and the whole Sanhedrin were seeking false testimony against Jesus in order to put Him to death;
B040C026V060	40	26	60	but they could find none, although many false witnesses came forward. At length there came two
B040C026V061	40	26	61	who testified, »This man said, `I am able to pull down the Sanctuary of God and three days afterwards to build a new one.'«
B040C026V062	40	26	62	Then the High Priest stood up and asked Him, »Have you no answer to make? What is it these men are saying in evidence against you?«
B040C026V063	40	26	63	Jesus however remained silent. Again the High Priest addressed Him. »In the name of the ever-living God,« he said, »I now put you on your oath. Tell us whether you are the Christ, the Son of God.«
B040C026V064	40	26	64	»I am He,« replied Jesus. »But I tell you that, later on, you will see 
B040C026V065	40	26	65	Then the High Priest tore his robes and exclaimed, »Impious language! What further need have we of witnesses! See, you have now heard the impiety.
B040C026V066	40	26	66	What is your verdict? »He deserves to die,« they replied.
B040C026V067	40	26	67	Then they spat in His face, and struck Him –some with the fist, some with the open hand–
B040C026V068	40	26	68	while they taunted Him, saying, »Christ, prove yourself a Prophet by telling us who it was that struck you.«
B040C026V069	40	26	69	Peter meanwhile was sitting outside in the court of the palace, when one of the maidservants came over to him and said, »You too were with Jesus the Galilaean.«
B040C026V070	40	26	70	He denied it before them all, saying, »I do not know what you mean.«
B040C026V071	40	26	71	Soon afterwards he went out and stood in the gateway, when another girl saw him, and said, addressing the people there, »This man was with Jesus the Nazarene.«
B040C026V072	40	26	72	Again he denied it with an oath. »I do not know the man,« he said.
B040C026V073	40	26	73	A short time afterwards the people standing there came and said to Peter, »Certainly you too are one of them, for your brogue shows it.«
B040C026V074	40	26	74	Then with curses and oaths he declared, »I do not know the man.« Immediately a cock crowed,
B040C026V075	40	26	75	and Peter recollected the words of Jesus, how He had said, »Before the cock crows you will three times disown me.« And he went out and wept aloud, bitterly.
B040C027V001	40	27	1	When morning came all the High Priests and the Elders of the people consulted together against Jesus to put Him to death;
B040C027V002	40	27	2	and binding Him they led Him away and handed Him over to Pilate the Governor.
B040C027V003	40	27	3	Then when Judas, who had betrayed Him, saw that He was condemned, smitten with remorse he brought back the thirty shekels to the High Priests and Elders
B040C027V004	40	27	4	and said, »I have sinned, in betraying to death one who is innocent.« »What does that matter to us?« they replied; »it is your business.«
B040C027V005	40	27	5	Flinging the shekels into the Sanctuary he left the place, and went and hanged himself.
B040C027V006	40	27	6	When the High Priests had gathered up the money they said, »It is illegal to put it into the Treasury, because it is the price of blood.«
B040C027V007	40	27	7	So after consulting together they spent the money in the purchase of the Potter's Field as a burial place for people not belonging to the city;
B040C027V008	40	27	8	for which reason that piece of ground received the name, which it still bears, of `the Field of Blood.'
B040C027V009	40	27	9	Then were fulfilled the words spoken by the Prophet Jeremiah, 
B040C027V010	40	27	10	
        
B040C027V011	40	27	11	Meanwhile Jesus was brought before the Governor, and the latter put the question, »Are you the King of the Jews?« »I am their King,« He answered.
B040C027V012	40	27	12	When however the High Priests and the Elders kept bringing their charges against Him, He said not a word in reply.
B040C027V013	40	27	13	»Do you not hear,« asked Pilate, »what a mass of evidence they are bringing against you?«
B040C027V014	40	27	14	But He made no reply to a single accusation, so that the Governor was greatly astonished.
B040C027V015	40	27	15	»Now it was the Governor's custom at the Festival to release some one prisoner, whomsoever the populace desired;
B040C027V016	40	27	16	and at this time they had a notorious prisoner called Barabbas.«
B040C027V017	40	27	17	So when they were now assembled Pilate appealed to them. »Whom shall I release to you,« he said, »Barabbas, or Jesus the so-called Christ?«
B040C027V018	40	27	18	For he knew that it was from envious hatred that Jesus had been brought before him.
B040C027V019	40	27	19	While he was sitting on the tribunal a message came to him from his wife. »Have nothing to do with that innocent man,« she said, »for during the night I have suffered terribly in a dream through him.«
B040C027V020	40	27	20	The High Priests, however, and the Elders urged the crowd to ask for Barabbas and to demand the death of Jesus.
B040C027V021	40	27	21	So when the Governor a second time asked them, »Which of the two shall I release to you?« –they cried, »Barabbas!«
B040C027V022	40	27	22	»What then,« said Pilate, »shall I do with Jesus, the so-called Christ?« With one voice they shouted, »Let him be crucified!«
B040C027V023	40	27	23	»Why, what crime has he committed?« asked Pilate. But they kept on furiously shouting, »Let him be crucified!«
B040C027V024	40	27	24	So when he saw that he could gain nothing, but that on the contrary there was a riot threatening, he called for water and washed his hands in sight of them all, saying, »I am not responsible for this murder: you must answer for it.«
B040C027V025	40	27	25	»His blood,« replied all the people, »be on us and on our children!«
B040C027V026	40	27	26	Then he released Barabbas to them, but Jesus he ordered to be scourged, and gave Him up to be crucified.
B040C027V027	40	27	27	Then the Governor's soldiers took Jesus into the Praetorium, and called together the whole battalion to make sport of Him.
B040C027V028	40	27	28	Stripping off His garments, they put on Him a general's short crimson cloak.
B040C027V029	40	27	29	They twisted a wreath of thorny twigs and put it on His head, and they put a sceptre of cane in His right hand, and kneeling to Him they shouted in mockery, »Long live the King of the Jews!«
B040C027V030	40	27	30	Then they spat upon Him, and taking the cane they repeatedly struck Him on the head with it.
B040C027V031	40	27	31	At last, having finished their sport, they took off the cloak, clothed Him again in His own garments, and led Him away for crucifixion.
B040C027V032	40	27	32	Going out they met a Cyrenaean named Simon; whom they compelled to carry His cross,
B040C027V033	40	27	33	and so they came to a place called Golgotha, which means `Skull-ground.'
B040C027V034	40	27	34	Here they gave Him a mixture of wine and gall to drink, but having tasted it He refused to drink it.
B040C027V035	40	27	35	After crucifying Him, they divided His garments among them by lot,
B040C027V036	40	27	36	and sat down there on guard.
B040C027V037	40	27	37	Over His head they placed a written statement of the charge against Him: THIS IS JESUS THE KING OF THE JEWS.
B040C027V038	40	27	38	At the same time two robbers were crucified with Him, one at His right hand and the other at His left.
B040C027V039	40	27	39	And the passers-by reviled Him. They shook their heads at Him
B040C027V040	40	27	40	and said, »You who would pull down the Sanctuary and build a new one within three days, save yourself. If you are God's Son, come down from the cross.«
B040C027V041	40	27	41	In like manner the High Priests also, together with the Scribes and the Elders, taunted Him.
B040C027V042	40	27	42	»He saved others,« they said, »himself he cannot save! He is the King of Israel! Let him now come down from the cross, and we will believe in him.
B040C027V043	40	27	43	His trust is in God: let God deliver him now, if He will have him; for he said, `I am God's Son.'«
B040C027V044	40	27	44	Insults of the same kind were heaped on Him even by the robbers who were being crucified with Him.
B040C027V045	40	27	45	Now from noon until three o'clock in the afternoon there was darkness over the whole land;
B040C027V046	40	27	46	but about three o'clock Jesus cried out in a loud voice, 
B040C027V047	40	27	47	»The man is calling for Elijah,« said some of the bystanders.
B040C027V048	40	27	48	One of them ran forthwith, and filling a sponge with sour wine put it on the end of a cane and offered it Him to drink;
B040C027V049	40	27	49	while the rest said, »Let us see whether Elijah is coming to deliver him.«
B040C027V050	40	27	50	But Jesus uttered another loud cry and then yielded up His spirit.
B040C027V051	40	27	51	Immediately the curtain of the Sanctuary was torn in two from top to bottom: the earth quaked; the rocks split;
B040C027V052	40	27	52	the tombs opened; and many of God's people who were asleep in death awoke.
B040C027V053	40	27	53	And coming out of their tombs after Christ's resurrection they entered the holy city and showed themselves to many.
B040C027V054	40	27	54	As for the Captain and the soldiers who were with Him keeping guard over Jesus, when they witnessed the earthquake and the other occurrences they were filled with terror, and exclaimed, »Assuredly he was God's Son.«
B040C027V055	40	27	55	And there were a number of women there looking on from a distance, who had followed Jesus from Galilee ministering to His necessities;
B040C027V056	40	27	56	among them being Mary of Magdala, Mary the mother of James and Joses, and the mother of the sons of Zabdi.
B040C027V057	40	27	57	Towards sunset there came a wealthy inhabitant of Arimathaea, named Joseph, who himself also had become a disciple of Jesus.
B040C027V058	40	27	58	He went to Pilate and begged to have the body of Jesus, and Pilate ordered it to be given to him.
B040C027V059	40	27	59	So Joseph took the body and wrapped it in a clean sheet of fine linen.
B040C027V060	40	27	60	He then laid it in his own new tomb which he had hewn in the solid rock, and after rolling a great stone against the door of the tomb he went home.
B040C027V061	40	27	61	Mary of Magdala and the other Mary were both present there, sitting opposite to the sepulchre.
B040C027V062	40	27	62	On the next day, the day after the Preparation, the High Priests and the Pharisees came in a body to Pilate.
B040C027V063	40	27	63	»Sir,« they said, »we recollect that during his lifetime that impostor pretended that after two days he was to rise to life again.
B040C027V064	40	27	64	So give orders for the sepulchre to be securely guarded till the third day, for fear his disciples should come by night and steal the body, and then tell the people that he has come back to life; and so the last imposture will be more serious than the first.«
B040C027V065	40	27	65	»You can have a guard,« said Pilate:»go and make all safe, as best you can.«
B040C027V066	40	27	66	So they went and made the sepulchre secure, sealing the stone besides setting the guard.
B040C028V001	40	28	1	After the Sabbath, in the early dawn of the first day of the week, Mary of Magdala and the other Mary came to see the sepulchre.
B040C028V002	40	28	2	But to their amazement there had been a great earthquake; for an angel of the Lord had descended from Heaven, and had come and rolled back the stone, and was sitting upon it.
B040C028V003	40	28	3	His appearance was like lightning, and his raiment white as snow.
B040C028V004	40	28	4	For fear of him the guards trembled violently, and became like dead men.
B040C028V005	40	28	5	But the angel said to the women, »As for you, dismiss your fears. I know that it is Jesus that you are looking for–the crucified One.
B040C028V006	40	28	6	He is not here: He has come back to life, as He foretold. Come and see the place where He lay.
B040C028V007	40	28	7	And go quickly and tell His disciples that He has risen from the dead and is going before you into Galilee: there you shall see Him. Remember, I have told you.«
B040C028V008	40	28	8	They quickly left the tomb and ran, still terrified but full of unspeakable joy, to carry the news to His disciples.
B040C028V009	40	28	9	And then suddenly they saw Jesus coming to meet them. »Peace be to you,« He said. And they came and clasped His feet, bowing to the ground before Him.
B040C028V010	40	28	10	Then He said, »Dismiss all fear! Go and take word to my brethren to go into Galilee, and there they shall see me.«
B040C028V011	40	28	11	While they went on this errand, some of the guards came into the city and reported to the High Priests every detail of what had happened.
B040C028V012	40	28	12	So the latter held a conference with the Elders, and after consultation with them they heavily bribed the soldiers,
B040C028V013	40	28	13	telling them to say, »His disciples came during the night and stole his body while we were asleep.«
B040C028V014	40	28	14	»And if this,« they added, »is reported to the Governor, we will satisfy him and screen you from punishment.«
B040C028V015	40	28	15	So they took the money and did as they were instructed; and this story was noised about among the Jews, and is current to this day.
B040C028V016	40	28	16	As for the eleven disciples, they proceeded into Galilee, to the hill where Jesus had arranged to meet them.
B040C028V017	40	28	17	There they saw Him and prostrated themselves before Him. Yet some doubted.
B040C028V018	40	28	18	Jesus however came near and said to them, »All power in Heaven and over the earth has been given to me.
B040C028V019	40	28	19	Go therefore and make disciples of all the nations; baptize them into the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit;
B040C028V020	40	28	20	and teach them to obey every command which I have given you. And remember, I am with you always, day by day, until the Close of the Age.«
B041C001V001	41	1	1	The beginning of the Good News of Jesus Christ the Son of God.
B041C001V002	41	1	2	As it is written in Isaiah the Prophet, 
B041C001V003	41	1	3	
        
B041C001V004	41	1	4	So John the Baptizer came, and was in the Desert proclaiming a baptism of the penitent for forgiveness of sins.
B041C001V005	41	1	5	There went out to him people of all classes from Judaea, and the inhabitants of Jerusalem of all ranks, and were baptized by him in the river Jordan, making open confession of their sins.
B041C001V006	41	1	6	As for John, his garment was of camel's hair, and he wore a loincloth of leather; and his food was locusts and wild honey.
B041C001V007	41	1	7	His announcement was, »There is One coming after me mightier than I–One whose sandal-strap I am unworthy to stoop down and unfasten.
B041C001V008	41	1	8	I have baptized you with water, but He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit.«
B041C001V009	41	1	9	At that time Jesus came from Nazareth in Galilee and was baptized by John in the Jordan;
B041C001V010	41	1	10	and immediately on His coming up out of the water He saw an opening in the sky, and the Spirit like a dove coming down to Him;
B041C001V011	41	1	11	and a voice came from the sky, saying, »Thou art My Son dearly loved: in Thee is My delight.«
B041C001V012	41	1	12	At once the Spirit impelled Him to go out into the Desert,
B041C001V013	41	1	13	where He remained for forty days, tempted by Satan; and He was among the wild beasts, but the angels waited upon Him.
B041C001V014	41	1	14	Then, after John had been thrown into prison, Jesus came into Galilee proclaiming God's Good News.
B041C001V015	41	1	15	»The time has fully come,« He said, »and the Kingdom of God is close at hand: repent, and believe this Good News.
B041C001V016	41	1	16	One day, passing along the shore of the Lake of Galilee, He saw Simon and Andrew, Simon's brother, throwing their nets in the Lake; for they were fisherman.
B041C001V017	41	1	17	»Come and follow me,« said Jesus, »and I will make you fishers for men.«
B041C001V018	41	1	18	At once they left their nets and followed Him.
B041C001V019	41	1	19	Going on a little further He saw James the son of Zabdi and his brother John: they also were in the boat mending the nets, and He immediately called them.
B041C001V020	41	1	20	They therefore left their father Zabdi in the boat with the hired men, and went and followed Him.
B041C001V021	41	1	21	So they came to Capernaum, and on the next Sabbath He went to the synagogue and began to teach.
B041C001V022	41	1	22	The people listened with amazement to His teaching –for there was authority about it: it was very different from that of the Scribes–
B041C001V023	41	1	23	when all at once, there in their synagogue, a man under the power of a foul spirit screamed out:
B041C001V024	41	1	24	»What have you to do with us, Jesus the Nazarene? Have you come to destroy us? I know who you are–God's Holy One.«
B041C001V025	41	1	25	But Jesus reprimanded him, saying, »Silence! come out of him.«
B041C001V026	41	1	26	So the foul spirit, after throwing the man into convulsions, came out of him with a loud cry.
B041C001V027	41	1	27	And all were amazed and awe-struck, so they began to ask one another, »What does this mean? Here is a new sort of teaching–and a tone of authority! And even to foul spirits he issues orders and they obey him!«
B041C001V028	41	1	28	And His fame spread at once everywhere in all that part of Galilee.
B041C001V029	41	1	29	Then on leaving the synagogue they came at once, with James and John, to the house of Simon and Andrew.
B041C001V030	41	1	30	Now Simon's mother-in-law was ill in bed with a fever, and without delay they informed Him about her.
B041C001V031	41	1	31	So He went to her, and taking her hand He raised her to her feet: the fever left her, and she began to wait upon them.
B041C001V032	41	1	32	When it was evening, after sunset people came bringing Him all who were sick and the demoniacs;
B041C001V033	41	1	33	and the whole town was assembled at the door.
B041C001V034	41	1	34	Then He cured numbers of people who were ill with various diseases, and He drove out many demons; not allowing the demons to speak, because they knew who He was.
B041C001V035	41	1	35	In the morning He rose early, while it was still quite dark, and leaving the house He went away to a solitary place and there prayed.
B041C001V036	41	1	36	And Simon and the others searched everywhere for Him.
B041C001V037	41	1	37	When they found Him they said, »Every one is looking for you.«
B041C001V038	41	1	38	»Let us go elsewhere, to the neighbouring country towns,« He replied, »that I may proclaim my Message there also; because for that purpose I came from God.«
B041C001V039	41	1	39	And He went through all Galilee, preaching in the synagogues and expelling the demons.
B041C001V040	41	1	40	One day there came a leper to Jesus entreating Him, and pleading on his knees. »If you are willing,« he said, »you are able to cleanse me.«
B041C001V041	41	1	41	Moved with pity Jesus reached out His hand and touched him. »I am willing,« He said; »be cleansed.«
B041C001V042	41	1	42	The leprosy at once left him, and he was cleansed.
B041C001V043	41	1	43	Jesus at once sent him away, strictly charging him,
B041C001V044	41	1	44	and saying, »Be careful not to tell any one, but go and show yourself to the Priest, and for your purification present the offerings that Moses appointed as evidence for them.«
B041C001V045	41	1	45	But the man, when he went out, began to tell every one and to publish the matter abroad, so that it was no longer possible for Jesus to go openly into any town; but He had to remain outside in unfrequented places, where people came to Him from all parts.
B041C002V001	41	2	1	After some days He entered Capernaum again, and it soon became known that He was at home;
B041C002V002	41	2	2	and such numbers of people came together that there was no longer room for them even round the door. He was speaking His Message to them,
B041C002V003	41	2	3	when there came a party of people bringing a paralytic–four men carrying him.
B041C002V004	41	2	4	Finding themselves unable, however, to bring him to Jesus because of the crowd, they untiled the roof just over His head, and after clearing an opening they lowered the mat on which the paralytic was lying.
B041C002V005	41	2	5	Seeing their faith, Jesus said to the paralytic, »My son, your sins are pardoned.«
B041C002V006	41	2	6	Now there were some of the Scribes sitting there, and reasoning in their hearts.
B041C002V007	41	2	7	»Why does this man use such words?« they said; »he is blaspheming. Who can pardon sins but One–that is, God?«
B041C002V008	41	2	8	At once perceiving by His spirit that they were reasoning within themselves, Jesus asked them, »Why do you thus argue in your minds?
B041C002V009	41	2	9	Which is easier?–to say to this paralytic, `Your sins are pardoned,' or to say, `Rise, take up your mat, and walk?'
B041C002V010	41	2	10	But that you may know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to pardon sins« –He turned to the paralytic, and said,
B041C002V011	41	2	11	»To you I say, `Rise, take up your mat and go home.'«
B041C002V012	41	2	12	The man rose, and immediately under the eyes of all took up his mat and went out, so that they were all filled with astonishment, gave the glory to God, and said, »We never saw anything like this.«
B041C002V013	41	2	13	Again He went out to the shore of the Lake, and the whole multitude kept coming to Him, and He taught them.
B041C002V014	41	2	14	And as He passed by, He saw Levi the son of Alphaeus sitting at the Toll Office, and said to him, »Follow me.« So he rose and followed Him.
B041C002V015	41	2	15	When He was sitting at table in Levi's house, a large number of tax-gatherers and notorious sinners were at table with Jesus and His disciples; for there were many such who habitually followed Him.
B041C002V016	41	2	16	But when the Scribes of the Pharisee sect saw Him eating with the sinners and the tax-gatherers, they said to His disciples, »He is eating and drinking with the tax-gatherers and sinners!«
B041C002V017	41	2	17	Jesus heard the words, and He said, »It is not the healthy who require a doctor, but the sick: I did not come to appeal to the righteous, but to sinners.«
B041C002V018	41	2	18	(Now John's disciples and those of the Pharisees were keeping a fast.) And they came and asked Him, »How is it that John's disciples and those of the Pharisees are fasting, and yours are not?«
B041C002V019	41	2	19	»Can a wedding party fast while the bridegroom is among them?« replied Jesus. »So long as they have the bridegroom with them, fasting is impossible.
B041C002V020	41	2	20	But a time will come when the Bridegroom will be taken away from them; then they will fast.
B041C002V021	41	2	21	No one mends an old garment with a piece of unshrunk cloth. Otherwise, the patch put on would tear away from it– the new from the old– and a worse hole would be made.
B041C002V022	41	2	22	And no one pours new wine into old wineskins. Otherwise the wine would burst the skins, and both wine and skins would be lost. New wine needs fresh skins!«
B041C002V023	41	2	23	One Sabbath He was walking through the wheatfields when His disciples began to pluck the ears of wheat as they went.
B041C002V024	41	2	24	So the Pharisees said to Him, »Look! why are they doing what on the Sabbath is unlawful?«
B041C002V025	41	2	25	»Have you never read,« Jesus replied, »what David did when the necessity arose and he and his men were hungry:
B041C002V026	41	2	26	how he entered the house of God in the High-priesthood of Abiathar, and ate the Presented Loaves –which none but the priests are allowed to eat– and gave some to his men also?«
B041C002V027	41	2	27	And Jesus said to them: »The Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath;
B041C002V028	41	2	28	so that the Son of Man is Lord even of the Sabbath.«
B041C003V001	41	3	1	At another time, when He went to the synagogue, there was a man there with one arm shrivelled up.
B041C003V002	41	3	2	They closely watched Him to see whether He would cure him on the Sabbath–so as to have a charge to bring against Him.
B041C003V003	41	3	3	»Come forward,« said He to the man with the shrivelled arm.
B041C003V004	41	3	4	Then He asked them, »Are we allowed to do good on the Sabbath, or to do evil? to save a life, or to destroy one?« They remained silent.
B041C003V005	41	3	5	Grieved and indignant at the hardening of their hearts, He looked round on them with anger, and said to the man, »Stretch out your arm.« He stretched it out, and the arm was completely restored.
B041C003V006	41	3	6	But no sooner had the Pharisees left the synagogue than they held a consultation with the Herodians against Jesus, to devise some means of destroying Him.
B041C003V007	41	3	7	Accordingly Jesus withdrew with His disciples to the Lake, and a vast crowd of people from Galilee followed Him;
B041C003V008	41	3	8	and from Judaea and Jerusalem and Idumaea and from beyond the Jordan and from the district of Tyre and Sidon there came to Him a vast crowd, hearing of all that He was doing.
B041C003V009	41	3	9	So He gave directions to His disciples to keep a small boat in constant attendance on Him because of the throng–to prevent their crushing Him.
B041C003V010	41	3	10	For He had cured many of the people, so that all who had any ailments pressed upon Him, to touch Him.
B041C003V011	41	3	11	And the foul spirits, whenever they saw Him, threw themselves down at His feet, screaming out:»You are the Son of God.«
B041C003V012	41	3	12	But He many a time checked them, forbidding them to say who He was.
B041C003V013	41	3	13	Then He went up the hill; and those whom He Himself chose He called, and they came to Him.
B041C003V014	41	3	14	He appointed twelve of them, that they might be with Him, and that He might also send them to proclaim His Message,
B041C003V015	41	3	15	with authority to expel the demons.
B041C003V016	41	3	16	These twelve were Simon (to whom He gave the surname of Peter),
B041C003V017	41	3	17	James the son of Zabdi and John the brother of James (these two He surnamed Boanerges, that is `Sons of Thunder'),
B041C003V018	41	3	18	Andrew, Philip, Bartholomew, Matthew, Thomas, James the son of Alphaeus, Thaddaeus, Simon the Cananaean,
B041C003V019	41	3	19	and Judas Iscariot, the man who also betrayed Him.
B041C003V020	41	3	20	And He went into a house. But again the crowd assembled, so that there was no opportunity for them even to snatch a meal.
B041C003V021	41	3	21	Hearing of this, His relatives came to seize Him by force, for they said, »He is out of his mind.«
B041C003V022	41	3	22	The Scribes, too, who had come down from Jerusalem said, »He has Baal-zebul in him; and it is by the power of the Prince of the demons that he expels the demons.«
B041C003V023	41	3	23	So He called them to Him, and using figurative language He appealed to them, saying, »How is it possible for Satan to expel Satan?
B041C003V024	41	3	24	For if civil war breaks out in a kingdom, nothing can make that kingdom last;
B041C003V025	41	3	25	and if a family splits into parties, that family cannot continue.
B041C003V026	41	3	26	So if Satan has risen in arms and has made war upon himself, stand he cannot, but meets his end.
B041C003V027	41	3	27	Nay, no one can go into a strong man's house and carry off his property, unless he first binds the strong man, and then he will plunder his house.
B041C003V028	41	3	28	In solemn truth I tell you that all their sins may be pardoned to the sons of men, and all their blasphemies, however they may have blasphemed;
B041C003V029	41	3	29	but whoever blasphemes against the Holy Spirit, he remains for ever unabsolved: he is guilty of a sin of the Ages.«
B041C003V030	41	3	30	This was because they said, »He is possessed by a foul spirit.«
B041C003V031	41	3	31	By this time His mother and His brothers arrive, and standing outside they send a message to Him to call Him.
B041C003V032	41	3	32	Now a crowd was sitting round Him; so they tell Him, »Your mother and your brothers and sisters are outside, inquiring for you.«
B041C003V033	41	3	33	»Who are my mother and my brothers?« He replied.
B041C003V034	41	3	34	And, fixing His eyes on the people who were sitting round Him in a circle, He said,
B041C003V035	41	3	35	»Here are my mother and my brothers. For wherever there is one who has been obedient to God, there is my brother –my sister– and my mother.«
B041C004V001	41	4	1	Once more He began to teach by the side of the Lake, and a vast multitude of people came together to listen to Him. He therefore went on board the boat and sat there, a little way from the land; and all the people were on the shore close to the water.
B041C004V002	41	4	2	Then He proceeded to teach them many lessons in figurative language; and in His teaching He said,
B041C004V003	41	4	3	»Listen: the sower goes out to sow.«
B041C004V004	41	4	4	As he sows, some of the seed falls by the way-side, and the birds come and peck it up.
B041C004V005	41	4	5	Some falls on the rocky ground where it finds but little earth, and it shoots up quickly because it has no depth of soil;
B041C004V006	41	4	6	but when the sun is risen, it is scorched, and through having no root it withers away.
B041C004V007	41	4	7	Some, again, falls among the thorns; and the thorns spring up and stifle it, so that it yields no crop.
B041C004V008	41	4	8	But some of the seed falls into good ground, and gives a return: it comes up and increases, and yields thirty, sixty, or a hundred-fold.«
B041C004V009	41	4	9	»Listen,« He added, »every one who has ears to listen with!«
B041C004V010	41	4	10	When He was alone, the Twelve and the others who were about Him requested Him to explain His figurative language.
B041C004V011	41	4	11	»To you,« He replied, »has been entrusted the secret truth concerning the Kingdom of God; but to those others outside your number all this is spoken in figurative language;
B041C004V012	41	4	12	that 
B041C004V013	41	4	13	»Do you all miss the meaning of this parable?« He added; »how then will you understand the rest of my parables?«
B041C004V014	41	4	14	»What the sower sows is the Message.«
B041C004V015	41	4	15	Those who receive the seed by the way-side are those in whom the Message is sown, but, when they have heard it, Satan comes at once and carries away the Message sown in them.
B041C004V016	41	4	16	In the same way those who receive the seed on the rocky places are those who, when they have heard the Message, at once accept it joyfully,
B041C004V017	41	4	17	but they have no root within them. They last for a time; then, when suffering or persecution comes because of the Message, they are immediately overthrown.
B041C004V018	41	4	18	Others there are who receive the seed among the thorns: these are they who have heard the Message,
B041C004V019	41	4	19	but worldly cares and the deceitfulness of wealth and the excessive pursuit of other objects come in and stifle the Message, and it becomes unfruitful.
B041C004V020	41	4	20	Those, on the other hand, who have received the seed on the good ground, are all who hear the Message and welcome it, and yield a return of thirty, sixty, or a hundred fold.«
B041C004V021	41	4	21	He went on to say, »Is the lamp brought in in order to be put under the bushel or under the bed? Is it not rather in order that it may be placed on the lampstand?
B041C004V022	41	4	22	Why, there is nothing hidden except with a view to its being ultimately disclosed, nor has anything been made a secret but that it may at last come to light.
B041C004V023	41	4	23	Listen, every one who has ears to listen with!«
B041C004V024	41	4	24	He also said to them, »Take care what you hear. With what measure you measure, it will be measured to you, and that with interest.
B041C004V025	41	4	25	For those who have will have more given them; and from those who have not, even what they have will be taken away.«
B041C004V026	41	4	26	Another saying of His was this: »The Kingdom of God is as if a man scattered seed over the ground:
B041C004V027	41	4	27	he spends days and nights, now awake, now asleep, while the seed sprouts and grows tall, he knows not how.
B041C004V028	41	4	28	Of itself the land produces the crop– first the blade, then the ear; afterwards the perfect grain is seen in the ear.
B041C004V029	41	4	29	But no sooner is the crop ripe, than he sends the reapers, because the time of harvest has come.«
B041C004V030	41	4	30	Another saying of His was this: »How are we to picture the Kingdom of God? or by what figure of speech shall we represent it?
B041C004V031	41	4	31	It is like a mustard-seed, which, when sown in the earth, is the smallest of all the seeds in the world;
B041C004V032	41	4	32	yet when sown it springs up and becomes larger than all the herbs, and throws out great branches, so that the birds build under its shadow.«
B041C004V033	41	4	33	With many such parables He used to speak the Message to them according to their capacity for receiving it.
B041C004V034	41	4	34	But except in figurative language He spoke nothing to them; while to His own disciples He expounded everything, in private.
B041C004V035	41	4	35	The same day, in the evening, He said to them, »Let us cross to the other side.«
B041C004V036	41	4	36	So they got away from the crowd, and took Him –as He was– in the boat; and other boats accompanied Him.
B041C004V037	41	4	37	But a heavy squall came on, and the waves were now dashing into the boat, so that it was fast filling.
B041C004V038	41	4	38	But He Himself was in the stern asleep, with His head on the cushion: so they woke Him. »Rabbi,« they cried, »is it nothing to you that we are drowning?«
B041C004V039	41	4	39	So He roused Himself and rebuked the wind, and said to the waves, »Silence! Be still!« The wind sank, and a perfect calm set in.
B041C004V040	41	4	40	»Why are you so timid?« He asked; »have you still no faith?«
B041C004V041	41	4	41	Then they were filled with terror, and began to say to one another, »Who is this, then? For even wind and sea obey Him.«
B041C005V001	41	5	1	So they arrived at the opposite shore of the Lake, in the country of the Gerasenes.
