B042C006V021	42	6	21	»Blessed are you who hunger now, because your hunger shall be satisfied.« Blessed are you who now weep aloud, because you shall laugh.
B042C006V022	42	6	22	»Blessed are you when men shall hate you and exclude you from their society and insult you, and spurn your very names as evil things, for the Son of Man's sake.«
B042C006V023	42	6	23	»Be glad at such a time, and dance for joy; for your reward is great in Heaven; for that is just the way their forefathers behaved to the Prophets!«
B042C006V024	42	6	24	»But alas for you rich men, because you already have your consolation!«
B042C006V025	42	6	25	»Alas for you who now have plenty to eat, because you will be hungry!« Alas for you who laugh now, because you will mourn and weep aloud!
B042C006V026	42	6	26	»Alas for you when men shall all have spoken well of you; for that is just the way their forefathers behaved to the false Prophets!«
B042C006V027	42	6	27	»But to you who are listening to me I say, Love your enemies; seek the welfare of those who hate you;«
B042C006V028	42	6	28	bless those who curse you; pray for those who revile you.
B042C006V029	42	6	29	To him who gives you a blow on one side of the face offer the other side also; and to him who is robbing you of your outer garment refuse not the under one also.
B042C006V030	42	6	30	To every one who asks, give; and from him who takes away your property, do not demand it back.
B042C006V031	42	6	31	And behave to your fellow men just as you would have them behave to you.
B042C006V032	42	6	32	»If you love those who love you, what credit is it to you? Why, even bad men love those who love them.«
B042C006V033	42	6	33	And if you are kind to those who are kind to you, what credit is it to you? Even bad men act thus.
B042C006V034	42	6	34	And if you lend to those from whom you hope to receive, what credit is it to you? Even bad men lend to their fellows so as to receive back an equal amount.
B042C006V035	42	6	35	Nevertheless love your enemies, be beneficent; and lend without hoping for any repayment. Then your recompense shall be great, and you will be sons of the Most High; for He is kind to the ungrateful and wicked.
B042C006V036	42	6	36	Be compassionate just as your Father is compassionate.
B042C006V037	42	6	37	»Judge not, and you shall not be judged; condemn not, and you shall not be condemned; pardon, and you shall be pardoned;«
B042C006V038	42	6	38	give, and gifts shall be bestowed on you. Full measure, pressed, shaken down, and running over, shall they pour into your laps; for with the same measure that you use they shall measure to you in return.«
B042C006V039	42	6	39	He also spoke to them in figurative language. »Can a blind man lead a blind man?« He asked; »would not both fall into the ditch?
B042C006V040	42	6	40	There is no disciple who is superior to his teacher; but every one whose instruction is complete will be like his teacher.
B042C006V041	42	6	41	»And why look at the splinter in your brother's eye instead of giving careful attention to the beam in your own?«
B042C006V042	42	6	42	How can you say to your brother, `Brother, let me take that splinter out of your eye,' when all the while you yourself do not see the beam in your own eye? Vain pretender! take the beam out of your own eye first, and then you will see clearly to take the splinter out of your brother's eye.
B042C006V043	42	6	43	»There is no good tree that yields unsound fruit, nor again any unsound tree that yields good fruit.«
B042C006V044	42	6	44	Every tree is known by its own fruit. It is not from thorns that men gather figs, nor from the bramble that they can get a bunch of grapes.
B042C006V045	42	6	45	A good man from the good stored up in his heart brings out what is good; and an evil man from the evil stored up brings out what is evil; for from the overflow of his heart his mouth speaks.
B042C006V046	42	6	46	»And why do you all call me `Master, Master' and yet not do what I tell you?«
B042C006V047	42	6	47	Every one who comes to me and listens to my words and puts them in practice, I will show you whom he is like.
B042C006V048	42	6	48	He is like a man building a house, who digs and goes deep, and lays the foundation on the rock; and when a flood comes, the torrent bursts upon that house, but is unable to shake it, because it is securely built.
B042C006V049	42	6	49	But he who has heard and not practised is like a man who has built a house upon the soft soil without a foundation, against which the torrent bursts, and immediately it collapses, and terrible is the wreck and ruin of that house.«
B042C007V001	42	7	1	After He had finished teaching all these things in the hearing of the people, He went into Capernaum.
B042C007V002	42	7	2	Here the servant of a certain Captain, a man dear to his master, was ill and at the point of death;
B042C007V003	42	7	3	and the Captain, hearing about Jesus, sent to Him some of the Jewish Elders, begging Him to come and restore his servant to health.
B042C007V004	42	7	4	And they, when they came to Jesus, earnestly entreated Him, pleading, »He deserves to have this favour granted him,
B042C007V005	42	7	5	for he loves our nation, and at his own expense he built our synagogue for us.«
B042C007V006	42	7	6	Then Jesus went with them. But when He was not far from the house, the Captain sent friends to Him with the message: »Sir, do not trouble to come. I am not worthy of having you come under my roof;
B042C007V007	42	7	7	and therefore I did not deem myself worthy to come to you. Only speak the word, and let my young man be cured.
B042C007V008	42	7	8	For I too am a man obedient to authority, and have soldiers under me; and I say to one, `Go,' and he goes; to another, `Come,' and he comes; and to my slave, `Do this or that,' and he does it.«
