B042C007V041	42	7	41	»There were once two men in debt to one money-lender,« said Jesus; »one owed him five hundred shillings and the other fifty.
B042C007V042	42	7	42	But neither of them could pay anything; so he freely forgave them both. Tell me, then, which of them will love him most?«
B042C007V043	42	7	43	»I suppose,« replied Simon, »the one to whom he forgave most.«»You have judged rightly,« Jesus rejoined.
B042C007V044	42	7	44	Then turning towards the woman He said to Simon, »Do you see this woman? I came into your house: you gave me no water for my feet; but she has made my feet wet with her tears, and then wiped the tears away with her hair.
B042C007V045	42	7	45	No kiss did you give me; but she from the moment I came in has not left off tenderly kissing my feet.
B042C007V046	42	7	46	No oil did you pour even on my head; but she has poured perfume upon my feet.
B042C007V047	42	7	47	This is the reason why I tell you that her sins, her many sins, are forgiven–because she has loved much; but he who is forgiven little, loves little.«
B042C007V048	42	7	48	And He said to her, »Your sins are forgiven.«
B042C007V049	42	7	49	Then the other guests began to say to themselves, »Who can this man be who even forgives sins?«
B042C007V050	42	7	50	But He said to the woman, »Your faith has cured you: go, and be at peace.«
B042C008V001	42	8	1	Shortly after this He visited town after town, and village after village, proclaiming His Message and telling the Good News of the Kingdom of God. The Twelve were with Him,
B042C008V002	42	8	2	and certain women whom He had delivered from evil spirits and various diseases–Mary of Magdala, out of whom seven demons had come,
B042C008V003	42	8	3	and Joanna the wife of Chuza, Herod's steward, and Susanna, and many other women, all of whom contributed to the support of Jesus and His Apostles.
B042C008V004	42	8	4	And when a great crowd was assembling, and was receiving additions from one town after another, He spoke a parable to them.
B042C008V005	42	8	5	»The sower,« He said, »goes out to sow his seed; and as he sows, some of the seed falls by the way-side, and is trodden upon, or the birds of the air come and peck it up.
B042C008V006	42	8	6	Another part drops upon the rock, and after growing up it withers away for want of moisture.
B042C008V007	42	8	7	Another part falls among the thorns, and the thorns grow up with it and stifle it.
B042C008V008	42	8	8	But some of the seed falls into good ground, and grows up and yields a return of a hundred for one.« While thus speaking, He cried aloud and said, »Listen, every one who has ears to listen with!«
B042C008V009	42	8	9	The disciples proceeded to ask Him what this parable meant.
B042C008V010	42	8	10	»To you,« He replied, »it is granted to know the secrets of the Kingdom of God; but all others are taught by parables, in order that they may see and yet not see, and may hear and yet not understand.
B042C008V011	42	8	11	The meaning of the parable is as follows. The seed is God's Message.
B042C008V012	42	8	12	Those by the way-side are those who have heard, and then the Devil comes and carries away the Message from their hearts, lest they should believe and be saved.
B042C008V013	42	8	13	Those on the rock are the people who on hearing the Message receive it joyfully; but they have no root: for a time they believe, but when trial comes they fall away.
B042C008V014	42	8	14	That which fell among the thorns means those who have heard, but as they go on their way, the Message is stifled by the anxieties, wealth and gaieties of time, and they yield nothing in perfection.
B042C008V015	42	8	15	But as for that in the good ground, it means those who, having listened to the Message with open minds and in a right spirit, hold it fast, and patiently yield a return.
B042C008V016	42	8	16	»When any one lights a lamp, he does not cover it with a vessel or hide it under a couch; he puts it on a lampstand, that people who enter the room may see the light.«
B042C008V017	42	8	17	There is nothing hidden, which shall not be openly seen; nor anything secret, which shall not be known and come into the light of day.
B042C008V018	42	8	18	Be careful, therefore, how you hear; for whoever has anything, to him more shall be given, and whoever has nothing, even that which he thinks he has shall be taken away from him.«
B042C008V019	42	8	19	Then came to Him His mother and His brothers, but could not get near Him for the crowd.
B042C008V020	42	8	20	But He was told, »Your mother and brothers are standing on the edge of the crowd, and want to see you.«
B042C008V021	42	8	21	»My mother and my brothers,« He replied, »are these who hear God's Message and obey it.«
B042C008V022	42	8	22	One day He went on board a boat–both He and his disciples; and He said to them, »Let us cross over to the other side of the Lake.« So they set sail.
B042C008V023	42	8	23	dummy verses inserted by amos
B042C008V024	42	8	24	So they came and woke Him, crying, »Rabbi, Rabbi, we are drowning.« Then He roused Himself and rebuked the wind and the surging of the water, and they ceased and there was a calm.
B042C008V025	42	8	25	»Where is your faith?« He asked them. But they were filled with terror and amazement, and said to one another, »Who then is this? for He gives orders both to wind and waves, and they obey Him.«
B042C008V026	42	8	26	Then they put in to shore in the country of the Gerasenes, which lies opposite to Galilee.
B042C008V027	42	8	27	Here, on landing, He was met by one of the townsmen who was possessed by demons–for a long time he had not put on any garment, nor did he live in a house, but in the tombs.
B042C008V028	42	8	28	When he saw Jesus, he cried out and fell down before Him, and said in a loud voice, »What have you to do with me, Jesus, Son of God Most High? Do not torture me, I beseech you.«
B042C008V029	42	8	29	For already He had been commanding the foul spirit to come out of the man. For many a time it had seized and held him, and they had repeatedly put him in chains and fetters and kept guard over him, but he used to break the chains to pieces, and, impelled by the demon, to escape into the Desert.
B042C008V030	42	8	30	»What is your name?« Jesus asked him. »Legion,« he replied–because a great number of demons had entered into him;
B042C008V031	42	8	31	and they besought Him not to command them to be gone into the Bottomless Pit.
B042C008V032	42	8	32	Now there was a great herd of swine there feeding on the hill-side; and the demons begged Him to give them leave to go into them, and He gave them leave.
B042C008V033	42	8	33	The demons came out of the man and left him, and entered into the swine; and the herd rushed violently over the cliff into the Lake and were drowned.
B042C008V034	42	8	34	The swineherds, seeing what had happened, fled and reported it both in town and country;
B042C008V035	42	8	35	whereupon the people came out to see what had happened. They came to Jesus, and they found the man from whom the demons had gone out sitting at the feet of Jesus, clothed and in his right mind; and they were terrified.
B042C008V036	42	8	36	And those who had seen it told them how the demoniac was cured.
B042C008V037	42	8	37	Then the whole population of the Gerasenes and of the adjacent districts begged Him to depart from them; for their terror was great. So He went on board and returned.
B042C008V038	42	8	38	But the man from whom the demons had gone out earnestly asked permission to go with Him; but He sent him away.
B042C008V039	42	8	39	»Return home,« He said, »and tell there all that God has done for you.« So he went and published through the whole town all that Jesus had done for him.
B042C008V040	42	8	40	Now when Jesus was returning, the people gave Him a warm welcome; for they had all been looking out for Him.
B042C008V041	42	8	41	Just then there came a man named Jair, a Warden of the Synagogue, who threw himself at the feet of Jesus, and entreated Him to come to his house;
B042C008V042	42	8	42	for he had an only daughter, about twelve years old, and she was dying. And as He went, the dense throng crowded on Him.
B042C008V043	42	8	43	And a woman who for twelve years had been afflicted with haemorrhage –and had spent on doctors all she had, but none of them had been able to cure her–
B042C008V044	42	8	44	came close behind Him and touched the tassel of His robe; and instantly her flow of blood stopped.
B042C008V045	42	8	45	»Who is it touched me?« Jesus asked. And when all denied having done so, Peter and the rest said, »Rabbi, the crowds are hemming you in and pressing on you.«
B042C008V046	42	8	46	»Some one has touched me,« Jesus replied, »for I feel that power has gone out from me.«
B042C008V047	42	8	47	Then the woman, perceiving that she had not escaped notice, came trembling, and throwing herself down at His feet she stated before all the people the reason why she had touched Him and how she was instantly cured.
B042C008V048	42	8	48	»Daughter,« said He, »your faith has cured you; go, and be at peace.«
B042C008V049	42	8	49	While He was still speaking, some one came to the Warden of the Synagogue from his house and said, »Your daughter is dead; trouble the Rabbi no further.«
B042C008V050	42	8	50	Jesus heard the words and said to him, »Have no fear. Only believe, and she shall be restored to life.«
B042C008V051	42	8	51	So He came to the house, but allowed no one to go in with Him but Peter and John and James and the girl's father and mother.
B042C008V052	42	8	52	The people were all weeping aloud and beating their breasts for her; but He said, »Leave off wailing; for she is not dead, but asleep.«
B042C008V053	42	8	53	And they jeered at Him, knowing that she was dead.
B042C008V054	42	8	54	He, however, took her by the hand and called aloud, »Child, awake!«
B042C008V055	42	8	55	And her spirit returned, and instantly she stood up; and He directed them to give her some food.
B042C008V056	42	8	56	Her parents were astounded; but He forbad them to mention the matter to any one.
B042C009V001	42	9	1	Then calling the Twelve together He conferred on them power and authority over all the demons and to cure diseases;
B042C009V002	42	9	2	and sent them out to proclaim the Kingdom of God and to cure the sick.
B042C009V003	42	9	3	And He commanded them, »Take nothing for your journey; neither stick nor bag nor bread nor money; and do not have an extra under garment.
B042C009V004	42	9	4	Whatever house you enter, make that your home, and from it start afresh.
B042C009V005	42	9	5	Wherever they refuse to receive you, as you leave that town shake off the very dust from your feet as a protest against them.«
B042C009V006	42	9	6	So they departed and visited village after village, spreading the Good News and performing cures everywhere.
B042C009V007	42	9	7	Now Herod the Tetrarch heard of all that was going on; and he was bewildered because of its being said by some that John had come back to life,
B042C009V008	42	9	8	by others that Elijah had appeared, and by others that some one of the ancient Prophets had come back to life.
B042C009V009	42	9	9	And Herod said, »John I have beheaded; but who is this, of whom I hear such reports?« And he sought for an opportunity of seeing Jesus.
B042C009V010	42	9	10	The Apostles, on their return, related to Jesus all they had done. Then He took them and withdrew to a quiet retreat, to a town called Bethsaida.
B042C009V011	42	9	11	But the immense crowd, aware of this, followed Him; and receiving them kindly He proceeded to speak to them of the Kingdom of God, and those who needed to be restored to health, He cured.
B042C009V012	42	9	12	Now when the day began to decline, the Twelve came to Him and said, »Send the people away, that they may go to the villages and farms round about and find lodging and a supply of food; because here we are in an uninhabited district.«
B042C009V013	42	9	13	»You yourselves,« He said, »must give them food.«»We have nothing,« they replied, »but five loaves and a couple of fish, unless indeed we were to go and buy provisions for all this host of people.«
B042C009V014	42	9	14	(For there were about 5,000 adult men.) But He said to His disciples, »Make them sit down in parties of about fifty each.«
B042C009V015	42	9	15	They did so, making them all, without exception, sit down.
B042C009V016	42	9	16	Then He took the five loaves and the two fish, and looking up to Heaven He blessed them and broke them into portions which He gave to the disciples to distribute to the people.
B042C009V017	42	9	17	So they ate and were fully satisfied, all of them; and what they had remaining over was gathered up, twelve baskets of fragments.
B042C009V018	42	9	18	One day when He was praying by Himself the disciples were present; and He asked them, »Who do the people say that I am?«
B042C009V019	42	9	19	»John the Baptist,« they replied; »but others say Elijah; and others that some one of the ancient Prophets has come back to life.«
B042C009V020	42	9	20	»But you,« He asked, »who do you say that I am?«»God's Anointed One,« replied Peter.
B042C009V021	42	9	21	And Jesus strictly forbad them to tell this to any one;
B042C009V022	42	9	22	and He said, »The Son of Man must suffer much cruelty, be rejected by the Elders and High Priests and Scribes, and be put to death, and on the third day be raised to life again.«
B042C009V023	42	9	23	And He said to all, »If any one is desirous of following me, let him ignore self and take up his cross day by day, and so be my follower.
B042C009V024	42	9	24	For whoever desires to save his life shall lose it, and whoever loses his life for my sake shall save it.
B042C009V025	42	9	25	Why, what benefit is it to a man to have gained the whole world, but to have lost or forfeited his own self.
B042C009V026	42	9	26	For whoever shall have been ashamed of me and my teachings, of him the Son of Man will be ashamed when He comes in His own and the Father's glory and in that of the holy angels.
B042C009V027	42	9	27	I tell you truly that there are some of those who stand here who will certainly not taste death till they have seen the Kingdom of God.«
B042C009V028	42	9	28	It was about eight days after this that Jesus, taking with Him Peter, John, and James, went up the mountain to pray.
B042C009V029	42	9	29	And while He was praying the appearance of His face underwent a change, and His clothing became white and radiant.
B042C009V030	42	9	30	And suddenly there were two men conversing with Him, who were Moses and Elijah.
B042C009V031	42	9	31	They came in glory, and kept speaking about His death, which He was so soon to undergo in Jerusalem.
B042C009V032	42	9	32	Now Peter and the others were weighed down with sleep; but, keeping themselves awake all through, they saw His glory, and the two men standing with Him.
B042C009V033	42	9	33	And when they were preparing to depart from Him, Peter said to Jesus, »Rabbi, we are thankful to you that we are here. Let us put up three tents–one for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah.« He did not know what he was saying.
B042C009V034	42	9	34	But while he was thus speaking, there came a cloud which spread over them; and they were awe-struck when they had entered into the cloud.
B042C009V035	42	9	35	Then there came a voice from within the cloud:»This is My Son, My Chosen One: listen to Him.«
B042C009V036	42	9	36	After this voice had spoken, Jesus was found alone. They kept it to themselves, and said not a word to any one at that time about what they had seen.
B042C009V037	42	9	37	On the following day, when they were come down from the mountain, a great crowd came to meet Him;
B042C009V038	42	9	38	and a man from the crowd called out, »Rabbi, I beg you to pity my son, for he is my only child.
B042C009V039	42	9	39	At times a spirit seizes him and he suddenly cries out. It convulses him, and makes him foam at the mouth, and does not leave him till it has well-nigh covered him with bruises.
B042C009V040	42	9	40	I entreated your disciples to expel the spirit, but they could not.«
B042C009V041	42	9	41	»O unbelieving and perverse generation!« replied Jesus; »how long shall I be with you and bear with you? Bring your son here to me.«
B042C009V042	42	9	42	Now while the youth was coming, the spirit dashed him to the ground and cruelly convulsed him. But Jesus rebuked the foul spirit, and cured the youth and gave him back to his father.
B042C009V043	42	9	43	And all were awe-struck at the mighty power of God. And while every one was expressing wonder at all that He was doing, He said to his disciples,
B042C009V044	42	9	44	»As for you, store these my sayings in your memory; for, before long, the Son of Man will be betrayed into the hands of men.«
B042C009V045	42	9	45	But they did not understand His meaning: it was veiled from them that they might not perceive it, and they were afraid to ask Him about it.
B042C009V046	42	9	46	Now there arose a dispute among them, which of them was to be the greatest.
B042C009V047	42	9	47	And Jesus, knowing the reasoning that was in their hearts, took a young child and made him stand by His side
B042C009V048	42	9	48	and said to them, »Whoever for my sake receives this little child, receives me; and whoever receives me, receives Him who sent me. For the lowliest among you all–he is the greatest.«
B042C009V049	42	9	49	»Rabbi,« replied John, »we have seen a man making use of your name to expel demons; and we forbad him, because he does not come with us.«
B042C009V050	42	9	50	»Do not forbid him,« said Jesus, »for he who is not against you is on your side.«
B042C009V051	42	9	51	Now when the time drew near for Him to be received up again into Heaven, He proceeded with fixed purpose towards Jerusalem, and sent messengers before Him.
B042C009V052	42	9	52	They went and entered a village of the Samaritans to make ready for Him.
B042C009V053	42	9	53	But the people there would not receive Him, because He was evidently going to Jerusalem.
B042C009V054	42	9	54	When the disciples James and John saw this, they said, »Master, do you wish us to order fire to come down from Heaven and consume them?«
B042C009V055	42	9	55	But He turned and rebuked them.
B042C009V056	42	9	56	And they went to another village.
B042C009V057	42	9	57	And, as they proceeded on their way, a man came to Him and said, »I will follow you wherever you go.«
B042C009V058	42	9	58	»The foxes have holes,« said Jesus, »and the birds of the air have nests; but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay His head.«
B042C009V059	42	9	59	»Follow me,« He said to another. »Master,« the man replied, »allow me first to go and bury my father.«
B042C009V060	42	9	60	»Leave the dead,« Jesus rejoined, »to bury their own dead; but you must go and announce far and wide the coming of the Kingdom of God.«
B042C009V061	42	9	61	»Master,« said yet another, »I will follow you; but allow me first to go and say good-bye to my friends at home.«
B042C009V062	42	9	62	Jesus answered him, »No one who has put his hand to the plough, and then looks behind him, is fit for the Kingdom of God.
B042C010V001	42	10	1	After this the Lord appointed seventy others, and sent them before Him, by twos, to go to every town or place which He Himself intended to visit.
B042C010V002	42	10	2	And He addressed them thus: »The harvest is abundant, but the reapers are few: therefore entreat the Owner of the harvest to send out more reapers into His fields. And now go.
B042C010V003	42	10	3	Remember that I am sending you out as lambs into the midst of wolves.
B042C010V004	42	10	4	Carry no purse, bag, nor change of shoes; and salute no one on your way.«
B042C010V005	42	10	5	»Whatever house you enter, first say, `Peace be to this house!'«
B042C010V006	42	10	6	And if there is a lover of peace there, your peace shall rest upon it; otherwise come back upon you.
B042C010V007	42	10	7	And in that same house stay, eating and drinking at their table; for the labourer deserves his wages. Do not move from one house to another.
B042C010V008	42	10	8	»And whatever town you come to and they receive you, eat what they put before you.«
B042C010V009	42	10	9	Cure the sick in that town, and tell them, »`The Kingdom of God is now at your door.'
B042C010V010	42	10	10	»But whatever town you come to and they will not receive you, go out into the broader streets and say,«
B042C010V011	42	10	11	»`The very dust of your town that hangs about us we wipe off as a protest. Only be sure of this, that the Kingdom of God is close at hand.'«
B042C010V012	42	10	12	»I tell you that it will be more endurable for Sodom on the great day than for that town.«
B042C010V013	42	10	13	»Alas for thee, Chorazin! Alas for thee, Bethsaida! For had the miracles been performed in Tyre and Sidon which have been performed in you, long ere now they would have repented, sitting in sackcloth and ashes.«
B042C010V014	42	10	14	However, for Tyre and Sidon it will be more endurable at the Judgement than for you.
B042C010V015	42	10	15	And thou, Capernaum, shalt thou be lifted high as Heaven? Thou shalt be driven down as low as Hades.
B042C010V016	42	10	16	»He who listens to you listens to me; and he who disregards you disregards me, and he who disregards me disregards Him who sent me.«
B042C010V017	42	10	17	When the Seventy returned, they exclaimed joyfully, »Master, even the demons submit to us when we utter your name.«
B042C010V018	42	10	18	»I saw Satan fall like a lightning-flash out of Heaven,« He replied.
B042C010V019	42	10	19	»I have given you power to tread serpents and scorpions underfoot, and to trample on all the power of the Enemy; and in no case shall anything do you harm.
B042C010V020	42	10	20	Nevertheless rejoice not at this, that the spirits submit to you; but rejoice that your names are registered in Heaven.«
B042C010V021	42	10	21	On that same occasion Jesus was filled by the Holy Spirit with rapturous joy. »I give Thee fervent thanks,« He exclaimed, »O Father, Lord of Heaven and earth, that Thou hast hidden these things from sages and men of understanding, and hast revealed them to babes. Yes, Father, for such has been Thy gracious will.
B042C010V022	42	10	22	All things are delivered to me by my Father; and no one knows who the Son is but the Father, nor who the Father is but the Son, and he to whom the Son may choose to reveal Him.«
B042C010V023	42	10	23	And He turned towards His disciples and said to them apart, »Blessed are the eyes which see what you see!
B042C010V024	42	10	24	For I tell you that many Prophets and kings have desired to see the things you see, and have not seen them, and to hear the things you hear, and have not heard them.«
B042C010V025	42	10	25	Then an expounder of the Law stood up to test Him with a question. »Rabbi,« he asked, »what shall I do to inherit the Life of the Ages?«
B042C010V026	42	10	26	»Go to the Law,« said Jesus; »what is written there? how does it read?«
B042C010V027	42	10	27	
        
B042C010V028	42	10	28	»A right answer,« said Jesus; »do that, and you shall live.«
B042C010V029	42	10	29	But he, desiring to justify himself, said, »But what is meant by my `fellow man'?«
B042C010V030	42	10	30	Jesus replied, »A man was once on his way down from Jerusalem to Jericho when he fell among robbers, who after both stripping and beating him went away, leaving him half dead.
B042C010V031	42	10	31	Now a priest happened to be going down that way, and on seeing him passed by on the other side.
B042C010V032	42	10	32	In like manner a Levite also came to the place, and seeing him passed by on the other side.
B042C010V033	42	10	33	But a certain Samaritan, being on a journey, came where he lay, and seeing him was moved with pity.
B042C010V034	42	10	34	He went to him, and dressed his wounds with oil and wine and bound them up. Then placing him on his own mule he brought him to an inn, where he bestowed every care on him.
B042C010V035	42	10	35	The next day he took out two shillings and gave them to the innkeeper. »`Take care of him,' he said, `and whatever further expense you are put to, I will repay it you at my next visit.'
B042C010V036	42	10	36	»Which of those three seems to you to have acted like a fellow man to him who fell among the robbers?«
B042C010V037	42	10	37	»The one who showed him pity,« he replied. »Go,« said Jesus, »and act in the same way.«
B042C010V038	42	10	38	As they pursued their journey He came to a certain village, where a woman named Martha welcomed Him to her house.
B042C010V039	42	10	39	She had a sister called Mary, who seated herself at the Lord's feet and listened to His teaching.
B042C010V040	42	10	40	Martha meanwhile was busy and distracted in waiting at table, and she came and said, »Master, do you not care that my sister is leaving me to do all the waiting? Tell her to assist me.«
B042C010V041	42	10	41	»Martha, Martha,« replied Jesus, »you are anxious and worried about a multitude of things;
B042C010V042	42	10	42	and yet only one thing is really necessary. Mary has chosen the good portion and she shall not be deprived of it.«
B042C011V001	42	11	1	At one place where He was praying, when He rose from His knees one of His disciples said to Him, »Master, teach us to pray, just as John taught his disciples.«
B042C011V002	42	11	2	So He said to them, »When you pray, say, `Father may Thy name be kept holy; let Thy Kingdom come;
B042C011V003	42	11	3	give us day after day our bread for the day;
B042C011V004	42	11	4	and forgive us our sins, for we ourselves also forgive every one who fails in his duty to us; and bring us not into temptation.'«
B042C011V005	42	11	5	And He said to them, »Which of you shall have a friend and shall go to him in the middle of the night and say, «`Friend, lend me three loaves of bread;
B042C011V006	42	11	6	for a friend of mine has just come to my house from a distance, and I have nothing for him to eat'?
B042C011V007	42	11	7	»And he from indoors shall answer,« `Do not pester me. The door is now barred, and I am here in bed with my children. I cannot get up and give you bread.'
B042C011V008	42	11	8	»I tell you that even if he will not rise and give him the loaves because he is his friend, at any rate because of his persistency he will rouse himself and give him as many as he requires.«
B042C011V009	42	11	9	»So I say to you, `Ask, and what you ask for shall be given to you; seek, and you shall find; knock, and the door shall be opened to you.'«
B042C011V010	42	11	10	For every one who asks, receives; and he who seeks, finds; and to him who knocks, the door shall be opened.
