B042C014V035	42	14	35	Neither for land nor dunghill is it of any use; they throw it away. Listen, every one who has ears to listen with!«
B042C015V001	42	15	1	Now the tax-gatherers and the notorious sinners were everywhere in the habit of coming close to Him to listen to Him;
B042C015V002	42	15	2	and this led the Pharisees and the Scribes indignantly to complain, saying, »He gives a welcome to notorious sinners, and joins them at their meals!«
B042C015V003	42	15	3	So in figurative language He asked them,
B042C015V004	42	15	4	»Which of you men, if he has a hundred sheep and has lost one of them, does not leave the ninety-nine in their pasture and go in search of the lost one till he finds it?«
B042C015V005	42	15	5	And when he has found it, he lifts it on his shoulder, glad at heart.
B042C015V006	42	15	6	Then coming home he calls his friends and neighbours together, and says, `Congratulate me, for I have found my sheep–the one I had lost.'
B042C015V007	42	15	7	I tell you that in the same way there will be rejoicing in Heaven over one repentant sinner–more rejoicing than over ninety-nine blameless persons who have no need of repentance.
B042C015V008	42	15	8	»Or what woman who has ten silver coins, if she loses one of them, does not light a lamp and sweep the house and search carefully till she finds it?«
B042C015V009	42	15	9	And when she has found it, she calls together her friends and neighbours, and says, »`Congratulate me, for I have found the coin which I had lost.'
B042C015V010	42	15	10	»I tell you that in the same way there is rejoicing in the presence of the angels of God over one repentant sinner.«
B042C015V011	42	15	11	He went on to say, »There was a man who had two sons.
B042C015V012	42	15	12	The younger of them said to his father, »`Father, give me the share of the property that comes to me.' «So he divided his wealth between them.
B042C015V013	42	15	13	No long time afterwards the younger son got all together and travelled to a distant country, where he wasted his money in debauchery and excess.
B042C015V014	42	15	14	At last, when he had spent everything, there came a terrible famine throughout that country, and he began to feel the pinch of want.
B042C015V015	42	15	15	So he went and hired himself to one of the inhabitants of that country, who sent him on to his farm to tend swine;
B042C015V016	42	15	16	and he longed to make a hearty meal of the pods the swine were eating, but no one gave him any.
B042C015V017	42	15	17	»But on coming to himself he said,« `How many of my father's hired men have more bread than they want, while I here am dying of hunger!
B042C015V018	42	15	18	I will rise and go to my father, and will say to him, Father, I have sinned against Heaven and before you:
B042C015V019	42	15	19	I no longer deserve to be called a son of yours: treat me as one of your hired men.'
B042C015V020	42	15	20	»So he rose and came to his father. But while he was still a long way off, his father saw him and pitied him, and ran and threw his arms round his neck and kissed him tenderly.«
B042C015V021	42	15	21	»`Father,' cried the son, `I have sinned against Heaven and before you: no longer do I deserve to be called a son of yours.'«
B042C015V022	42	15	22	»But the father said to his servants,« `Fetch a good coat quickly –the best one– and put it on him; and bring a ring for his finger and shoes for his feet.
B042C015V023	42	15	23	Fetch the fat calf and kill it, and let us feast and enjoy ourselves;
B042C015V024	42	15	24	for my son here was dead and has come to life again: he was lost and has been found.' »And they began to be merry.
B042C015V025	42	15	25	»Now his elder son was out on the farm; and when he returned and came near home, he heard music and dancing.«
B042C015V026	42	15	26	Then he called one of the lads to him and asked what all this meant.
B042C015V027	42	15	27	»`Your brother has come,' he replied; `and your father has had the fat calf killed, because he has got him home safe and sound.'«
B042C015V028	42	15	28	»Then he was angry and would not go in. But his father came out and entreated him.«
B042C015V029	42	15	29	»`All these years,' replied the son, `I have been slaving for you, and I have never at any time disobeyed any of your orders, and yet you have never given me so much as a kid, for me to enjoy myself with my friends;«
B042C015V030	42	15	30	but now that this son of yours is come who has eaten up your property among his bad women, you have killed the fat calf for him.'
B042C015V031	42	15	31	»`You my dear son,' said the father, `are always with me, and all that is mine is also yours.«
B042C015V032	42	15	32	We are bound to make merry and rejoice, for this brother of yours was dead and has come back to life, he was lost and has been found.'«
B042C016V001	42	16	1	He said also to His disciples: »There was a rich man who had a steward, about whom a report was brought to him, that he was wasting his property.
B042C016V002	42	16	2	He called him and said, »`What is this I hear about you? Render an account of your stewardship, for I cannot let you hold it any longer.'
B042C016V003	42	16	3	»Then the steward said within himself,« `What am I to do? For my master is taking away the stewardship from me. I am not strong enough for field labour: to beg, I should be ashamed.
B042C016V004	42	16	4	I see what to do, in order that when I am discharged from the stewardship they may give me a home in their own houses.'
B042C016V005	42	16	5	»So he called all his master's debtors, one by one, and asked the first, `How much are you in debt to my master?'«
B042C016V006	42	16	6	»`A hundred firkins of oil,' he replied.« `Here is your account,' said the steward: `sit down quickly and change it into fifty firkins.'
B042C016V007	42	16	7	»To a second he said,« `And how much do you owe?' »`A hundred quarters of wheat,' was the answer.« »`Here is your account,' said he: `change it into eighty quarters.'«
B042C016V008	42	16	8	»And the master praised the dishonest steward for his shrewdness; for, in relation to their own contemporaries, the men of this age are shrewder than the sons of Light.«
B042C016V009	42	16	9	»But I charge you, so to use the wealth which is ever tempting to dishonesty as to win friends who, when it fails, shall welcome you to the tents that never perish.«
B042C016V010	42	16	10	The man who is honest in a very small matter is honest in a great one also; and he who is dishonest in a very small matter is dishonest in a great one also.
B042C016V011	42	16	11	If therefore you have not proved yourselves faithful in dealing with the wealth that is tainted with fraud, who will entrust to you the true good?
B042C016V012	42	16	12	And if you have not been faithful in dealing with that which is not your own, who will give you that which is your own?
B042C016V013	42	16	13	»No servant can be in bondage to two masters. For either he will hate one and love the other, or else he will cling fast to one and scorn the other. You cannot be bondservants both of God and of gold.«
B042C016V014	42	16	14	To all this the Pharisees listened, bitterly jeering at Him; for they were lovers of money.
B042C016V015	42	16	15	»You are they,« He said to them, »who boast of their own goodness before men, but God sees your hearts; for that which holds a proud position among men is detestable in God's sight.
B042C016V016	42	16	16	The Law and the Prophets continued until John came: from that time the Good News of the Kingdom of God has been spreading, and all classes have been forcing their way into it.
B042C016V017	42	16	17	But it is easier for earth and sky to pass away than for one smallest detail of the Law to fall to the ground.
B042C016V018	42	16	18	Every man who divorces his wife and marries another commits adultery; and he who marries her when so divorced from her husband commits adultery.
B042C016V019	42	16	19	»There was once a rich man who habitually arrayed himself in purple and fine linen, and enjoyed a splendid banquet every day,
B042C016V020	42	16	20	while at his outer door there lay a beggar, Lazarus by name,
B042C016V021	42	16	21	covered with sores and longing to make a full meal off the scraps flung on the floor from the rich man's table. Nay, the dogs, too, used to come and lick his sores.«
B042C016V022	42	16	22	»But in course of time the beggar died; and he was carried by the angels into Abraham's bosom. The rich man also died, and had a funeral.«
B042C016V023	42	16	23	And in Hades, being in torment, he looked and saw Abraham in the far distance, and Lazarus resting in his arms.
B042C016V024	42	16	24	So he cried aloud, and said, »`Father Abraham, take pity on me and send Lazarus to dip the tip of his finger in water and cool my tongue, for I am in agony in this flame.'
B042C016V025	42	16	25	»`Remember, my child,' said Abraham, `that you had all your good things during your lifetime, and that Lazarus in like manner had his bad things. But, now and here, he is receiving consolation and you are in agony.«
B042C016V026	42	16	26	And, besides all this, a vast chasm is immovably fixed between us and you, put there in order that those who desire to cross from this side to you may not be able, nor any be able to cross over from your side to us.'
B042C016V027	42	16	27	»`I entreat you then, father,' said he, `to send him to my father's house.«
B042C016V028	42	16	28	For I have five brothers. Let him earnestly warn them, lest they also come to this place of torment.'
B042C016V029	42	16	29	»`They have Moses and the Prophets,' replied Abraham; `let them hear them.'«
B042C016V030	42	16	30	»`No, father Abraham,' he pleaded; `but if some one goes to them from the dead, they will repent.'«
B042C016V031	42	16	31	»`If they are deaf to Moses and the Prophets,' replied Abraham, `they would not be led to believe even if some one should rise from the dead.'«
B042C017V001	42	17	1	Jesus said to His disciples, »It is inevitable that causes of stumbling should come; but alas for him through whom they come!
B042C017V002	42	17	2	It would be well for him if, with a millstone round his neck, he were lying at the bottom of the sea, rather than that he should cause even one of these little ones to fall.
B042C017V003	42	17	3	Be on your guard. »If your brother acts wrongly, reprove him; and if he is sorry, forgive him;
B042C017V004	42	17	4	and if seven times in a day he acts wrongly towards you, and seven times turns again to you and says, `I am sorry,' you must forgive him.«
B042C017V005	42	17	5	And the Apostles said to the Lord, »Give us faith.«
B042C017V006	42	17	6	»If your faith,« replied the Lord, »is like a mustard seed, you might command this black-mulberry-tree, `Tear up your roots and plant yourself in the sea,' and instantly it would obey you.
B042C017V007	42	17	7	But which of you who has a servant ploughing, or tending sheep, will say to him when he comes in from the farm, `Come at once and take your place at table,'
B042C017V008	42	17	8	and will not rather say to him, `Get my dinner ready, make yourself tidy, and wait upon me till I have finished my dinner, and then you shall have yours'?
B042C017V009	42	17	9	Does he thank the servant for obeying his orders?
B042C017V010	42	17	10	So you also, when you have obeyed all the orders given you, must say, »`There is no merit in our service: what we have done is only what we were in duty bound to do.'«
B042C017V011	42	17	11	As they pursued their journey to Jerusalem, He passed through Samaria and Galilee.
B042C017V012	42	17	12	And as He entered a certain village, ten men met Him who were lepers and stood at a distance.
B042C017V013	42	17	13	In loud voices they cried out, »Jesus, Rabbi, take pity on us.«
B042C017V014	42	17	14	Perceiving this, He said to them, »Go and show yourselves to the Priests.« And while on their way to do this they were made clean.
B042C017V015	42	17	15	One of them, seeing that he was cured, came back, adoring and praising God in a loud voice,
B042C017V016	42	17	16	and he threw himself at the feet of Jesus, thanking Him. He was a Samaritan.
B042C017V017	42	17	17	»Were not all ten made clean?« Jesus asked; »but where are the nine?
B042C017V018	42	17	18	Have none been found to come back and give glory to God except this foreigner?«
B042C017V019	42	17	19	And He said to him, »Rise and go: your faith has cured you.«
B042C017V020	42	17	20	Being asked by the Pharisees when the Kingdom of God was coming, He answered, »The Kingdom of God does not so come that you can stealthily watch for it.
B042C017V021	42	17	21	Nor will they say, `See here!' or `See there!' –for the Kingdom of God is within you.«
B042C017V022	42	17	22	Then, turning to His disciples, He said, »There will come a time when you will wish you could see a single one of the days of the Son of Man, but will not see one.
B042C017V023	42	17	23	And they will say to you, `See there!' `See here!' Do not start off and go in pursuit.
B042C017V024	42	17	24	For just as the lightning, when it flashes, shines from one part of the horizon to the opposite part, so will the Son of Man be on His day.
B042C017V025	42	17	25	But first He must endure much suffering, and be rejected by the present generation.
B042C017V026	42	17	26	»And as it was in the time of Noah, so will it also be in the time of the Son of Man.«
B042C017V027	42	17	27	Men were eating and drinking, taking wives and giving wives, up to the very day on which Noah entered the Ark, and the Deluge came and destroyed them all.
B042C017V028	42	17	28	The same was true in the time of Lot: they were eating and drinking, buying and selling, planting and building;
B042C017V029	42	17	29	but on the day that Lot left Sodom, God rained fire and brimstone from the sky and destroyed them all.
B042C017V030	42	17	30	Exactly so will it be on the day that the veil is lifted from the Son of Man.
B042C017V031	42	17	31	»On that day, if a man is on the roof and his property indoors, let him not go down to fetch it; and, in the same way, he who is in the field, let him not turn back.«
B042C017V032	42	17	32	Remember Lot's wife.
B042C017V033	42	17	33	Any man who makes it his object to keep his own life safe, will lose it; but whoever loses his life will preserve it.
B042C017V034	42	17	34	On that night, I tell you, there will be two men in one bed: one will be taken away and the other left behind.
B042C017V035	42	17	35	There will be two women turning the mill together: one will be taken away and the other left behind.«
B042C017V036	42	17	36	[]
B042C017V037	42	17	37	»Where, Master?« they inquired. »Where the dead body is,« He replied, »there also will the vultures flock together.«
B042C018V001	42	18	1	He also taught them by a parable that they must always pray and never lose heart.
B042C018V002	42	18	2	»In a certain town,« He said, »there was a judge who had no fear of God and no respect for man.
B042C018V003	42	18	3	And in the same town was a widow who repeatedly came and entreated him, saying, »`Give me justice and stop my oppressor.'
B042C018V004	42	18	4	»For a time he would not, but afterwards he said to himself,« `Though I have neither reverence for God nor respect for man,
B042C018V005	42	18	5	yet because she annoys me I will give her justice, to prevent her from constantly coming to pester me.'«
B042C018V006	42	18	6	And the Lord said, »Hear those words of the unjust judge.
B042C018V007	42	18	7	And will not God avenge the wrongs of His own People who cry aloud to Him day and night, although He seems slow in taking action on their behalf?
B042C018V008	42	18	8	Yes, He will soon avenge their wrongs. Yet, when the Son of Man comes, will He find faith on earth?«
B042C018V009	42	18	9	And to some who relied on themselves as being righteous men, and looked down upon all others, He addressed this parable.
B042C018V010	42	18	10	»Two men went up to the Temple to pray,« He said; »one being a Pharisee and the other a tax-gatherer.
B042C018V011	42	18	11	The Pharisee, standing erect, prayed as follows by himself: »`O God, I thank Thee that I am not like other people–I am not a thief nor a cheat nor an adulterer, nor do I even resemble this tax-gatherer.
B042C018V012	42	18	12	I fast twice a week. I pay the tithe on all my gains.'
B042C018V013	42	18	13	»But the tax-gatherer, standing far back, would not so much as lift his eyes to Heaven, but kept beating his breast and saying,« `O God, be reconciled to me, sinner that I am.'
B042C018V014	42	18	14	»I tell you that this man went home more thoroughly absolved from guilt than the other; for every one who uplifts himself will be humbled, but he who humbles himself will be uplifted.«
B042C018V015	42	18	15	On one occasion people also brought with them their infants, for Him to touch them; but the disciples, noticing this, proceeded to find fault with them.
B042C018V016	42	18	16	Jesus however called the infants to Him. »Let the little children come to me,« He said; »do not hinder them; for it is to those who are childlike that the Kingdom of God belongs.
B042C018V017	42	18	17	I tell you in solemn truth that, whoever does not receive the Kingdom of God like a little child will certainly not enter it.«
B042C018V018	42	18	18	The question was put to Him by a Ruler:»Good Rabbi, what shall I do to inherit the Life of the Ages?«
B042C018V019	42	18	19	»Why do you call me good?« replied Jesus; »there is no one good but One, namely God.
B042C018V020	42	18	20	You know the Commandments: 
B042C018V021	42	18	21	»All of those,« he replied, »I have kept from my youth.«
B042C018V022	42	18	22	On receiving this answer Jesus said to him, »There is still one thing wanting in you. Sell everything you possess and give the money to the poor, and you shall have wealth in Heaven; and then come, follow me.«
B042C018V023	42	18	23	But on hearing these words he was deeply sorrowful, for he was exceedingly rich.
B042C018V024	42	18	24	Jesus saw his sorrow, and said, »With how hard a struggle do the possessors of riches ever enter the Kingdom of God!
B042C018V025	42	18	25	Why, it is easier for a camel to go through a needle's eye than for a rich man to enter the Kingdom of God.«
B042C018V026	42	18	26	»Who then can be saved?« exclaimed the hearers.
B042C018V027	42	18	27	»Things impossible with man,« He replied, »are possible with God.«
B042C018V028	42	18	28	Then Peter said, »See, we have given up our homes and have followed you.«
B042C018V029	42	18	29	»I solemnly tell you,« replied Jesus, »that there is no one who has left house or wife, or brothers or parents or children, for the sake of God's Kingdom,
B042C018V030	42	18	30	who shall not certainly receive many times as much in this life, and in the age that is coming the Life of the Ages.«
B042C018V031	42	18	31	Then He drew the Twelve to Him and said, »See, we are going up to Jerusalem, and everything written in the Prophets which refers to the Son of Man will be fulfilled.
B042C018V032	42	18	32	For He will be given up to the Gentiles, and be mocked, outraged and spit upon.
B042C018V033	42	18	33	They will scourge Him and put Him to death, and on the third day He will rise to life again.«
B042C018V034	42	18	34	Nothing of this did they understand. The words were a mystery to them, nor could they see what He meant.
B042C018V035	42	18	35	As Jesus came near to Jericho, there was a blind man sitting by the way-side begging.
B042C018V036	42	18	36	He heard a crowd of people going past, and inquired what it all meant.
B042C018V037	42	18	37	»Jesus the Nazarene is passing by,« they told him.
B042C018V038	42	18	38	Then, at the top of his voice, he cried out, »Jesus, son of David, take pity on me.«
B042C018V039	42	18	39	Those in front reproved him and tried to silence him; but he continued shouting, louder than ever, »Son of David, take pity on me.«
B042C018V040	42	18	40	At length Jesus stopped and desired them to bring the man to Him; and when he had come close to Him He asked him,
B042C018V041	42	18	41	»What shall I do for you?« »Sir,« he replied, »let me recover my sight.«
B042C018V042	42	18	42	»Recover your sight,« said Jesus:»your faith has cured you.«
B042C018V043	42	18	43	No sooner were the words spoken than the man regained his sight and followed Jesus, giving glory to God; and all the people, seeing it, gave praise to God.
B042C019V001	42	19	1	So He entered Jericho and was passing through the town.
B042C019V002	42	19	2	There was a man there called Zacchaeus, who was the local surveyor of taxes, and was wealthy.
B042C019V003	42	19	3	He was anxious to see what sort of man Jesus was; but he could not because of the crowd, for he was short in stature.
B042C019V004	42	19	4	So he ran on in front and climbed up a mulberry tree to see Him; for He was about to pass that way.
B042C019V005	42	19	5	As soon as Jesus came to the place, He looked up and said to him, »Zacchaeus, come down quickly, for I must stay at your house to-day.«
B042C019V006	42	19	6	So he came down in haste, and welcomed Him joyfully.
B042C019V007	42	19	7	When they all saw this, they began to complain with indignation. »He has gone in to be the guest of a notorious sinner!« they said.
B042C019V008	42	19	8	Zacchaeus however stood up, and addressing the Lord said, »Here and now, Master, I give half my property to the poor, and if I have unjustly exacted money from any man, I pledge myself to repay to him four times the amount.«
B042C019V009	42	19	9	Turning towards him, Jesus replied, »To-day salvation has come to this house, seeing that he too is a son of Abraham.
B042C019V010	42	19	10	For the Son of Man has come to seek and to save that which was lost.«
B042C019V011	42	19	11	As they were listening to His words, He went on to teach them by a parable, because He was near to Jerusalem and they supposed that the Kingdom of God was going to appear immediately.
B042C019V012	42	19	12	So He said to them, »A man of noble family travelled to a distant country to obtain the rank of king, and to return.
B042C019V013	42	19	13	And he called ten of his servants and gave each of them a pound, instructing them to trade with the money during his absence.
B042C019V014	42	19	14	»Now his countrymen hated him, and sent a deputation after him to say, `We are not willing that he should become our king.'«
B042C019V015	42	19	15	And upon his return, after he had obtained the sovereignty, he ordered those servants to whom he had given the money to be summoned before him, that he might learn their success in trading.
B042C019V016	42	19	16	»So the first came and said,« `Sir, your pound has produced ten pounds more.'
B042C019V017	42	19	17	»`Well done, good servant,' he replied; `because you have been faithful in a very small matter, be in authority over ten towns.'«
B042C019V018	42	19	18	»The second came, and said,« `Your pound, Sir, has produced five pounds.'
B042C019V019	42	19	19	»So he said to this one also,« `And you, be the governor of five towns.'
B042C019V020	42	19	20	»The next came.« `Sir,' he said, `here is your pound, which I have kept wrapt up in a cloth.
B042C019V021	42	19	21	For I was afraid of you, because you are a severe man: you take up what you did not lay down, and you reap what you did not sow.'
B042C019V022	42	19	22	»`By your own words,' he replied, `I will judge you, you bad servant. You knew me to be a severe man, taking up what I did not lay down, and reaping what I did not sow:«
B042C019V023	42	19	23	why then did you not put my money into a bank, that when I came I might have received it back with interest?
B042C019V024	42	19	24	»And he said to those who stood by,« `Take the pound from him and give it to him who has the ten pounds.'
B042C019V025	42	19	25	(They said to him, »`Sir, he already has ten pounds.')
B042C019V026	42	19	26	»`I tell you that to every one who has anything, more shall be given; and from him who has not anything, even what he has shall be taken away.
B042C019V027	42	19	27	But as for those enemies of mine who were unwilling that I should become their king, bring them here, and cut them to pieces in my presence.'«
B042C019V028	42	19	28	After thus speaking, He journeyed onward, proceeding up to Jerusalem.
B042C019V029	42	19	29	And when he was come near Bethphage and Bethany, at the Mount called the Oliveyard, He sent two of the disciples on in front,
B042C019V030	42	19	30	saying to them, »Go into the village facing you. On entering it you will find an ass's foal tied up which no one has ever yet ridden: untie it, and bring it here.
B042C019V031	42	19	31	And if any one asks you, `Why are you untying the colt?' simply say, `The Master needs it.'«
B042C019V032	42	19	32	So those who were sent went and found things as He had told them.
B042C019V033	42	19	33	And while they were untying the colt the owners called out, »Why are you untying the colt?«
B042C019V034	42	19	34	and they replied, »The Master needs it.«
B042C019V035	42	19	35	Then they brought it to Jesus, and after throwing their outer garments on the colt they placed Jesus on it.
B042C019V036	42	19	36	So He rode on, while they carpeted the road with their garments.
B042C019V037	42	19	37	And when He was now getting near Jerusalem, and descending the Mount of Olives, the whole multitude of the disciples began in their joy to praise God in loud voices for all the mighty deeds they had witnessed.
B042C019V038	42	19	38	
        
B042C019V039	42	19	39	Thereupon some of the Pharisees in the crowd appealed to Him, saying, »Rabbi, reprove your disciples.«
B042C019V040	42	19	40	»I tell you,« He replied, »that if 
B042C019V041	42	19	41	When He came into full view of the city, He wept aloud over it, and exclaimed,
B042C019V042	42	19	42	»O that at this time thou hadst known –yes even thou– what makes peace possible! But now it is hid from thine eyes.
B042C019V043	42	19	43	For the time is coming upon thee when thy foes will throw up around thee earthworks and a wall, investing thee and hemming thee in on every side.
B042C019V044	42	19	44	And they will dash thee to the ground and thy children within thee, and will not leave one stone upon another within thee; because thou hast not recognized the time of thy visitation.«
B042C019V045	42	19	45	Then Jesus entered the Temple and proceeded to drive out the dealers.
B042C019V046	42	19	46	»It is written,« He said, 
B042C019V047	42	19	47	And day after day He taught in the Temple, while the High Priests and the Scribes were devising some means of destroying Him, as were also the leading men of the people.
B042C019V048	42	19	48	But they could not find any way of doing it, for the people all hung upon His lips.
B042C020V001	42	20	1	On one of those days while He was teaching the people in the Temple and proclaiming the Good News, the High Priests came upon Him, and the Scribes,
B042C020V002	42	20	2	together with the Elders, and they asked Him, »Tell us, By what authority are you doing these things? And who is it that gave you this authority?«
B042C020V003	42	20	3	»I also will put a question to you,« He said;
B042C020V004	42	20	4	»was John's baptism of Heavenly or of human origin?«
B042C020V005	42	20	5	So they debated the matter with one another. »If we say `Heavenly,'« they argued, »he will say, `Why did you not believe him?'
B042C020V006	42	20	6	And if we say, `human,' the people will all stone us; for they are thoroughly convinced that John was a Prophet.«
B042C020V007	42	20	7	And they answered that they did not know the origin of it.
B042C020V008	42	20	8	»Nor will I tell you,« said Jesus, »by what authority I do these things.«
B042C020V009	42	20	9	Then He proceeded to speak a parable to the people. »There was a man,« He said, »who planted a vineyard, let it out to vine-dressers, and went abroad for a considerable time.
B042C020V010	42	20	10	At vintage-time he sent a servant to the vine-dressers, for them to give him a share of the crop; but the vine-dressers beat him cruelly and sent him away empty-handed.
B042C020V011	42	20	11	Then he sent a second servant; and him too they beat and ill treated and sent away empty-handed.
B042C020V012	42	20	12	Then again he sent a third; and this one also they wounded and drove away.
B042C020V013	42	20	13	Then the owner of the vineyard said, »`What am I to do? I will send my son–my dearly-loved son: they will probably respect him.'
B042C020V014	42	20	14	»But when the vine-dressers saw him, they discussed the matter with one another, and said,« `This is the heir: let us kill him, that the inheritance may be ours.'
B042C020V015	42	20	15	»So they turned him out of the vineyard and murdered him. What then will the owner of the vineyard do to them?«
B042C020V016	42	20	16	He will come and put these vine-dressers to death, and give the vineyard to others.« »God forbid!« exclaimed the hearers.
B042C020V017	42	20	17	He looked at them and said, »What then does that mean which is written, 
B042C020V018	42	20	18	Every one who falls on that stone will be severely hurt, but on whomsoever it falls, he will be utterly crushed.«
B042C020V019	42	20	19	At this the Scribes and the High Priests wanted to lay hands on Him, then and there; only they were afraid of the people. For they saw that in this parable He had referred to them.
B042C020V020	42	20	20	So, after impatiently watching their opportunity, they sent spies who were to act the part of good and honest men, that they might fasten on some expression of His, so as to hand Him over to the ruling power and the Governor's authority.
B042C020V021	42	20	21	So they put a question to Him. »Rabbi,« they said, »we know that you say and teach what is right and that you make no distinctions between one man and another, but teach God's way truly.
B042C020V022	42	20	22	Is it allowable to pay a tax to Caesar, or not?«
B042C020V023	42	20	23	But He saw through their knavery and replied,
B042C020V024	42	20	24	»Show me a shilling; whose likeness and inscription does it bear?« »Caesar's,« they said.
B042C020V025	42	20	25	»Pay therefore,« He replied, »what is Caesar's to Caesar–and what is God's to God.«
B042C020V026	42	20	26	There was nothing here that they could lay hold of before the people, and marvelling at His answer they said no more.
B042C020V027	42	20	27	Next some of the Sadducees came forward (who deny that there is a Resurrection), and they asked Him,
B042C020V028	42	20	28	»Rabbi, Moses made it a law for us that if a man's brother should die, leaving a wife but no children, the man shall marry the widow and raise up a family for his brother.«
B042C020V029	42	20	29	Now there were seven brothers. The first of them took a wife and died childless.
B042C020V030	42	20	30	The second and the third also took her;
B042C020V031	42	20	31	and all seven, having done the same, left no children when they died.
B042C020V032	42	20	32	Finally the woman also died.
B042C020V033	42	20	33	The woman, then –at the Resurrection– whose wife shall she be? for they all seven married her.«
B042C020V034	42	20	34	»The men of this age,« replied Jesus, »marry, and the women are given in marriage.
B042C020V035	42	20	35	But as for those who shall have been deemed worthy to find a place in that other age and in the Resurrection from among the dead, the men do not marry and the women are not given in marriage.
B042C020V036	42	20	36	For indeed they cannot die again; they are like angels, and are sons of God through being sons of the Resurrection.
B042C020V037	42	20	37	But that the dead rise to life even Moses clearly implies in the passage about the Bush, where he calls the Lord 
B042C020V038	42	20	38	He is not a God of dead, but of living men, for to Him are all living.«
B042C020V039	42	20	39	Then some of the Scribes replied, »Rabbi, you have spoken well.«
B042C020V040	42	20	40	From that time, however, no one ventured to challenge Him with a single question.
B042C020V041	42	20	41	But He asked them, »How is it they say that the Christ is a son of David?
B042C020V042	42	20	42	Why, David himself says in the Book of Psalms, 
B042C020V043	42	20	43	
        
B042C020V044	42	20	44	»David himself therefore calls Him Lord, and how can He be his son?«
B042C020V045	42	20	45	Then, in the hearing of all the people, He said to the disciples,
B042C020V046	42	20	46	»Beware of the Scribes, who like to walk about in long robes, and love to be bowed to in places of public resort and to occupy the best seats in the synagogues or at a dinner party;
B042C020V047	42	20	47	who swallow up the property of widows and mask their wickedness by making long prayers. They will be punished far more severely than others.«
B042C021V001	42	21	1	Looking up He saw the people throwing their gifts into the Treasury–the rich people.
B042C021V002	42	21	2	He also saw a poor widow dropping in two farthings,
B042C021V003	42	21	3	and He said, »In truth I tell you that this widow, so poor, has thrown in more than any of them.
B042C021V004	42	21	4	For from what they could well spare they have all of them contributed to the offerings, but she in her need has thrown in all she had to live on.«
B042C021V005	42	21	5	When some were remarking about the Temple, how it was embellished with beautiful stones and dedicated gifts, He said,
B042C021V006	42	21	6	»As to these things which you now admire, the time is coming when there will not be one stone left here upon another which will not be pulled down.«
B042C021V007	42	21	7	»Rabbi, when will this be?« they asked Him, »and what will be the token given when these things are about to take place?«
B042C021V008	42	21	8	»See to it,« He replied, »that you are not misled; for many will come assuming my name and professing, `I am He,' or saying, `The time is close at hand.' Do not go and follow them.
B042C021V009	42	21	9	But when you hear of wars and turmoils, be not afraid; for these things must happen first, but the end does not come immediately.«
B042C021V010	42	21	10	Then He said to them, 
B042C021V011	42	21	11	And there will be great earthquakes, and in places famines and pestilence; and there will be terrible sights and wonderful tokens from Heaven.
B042C021V012	42	21	12	»But before all these things happen they will lay hands on you and persecute you. They will deliver you up to synagogues and to prison, and you will be brought before kings and governors for my sake.«
B042C021V013	42	21	13	In the end all this will be evidence of your fidelity.
B042C021V014	42	21	14	»Make up your minds, however, not to prepare a defence beforehand,
B042C021V015	42	21	15	for I will give you utterance and wisdom which none of your opponents will be able to withstand or reply to.«
B042C021V016	42	21	16	You will be betrayed even by parents, brothers, relatives, friends; and some of you they will put to death.
B042C021V017	42	21	17	You will be the objects of universal hatred because you are called by my name;
B042C021V018	42	21	18	and yet not a hair of your heads shall perish.
B042C021V019	42	21	19	By your patient endurance you will purchase your lives.
B042C021V020	42	21	20	»But when you see Jerusalem with armies encamping round her on every side, then be certain that her overthrow is close at hand.«
B042C021V021	42	21	21	Then let those who shall be in Judaea escape to the hills; let those who are in the city leave it, and those who are in the country not enter in.
B042C021V022	42	21	22	For those are the 
B042C021V023	42	21	23	»Alas for the women who at that time are with child or who have infants; for there will be great distress in the land, and anger towards this People.«
B042C021V024	42	21	24	They will fall by the sword, or be carried off into slavery among all the Gentiles. And Jerusalem will be trampled under foot by the Gentiles, till the appointed times of the Gentiles have expired.
B042C021V025	42	21	25	»There will be signs in sun, moon, and stars; and on earth anguish among the nations in their bewilderment at the roaring of the sea and its billows;«
B042C021V026	42	21	26	while men's hearts are fainting for fear, and for anxious expectation of what is coming on the world. For 
B042C021V027	42	21	27	And then will they see the 
B042C021V028	42	21	28	But when all this is beginning to take place, grieve no longer. Lift up your heads, because your deliverance is drawing near.«
B042C021V029	42	21	29	And He spoke a parable to them. »See,« He said, »the fig-tree and all the trees.
B042C021V030	42	21	30	As soon as they have shot out their leaves, you know at a glance that summer is now near.
B042C021V031	42	21	31	So also, when you see these things happening, you may be sure that the Kingdom of God is near.
B042C021V032	42	21	32	I tell you in solemn truth that the present generation will certainly not pass away without all these things having first taken place.
B042C021V033	42	21	33	Earth and sky will pass away, but it is certain that my words will not pass away.
B042C021V034	42	21	34	»But take heed to yourselves, lest your souls be weighed down with self-indulgence and drunkenness or the anxieties of this life, and that day come upon you, suddenly, like a falling trap;
B042C021V035	42	21	35	for it will come on all dwellers on the face of the whole earth.
B042C021V036	42	21	36	But beware of slumbering; and every moment pray that you may be fully strengthened to escape from all these coming evils, and to take your stand in the presence of the Son of Man.«
B042C021V037	42	21	37	His habit at this time was to teach in the Temple by day, but to go out and spend the night on the Mount called the Oliveyard.
B042C021V038	42	21	38	And all the people came to Him in the Temple, early in the morning, to listen to Him.
B042C022V001	42	22	1	Meanwhile the Festival of the Unleavened Bread, called the Passover, was approaching,
B042C022V002	42	22	2	and the High Priests and the Scribes were contriving how to destroy Him. But they feared the people.
B042C022V003	42	22	3	Satan, however, entered into Judas (the man called Iscariot) who was one of the Twelve.
B042C022V004	42	22	4	He went and conferred with the High Priests and Commanders as to how he should deliver Him up to them.
B042C022V005	42	22	5	This gave them great pleasure, and they agreed to pay him.
B042C022V006	42	22	6	He accepted their offer, and then looked out for an opportunity to betray Him when the people were not there.
B042C022V007	42	22	7	When the day of the Unleavened Bread came –the day for the Passover lamb to be sacrificed–
B042C022V008	42	22	8	Jesus sent Peter and John with instructions. »Go,« He said, »and prepare the Passover for us, that we may eat it.«
B042C022V009	42	22	9	»Where shall we prepare it?« they asked.
B042C022V010	42	22	10	»You will no sooner have entered the city,« He replied, »than you will meet a man carrying a pitcher of water. Follow him into the house to which he goes,
B042C022V011	42	22	11	and say to the master of the house, »`The Rabbi asks you, Where is the room where I can eat the Passover with my disciples?'
B042C022V012	42	22	12	»And he will show you a large furnished room upstairs. There make your preparations.«
B042C022V013	42	22	13	So they went and found all as He had told them; and they got the Passover ready.
B042C022V014	42	22	14	When the time was come, and He had taken His place at table, and the Apostles with Him,
B042C022V015	42	22	15	He said to them, »Earnestly have I longed to eat this Passover with you before I suffer;
B042C022V016	42	22	16	for I tell you that I certainly shall not eat one again till its full meaning has been brought out in the Kingdom of God.«
B042C022V017	42	22	17	Then, having received the cup and given thanks, He said, »Take this and share it among yourselves;
B042C022V018	42	22	18	for I tell you that from this time I will never drink the produce of the vine till the Kingdom of God has come.«
B042C022V019	42	22	19	Then, taking a Passover biscuit, He gave thanks and broke it, and gave it to them, saying, »This is my body which is being given on your behalf: this do in remembrance of me.«
B042C022V020	42	22	20	He gave them the cup in like manner, when the meal was over. »This cup,« He said, »is the new Covenant ratified by my blood which is to be poured out on your behalf.
B042C022V021	42	22	21	Yet the hand of him who is betraying me is at the table with me.
B042C022V022	42	22	22	For indeed the Son of Man goes on His way–His pre-destined way; yet alas for that man who is betraying Him!«
B042C022V023	42	22	23	Thereupon they began to discuss with one another which of them it could possibly be who was about to do this.
B042C022V024	42	22	24	There arose also a dispute among them which of them should be regarded as greatest.
B042C022V025	42	22	25	But He said to them, »The kings of the Gentiles are their masters, and those who exercise authority over them are called Benefactors.
B042C022V026	42	22	26	With you it is not so; but let the greatest among you be as the younger, and the leader be like him who serves.
B042C022V027	42	22	27	For which is the greater–he who sits at table, or he who waits on him? Is it not he who sits at table? But my position among you is that of one who waits on others.
B042C022V028	42	22	28	You however have remained with me amid my trials;
B042C022V029	42	22	29	and I covenant to give you, as my Father has covenanted to give me, a Kingdom–
B042C022V030	42	22	30	so that you shall eat and drink at my table in my Kingdom, and sit on thrones as judges over the twelve tribes of Israel.
B042C022V031	42	22	31	»Simon, Simon, I tell you that Satan has obtained permission to have all of you to sift as wheat is sifted.
B042C022V032	42	22	32	But 
B042C022V033	42	22	33	»Master,« replied Peter, »with you I am ready to go both to prison and to death.«
B042C022V034	42	22	34	»I tell you, Peter,« said Jesus, »that the cock will not crow to-day till you have three times denied that you know me.«
B042C022V035	42	22	35	Then He asked them, »When I sent you out without purse or bag or shoes, was there anything you needed?«»No, nothing,« they replied.
B042C022V036	42	22	36	»But now,« said He, »let the one who has a purse take it, and he who has a bag must do the same. And let him who has no sword sell his outer garment and buy one.
B042C022V037	42	22	37	For I tell you that those words of Scripture must yet find their fulfilment in me: 
B042C022V038	42	22	38	»Master, here are two swords,« they exclaimed. »That is enough,« He replied.
B042C022V039	42	22	39	On going out, He proceeded as usual to the Mount of Olives, and His disciples followed Him.
B042C022V040	42	22	40	But when He arrived at the place, He said to them, »Pray that you may not come into temptation.«
B042C022V041	42	22	41	But He Himself withdrew from them about a stone's throw, and knelt down and prayed repeatedly, saying,
B042C022V042	42	22	42	»Father, if it be Thy will, take this cup away from me; yet not my will but Thine be done!«
B042C022V043	42	22	43	And there appeared to Him an angel from Heaven, strengthening Him;
B042C022V044	42	22	44	while He –an agony of distress having come upon Him– prayed all the more with intense earnestness, and His sweat became like clots of blood dropping on the ground.
B042C022V045	42	22	45	When He rose from his prayer and came to His disciples, He found them sleeping for sorrow.
B042C022V046	42	22	46	»Why are you sleeping?« He said; »stand up; and pray that you may not come into temptation.«
B042C022V047	42	22	47	While He was still speaking there came a crowd with Judas, already mentioned as one of the Twelve, at their head. He went up to Jesus to kiss Him.
B042C022V048	42	22	48	»Judas,« said Jesus, »are you betraying the Son of Man with a kiss?«
B042C022V049	42	22	49	Those who were about Him, seeing what was likely to happen, asked Him, »Master, shall we strike with the sword?«
B042C022V050	42	22	50	And one of them struck a blow at the High Priest's servant and cut off his right ear.
B042C022V051	42	22	51	»Permit me thus far,« said Jesus. And He touched the ear and healed it.
B042C022V052	42	22	52	Then Jesus said to the High Priests and Commanders of the Temple and Elders, who had come to arrest Him, »Have you come out as if to fight with a robber, with swords and cudgels?
B042C022V053	42	22	53	While day after day I was with you in the Temple, you did not lay hands upon me; but to you belongs this hour–and the power of darkness.«
B042C022V054	42	22	54	And they arrested Him and led Him away, and brought Him to the High Priest's house, while Peter followed a good way behind.
B042C022V055	42	22	55	And when they had lighted a fire in the middle of the court and had seated themselves in a group round it, Peter was sitting among them,
B042C022V056	42	22	56	when a maidservant saw him sitting by the fire, and, looking fixedly at him, she said, »This man also was with him.«
B042C022V057	42	22	57	But he denied it, and declared, »Woman, I do not know him.«
B042C022V058	42	22	58	Shortly afterwards a man saw him and said, »You, too, are one of them.«»No, man, I am not,« said Peter.
B042C022V059	42	22	59	After an interval of about an hour some one else stoutly maintained:»Certainly this fellow also was with him, for in fact he is a Galilaean.«
B042C022V060	42	22	60	»Man, I don't know what you mean,« replied Peter. No sooner had he spoken than a cock crowed.
B042C022V061	42	22	61	The Master turned and looked on Peter; and Peter recollected the Master's words, how He had said to him, »This very day, before the cock crows, you will disown me three times.«
B042C022V062	42	22	62	And he went out and wept aloud bitterly.
B042C022V063	42	22	63	Meanwhile the men who held Jesus in custody repeatedly beat Him in cruel sport,
B042C022V064	42	22	64	or blindfolded Him, and then challenged Him. »Prove to us,« they said, »that you are a prophet, by telling us who it was that struck you.«
B042C022V065	42	22	65	And they said many other insulting things to Him.
B042C022V066	42	22	66	As soon as it was day, the whole body of the Elders, both High Priests and Scribes, assembled. Then He was brought into their Sanhedrin, and they asked Him,
B042C022V067	42	22	67	»Are you the Christ? Tell us.« »If I tell you,« He replied, »you will certainly not believe;
B042C022V068	42	22	68	and if I ask you questions, you will certainly not answer.
B042C022V069	42	22	69	But from this time forward the Son of Man will be seated at the right hand of God's omnipotence.«
B042C022V070	42	22	70	Thereupon they cried out with one voice, »You, then, are the Son of God?«»It is as you say,« He answered; »I am He.«
B042C022V071	42	22	71	»What need have we of further evidence?« they said; »for we ourselves have heard it from his own lips.«
B042C023V001	42	23	1	Then the whole assembly rose and brought Him to Pilate, and began to accuse Him.
B042C023V002	42	23	2	»We have found this man,« they said, »an agitator among our nation, forbidding the payment of tribute to Caesar, and claiming to be himself an anointed king.«
B042C023V003	42	23	3	Then Pilate asked Him, »You, then, are the King of the Jews?«»It is as you say,« He replied.
B042C023V004	42	23	4	Pilate said to the High Priests and to the crowd, »I can find no crime in this man.«
B042C023V005	42	23	5	But they violently insisted. »He stirs up the people,« they said, »throughout all Judaea with His teaching–even from Galilee (where He first started) to this city.«
B042C023V006	42	23	6	On hearing this, Pilate inquired, »Is this man a Galilaean?«
B042C023V007	42	23	7	And learning that He belonged to Herod's jurisdiction he sent Him to Herod, for he too was in Jerusalem at that time.
B042C023V008	42	23	8	To Herod the sight of Jesus was a great gratification, for, for a long time, he had been wanting to see Him, because he had heard so much about Him. He hoped also to see some miracle performed by Him.
B042C023V009	42	23	9	So he put a number of questions to Him, but Jesus gave him no reply.
B042C023V010	42	23	10	Meanwhile the High Priests and the Scribes were standing there and vehemently accusing Him.
B042C023V011	42	23	11	Then, laughing to scorn the claims of Jesus, Herod (and his soldiers with him) made sport of Him, dressed Him in a gorgeous costume, and sent Him back to Pilate.
B042C023V012	42	23	12	And on that very day Herod and Pilate became friends again, for they had been for some time at enmity.
B042C023V013	42	23	13	Then calling together the High Priests and the Rulers and the people, Pilate said,
B042C023V014	42	23	14	»You have brought this man to me on a charge of corrupting the loyalty of the people. But, you see, I have examined him in your presence and have discovered in the man no ground for the accusations which you bring against him.
B042C023V015	42	23	15	No, nor does Herod; for he has sent him back to us; and, you see, there is nothing he has done that deserves death.
B042C023V016	42	23	16	I will therefore give him a light punishment and release him.«
B042C023V017	42	23	17	[]
B042C023V018	42	23	18	Then the whole multitude burst out into a shout. »Away with this man,« they said, »and release Barabbas to us«
B042C023V019	42	23	19	–Barabbas! who had been lodged in jail for some time in connexion with a riot which had occurred in the city, and for murder.
B042C023V020	42	23	20	But Pilate once more addressed them, wishing to set Jesus free.
B042C023V021	42	23	21	They, however, persistently shouted, »Crucify, crucify him!«
B042C023V022	42	23	22	A third time he appealed to them: »Why, what crime has the man committed? I have discovered in him nothing that deserves death. I will therefore give him a light punishment and release him.«
B042C023V023	42	23	23	But they urgently insisted, demanding with frantic outcries that He should be crucified; and their clamour prevailed.
B042C023V024	42	23	24	So Pilate gave judgement, yielding to their demand.
B042C023V025	42	23	25	The man who was lying in prison charged with riot and murder and for whom they clamoured he set free, but Jesus he gave up to be dealt with as they desired.
B042C023V026	42	23	26	As soon as they led Him away, they laid hold on one Simon, a Cyrenaean, who was coming in from the country, and on his shoulders they put the cross, for him to carry it behind Jesus.
B042C023V027	42	23	27	A vast crowd of the people also followed Him, and of women who were beating their breasts and wailing for Him.
B042C023V028	42	23	28	But Jesus turned towards them and said, »Daughters of Jerusalem, weep not for me, but weep for yourselves and for your children.
B042C023V029	42	23	29	For a time is coming when they will say, `Blessed are the women who never bore children, and the breasts which have never given nourishment.'
B042C023V030	42	23	30	Then will they begin to say to the mountains, `Fall on us;' and to the hills, `Cover us.'
B042C023V031	42	23	31	For if they are doing these things in the case of the green tree, what will be done in that of the dry?«
B042C023V032	42	23	32	They brought also two others, criminals, to put them to death with Him.
B042C023V033	42	23	33	When they reached the place called `The Skull,' there they nailed Him to the cross, and the criminals also, one at His right hand and one at His left.
B042C023V034	42	23	34	Jesus prayed, »Father, forgive them, for they know not what they are doing.« And they divided His garments among them, drawing lots for them;
B042C023V035	42	23	35	and the people stood looking on. The Rulers, too, repeatedly uttered their bitter taunts. »This fellow,« they said, »saved others: let him save himself, if he is God's Anointed, the Chosen One.«
B042C023V036	42	23	36	And the soldiers also made sport of Him, coming and offering Him sour wine and saying,
B042C023V037	42	23	37	»Are 
B042C023V038	42	23	38	There was moreover a writing over His head: THIS IS THE KING OF THE JEWS.
B042C023V039	42	23	39	Now one of the criminals who had been crucified insulted Him, saying, »Are not you the Christ? Save yourself and us.«
B042C023V040	42	23	40	But the other, answering, reproved him. »Do you also not fear God,« he said, »when you are actually suffering the same punishment?
B042C023V041	42	23	41	And we indeed are suffering justly, for we are receiving due requital for what we have done. But He has done nothing amiss.«
B042C023V042	42	23	42	And he said, »Jesus, remember me when you come in your Kingdom.«
B042C023V043	42	23	43	»I tell you in solemn truth,« replied Jesus, »that this very day you shall be with me in Paradise.«
B042C023V044	42	23	44	It was now about noon, and a darkness came over the whole country till three o'clock in the afternoon.
B042C023V045	42	23	45	The sun was darkened, and the curtain of the Sanctuary was torn down the middle,
B042C023V046	42	23	46	and Jesus cried out in a loud voice, and said, »Father, to Thy hands I entrust my spirit.« And after uttering these words He yielded up His spirit.
B042C023V047	42	23	47	The Captain, seeing what had happened, gave glory to God, saying, »Beyond question this man was innocent.«
B042C023V048	42	23	48	And all the crowds that had come together to this sight, after seeing all that had occurred, returned to the city beating their breasts.
B042C023V049	42	23	49	But all His acquaintances, and the women who had been His followers after leaving Galilee, continued standing at a distance and looking on.
B042C023V050	42	23	50	There was a member of the Council of the name of Joseph, a kind-hearted and upright man,
B042C023V051	42	23	51	who came from the Jewish town of Arimathaea and was awaiting the coming of the Kingdom of God. He had not concurred in the design or action of the Council,
B042C023V052	42	23	52	and now he went to Pilate and asked for the body of Jesus.
B042C023V053	42	23	53	Then, taking it down, he wrapped it in a linen sheet and laid it in a tomb in the rock, where no one else had yet been put.
B042C023V054	42	23	54	It was the Preparation Day, and the Sabbath was near at hand.
B042C023V055	42	23	55	The women –those who had come with Jesus from Galilee– followed close behind, and saw the tomb and how His body was placed.
B042C023V056	42	23	56	Then they returned, and prepared spices and perfumes. On the Sabbath they rested in obedience to the Commandment.
B042C024V001	42	24	1	And, on the first day of the week, at early dawn, they came to the tomb bringing the spices they had prepared.
B042C024V002	42	24	2	But they found the stone rolled back from the tomb,
B042C024V003	42	24	3	and on entering they found that the body of the Lord Jesus was not there.
B042C024V004	42	24	4	At this they were in great perplexity, when suddenly there stood by them two men whose raiment flashed like lightning.
B042C024V005	42	24	5	The women were terrified; but, as they stood with their faces bowed to the ground, the men said to them, »Why do you search among the dead for Him who is living?
B042C024V006	42	24	6	He is not here. He has come back to life. Remember how He spoke to you while He was still in Galilee,
B042C024V007	42	24	7	when He told you that the Son of Man must be betrayed into the hands of sinful men, and be crucified, and on the third day rise again.«
B042C024V008	42	24	8	Then they remembered His words,
B042C024V009	42	24	9	and returning from the tomb they reported all this to the Eleven and to all the rest.
B042C024V010	42	24	10	The women were Mary of Magdala, Joanna, and Mary the mother of James; and they and the rest of the women related all this to the Apostles.
B042C024V011	42	24	11	But the whole story seemed to them an idle tale; they could not believe the women.
B042C024V012	42	24	12	Peter, however, rose and ran to the tomb. Stooping and looking in, he saw nothing but the linen cloths: so he went away to his own home, wondering at what had happened.
B042C024V013	42	24	13	On that same day two of the disciples were walking to Emmaus, a village seven or eight miles from Jerusalem,
B042C024V014	42	24	14	and were conversing about all these recent events;
B042C024V015	42	24	15	and, in the midst of their conversation and discussion, Jesus Himself came and joined them,
B042C024V016	42	24	16	though they were prevented from recognizing Him.
B042C024V017	42	24	17	»What is the subject,« He asked them, »on which you are talking so earnestly, as you walk?« And they stood still, looking full of sorrow.
B042C024V018	42	24	18	Then one of them, named Cleopas, answered, »Are you a stranger lodging alone in Jerusalem, that you have known nothing of the things that have lately happened in the city?«
B042C024V019	42	24	19	»What things?« He asked. »The things about Jesus the Nazarene,« they said, »who was a Prophet powerful in work and word before God and all the people;
B042C024V020	42	24	20	and how our High Priests and Rulers delivered Him up to be sentenced to death, and crucified Him.
B042C024V021	42	24	21	But we were hoping that it was He who was about to ransom Israel. Yes, and moreover it was the day before yesterday that these things happened.
B042C024V022	42	24	22	And, besides, some of the women of our company have amazed us. They went to the tomb at daybreak,
B042C024V023	42	24	23	and, finding that His body was not there, they came and declared to us that they had also seen a vision of angels who said that He was alive.
B042C024V024	42	24	24	Thereupon some of our party went to the tomb and found things just as the women had said; but Jesus Himself they did not see.«
B042C024V025	42	24	25	»O dull-witted men,« He replied, »with minds so slow to believe all that the Prophets have spoken!
B042C024V026	42	24	26	Was there not a necessity for the Christ thus to suffer, and then enter into His glory?«
B042C024V027	42	24	27	And, beginning with Moses and all the Prophets, He explained to them the passages in Scripture which refer to Himself.
B042C024V028	42	24	28	When they had come near the village to which they were going, He appeared to be going further.
B042C024V029	42	24	29	But they pressed Him to remain with them. »Because,« said they, »it is getting towards evening, and the day is nearly over.« So He went in to stay with them.
B042C024V030	42	24	30	But as soon as He had sat down with them, and had taken the bread and had blessed and broken it, and was handing it to them,
B042C024V031	42	24	31	their eyes were opened and they recognized Him. But He vanished from them.
B042C024V032	42	24	32	»Were not our hearts,« they said to one another, »burning within us while He talked to us on the way and explained the Scriptures to us?«
B042C024V033	42	24	33	So they rose and without an hour's delay returned to Jerusalem, and found the Eleven and the rest met together, who said to them,
B042C024V034	42	24	34	»Yes, it is true: the Master has come back to life. He has been seen by Simon.«
B042C024V035	42	24	35	Then they related what had happened on the way, and how He had been recognized by them in the breaking of the bread.
B042C024V036	42	24	36	While they were thus talking, He Himself stood in their midst and said, »Peace be to you!«
B042C024V037	42	24	37	Startled, and in the utmost alarm, they thought they were looking at a spirit;
B042C024V038	42	24	38	but He said to them, »Why such alarm? And why are there such questionings in your minds?
B042C024V039	42	24	39	See my hands and my feet–it is my very self. Feel me and see, for a spirit has not flesh and bones as you see I have.«
B042C024V040	42	24	40	And then He showed them His hands and His feet.
B042C024V041	42	24	41	But, while they still could not believe it for joy and were full of astonishment, He asked them, »Have you any food here?«
B042C024V042	42	24	42	And they gave Him a piece of roasted fish,
B042C024V043	42	24	43	and He took it and ate it in their presence.
B042C024V044	42	24	44	And He said to them, »This is what I told you while I was still with you–that everything must be fulfilled that is written in the Law of Moses and in the Prophets and the Psalms concerning me.«
B042C024V045	42	24	45	Then He opened their minds to understand the Scriptures,
B042C024V046	42	24	46	and He said, »Thus it is written that the Christ would suffer and on the third day rise again from among the dead;
B042C024V047	42	24	47	and that proclamation would be made, in His name, of repentance and forgiveness of sins to all the nations, beginning in Jerusalem.
B042C024V048	42	24	48	You are witnesses as to these things.
B042C024V049	42	24	49	And remember that I am about to send out my Father's promised gift to rest upon you. But, as for you, wait patiently in the city until you are clothed with power from on high.«
B042C024V050	42	24	50	And He brought them out to within view of Bethany, and then lifted up His hands and blessed them.
B042C024V051	42	24	51	And while He was blessing them, He parted from them and was carried up into Heaven.
B042C024V052	42	24	52	They worshipped Him, and returned to Jerusalem with great joy.
B042C024V053	42	24	53	Afterwards they were continually in attendance at the Temple, blessing God.
B043C001V001	43	1	1	In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God.
B043C001V002	43	1	2	He was in the beginning with God.
B043C001V003	43	1	3	All things came into being through Him, and apart from Him nothing that exists came into being.
B043C001V004	43	1	4	In Him was Life, and that Life was the Light of men.
B043C001V005	43	1	5	The Light shines in the darkness, and the darkness has not overpowered it.
B043C001V006	43	1	6	There was a man sent from God, whose name was John.
B043C001V007	43	1	7	He came as a witness, in order that he might give testimony concerning the Light–so that all might believe through him.
B043C001V008	43	1	8	He was not the Light, but he existed that he might give testimony concerning the Light.
B043C001V009	43	1	9	The true Light was that which illumines every man by its coming into the world.
B043C001V010	43	1	10	He was in the world, and the world came into existence through Him, and the world did not recognize Him.
B043C001V011	43	1	11	He came to the things that were His own, and His own people gave Him no welcome.
B043C001V012	43	1	12	But all who have received Him, to them –that is, to those who trust in His name– He has given the privilege of becoming children of God;
B043C001V013	43	1	13	who were begotten as such not by human descent, nor through an impulse of their own nature, nor through the will of a human father, but from God.
B043C001V014	43	1	14	And the Word came in the flesh, and lived for a time in our midst, so that we saw His glory–the glory as of the Father's only Son, sent from His presence. He was full of grace and truth.
B043C001V015	43	1	15	John gave testimony concerning Him and cried aloud, saying, »This is He of whom I said, `He who is coming after me has been put before me,' for He was before me.«
B043C001V016	43	1	16	For He it is from whose fulness we have all received, and grace upon grace.
B043C001V017	43	1	17	For the Law was given through Moses; grace and truth came through Jesus Christ.
B043C001V018	43	1	18	No human eye has ever seen God: the only Son, who is in the Father's bosom–He has made Him known.
B043C001V019	43	1	19	This also is John's testimony, when the Jews sent to him a deputation of Priests and Levites from Jerusalem to ask him who he was.
B043C001V020	43	1	20	He avowed–he did not conceal the truth, but avowed, »I am not the Christ.«
B043C001V021	43	1	21	»What then?« they inquired; »are you Elijah?«»I am not,« he said. »Are you the Prophet?«»No,« he answered.
B043C001V022	43	1	22	So they pressed the question. »Who are you?« they said– »that we may take an answer to those who sent us. What account do you give of yourself?«
B043C001V023	43	1	23	»I am 
B043C001V024	43	1	24	They were Pharisees who had been sent.
B043C001V025	43	1	25	Again they questioned him. »Why then do you baptize,« they said, »if you are neither the Christ nor Elijah nor the Prophet?«
B043C001V026	43	1	26	»I baptize in water only,« John answered, »but in your midst stands One whom you do not know–
B043C001V027	43	1	27	He who is to come after me, and whose sandal-strap I am not worthy to unfasten.«
B043C001V028	43	1	28	This conversation took place at Bethany beyond the Jordan, where John was baptizing.
B043C001V029	43	1	29	The next day John saw Jesus coming towards him and exclaimed, »Look, that is the Lamb of God who is to take away the sin of the world!
B043C001V030	43	1	30	This is He about whom I said, `After me is to come One who has been put before me, because He was before me.'
B043C001V031	43	1	31	I did not yet know Him; but that He may be openly shown to Israel is the reason why I have come baptizing in water.«
B043C001V032	43	1	32	John also gave testimony by stating: »I have seen the Spirit coming down like a dove out of Heaven; and it remained upon Him.
B043C001V033	43	1	33	I did not yet know Him, but He who sent me to baptize in water said to me, »`The One on whom you see the Spirit coming down, and remaining, He it is who baptizes in the Holy Spirit.'
B043C001V034	43	1	34	»This I have seen, and I have become a witness that He is the Son of God.«
B043C001V035	43	1	35	Again the next day John was standing with two of his disciples,
B043C001V036	43	1	36	when he saw Jesus passing by, and said, »Look! that is the Lamb of God!«
B043C001V037	43	1	37	The two disciples heard his exclamation, and they followed Jesus.
B043C001V038	43	1	38	Then Jesus turned round, and seeing them following He asked them, »What is your wish?« »Rabbi,« they replied- 
B043C001V039	43	1	39	»Come and you shall see,« He said. So they went and saw where He was staying, and they remained and spent that day with Him. It was then about ten o'clock in the morning.
B043C001V040	43	1	40	Andrew, Simon Peter's brother, was one of the two who heard John's exclamation and followed Jesus.
B043C001V041	43	1	41	He first found his own brother Simon, and said to him, »We have found the Messiah!« –that is to say, the Anointed One.
B043C001V042	43	1	42	He brought him to Jesus. Jesus looked at him and said, »You are Simon, son of John: you shall be called Cephas« –that is to say, Peter (or `Rock').
B043C001V043	43	1	43	The next day, having decided to leave Bethany and go into Galilee, Jesus found Philip, and invited him to follow Him.
B043C001V044	43	1	44	(Now Philip came from Bethsaida, the same town as Andrew and Peter.)
B043C001V045	43	1	45	Then Philip found Nathanael, and said to him, »We have found him about whom Moses in the Law wrote, as well as the Prophets–Jesus, the son of Joseph, a man of Nazareth.«
B043C001V046	43	1	46	»Can anything good come out of Nazareth?« replied Nathanael. »Come and see,« said Philip.
B043C001V047	43	1	47	Jesus saw Nathanael approaching, and said of him, »Look! here is a true Israelite, in whom there is no deceitfulness!«
B043C001V048	43	1	48	»How do you know me?« Nathanael asked. »Before Philip called you,« said Jesus, »when you were under the fig-tree I saw you.«
B043C001V049	43	1	49	»Rabbi,« cried Nathanael, »you are the Son of God, you are Israel's King!«
B043C001V050	43	1	50	»Because I said to you, `I saw you under the fig-tree,'« replied Jesus, »do you believe? You shall see greater things than that.«
B043C001V051	43	1	51	»I tell you all in most solemn truth,« He added, »that you shall see Heaven opened wide, and God's angels going up, and coming down to the Son of Man.«
B043C002V001	43	2	1	Two days later there was a wedding at Cana in Galilee, and the mother of Jesus was there,
B043C002V002	43	2	2	and Jesus also was invited and His disciples.
B043C002V003	43	2	3	Now the wine ran short; whereupon the mother of Jesus said to Him, »They have no wine.«
B043C002V004	43	2	4	»Leave the matter in my hands,« He replied; »the time for me to act has not yet come.«
B043C002V005	43	2	5	His mother said to the attendants, »Whatever he tells you to do, do it.«
B043C002V006	43	2	6	Now there were six stone jars standing there (in accordance with the Jewish regulations for purification), each large enough to hold twenty gallons or more.
B043C002V007	43	2	7	Jesus said to the attendants, »Fill the jars with water.« And they filled them to the brim.
B043C002V008	43	2	8	Then He said, »Now, take some out, and carry it to the President of the feast.«
B043C002V009	43	2	9	So they carried some to him. And no sooner had the President tasted the water now turned into wine, than –not knowing where it came from, though the attendants who had drawn the water knew– he called to the bridegroom
B043C002V010	43	2	10	and said to him, »It is usual to put on the good wine first, and when people have drunk freely, then that which is inferior. But you have kept the good wine till now.«
B043C002V011	43	2	11	This, the first of His miracles, Jesus performed at Cana in Galilee, and thus displayed His glorious power; and His disciples believed in Him.
B043C002V012	43	2	12	Afterwards He went down to Capernaum–He, and His mother, and His brothers, and His disciples; and they made a short stay there.
B043C002V013	43	2	13	But the Jewish Passover was approaching, and for this Jesus went up to Jerusalem.
B043C002V014	43	2	14	And He found in the Temple the dealers in cattle and sheep and in pigeons, and the money-changers sitting there.
B043C002V015	43	2	15	So He plaited a whip of rushes, and drove all –both sheep and bullocks– out of the Temple. The small coin of the brokers He upset on the ground and overturned their tables.
B043C002V016	43	2	16	And to the pigeon-dealers He said, »Take these things away. Do not turn my Father's house into a market.«
B043C002V017	43	2	17	This recalled to His disciples the words of Scripture, 
B043C002V018	43	2	18	So the Jews asked Him, »What proof of your authority do you exhibit to us, seeing that you do these things?«
B043C002V019	43	2	19	»Demolish this Sanctuary,« said Jesus, »and in three days I will rebuild it.«
B043C002V020	43	2	20	»It has taken forty-six years,« replied the Jews, »to build this Sanctuary, and will you rebuild it in three days?«
B043C002V021	43	2	21	But He was speaking of the Sanctuary of His body.
B043C002V022	43	2	22	When however He had risen from among the dead, His disciples recollected that He had said this; and they believed the Scripture and the teaching which Jesus had given them.
B043C002V023	43	2	23	Now when He was in Jerusalem, at the Festival of the Passover, many became believers in Him through watching the miracles He performed.
B043C002V024	43	2	24	But for His part, Jesus did not trust Himself to them, because He knew them all,
B043C002V025	43	2	25	and did not need any one's testimony concerning a man, for He of Himself knew what was in the man.
B043C003V001	43	3	1	Now there was one of the Pharisees whose name was Nicodemus–a ruler among the Jews.
B043C003V002	43	3	2	He came to Jesus by night and said, »Rabbi, we know that you are a teacher from God; for no one can do these miracles which you are doing, unless God is with him.
B043C003V003	43	3	3	»In most solemn truth I tell you,« answered Jesus, »that unless a man is born anew he cannot see the Kingdom of God.«
B043C003V004	43	3	4	»How is it possible,« Nicodemus asked, »for a man to be born when he is old? Can he a second time enter his mother's womb and be born?«
B043C003V005	43	3	5	»In most solemn truth I tell you,« replied Jesus, »that unless a man is born of water and the Spirit, he cannot enter the Kingdom of God.
B043C003V006	43	3	6	Whatever has been born of the flesh is flesh, and whatever has been born of the Spirit is spirit.
B043C003V007	43	3	7	Do not be astonished at my telling you, `You must all be born anew.'
B043C003V008	43	3	8	The wind blows where it chooses, and you hear its sound, but you do not know where it comes from or where it is going. So is it with every one who has been born of the Spirit.«
B043C003V009	43	3	9	»How is all this possible?« asked Nicodemus.
B043C003V010	43	3	10	»Are you,« replied Jesus, »`the Teacher of Israel,' and yet do you not understand these things?
B043C003V011	43	3	11	In most solemn truth I tell you that we speak what we know, and give testimony of that of which we were eye-witnesses, and yet you all reject our testimony.
B043C003V012	43	3	12	If I have told you earthly things and none of you believe me, how will you believe me if I tell you of things in Heaven?
B043C003V013	43	3	13	There is no one who has gone up to Heaven, but there is One who has come down from Heaven, namely the Son of Man whose home is in Heaven.
B043C003V014	43	3	14	And just as Moses lifted high the serpent in the Desert, so must the Son of Man be lifted up,
B043C003V015	43	3	15	in order that every one who trusts in Him may have the Life of the Ages.«
B043C003V016	43	3	16	For so greatly did God love the world that He gave His only Son, that every one who trusts in Him may not perish but may have the Life of Ages.
B043C003V017	43	3	17	For God did not send His Son into the world to judge the world, but that the world might be saved through Him.
B043C003V018	43	3	18	He who trusts in Him does not come up for judgement. He who does not trust has already received sentence, because he has not his trust resting on the name of God's only Son.
B043C003V019	43	3	19	And this is the test by which men are judged–the Light has come into the world, and men loved the darkness more than they loved the Light, because their deeds were wicked.
B043C003V020	43	3	20	For every wrongdoer hates the light, and does not come to the light, for fear his actions should be exposed and condemned.
B043C003V021	43	3	21	But he who does what is honest and right comes to the light, in order that his actions may be plainly shown to have been done in God.
B043C003V022	43	3	22	After this Jesus and His disciples went into Judaea; and there He made a stay in company with them and baptized.
B043C003V023	43	3	23	And John too was baptizing at Aenon, near Salim, because there were many pools of water there; and people came and received baptism.
B043C003V024	43	3	24	(For John was not yet in prison.)
B043C003V025	43	3	25	As the result, a discussion having arisen on the part of John's disciples with a Jew about purification,
B043C003V026	43	3	26	they came to John and reported to him, »Rabbi, he who was with you on the other side of the Jordan and to whom you bore testimony is now baptizing, and great numbers of people are resorting to him.«
B043C003V027	43	3	27	»A man cannot obtain anything,« replied John, »unless it has been granted to him from Heaven.
B043C003V028	43	3	28	You yourselves can bear witness to my having said, `I am not the Christ,' but `I am His appointed forerunner.'
B043C003V029	43	3	29	He who has the bride is the bridegroom; and the bridegroom's friend who stands by his side and listens to him, rejoices heartily on account of the bridegroom's happiness. Therefore this joy of mine is now complete.
B043C003V030	43	3	30	He must grow greater, but I must grow less.
B043C003V031	43	3	31	He who comes from above is above all. He whose origin is from the earth is not only himself from the earth, his teaching also is from the earth. He who comes from Heaven is above all.
B043C003V032	43	3	32	What He has seen and heard, to that He bears witness; but His testimony no one receives.
B043C003V033	43	3	33	Any man who has received His testimony has solemnly declared that God is true.
B043C003V034	43	3	34	For He whom God has sent speaks God's words; for God does not give the Spirit with limitations.«
B043C003V035	43	3	35	The Father loves the Son and has entrusted everything to His hands.
B043C003V036	43	3	36	He who believes in the Son has the Life of the Ages; he who disobeys the Son will not enter into Life, but God's anger remains upon him.
B043C004V001	43	4	1	Now as soon as the Master was aware that the Pharisees had heard it said, »Jesus is gaining and baptizing more disciples than John«–
B043C004V002	43	4	2	though Jesus Himself did not baptize them, but His disciples did–
B043C004V003	43	4	3	He left Judaea and returned to Galilee.
B043C004V004	43	4	4	His road lay through Samaria,
B043C004V005	43	4	5	and so He came to Sychar, a town in Samaria near the piece of land that Jacob gave to his son Joseph.
B043C004V006	43	4	6	Jacob's Well was there: and accordingly Jesus, tired out with His journey, sat down by the well to rest. It was about six o'clock in the evening.
B043C004V007	43	4	7	Presently there came a woman of Samaria to draw water. Jesus asked her to give Him some water;
B043C004V008	43	4	8	for His disciples were gone to the town to buy provisions.
B043C004V009	43	4	9	»How is it,« replied the woman, »that a Jew like you asks me, who am a woman and a Samaritan, for water?« (For Jews have no dealings with Samaritans.)
B043C004V010	43	4	10	»If you had known God's free gift,« replied Jesus, »and who it is that said to you, `Give me some water,' you would have asked Him, and He would have given you living water.«
B043C004V011	43	4	11	»Sir,« she said, »you have nothing to draw with, and the well is deep; so where can you get the living water from?
B043C004V012	43	4	12	Are you greater than our forefather Jacob, who gave us the well, and himself drank from it, as did also his sons and his cattle?«
B043C004V013	43	4	13	»Every one,« replied Jesus, »who drinks any of this water will be thirsty again;
B043C004V014	43	4	14	but whoever drinks any of the water that I shall give him will never, never thirst. But the water that I shall give him will become a fountain within him of water springing up for the Life of the Ages.«
B043C004V015	43	4	15	»Sir,« said the woman, »give me that water, that I may never be thirsty, nor continually come all the way here to draw from the well.«
B043C004V016	43	4	16	»Go and call your husband,« said Jesus; »and come back.«
B043C004V017	43	4	17	»I have no husband,« she replied. »You rightly say that you have no husband,« said Jesus;
B043C004V018	43	4	18	»for you have had five husbands, and the man you have at present is not your husband. You have spoken the truth in saying that.«
B043C004V019	43	4	19	»Sir,« replied the woman, »I see that you are a Prophet.
B043C004V020	43	4	20	Our forefathers worshipped on this mountain, but you Jews say that the place where people must worship is in Jerusalem.«
B043C004V021	43	4	21	»Believe me,« said Jesus, »the time is coming when you will worship the Father neither on this mountain nor in Jerusalem.
B043C004V022	43	4	22	You worship One of whom you know nothing. We worship One whom we know; for salvation comes from the Jews.
B043C004V023	43	4	23	But a time is coming –nay, has already come– when the true worshippers will worship the Father with true spiritual worship; for indeed the Father desires such worshippers.
B043C004V024	43	4	24	God is Spirit; and those who worship Him must bring Him true spiritual worship.«
B043C004V025	43	4	25	»I know,« replied the woman, »that Messiah is coming–`the Christ,' as He is called. When He has come, He will tell us everything.«
B043C004V026	43	4	26	»I am He,« said Jesus– »I who am now talking to you.«
B043C004V027	43	4	27	Just then His disciples came, and were surprised to find Him talking with a woman. Yet not one of them asked Him, »What is your wish?« or »Why are you talking with her?«
B043C004V028	43	4	28	The woman however, leaving her pitcher, went away to the town, and called the people.
B043C004V029	43	4	29	»Come,« she said, »and see a man who has told me everything I have ever done. Can this be the Christ, do you think?«
B043C004V030	43	4	30	They left the town and set out to go to Him.
B043C004V031	43	4	31	Meanwhile the disciples were urging Jesus. »Rabbi,« they said, »eat something.«
B043C004V032	43	4	32	»I have food to eat,« He replied, »of which you do not know.«
B043C004V033	43	4	33	So the disciples began questioning one another. »Can it be,« they said, »that some one has brought Him something to eat?«
B043C004V034	43	4	34	»My food,« said Jesus, »is to be obedient to Him who sent me, and fully to accomplish His work.
B043C004V035	43	4	35	Do you not say, `It wants four months yet to the harvest'? But look round, I tell you, and observe these plains– they are already ripe for the sickle.
B043C004V036	43	4	36	The reaper gets pay and gathers in a crop in preparation for the Life of the Ages, that so the sower and the reapers may rejoice together.
B043C004V037	43	4	37	For it is in this that you see the real meaning of the saying, `The sower is one person, and the reaper is another.'
B043C004V038	43	4	38	I sent you to reap a harvest which is not the result of your own labours. Others have laboured, and you are getting benefit from their labours.«
B043C004V039	43	4	39	Of the Samaritan population of that town a good many believed in Him because of the woman's statement when she declared, »He has told me all that I have ever done.«
B043C004V040	43	4	40	When however the Samaritans came to Him, they asked Him on all sides to stay with them; and He stayed there two days.
B043C004V041	43	4	41	Then a far larger number of people believed because of His own words,
B043C004V042	43	4	42	and they said to the woman, »We no longer believe in Him simply because of your statements; for we have now heard for ourselves, and we know that this man really is the Saviour of the world.«
B043C004V043	43	4	43	After the two days He departed, and went into Galilee;
B043C004V044	43	4	44	though Jesus Himself declared that a Prophet has no honour in his own country.
B043C004V045	43	4	45	When however He reached Galilee, the Galilaeans welcomed Him eagerly, having been eye-witnesses of all that He had done in Jerusalem at the Festival; for they also had been to the Festival.
B043C004V046	43	4	46	So He came once more to Cana in Galilee, where He had made the water into wine. Now there was a certain officer of the King's court whose son was ill at Capernaum.
B043C004V047	43	4	47	Having heard that Jesus had come from Judaea to Galilee, he came to Him and begged Him to go down and cure his son; for he was at the point of death.
B043C004V048	43	4	48	»Unless you and others see miracles and marvels,« said Jesus, »nothing will induce you to believe.«
B043C004V049	43	4	49	»Sir,« pleaded the officer, »come down before my child dies.«
B043C004V050	43	4	50	»You may return home,« replied Jesus; »your son has recovered.« He believed the words of Jesus, and started back home;
B043C004V051	43	4	51	and he was already on his way down when his servants met him and told him that his son was alive and well.
B043C004V052	43	4	52	So he inquired of them at what hour he had shown improvement. »Yesterday, about seven o'clock,« they replied, »the fever left him.«
B043C004V053	43	4	53	Then the father recollected that that was the time at which Jesus had said to him, »Your son has recovered,« and he and his whole household became believers.
B043C004V054	43	4	54	This is the second miracle that Jesus performed, after coming from Judaea into Galilee.
B043C005V001	43	5	1	After this there was a Festival of the Jews, and Jesus went up to Jerusalem.
B043C005V002	43	5	2	Now there is in Jerusalem near the Sheep Gate a pool, called in Hebrew `Bethesda.' It has five arcades.
B043C005V003	43	5	3	In these there used to lie a great number of sick persons, and of people who were blind or lame or paralyzed.
B043C005V004	43	5	4	[]
B043C005V005	43	5	5	And there was one man there who had been an invalid for thirty-eight years.
B043C005V006	43	5	6	Jesus saw him lying there, and knowing that he had been a long time in that condition, He asked him, »Do you wish to have health and strength?«
B043C005V007	43	5	7	»Sir,« replied the sufferer, »I have no one to put me into the pool when the water is moved; but while I am coming some one else steps down before me.«
B043C005V008	43	5	8	»Rise,« said Jesus, »take up your mat and walk.«
B043C005V009	43	5	9	Instantly the man was restored to perfect health, and he took up his mat and began to walk.
B043C005V010	43	5	10	That day was a Sabbath. So the Jews said to the man who had been cured, »It is the Sabbath: you must not carry your mat.«
B043C005V011	43	5	11	»He who cured me,« he replied, »said to me, `Take up your mat and walk.'«
B043C005V012	43	5	12	»Who is it,« they asked, »that said to you, `Take up your mat and walk'?«
B043C005V013	43	5	13	But the man who had been cured did not know who it was; for Jesus had passed out unnoticed, there being a crowd in the place.
B043C005V014	43	5	14	Afterwards Jesus found him in the Temple and said to him, »You are now restored to health. Do not sin any more, or a worse thing may befall you.«
B043C005V015	43	5	15	The man went and told the Jews that it was Jesus who had restored him to health;
B043C005V016	43	5	16	and on this account the Jews began to persecute Jesus–because He did these things on the Sabbath.
B043C005V017	43	5	17	His reply to their accusation was, »My Father works unceasingly, and so do I.«
B043C005V018	43	5	18	On this account then the Jews were all the more eager to put Him to death–because He not only broke the Sabbath, but also spoke of God as being in a special sense His Father, thus putting Himself on a level with God.
B043C005V019	43	5	19	»In most solemn truth I tell you,« replied Jesus, »that the Son can do nothing of Himself–He can only do what He sees the Father doing; for whatever He does, that the Son does in like manner.
B043C005V020	43	5	20	For the Father loves the Son and reveals to Him all that He Himself is doing. And greater deeds than these will He reveal to Him, in order that you may wonder.
B043C005V021	43	5	21	For just as the Father awakens the dead and gives them life, so the Son also gives life to whom He wills.
B043C005V022	43	5	22	The Father indeed does not judge any one, but He has entrusted all judgement to the Son,
B043C005V023	43	5	23	that all may honour the Son even as they honour the Father. The man who withholds honour from the Son withholds honour from the Father who sent Him.
B043C005V024	43	5	24	»In most solemn truth I tell you that he who listens to my teaching and believes Him who sent me, has the Life of the Ages, and does not come under judgement, but has passed over out of death into Life.«
B043C005V025	43	5	25	»In most solemn truth I tell you that a time is coming –nay, has already come– when the dead will hear the voice of the Son of God, and those who hear it will live.«
B043C005V026	43	5	26	For just as the Father has life in Himself, so He has also given to the Son to have life in Himself.
B043C005V027	43	5	27	And He has conferred on Him authority to act as Judge, because He is the Son of Man.
B043C005V028	43	5	28	Wonder not at this. For a time is coming when all who are in the graves will hear His voice and will come forth–
B043C005V029	43	5	29	they who have done what is right to the resurrection of Life, and they whose actions have been evil to the resurrection of judgement.
B043C005V030	43	5	30	»I can of my own self do nothing. As I am bidden, so I judge; and mine is a just judgement, because it is not my own will that guides me, but the will of Him who sent me.«
B043C005V031	43	5	31	»If I give testimony concerning myself, my testimony cannot be accepted.«
B043C005V032	43	5	32	There is Another who gives testimony concerning me, and I know that the testimony is true which He offers concerning me.
B043C005V033	43	5	33	»You sent to John, and he both was and still is a witness to the truth.«
B043C005V034	43	5	34	But the testimony on my behalf which I accept is not from man; though I say all this in order that you may be saved.
B043C005V035	43	5	35	He was the lamp that burned and shone, and for a time you were willing to be gladdened by his light.
B043C005V036	43	5	36	»But the testimony which I have is weightier than that of John; for the work the Father has assigned to me for me to bring it to completion –the very work which I am doing– affords testimony concerning me that the Father has sent me.«
B043C005V037	43	5	37	And the Father who sent me, 
B043C005V038	43	5	38	Nor have you His word dwelling within you, for you refuse to believe Him whom 
B043C005V039	43	5	39	»You search the Scriptures, because you suppose that in them you will find the Life of the Ages; and it is those Scriptures that yield testimony concerning me;«
B043C005V040	43	5	40	and yet you are unwilling to come to me that you may have Life.
B043C005V041	43	5	41	»I do not accept glory from man,
B043C005V042	43	5	42	but I know you well, and I know that in your hearts you do not really love God.«
B043C005V043	43	5	43	I have come as my Father's representative, and you do not receive me. If some one else comes representing only himself, him you will receive.
B043C005V044	43	5	44	How is it possible for you to believe, while you receive glory from one another and have no desire for the glory that comes from the only God?
B043C005V045	43	5	45	»Do not suppose that I will accuse you to the Father. There is one who accuses you, namely Moses, on whom your hope rests.
B043C005V046	43	5	46	For if you believe Moses, you would believe me; for he wrote about me.
B043C005V047	43	5	47	But if you disbelieve his writings, how are you to believe my words?«
B043C006V001	43	6	1	After this Jesus went away across the Lake of Galilee (that is, the Lake of Tiberias).
B043C006V002	43	6	2	A vast multitude followed Him, because they witnessed the miracles on the sick which He was constantly performing.
B043C006V003	43	6	3	Then Jesus went up the hill, and sat there with His disciples.
B043C006V004	43	6	4	The Jewish Festival, the Passover, was at hand.
B043C006V005	43	6	5	And when He looked round and saw an immense crowd coming towards Him, He said to Philip, »Where shall we buy bread for all these people to eat?«
B043C006V006	43	6	6	He said this to put Philip to the test, for He Himself knew what He was going to do.
B043C006V007	43	6	7	»Seven pounds' worth of bread,« replied Philip, »is not enough for them all to get even a scanty meal.«
B043C006V008	43	6	8	One of His disciples, Andrew, Simon Peter's brother, said to Him,
B043C006V009	43	6	9	»There is a boy here with five barley loaves and a couple of fish: but what is that among so many?«
B043C006V010	43	6	10	»Make the people sit down,« said Jesus. The ground was covered with thick grass; so they sat down, the adult men numbering about 5,000.
B043C006V011	43	6	11	Then Jesus took the loaves, and after giving thanks He distributed them to those who were resting on the ground; and also the fish in like manner–as much as they desired.
B043C006V012	43	6	12	When all were fully satisfied, He said to His disciples, »Gather up the broken portions that remain over, so that nothing be lost.«
B043C006V013	43	6	13	Accordingly they gathered them up; and with the fragments of the five barley loaves –the broken portions that remained over after they had done eating– they filled twelve baskets.
B043C006V014	43	6	14	Thereupon the people, having seen the miracle He had performed, said, »This is indeed the Prophet who was to come into the world.«
B043C006V015	43	6	15	Perceiving, however, that they were about to come and carry Him off by force to make Him a king, Jesus withdrew again up the hill alone by Himself.
B043C006V016	43	6	16	When evening came on, His disciples went down to the Lake.
B043C006V017	43	6	17	There they got on board a boat, and pushed off to cross the Lake to Capernaum. By this time it had become dark, and Jesus had not yet joined them.
B043C006V018	43	6	18	The Lake also was getting rough, because a strong wind was blowing.
B043C006V019	43	6	19	When, however, they had rowed three or four miles, they saw Jesus walking on the water and coming near the boat.
B043C006V020	43	6	20	They were terrified; but He called to them. »It is I,« He said, »do not be afraid.«
B043C006V021	43	6	21	Then they were willing to take Him on board; and in a moment the boat reached the shore at the point to which they were going.
B043C006V022	43	6	22	Next morning the crowd who were still standing about on the other side of the Lake found that there had been but one small boat there, and they had seen that Jesus did not go on board with His disciples, but that His disciples went away without Him.
B043C006V023	43	6	23	Yet a number of small boats came from Tiberias to the neighbourhood of the place where they had eaten the bread after the Lord had given thanks.
B043C006V024	43	6	24	When however the crowd saw that neither Jesus nor His disciples were there, they themselves also took boats and came to Capernaum to look for Jesus.
B043C006V025	43	6	25	So when they had crossed the Lake and had found Him, they asked Him, »Rabbi, when did you come here?«
B043C006V026	43	6	26	»In most solemn truth I tell you,« replied Jesus, »that you are searching for me not because you have seen miracles, but because you ate the loaves and had a hearty meal.
B043C006V027	43	6	27	Bestow your pains not on the food which perishes, but on the food that remains unto the Life of the Ages–that food which will be the Son of Man's gift to you; for on Him the Father, God, has set His seal.«
B043C006V028	43	6	28	»What are we to do,« they asked, »in order to carry out the things that God requires?«
B043C006V029	43	6	29	»This,« replied Jesus, »is above all the thing that God requires–that you should be believers in Him whom He has sent.«
B043C006V030	43	6	30	»What miracle then,« they asked, »do you perform for us to see and become believers in you? What do you 
B043C006V031	43	6	31	Our forefathers ate the manna in the Desert, as it is written, 
B043C006V032	43	6	32	»In most solemn truth I tell you,« replied Jesus, »that Moses did not give you the bread out of Heaven, but my Father is giving you the bread –the true bread– out of Heaven.
B043C006V033	43	6	33	For God's bread is that which comes down out of Heaven and gives Life to the world.«
B043C006V034	43	6	34	»Sir,« they said, »always give us that bread.«
B043C006V035	43	6	35	»I am the bread of Life,« replied Jesus; »he who comes to me shall never hunger, and he who believes in me shall never, never thirst.
B043C006V036	43	6	36	But it is as I have said to you: you have seen me and yet you do not believe.
B043C006V037	43	6	37	Every one whom the Father gives me will come to me, and him who comes to me I will never on any account drive away.
B043C006V038	43	6	38	For I have left Heaven and have come down to earth not to seek my own pleasure, but to do the will of Him who sent me.
B043C006V039	43	6	39	And this is the will of Him who sent me, that of all that He has given me I should lose nothing, but should raise it to life on the last day.
B043C006V040	43	6	40	For this is my Father's will, that every one who fixes his gaze on the Son of God and believes in Him should have the Life of the Ages, and I will raise him to life on the last day.«
B043C006V041	43	6	41	Now the Jews began to find fault about Him because of His claiming to be the bread which came down out of Heaven.
B043C006V042	43	6	42	They kept asking, »Is not this man Joseph's son? Is he not Jesus, whose father and mother we know? What does he mean by now saying, `I have come down out of Heaven'?«
B043C006V043	43	6	43	»Do not thus find fault among yourselves,« replied Jesus;
B043C006V044	43	6	44	»no one can come to me unless the Father who sent me draws him; then I will raise him to life on the last day.«
B043C006V045	43	6	45	It stands written in the Prophets, 
B043C006V046	43	6	46	No one has ever seen the Father–except Him who is from God. He has seen the Father.
B043C006V047	43	6	47	»In most solemn truth I tell you that he who believes has the Life of the Ages.
B043C006V048	43	6	48	I am the bread of Life.
B043C006V049	43	6	49	Your forefathers ate the manna in the Desert, and they died.
B043C006V050	43	6	50	Here is the bread that comes down out of Heaven that a man may eat it and not die.
B043C006V051	43	6	51	I am the living bread come down out of Heaven. If a man eats this bread, he shall live for ever. Moreover the bread which I will give is my flesh given for the life of the world.«
B043C006V052	43	6	52	This led to an angry debate among the Jews. »How can this man,« they argued, »give us his flesh to eat?«
B043C006V053	43	6	53	»In most solemn truth I tell you,« said Jesus, »that unless you eat the flesh of the Son of Man and drink His blood, you have no Life in you.
B043C006V054	43	6	54	He who eats my flesh and drinks my blood has the Life of the Ages, and I will raise him up on the last day.
B043C006V055	43	6	55	For my flesh is true food, and my blood is true drink.
B043C006V056	43	6	56	He who eats my flesh and drinks my blood remains in union with me, and I remain in union with him.
B043C006V057	43	6	57	As the ever-living Father has sent me, and I live because of the Father, so also he who eats me will live because of me.
B043C006V058	43	6	58	This is the bread which came down out of Heaven; it is unlike that which your forefathers ate–for they ate and yet died. He who eats this bread shall live for ever.«
B043C006V059	43	6	59	Jesus said all this in the synagogue while teaching at Capernaum.
B043C006V060	43	6	60	Many therefore of His disciples, when they heard it, said, »This is hard to accept. Who can listen to such teaching?«
B043C006V061	43	6	61	But, knowing in Himself that His disciples were dissatisfied about it, Jesus asked them,
B043C006V062	43	6	62	»Does this seem incredible to you? What then if you were to see the Son of Man ascending again where He was before?
B043C006V063	43	6	63	It is the spirit which gives Life. The flesh confers no benefit whatever. The words I have spoken to you are spirit and are Life.
B043C006V064	43	6	64	But there are some of you who do not believe.« For Jesus knew from the beginning who those were that did not believe, and who it was that would betray Him.
B043C006V065	43	6	65	So He added, »That is why I told you that no one can come to me unless it be granted him by the Father.«
B043C006V066	43	6	66	Thereupon many of His disciples left Him and went away, and no longer associated with Him.
B043C006V067	43	6	67	Jesus therefore appealed to the Twelve. »Will you go also?« He asked.
B043C006V068	43	6	68	»Master,« replied Simon Peter, »to whom shall we go? Your teachings tell us of the Life of the Ages.
B043C006V069	43	6	69	And we have come to believe and know that 
B043C006V070	43	6	70	»Did not I choose you–the Twelve?« said Jesus, »and even of you one is a devil.«
B043C006V071	43	6	71	He alluded to Judas, the son of Simon the Iscariot. For he it was who, though one of the Twelve, was afterwards to betray Him.
B043C007V001	43	7	1	After this Jesus moved from place to place in Galilee. He would not go about in Judaea, because the Jews were seeking an opportunity to kill Him.
B043C007V002	43	7	2	But the Jewish Festival of the Tent-Pitching was approaching.
B043C007V003	43	7	3	So His brothers said to Him, »Leave these parts and go into Judaea, that not only we but your disciples also may witness the miracles which you perform.
B043C007V004	43	7	4	For no one acts in secret, desiring all the while to be himself known publicly. Since you are doing these things, show yourself openly to the world.«
B043C007V005	43	7	5	For even His brothers were not believers in Him.
B043C007V006	43	7	6	»My time,« replied Jesus, »has not yet come, but for you any time is suitable.
B043C007V007	43	7	7	It is impossible for the world to hate you; but me it does hate, because I give testimony concerning it that its conduct is evil.
B043C007V008	43	7	8	As for you, go up to the Festival. I do not now go up to this Festival, because my time is not yet fully come.«
B043C007V009	43	7	9	Such was His answer, and He remained in Galilee.
B043C007V010	43	7	10	When however His brothers had gone up to the Festival, then He also went up, not openly, but as it were privately.
B043C007V011	43	7	11	Meanwhile the Jews at the Festival were looking for Him and were inquiring, »Where is he?«
B043C007V012	43	7	12	Among the mass of the people there was much muttered debate about Him. Some said, »He is a good man.« Others said, »Not so: he is imposing on the people.«
B043C007V013	43	7	13	Yet for fear of the Jews no one spoke out boldly about Him.
B043C007V014	43	7	14	But when the Festival was already half over, Jesus went up to the Temple and commenced teaching.
B043C007V015	43	7	15	The Jews were astonished. »How does this man know anything of books,« they said, »although he has never been at any of the schools?«
B043C007V016	43	7	16	Jesus answered their question by saying, »My teaching does not belong to me, but comes from Him who sent me.
B043C007V017	43	7	17	If any one is willing to do His will, he shall know about the teaching, whether it is from God or originates with me.
B043C007V018	43	7	18	The man whose teaching originates with himself aims at his own glory. He who aims at the glory of Him who sent him teaches the truth, and there is no deception in him.
B043C007V019	43	7	19	Did not Moses give you the Law? And yet not a man of you obeys the Law. Why do you want to kill me?«
B043C007V020	43	7	20	»You are possessed by a demon,« replied the crowd; »no one wants to kill you.«
B043C007V021	43	7	21	»One deed I have done,« replied Jesus, »and you are all full of wonder.
B043C007V022	43	7	22	Consider therefore. Moses gave you the rite of circumcision (not that it began with Moses, but with your earlier forefathers), and even on a Sabbath day you circumcise a child.
B043C007V023	43	7	23	If a child is circumcised even on a Sabbath day, are you bitter against me because I have restored a man to perfect health on a Sabbath day?
B043C007V024	43	7	24	Do not form superficial judgements, but form the judgements that are just.«
B043C007V025	43	7	25	Some however of the people of Jerusalem said, »Is not this the man they are wanting to kill?
B043C007V026	43	7	26	But here he is, speaking openly and boldly, and they say nothing to him! Can the Rulers really have ascertained that this man is the Christ?
B043C007V027	43	7	27	And yet we know this man, and we know where he is from; but as for the Christ, when He comes, no one can tell where He is from.«
B043C007V028	43	7	28	Jesus therefore, while teaching in the Temple, cried aloud, and said, »Yes, you know me, and you know where I am from. And yet I have not come of my own accord; but there is One who has sent me, an Authority indeed, of whom you have no knowledge.
B043C007V029	43	7	29	I know Him, because I came from Him, and He sent me.«
B043C007V030	43	7	30	On hearing this they wanted to arrest Him; yet not a hand was laid on Him, because His time had not yet come.
B043C007V031	43	7	31	But from among the crowd a large number believed in Him. »When the Christ comes,« they said, »will He perform more miracles than this teacher has performed?«
B043C007V032	43	7	32	The Pharisees heard the people thus expressing their various doubts about Him, and the High Priests and the Pharisees sent some officers to apprehend Him.
B043C007V033	43	7	33	So Jesus said, »Still for a short time I am with you, and then I go my way to Him who sent me.
B043C007V034	43	7	34	You will look for me and will not find me, and where I am you cannot come.«
B043C007V035	43	7	35	The Jews therefore said to one another, »Where is he about to betake himself, so that we shall not find him? Will he betake himself to the Dispersion among the Gentiles, and teach the Gentiles?
B043C007V036	43	7	36	What do those words of his mean, `You will look for me, but will not find me, and where I am you cannot come'?«
B043C007V037	43	7	37	On the last day of the Festival –the great day– Jesus stood up and cried aloud. »Whoever is thirsty,« He said, »let him come to me and drink.
B043C007V038	43	7	38	He who believes in me, from within him –as the Scripture has said– rivers of living water shall flow.«
B043C007V039	43	7	39	He referred to the Spirit which those who believed in Him were to receive; for the Spirit was not bestowed as yet, because Jesus had not yet been glorified.
B043C007V040	43	7	40	After listening to these discourses, some of the crowd began to say, »This is beyond doubt the Prophet.«
B043C007V041	43	7	41	Others said, »He is the Christ.« But others again, »Not so, for is the Christ to come from Galilee?
B043C007V042	43	7	42	Has not the Scripture declared that the Christ is to come of the family of David and from Bethlehem, David's village?«
B043C007V043	43	7	43	So there was a violent dissension among the people on His account.
B043C007V044	43	7	44	Some of them wanted at once to arrest Him, but no one laid hands upon Him.
B043C007V045	43	7	45	Meanwhile the officers returned to the High Priests and Pharisees, who asked them, »Why have you not brought him?«
B043C007V046	43	7	46	»No mere man has ever spoken as this man speaks,« said the officers.
B043C007V047	43	7	47	»Are 
B043C007V048	43	7	48	»has any one of the Rulers or of the Pharisees believed in him?
B043C007V049	43	7	49	But this rabble who understand nothing about the Law are accursed!«
B043C007V050	43	7	50	Nicodemus interposed–he who had formerly gone to Jesus, being himself one of them.
B043C007V051	43	7	51	»Does our Law,« he asked, »judge a man without first hearing what he has to say and ascertaining what his conduct is?«
B043C007V052	43	7	52	»Do you also come from Galilee?« they asked in reply. »Search and see for yourself that no Prophet is of Galilaean origin.«
B043C007V053	43	7	53	[So they went away to their several homes;
B043C008V001	43	8	1	but Jesus went to the Mount of Olives.
B043C008V002	43	8	2	At break of day however He returned to the Temple, and there the people came to Him in crowds. He seated Himself;
B043C008V003	43	8	3	and was teaching them when the Scribes and the Pharisees brought to Him a woman who had been found committing adultery. They made her stand in the centre of the court, and they put the case to Him.
B043C008V004	43	8	4	»Rabbi,« they said, »this woman has been found in the very act of committing adultery.
B043C008V005	43	8	5	Now, in the Law, Moses has ordered us to stone such women to death. But what do you say?«
B043C008V006	43	8	6	They asked this in order to put Him to the test, so that they might have some charge to bring against Him. But Jesus leant forward and began to write with His finger on the ground.
B043C008V007	43	8	7	When however they persisted with their question, He raised His head and said to them, »Let the sinless man among you be the first to throw a stone at her.«
B043C008V008	43	8	8	Then He leant forward again, and again began to write on the ground.
B043C008V009	43	8	9	They listened to Him, and then, beginning with the eldest, took their departure, one by one, till all were gone. And Jesus was left behind alone–and the woman in the centre of the court.
B043C008V010	43	8	10	Then, raising His head, Jesus said to her, »Where are they? Has no one condemned you?«
B043C008V011	43	8	11	»No one, Sir,« she replied. »And 
B043C008V012	43	8	12	Once more Jesus addressed them. »I am the Light of the world,« He said; »the man who follows me shall certainly not walk in the dark, but shall have the light of Life.«
B043C008V013	43	8	13	»You are giving testimony about yourself,« said the Pharisees; »your testimony is not true.«
B043C008V014	43	8	14	»Even if I am giving testimony about myself,« replied Jesus, »my testimony is true; for I know where I came from and where I am going, but you know neither of these two things.
B043C008V015	43	8	15	You judge according to appearances: I am judging no one.
B043C008V016	43	8	16	And even if I do judge, my judgement is just; for I am not alone, but the Father who sent me is with me.
B043C008V017	43	8	17	In your own Law, too, it is written that 
B043C008V018	43	8	18	I am one giving testimony about myself, and the Father who sent me gives testimony about me.«
B043C008V019	43	8	19	»Where is your Father?« they asked. »You know my Father as little as you know me.« He replied; »if you knew me, you would know my Father also.«
B043C008V020	43	8	20	These sayings He uttered in the Treasury, while teaching in the Temple; yet no one arrested Him, because His time had not yet come.
B043C008V021	43	8	21	Again He said to them, »I am going away. Then you will try to find me, but you will die in your sins. Where I am going, it is impossible for you to come.«
B043C008V022	43	8	22	The Jews began to ask one another, »Is he going to kill himself, do you think, that he says, `Where I am going, it is impossible for you to come'?«
B043C008V023	43	8	23	»You,« He continued, »are from below, I am from above: you are of this present world, I am not of this present world.
B043C008V024	43	8	24	That is why I told you that you will die in your sins; for, unless you believe that I am He, that is what will happen.«
B043C008V025	43	8	25	»You–who are you?« they asked. »How is it that I am speaking to you at all?« replied Jesus.
B043C008V026	43	8	26	»Many things I have to speak and to judge concerning you. But He who sent me is true, and the things which I have heard from Him are those which I have come into the world to speak.«
B043C008V027	43	8	27	They did not perceive that He was speaking to them of the Father.
B043C008V028	43	8	28	So Jesus added, »When you have lifted up the Son of Man, then you will know that I am He. Of myself I do nothing; but as the Father has taught me, so I speak.
B043C008V029	43	8	29	And He who sent me is with me. He has not left me alone: for I do always what is pleasing to Him.«
B043C008V030	43	8	30	As He thus spoke, many became believers in Him.
B043C008V031	43	8	31	Jesus therefore said to those of the Jews who had now believed in Him, »As for you, if you hold fast to my teaching, then you are truly my disciples;
B043C008V032	43	8	32	and you shall know the Truth, and the Truth will make you free.«
B043C008V033	43	8	33	»We are descendants of Abraham,« they answered, »and have never at any time been in slavery to any one. What do those words of yours mean, `You shall become free'?«
B043C008V034	43	8	34	»In most solemn truth I tell you,« replied Jesus, »that every one who commits sin is the slave of sin.
B043C008V035	43	8	35	Now a slave does not remain permanently in his master's house, but a son does.
B043C008V036	43	8	36	If then the Son shall make you free, you will be free indeed.
B043C008V037	43	8	37	You are descendants of Abraham, I know; but you want to kill me, because my teaching gains no ground within you.
B043C008V038	43	8	38	The words I speak are those I have learnt in the presence of the Father. Therefore you also should do what you have heard from your father.«
B043C008V039	43	8	39	»Our father is Abraham,« they said. »If you were Abraham's children,« replied Jesus, »it is Abraham's deeds that you would be doing.
B043C008V040	43	8	40	But, in fact, you are longing to kill me, a man who has spoken to you the truth which I have heard from God. Abraham did not do that.
B043C008V041	43	8	41	You are doing the deeds of your father. »We,« they replied, »are not illegitimate children. We have one Father, namely God.«
B043C008V042	43	8	42	»If God were your Father,« said Jesus, »you would love me; for it is from God that I came and I am now here. I have not come of myself, but 
B043C008V043	43	8	43	How is it you do not understand me when I speak? It is because you cannot bear to listen to my words.
B043C008V044	43	8	44	The father whose sons you are is the Devil; and you desire to do what gives him pleasure. 
B043C008V045	43	8	45	But because I speak the truth, you do not believe me.
B043C008V046	43	8	46	Which of 
B043C008V047	43	8	47	He who is a child of God listens to God's words. You do not listen to them: and why? It is because you are not God's children.«
B043C008V048	43	8	48	»Are we not right,« answered the Jews, »in saying that you are a Samaritan and are possessed by a demon?«
B043C008V049	43	8	49	»I am not possessed by a demon,« replied Jesus. »On the contrary I honour my Father, and you dishonour me.
B043C008V050	43	8	50	I, however, am not aiming at glory for myself: there is One who aims at glory for me–and who judges.
B043C008V051	43	8	51	In most solemn truth I tell you that if any one shall have obeyed my teaching he shall in no case ever see death.«
B043C008V052	43	8	52	»Now,« exclaimed the Jews, »we know that you are possessed by a demon. Abraham died, and so did the Prophets, and yet 
B043C008V053	43	8	53	Are you really greater than our forefather Abraham? For he died. And the prophets died. Who do you make yourself out to be?«
B043C008V054	43	8	54	»Were I to glorify myself,« answered Jesus, »I should have no real glory. There is One who glorifies me–namely my Father, who you say is your God.
B043C008V055	43	8	55	You do not know Him, but I know Him perfectly; and were I to deny my knowledge of Him, I should resemble you, and be a liar. On the contrary I do know Him, and I obey His commands.
B043C008V056	43	8	56	Abraham your forefather exulted in the hope of seeing my day: and he saw it, and was glad.«
B043C008V057	43	8	57	»You are not yet fifty years old,« cried the Jews, »and have you seen Abraham?«
B043C008V058	43	8	58	»In most solemn truth,« answered Jesus, »I tell you that before Abraham came into existence, I am.«
B043C008V059	43	8	59	Thereupon they took up stones with which to stone Him, but He hid Himself and went away out of the Temple.
B043C009V001	43	9	1	As He passed by, He saw a man who had been blind from his birth.
B043C009V002	43	9	2	So His disciples asked Him, »Rabbi, who sinned –this man or his parents– that he was born blind?«
B043C009V003	43	9	3	»Neither he nor his parents sinned,« answered Jesus, »but he was born blind in order that God's mercy might be openly shown in him.
B043C009V004	43	9	4	We must do the works of Him who sent me while there is daylight. Night is coming on, when no one can work.
B043C009V005	43	9	5	When I am in the world, I am the Light of the world.«
B043C009V006	43	9	6	After thus speaking, He spat on the ground, and then, kneading the dust and spittle into clay, He smeared the clay over the man's eyes and said to him,
B043C009V007	43	9	7	»Go and wash in the pool of Siloam« –the name means `Sent.' So he went and washed his eyes, and returned able to see.
B043C009V008	43	9	8	His neighbours, therefore, and the other people to whom he had been a familiar object because he was a beggar, began asking, »Is not this the man who used to sit and beg?«
B043C009V009	43	9	9	»Yes it is,« replied some of them. »No it is not,« said others, »but he is like him.« His own statement was, »I am the man.«
B043C009V010	43	9	10	»How then were your eyes opened?« they asked.
B043C009V011	43	9	11	»He whose name is Jesus,« he answered, »made clay and smeared my eyes with it, and then told me to go to Siloam and wash. So I went and washed and obtained sight.«
B043C009V012	43	9	12	»Where is he?« they inquired, but the man did not know.
B043C009V013	43	9	13	They brought him to the Pharisees–the man who had been blind.
B043C009V014	43	9	14	Now the day on which Jesus made the clay and opened the man's eyes was the Sabbath.
B043C009V015	43	9	15	So the Pharisees renewed their questioning as to how he had obtained his sight. »He put clay on my eyes,« he replied, »and I washed, and now I can see.«
B043C009V016	43	9	16	This led some of the Pharisees to say, »That man has not come from God, for he does not keep the Sabbath.«»How is it possible for a bad man to do such miracles?« argued others.
B043C009V017	43	9	17	And there was a division among them. So again they asked the once blind man, »What is your account of him? –for he opened your eyes.«»He is a Prophet,« he replied.
B043C009V018	43	9	18	The Jews, however, did not believe the statement concerning him –that he had been blind and had obtained his sight– until they called his parents and asked them,
B043C009V019	43	9	19	»Is this your son, who you say was born blind? How is it then that he can now see?«
B043C009V020	43	9	20	»We know,« replied the parents, »that this is our son and that he was born blind;
B043C009V021	43	9	21	but how it is that he can now see or who has opened his eyes we do not know. Ask him himself; he is of full age; he himself will give his own account of it.«
B043C009V022	43	9	22	Such was their answer, because they were afraid of the Jews; for the Jews had already settled among themselves that if any one should acknowledge Jesus as the Christ, he should be excluded from the synagogue.
B043C009V023	43	9	23	That was why his parents said, »He is of full age: ask him himself.«
B043C009V024	43	9	24	A second time therefore they called the man who had been blind, and said, »Give God the praise: we know that that man is a sinner.«
B043C009V025	43	9	25	»Whether he is a sinner or not, I do not know,« he replied; »one thing I know–that I was once blind and that now I can see.«
B043C009V026	43	9	26	»What did he do to you?« they asked; »how did he open your eyes?«
B043C009V027	43	9	27	»I have told you already,« he replied, »and you did not listen to me. Why do you want to hear it again? Do you also mean to be disciples of his?«
B043C009V028	43	9	28	Then they railed at him, and said, »You are that man's disciple, but we are disciples of Moses.
B043C009V029	43	9	29	We know that God spoke to Moses; but as for this fellow we do not know where he comes from.«
B043C009V030	43	9	30	»Why, this is marvellous!« the man replied; »you do not know where he comes from, and yet he has opened my eyes!
B043C009V031	43	9	31	We know that God does not listen to bad people, but that if any one is a God-fearing man and obeys Him, to him He listens.
B043C009V032	43	9	32	From the beginning of the world such a thing was never heard of as that any one should open the eyes of a man blind from his birth.
B043C009V033	43	9	33	Had that man not come from God, he could have done nothing.«
B043C009V034	43	9	34	»You,« they replied, »were wholly begotten and born in sin, and do 
B043C009V035	43	9	35	Jesus heard that they had done this. So having found him, He asked him, »Do you believe in the Son of God?«
B043C009V036	43	9	36	»Who is He, Sir?« replied the man. »Tell me, so that I may believe in Him.«
B043C009V037	43	9	37	»You have seen Him,« said Jesus; »and not only so: He is now speaking to you.«
B043C009V038	43	9	38	»I believe, Sir,« he said. And he threw himself at His feet.
B043C009V039	43	9	39	»I came into this world,« said Jesus, »to judge men, that those who do not see may see, and that those who do see may become blind.«
B043C009V040	43	9	40	These words were heard by those of the Pharisees who were present, and they asked Him, »Are 
B043C009V041	43	9	41	»If you were blind,« answered Jesus, »you would have no sin; but as a matter of fact you boast that you see. So your sin remains!«
B043C010V001	43	10	1	»In most solemn truth I tell you that the man who does not enter the sheepfold by the door, but climbs over some other way, is a thief and a robber.
B043C010V002	43	10	2	But he who enters by the door is the shepherd of the sheep.
B043C010V003	43	10	3	To him the porter opens the door, and the sheep hear his voice; and he calls his own sheep by their names and leads them out.
B043C010V004	43	10	4	When he has brought out his own sheep –all of them– he walks at the head of them; and the sheep follow him, because they know his voice.
B043C010V005	43	10	5	But a stranger they will by no means follow, but will run away from him, because they do not know the voice of strangers.«
B043C010V006	43	10	6	Jesus spoke to them in this figurative language, but they did not understand what He meant.
B043C010V007	43	10	7	Again therefore Jesus said to them, »In most solemn truth I tell you that I am the Door of the sheep.
B043C010V008	43	10	8	All who have come before me are thieves and robbers; but the sheep would not listen to them.
B043C010V009	43	10	9	I am the Door. If any one enters by me, he will find safety, and will go in and out and find pasture.
B043C010V010	43	10	10	The thief comes only to steal and kill and destroy: I have come that they may have Life, and may have it in abundance.
B043C010V011	43	10	11	»I am the Good Shepherd. A good shepherd lays down his very life for the sheep.«
B043C010V012	43	10	12	The hired servant –one who is not a shepherd and does not own the sheep– no sooner sees the wolf coming than he leaves the sheep and runs away; and the wolf worries and scatters them.
B043C010V013	43	10	13	For he is only a hired servant and cares nothing for the sheep.
B043C010V014	43	10	14	»I am the Good Shepherd. And I know my sheep and my sheep know me,
B043C010V015	43	10	15	just as the Father knows me and I know the Father; and I am laying down my life for the sheep.
B043C010V016	43	10	16	I have also other sheep–which do not belong to this fold. Those also I must bring, and they will listen to my voice; and they shall become one flock under one Shepherd.
B043C010V017	43	10	17	For this reason my Father loves me, because I am laying down my life in order to receive it back again.
B043C010V018	43	10	18	No one is taking it away from me, but I myself am laying it down. I am authorized to lay it down, and I am authorized to receive it back again. This is the command I received from my Father.«
B043C010V019	43	10	19	Again there arose a division among the Jews because of these words.
B043C010V020	43	10	20	Many of them said, »He is possessed by a demon and is mad. Why do you listen to him?«
B043C010V021	43	10	21	Others argued, »That is not the language of a demoniac: and can a demon open blind men's eyes?«
B043C010V022	43	10	22	The Dedication Festival came on in Jerusalem. It was winter,
B043C010V023	43	10	23	and Jesus was walking in the Temple in Solomon's Portico,
B043C010V024	43	10	24	when the Jews gathered round Him and kept asking Him, »How long do you mean to keep us in suspense? If you are the Christ, tell us so plainly.«
B043C010V025	43	10	25	»I have told you,« answered Jesus, »and you do not believe. The deeds that I do in my Father's name–they give testimony about me.
B043C010V026	43	10	26	But you do not believe, because you are not my sheep.
B043C010V027	43	10	27	My sheep listen to my voice, and I know them, and they follow me.
B043C010V028	43	10	28	I give them the Life of the Ages, and they shall never, never perish, nor shall any one wrest them from my hand.
B043C010V029	43	10	29	What my Father has given me is more precious than all besides; and no one is able to wrest anything from my Father's hand.
B043C010V030	43	10	30	I and the Father are one.«
B043C010V031	43	10	31	Again the Jews brought stones with which to stone Him.
B043C010V032	43	10	32	Jesus remonstrated with them. »Many good deeds,« He said, »have I shown you as coming from the Father; for which of them are you going to stone me?«
B043C010V033	43	10	33	»For no good deed,« the Jews replied, »are we going to stone you, but for blasphemy, and because you, who are only a man, are making yourself out to be God.«
B043C010V034	43	10	34	»Does it not stand written in your Law,« replied Jesus, 
B043C010V035	43	10	35	If those to whom God's word was addressed are called gods (and the Scripture cannot be annulled),
B043C010V036	43	10	36	how is it that you say to one whom the Father consecrated and sent into the world, `You are blaspheming,' because I said, `I am God's Son'?
B043C010V037	43	10	37	If the deeds I do are not my Father's deeds, do not believe me.
B043C010V038	43	10	38	But if they are, then even if you do not believe me, at least believe the deeds, that you may know and see clearly that the Father is in me, and that I am in the Father.«
B043C010V039	43	10	39	This made them once more try to arrest Him, but He withdrew out of their power.
B043C010V040	43	10	40	Then He went away again to the other side of the Jordan, to the place where John had been baptizing at first; and there He stayed.
B043C010V041	43	10	41	Large numbers of people also came to Him. Their report was, »John did not work any miracle, but all that John said about this Teacher was true.«
B043C010V042	43	10	42	And many became believers in Him there.
B043C011V001	43	11	1	Now a certain man, named Lazarus, of Bethany, was lying ill– Bethany being the village of Mary and her sister Martha.
B043C011V002	43	11	2	(It was the Mary who poured the perfume over the Lord and wiped His feet with her hair, whose brother Lazarus was ill.)
B043C011V003	43	11	3	So the sisters sent to Him to say, »Master, he whom you hold dear is ill.«
B043C011V004	43	11	4	Jesus received the message and said, »This illness is not to end in death, but is to promote the glory of God, in order that the Son of God may be glorified by it.«
B043C011V005	43	11	5	Now Jesus loved Martha, and her sister, and Lazarus.
B043C011V006	43	11	6	When, however, He heard that Lazarus was ill, He still remained two days in that same place.
B043C011V007	43	11	7	Then, after that, He said to the disciples, »Let us return to Judaea.«
B043C011V008	43	11	8	»Rabbi,« exclaimed the disciples, »the Jews have just been trying to stone you, and do you think of going back there again?«
B043C011V009	43	11	9	»Are there not twelve hours in the day?« replied Jesus. »If any one walks in the daytime, he does not stumble–because he sees the light of this world.
B043C011V010	43	11	10	But if a man walks by night, he does stumble, because the light is not in him.«
B043C011V011	43	11	11	He said this, and afterwards He added, »Our friend Lazarus is sleeping, but I will go and wake him.«
B043C011V012	43	11	12	»Master,« said the disciples, »if he is asleep he will recover.«
B043C011V013	43	11	13	Now Jesus had spoken of his death, but they thought He referred to the rest taken in ordinary sleep.
B043C011V014	43	11	14	So then He told them plainly,
B043C011V015	43	11	15	»Lazarus is dead; and for your sakes I am glad I was not there, in order that you may believe. But let us go to him.«
B043C011V016	43	11	16	»Let us go also,« Thomas, the Twin, said to his fellow disciples, »that we may die with him.«
B043C011V017	43	11	17	On His arrival Jesus found that Lazarus had already been three days in the tomb.
B043C011V018	43	11	18	Bethany was near Jerusalem, the distance being a little less than two miles;
B043C011V019	43	11	19	and a considerable number of the Jews were with Martha and Mary, having come to express sympathy with them on the death of their brother.
B043C011V020	43	11	20	Martha, however, as soon as she heard the tidings, »Jesus is coming,« went to meet Him; but Mary remained sitting in the house.
B043C011V021	43	11	21	So Martha came and spoke to Jesus. »Master, if you had been here,« she said, »my brother would not have died.
B043C011V022	43	11	22	And even now I know that whatever you ask God for, God will give you.«
B043C011V023	43	11	23	»Your brother shall rise again,« replied Jesus.
B043C011V024	43	11	24	»I know,« said Martha, »that he will rise again at the resurrection, on the last day.«
B043C011V025	43	11	25	»I am the Resurrection and the Life,« said Jesus; »he who believes in me, even if he has died, he shall live;
B043C011V026	43	11	26	and every one who is living and is a believer in me shall never, never die. Do you believe this?«
B043C011V027	43	11	27	»Yes, Master,« she replied; »I thoroughly believe that you are the Christ, the Son of God, who was to come into the world.«
B043C011V028	43	11	28	After saying this, she went and called her sister Mary privately, telling her, »The Rabbi is here and is asking for you.«
B043C011V029	43	11	29	So she, on hearing that, rose up quickly to go to Him.
B043C011V030	43	11	30	Now Jesus was not yet come into the village, but was still at the place where Martha had met Him.
B043C011V031	43	11	31	So the Jews who were with Mary in the house sympathizing with her, when they saw that she had risen hastily and had gone out, followed her, supposing that she was going to the tomb to weep aloud there.
B043C011V032	43	11	32	Mary then, when she came to Jesus and saw Him, fell at His feet and exclaimed, »Master, if you had been here, my brother would not have died.«
B043C011V033	43	11	33	Seeing her weeping aloud, and the Jews in like manner weeping who had come with her, Jesus, curbing the strong emotion of His spirit,
B043C011V034	43	11	34	though deeply troubled, asked them, »Where have you laid him?«»Master, come and see,« was their reply.
B043C011V035	43	11	35	Jesus wept.
B043C011V036	43	11	36	»See how dear he held him,« said the Jews.
B043C011V037	43	11	37	But others of them asked, »Was this man who opened the blind man's eyes unable to prevent this man from dying?«
B043C011V038	43	11	38	Jesus, however, again restraining His strong feeling, came to the tomb. It was a cave, and a stone had been laid against the mouth of it.
B043C011V039	43	11	39	»Take away the stone,« said Jesus. Martha, the sister of the dead man, exclaimed, »Master, by this time there is a foul smell; for it is three days since he died.«
B043C011V040	43	11	40	»Did I not promise you,« replied Jesus, »that if you believe, you shall see the glory of God?«
B043C011V041	43	11	41	So they removed the stone. Then Jesus lifted up His eyes and said, »Father, I thank Thee that Thou hast heard me.
B043C011V042	43	11	42	I know that Thou always hearest me; but for the sake of the crowd standing round I have said this–that they may believe that Thou didst send me.«
B043C011V043	43	11	43	After speaking thus, He called out in a loud voice, »Lazarus, come out.«
B043C011V044	43	11	44	The dead man came out, his hands and feet wrapped in cloths, and his face wrapped round with a towel. »Untie him,« said Jesus, »and let him go free.«
B043C011V045	43	11	45	Thereupon a considerable number of the Jews– namely those who had come to Mary and had witnessed His deeds– became believers in Him;
B043C011V046	43	11	46	though some of them went off to the Pharisees and told them what He had done.
B043C011V047	43	11	47	Therefore the High Priests and the Pharisees held a meeting of the Sanhedrin. »What steps are we taking?« they asked one another; »for this man is performing a great number of miracles.
B043C011V048	43	11	48	If we leave him alone in this way, everybody will believe in him, and the Romans will come and blot out both our city and our nation.«
B043C011V049	43	11	49	But one of them, named Caiaphas, being High Priest that year, said, »You know nothing about it.
B043C011V050	43	11	50	You do not reflect that it is to your interest that one man should die for the people rather than the whole nation perish.«
B043C011V051	43	11	51	It was not as a mere man that he thus spoke. But being High Priest that year he was inspired to declare that Jesus was to die for the nation,
B043C011V052	43	11	52	and not for the nation only, but in order to unite into one body all the far-scattered children of God.
B043C011V053	43	11	53	So from that day forward they planned and schemed in order to put Him to death.
B043C011V054	43	11	54	Therefore Jesus no longer went about openly among the Jews, but He left that neighbourhood and went into the district near the Desert, to a town called Ephraim, and remained there with the disciples.
B043C011V055	43	11	55	The Jewish Passover was coming near, and many from that district went up to Jerusalem before the Passover, to purify themselves.
B043C011V056	43	11	56	They therefore looked out for Jesus, and asked one another as they stood in the Temple, »What do you think? –will he come to the Festival at all?«
B043C011V057	43	11	57	Now the High Priests and the Pharisees had issued orders that if any one knew where He was, he should give information, so that they might arrest Him.
B043C012V001	43	12	1	Jesus, however, six days before the Passover, came to Bethany, where Lazarus was whom He had raised from the dead.
B043C012V002	43	12	2	So they gave a dinner there in honour of Jesus, at which Martha waited at table, but Lazarus was one of the guests who were with Him.
B043C012V003	43	12	3	Availing herself of the opportunity, Mary took a pound weight of pure spikenard, very costly, and poured it over His feet, and wiped His feet with her hair, so that the house was filled with the fragrance of the perfume.
B043C012V004	43	12	4	Then said Judas (the Iscariot, one of the Twelve–the one who afterwards betrayed Jesus),
B043C012V005	43	12	5	»Why was not that perfume sold for 300 shillings and the money given to the poor?«
B043C012V006	43	12	6	The reason he said this was not that he cared for the poor, but that he was a thief, and that being in charge of the money-box, he used to steal what was put into it.
B043C012V007	43	12	7	But Jesus interposed. »Do not blame her,« He said, »allow her to have kept it for the time of my preparation for burial.
B043C012V008	43	12	8	For the poor you always have with you, but you have not me always.«
B043C012V009	43	12	9	Now it became widely known among the Jews that Jesus was there; but they came not only on His account, but also in order to see Lazarus whom He had brought back to life.
B043C012V010	43	12	10	The High Priests, however, consulted together to put Lazarus also to death,
B043C012V011	43	12	11	for because of him many of the Jews left them and became believers in Jesus.
B043C012V012	43	12	12	The next day a great crowd of those who had come to the Festival, hearing that Jesus was coming to Jerusalem,
B043C012V013	43	12	13	took branches of the palm trees and went out to meet Him, shouting as they went, »God save him! 
B043C012V014	43	12	14	And Jesus, having procured a young ass, sat upon it, just as the Scripture says,
B043C012V015	43	12	15	
        
B043C012V016	43	12	16	The meaning of this His disciples did not understand at the time; but after Jesus was glorified they recollected that this was written about Him, and that they had done this to Him.
B043C012V017	43	12	17	The large number of people, however, who had been present when He called Lazarus out of the tomb and brought him back to life, related what they had witnessed.
B043C012V018	43	12	18	This was also why the crowd came to meet Him, because they had heard of His having performed that miracle.
B043C012V019	43	12	19	The result was that the Pharisees said among themselves, »Observe how idle all your efforts are! The world is gone after him!«
B043C012V020	43	12	20	Now some of those who used to come up to worship at the Festival were Greeks.
B043C012V021	43	12	21	They came to Philip, of Bethsaida in Galilee, with the request, »Sir, we wish to see Jesus.«
B043C012V022	43	12	22	Philip came and told Andrew: Andrew and Philip told Jesus.
B043C012V023	43	12	23	His answer was, »The time has come for the Son of Man to be glorified.
B043C012V024	43	12	24	In most solemn truth I tell you that unless the grain of wheat falls into the ground and dies, it remains what it was–a single grain; but that if it dies, it yields a rich harvest.
B043C012V025	43	12	25	He who holds his life dear, is destroying it; and he who makes his life of no account in this world shall keep it to the Life of the Ages.
B043C012V026	43	12	26	If a man wishes to be my servant, let him follow me; and where I am, there too shall my servant be. If a man wishes to be my servant, the Father will honour him.
B043C012V027	43	12	27	Now is my soul full of trouble; and what shall I say? Father, save me from this hour. But for this purpose I have come to this hour.
B043C012V028	43	12	28	Father, glorify Thy name.« Thereupon there came a voice from the sky, »I have glorified it and will also glorify it again.«
B043C012V029	43	12	29	The crowd that stood by and heard it, said that there had been thunder. Others said, »An angel spoke to him.«
B043C012V030	43	12	30	»It is not for my sake,« said Jesus, »that that voice came, but for your sakes.
B043C012V031	43	12	31	Now is a judgement of this world: now will the Prince of this world be driven out.
B043C012V032	43	12	32	And I – if I am lifted up from the earth– will draw all men to me.«
B043C012V033	43	12	33	He said this to indicate the kind of death He would die.
B043C012V034	43	12	34	The crowd answered Him, »We have heard out of the Law that the Christ remains for ever. In what sense do you say that the Son of Man must be lifted up? Who is that Son of Man?«
B043C012V035	43	12	35	»Yet a little while,« He replied, »the light is among you. Be faithful to the light that you have, for fear darkness should overtake you; for a man who walks in the dark does not know where he is going.
B043C012V036	43	12	36	In the degree that you have light, believe in the Light, so that you may become sons of Light.« Jesus said this, and went away and hid Himself from them.
B043C012V037	43	12	37	But though He had performed such great miracles in their presence, they did not believe in Him–
B043C012V038	43	12	38	in order that the words of Isaiah the Prophet might be fulfilled, 
B043C012V039	43	12	39	For this reason they were unable to believe–because Isaiah said again,
B043C012V040	43	12	40	
        
B043C012V041	43	12	41	Isaiah uttered these words because he saw His glory; and he spoke of Him.
B043C012V042	43	12	42	Nevertheless even from among the Rulers many believed in Him. But because of the Pharisees they did not avow their belief, for fear they should be shut out from the synagogue.
B043C012V043	43	12	43	For they loved the glory that comes from men rather than the glory that comes from God.
B043C012V044	43	12	44	But Jesus cried aloud, »He who believes in me, believes not so much in me, as in Him who sent me;
B043C012V045	43	12	45	and he who sees me sees Him who sent me.
B043C012V046	43	12	46	I have come like light into the world, in order that no one who believes in me may remain in the dark.
B043C012V047	43	12	47	And if any one hears my teachings and regards them not, I do not judge him; for I did not come to judge the world, but to save the world.
B043C012V048	43	12	48	He who sets me at naught and does not receive my teachings is not left without a judge: the Message which I have spoken will judge him on the last day.
B043C012V049	43	12	49	Because I have not spoken on my own authority; but the Father who sent me, Himself gave me a command what to say and in what words to speak.
B043C012V050	43	12	50	And I know that His command is the Life of the Ages. What therefore I speak, I speak just as the Father has bidden me.«
B043C013V001	43	13	1	Now just before the Feast of the Passover this incident took place. Jesus knew that the time had come for Him to leave this world and go to the Father; and having loved His own who were in the world, He loved them to the end.
B043C013V002	43	13	2	While supper was proceeding, the Devil having by this time suggested to Judas Iscariot, the son of Simon, the thought of betraying Him, Jesus,
B043C013V003	43	13	3	although He knew that the Father had put everything into His hands, and that He had come forth from God and was now going to God,
B043C013V004	43	13	4	rose from the table, threw off His upper garments, and took a towel and tied it round Him.
B043C013V005	43	13	5	Then He poured water into a basin, and proceeded to wash the feet of the disciples and to wipe them with the towel which He had put round Him.
B043C013V006	43	13	6	When He came to Simon Peter, Peter objected. »Master,« he said, »are 
B043C013V007	43	13	7	»What I am doing,« answered Jesus, »for the present you do not know, but afterwards you shall know.«
B043C013V008	43	13	8	»Never, while the world lasts,« said Peter, »shall you wash my feet.«»If I do not wash you,« replied Jesus, »you have no share with me.«
B043C013V009	43	13	9	»Master,« said Peter, »wash not only my feet, but also my hands and my head.«
B043C013V010	43	13	10	»Any one who has lately bathed,« said Jesus, »does not need to wash more than his feet, but is clean all over. And you my disciples are clean, and yet this is not true of all of you.«
B043C013V011	43	13	11	For He knew who was betraying Him, and that was why He said, »You are not all of you clean.«
B043C013V012	43	13	12	So after He had washed their feet, put on His garments again, and returned to the table, He said to them, »Do you understand what I have done to you?
B043C013V013	43	13	13	You call me `The Rabbi' and `The Master,' and rightly so, for such I am.
B043C013V014	43	13	14	If I then, your Master and Rabbi, have washed your feet, it is also your duty to wash one another's feet.
B043C013V015	43	13	15	For I have set you an example in order that you may do what I have done to you.
B043C013V016	43	13	16	In most solemn truth I tell you that a servant is not superior to his master, nor is a messenger superior to him who sent him.
B043C013V017	43	13	17	If you know all this, blessed are you if you act accordingly.
B043C013V018	43	13	18	I am not speaking of all of you. I know whom I have chosen, but things are as they are in order that the Scripture may be fulfilled, which says, 
B043C013V019	43	13	19	From this time forward I tell you things before they happen, in order that when they do happen you may believe that I am He.
B043C013V020	43	13	20	In most solemn truth I tell you that he who receives whoever I send receives me, and that he who receives me receives Him who sent me.«
B043C013V021	43	13	21	After speaking thus Jesus was troubled in spirit and said with deep earnestness, »In most solemn truth I tell you that one of you will betray me.«
B043C013V022	43	13	22	The disciples began looking at one another, at a loss to know to which of them He was referring.
B043C013V023	43	13	23	There was at table one of His disciples –the one Jesus loved– reclining with his head on Jesus's bosom.
B043C013V024	43	13	24	Making a sign therefore to him, Simon Peter said, »Tell us to whom he is referring.«
B043C013V025	43	13	25	So he, having his head on Jesus's bosom, leaned back and asked, »Master, who is it?«
B043C013V026	43	13	26	»It is the one,« answered Jesus, »for whom I shall dip this piece of bread and to whom I shall give it.« Accordingly He dipped the piece of bread, and took it and gave it to Judas, the son of the Iscariot Simon.
B043C013V027	43	13	27	Then, after Judas had received the piece of bread, Satan entered into him. »Lose no time about it,« said Jesus to him.
B043C013V028	43	13	28	But why He said this no one else at the table understood.
B043C013V029	43	13	29	Some, however, supposed that because Judas had the money-box Jesus meant, »Buy what we require for the Festival,« or that he should give something to the poor.
B043C013V030	43	13	30	So Judas took the piece of bread and immediately went out. And it was night.
B043C013V031	43	13	31	So when he was gone out, Jesus said, »Now is the Son of Man glorified, and God is glorified in Him.
B043C013V032	43	13	32	Moreover God will glorify Him in Himself, and will glorify Him without delay.
B043C013V033	43	13	33	Dear children, I am still with you a little longer. You will seek me, but, as I said to the Jews, `Where I am going you cannot come,' so for the present I say to you.
B043C013V034	43	13	34	A new commandment I give you, to love one another; that as I have loved you, you also may love one another.
B043C013V035	43	13	35	It is by this that every one will know that you are my disciples–if you love one another.«
B043C013V036	43	13	36	»Master,« inquired Simon Peter, »where are you going?«»Where I am going,« replied Jesus, »you cannot be my follower now, but you shall be later.«
B043C013V037	43	13	37	»Master,« asked Peter again, »why cannot I follow you now? I will lay down my life on your behalf.
B043C013V038	43	13	38	»You say you will lay down your life on my behalf!« said Jesus; »in most solemn truth I tell you that the cock will not crow before you have three times disowned me.«
B043C014V001	43	14	1	»Let not your hearts be troubled. Trust in God: trust in me also.
B043C014V002	43	14	2	In my Father's house there are many resting-places. Were it otherwise, I would have told you; for I am going to make ready a place for you.
B043C014V003	43	14	3	And if I go and make ready a place for you, I will return and take you to be with me, that where I am you also may be.
B043C014V004	43	14	4	And where I am going, you all know the way.«
B043C014V005	43	14	5	»Master,« said Thomas, »we do not know where you are going. In what sense do we know the way?«
B043C014V006	43	14	6	»I am the Way,« replied Jesus, »and the Truth and the Life. No one comes to the Father except through me.
B043C014V007	43	14	7	If you –all of you– knew me, you would fully know my Father also. From this time forward you know Him and have seen Him.«
B043C014V008	43	14	8	»Master,« said Philip, »cause us to see the Father: that is all we need.«
B043C014V009	43	14	9	»Have I been so long among you,« Jesus answered, »and yet you, Philip, do not know me? He who has seen me has seen the Father. How can 
B043C014V010	43	14	10	Do you not believe that I am in the Father and that the Father is in me? The things that I tell you all I do not speak on my own authority: but the Father dwelling within me carries on His own work.
B043C014V011	43	14	11	Believe me, all of you, that I am in the Father and that the Father is in me; or at any rate, believe me because of what I do.
B043C014V012	43	14	12	In most solemn truth I tell you that he who trusts in me–the things which I do he shall do also; and greater things than these he shall do, because I am going to the Father.
B043C014V013	43	14	13	And whatever any of you ask in my name, I will do, in order that the Father may be glorified in the Son.
B043C014V014	43	14	14	If you make any request of me in my name, I will do it.
B043C014V015	43	14	15	»If you love me, you will obey my commandments.
B043C014V016	43	14	16	And I will ask the Father, and He will give you another Advocate to be for ever with you–the Spirit of truth.
B043C014V017	43	14	17	That Spirit the world cannot receive, because it does not see Him or know Him. You know Him, because He remains by your side and is in you.
B043C014V018	43	14	18	I will not leave you bereaved: I am coming to you.
B043C014V019	43	14	19	Yet a little while and the world will see me no more, but you will see me: because I live, you also shall live.
B043C014V020	43	14	20	At that time you will know that I am in my Father, and that you are in me, and that I am in you.
B043C014V021	43	14	21	He who has my commandments and obeys them–he it is who loves me. And he who loves me will be loved by my Father, and I will love him and will clearly reveal myself to him.«
B043C014V022	43	14	22	Judas (not the Iscariot) asked, »Master, how is it that you will reveal yourself clearly to us and not to the world?«
B043C014V023	43	14	23	»If any one loves me,« replied Jesus, »he will obey my teaching; and my Father will love him, and we will come to him and make our home with him.
B043C014V024	43	14	24	He who has no love for me does not obey my teaching; and yet the teaching to which you are listening is not mine, but is the teaching of the Father who sent me.
B043C014V025	43	14	25	»All this I have spoken to you while still with you.«
B043C014V026	43	14	26	But the Advocate, the Holy Spirit whom the Father will send at my request, will teach you everything, and will bring to your memories all that I have said to you.
B043C014V027	43	14	27	Peace I leave with you: my own peace I give to you. It is not as the world gives its greetings that I give you peace. Let not your hearts be troubled or dismayed.
B043C014V028	43	14	28	»You heard me say to you, `I am going away, and yet I am coming to you.' If you loved me, you would have rejoiced because I am going to the Father; for the Father is greater than I am.
B043C014V029	43	14	29	I have now told you before it comes to pass, that when it has come to pass you may believe.
B043C014V030	43	14	30	In future I shall not talk much with you, for the Prince of this world is coming. And yet in me he has nothing;
B043C014V031	43	14	31	but it is in order that the world may know that I love the Father, and that it is in obedience to the command which the Father gave me that I thus act. Rise, let us be going.«
B043C015V001	43	15	1	»I am the Vine–the True Vine, and my Father is the vine-dresser.«
B043C015V002	43	15	2	Every branch in me–if it bears no fruit, He takes away; and every branch that bears fruit He prunes, that it may bear more fruit.
B043C015V003	43	15	3	Already you are cleansed–through the teaching which I have given you.
B043C015V004	43	15	4	Continue in me, and let me continue in you. Just as the branch cannot bear fruit of itself –that is, if it does not continue in the vine– so neither can you if you do not continue in me.
B043C015V005	43	15	5	I am the Vine, you are the branches. He who continues in me and in whom I continue bears abundant fruit, for apart from me you can do nothing.
B043C015V006	43	15	6	If any one does not continue in me, he is like the unfruitful branch which is at once thrown away and then withers up. Such branches they gather up and throw into the fire and they are burned.
B043C015V007	43	15	7	»If you continue in me and my sayings continue in you, ask what you will and it shall be done for you.«
B043C015V008	43	15	8	By this is God glorified–by your bearing abundant fruit and thus being true disciples of mine.
B043C015V009	43	15	9	As the Father has loved me, I have also loved you: continue in my love.
B043C015V010	43	15	10	If you obey my commands, you will continue in my love, as I have obeyed my Father's commands and continue in His love.
B043C015V011	43	15	11	»These things I have spoken to you in order that I may have joy in you, and that your joy may become perfect.«
B043C015V012	43	15	12	This is my commandment to you, to love one another as I have loved you.
B043C015V013	43	15	13	No one has greater love than this–a man laying down his life for his friends.
B043C015V014	43	15	14	You are my friends, if you do what I command you.
B043C015V015	43	15	15	No longer do I call you servants, because a servant does not know what his master is doing; but I have called you friends, because all that I have heard from the Father I have made known to you.
B043C015V016	43	15	16	It is not you who chose me, but it is I who chose you and appointed you that you might go and be fruitful and that your fruit might remain; so that whatever petition you present to the Father in my name He may give you.
B043C015V017	43	15	17	»Thus I command you to love one another.«
B043C015V018	43	15	18	If the world hates you, remember that it has first had me as the fixed object of its hatred.
B043C015V019	43	15	19	If you belonged to the world, the world would love its own property. But because you do not belong to the world, and I have chosen you out of the world–for that reason the world hates you.
B043C015V020	43	15	20	Bear in mind what I said to you, `A servant is not superior to his master.' If they have persecuted me, they will also persecute you: if they have obeyed my teaching, they will obey yours also.
B043C015V021	43	15	21	But they will inflict all this suffering upon you on account of your bearing my name–because they do not know Him who sent me.
B043C015V022	43	15	22	»If I had not come and spoken to them, they would have had no sin; but as the case stands they are without excuse for their sin.«
B043C015V023	43	15	23	He who hates me hates my Father also.
B043C015V024	43	15	24	If I had not done among them, as I have, such miracles as no one else ever did, they would have had no sin; but they have in fact seen and also hated both me and my Father.
B043C015V025	43	15	25	But this has been so, in order that the saying may be fulfilled which stands written in their Law, 
B043C015V026	43	15	26	»When the Advocate is come whom I will send to you from the Father's presence –the Spirit of Truth who comes forth from the Father's presence– He will be a witness concerning me.«
B043C015V027	43	15	27	And you also are witnesses, because you have been with me from the first.
B043C016V001	43	16	1	»These things I have spoken to you in order to clear stumbling-blocks out of your path.«
B043C016V002	43	16	2	You will be excluded from the synagogues; nay more, the time is coming when any one who has murdered one of you will suppose he is offering service to God.
B043C016V003	43	16	3	And they will do these things because they have failed to recognize the Father and to discover who I am.
B043C016V004	43	16	4	But I have spoken these things to you in order that when the time for their accomplishment comes you may remember them, and may recollect that I told you. I did not, however, tell you all this at first, because I was still with you.
B043C016V005	43	16	5	But now I an returning to Him who sent me; and not one of you asks me where I am going.
B043C016V006	43	16	6	But grief has filled your hearts because I have said all this to you.
B043C016V007	43	16	7	»Yet it is the truth that I am telling you–it is to your advantage that I go away. For unless I go away, the Advocate will not come to you; but if I go, I will send Him to you.«
B043C016V008	43	16	8	And He, when He comes, will convict the world in respect of sin, of righteousness, and of judgement; –
B043C016V009	43	16	9	of sin, because they do not believe in me;
B043C016V010	43	16	10	of righteousness, because I am going to the Father, and you will no longer see me;
B043C016V011	43	16	11	of judgement, because the Prince of this world is under sentence.
B043C016V012	43	16	12	»I have much more to say to you, but you are unable at present to bear the burden of it.«
B043C016V013	43	16	13	But when He has come –the Spirit of Truth– He will guide you into all the truth. For He will not speak as Himself originating what He says, but all that He hears He will speak, and He will make known the future to you.
B043C016V014	43	16	14	He will glorify me, because He will take of what is mine and will make it known to you.
B043C016V015	43	16	15	Everything that the Father has is mine; that is why I said that the Spirit of Truth takes of what is mine and will make it known to you.
B043C016V016	43	16	16	»A little while and you see me no more, and again a little while and you shall see me.«
B043C016V017	43	16	17	Some of His disciples therefore said to one another, »What does this mean which He is telling us, `A little while and you do not see me, and again a little while and you shall see me,' and `Because I am going to the Father'?«
B043C016V018	43	16	18	So they asked one another repeatedly, »What can that `little while' mean which He speaks of? We do not understand His words.«
B043C016V019	43	16	19	Jesus perceived that they wanted to ask Him, and He said, »Is this what you are questioning one another about–my saying, `A little while and you do not see me, and again a little while and you shall see me'?
B043C016V020	43	16	20	In most solemn truth I tell you that you will weep aloud and lament, but the world will be glad. You will mourn, but your grief will be turned into gladness.
B043C016V021	43	16	21	A woman, when she is in labour, has sorrow, because her time has come. But when she has given birth to the babe, she no longer remembers the pain, because of her joy at a child being born into the world.
B043C016V022	43	16	22	So you also now have sorrow; but I shall see you again, and your hearts will be glad, and your gladness no one will take away from you.
B043C016V023	43	16	23	You will put no questions to me then. »In most solemn truth I tell you that whatever you ask the Father for in my name He will give you.
B043C016V024	43	16	24	As yet you have not asked for anything in my name: ask, and you shall receive, that your hearts may be filled with gladness.
B043C016V025	43	16	25	»All this I have spoken to you in veiled language. The time is coming when I shall no longer speak to you in veiled language, but will tell you about the Father in plain words.«
B043C016V026	43	16	26	At that time you will make your requests in my name; and I do not promise to ask the Father on your behalf,
B043C016V027	43	16	27	for the Father Himself holds you dear, because you have held me dear and have believed that I came from the Father's presence.
B043C016V028	43	16	28	I came from the Father and have come into the world. Again I am leaving the world and am going to the Father.«
B043C016V029	43	16	29	»Ah, now you are using plain language,« said His disciples, »and are uttering no figure of speech!
B043C016V030	43	16	30	Now we know that you have all knowledge, and do not need to be pressed with questions. Through this we believe that you came from God.«
B043C016V031	43	16	31	»Do you at last believe?« replied Jesus.
B043C016V032	43	16	32	»Remember that the time is coming, nay, has already come, for you all to be dispersed each to his own home and to leave me alone. And yet I am not alone, for the Father is with me.«
B043C016V033	43	16	33	»I have spoken all this to you in order that in me you may have peace. In the world you have affliction. But keep up your courage: 
B043C017V001	43	17	1	When Jesus had thus spoken, He raised his eyes towards Heaven and said, »Father, the hour has come. Glorify Thy Son that the Son may glorify Thee;
B043C017V002	43	17	2	even as Thou hast given Him authority over all mankind, so that on all whom Thou hast given Him He may bestow the Life of the Ages.
B043C017V003	43	17	3	And in this consists the Life of the Ages–in knowing Thee the only true God and Jesus Christ whom Thou hast sent.
B043C017V004	43	17	4	I have glorified Thee on earth, having done perfectly the work which by Thine appointment has been mine to do.
B043C017V005	43	17	5	And now, Father, do Thou glorify me in Thine own presence, with the glory that I had in Thy presence before the world existed.
B043C017V006	43	17	6	»I have revealed Thy perfections to the men whom Thou gavest me out of the world. Thine they were, and Thou gavest them to me, and they have obeyed Thy message.«
B043C017V007	43	17	7	Now they know that whatever Thou hast given me is from Thee.
B043C017V008	43	17	8	For the truths which Thou didst teach me I have taught them. And they have received them, and have known for certain that I came out from Thy presence, and have believed that Thou didst send me.
B043C017V009	43	17	9	»I am making request for them: for the world I do not make any request, but for those whom Thou hast given me. Because they are Thine,
B043C017V010	43	17	10	and everything that is mine is Thine, and everything that is Thine is mine; and I am crowned with glory in them.«
B043C017V011	43	17	11	I am now no longer in the world, but they are in the world and I am coming to Thee. »Holy Father, keep them true to Thy name –the name which Thou hast given me to bear– that they may be one, even as we are.
B043C017V012	43	17	12	While I was with them, I kept them true to Thy name –the name Thou hast given me to bear– and I kept watch over them, and not one of them is lost but only he who is doomed to destruction–that the Scripture may be fulfilled.
B043C017V013	43	17	13	»But now I am coming to Thee, and I speak these words while I am in the world, in order that they may have my gladness within them filling their hearts.«
B043C017V014	43	17	14	I have given them Thy Message, and the world has hated them, because they do not belong to the world, just as I do not belong to the world.
B043C017V015	43	17	15	I do not ask that Thou wilt remove them out of the world, but that Thou wilt protect them from the Evil one.
B043C017V016	43	17	16	They do not belong to the world, just as I do not belong to the world.
B043C017V017	43	17	17	Make them holy in the truth: Thy Message is truth.
B043C017V018	43	17	18	Just as Thou didst send me into the world, I also have sent them;
B043C017V019	43	17	19	and on their behalf I consecrate myself, in order that they may become perfectly consecrated in truth.
B043C017V020	43	17	20	»Nor is it for them alone that I make request. It is also for those who trust in me through their teaching;«
B043C017V021	43	17	21	that they may all be one, even as Thou art in me, O Father, and I am in Thee; that they also may be in us; that the world may believe that Thou didst send me.
B043C017V022	43	17	22	And the glory which Thou hast given me I have given them, that they may be one, just as we are one:
B043C017V023	43	17	23	I in them and Thou in me; that they may stand perfected in one; that the world may come to understand that Thou didst send me and hast loved them with the same love as that with which Thou hast loved me.
B043C017V024	43	17	24	»Father, those whom Thou hast given me – I desire that where I am they also may be with me, that they may see the glory –my glory– my gift from Thee, which Thou hast given me because Thou didst love me before the creation of the world.
B043C017V025	43	17	25	And, righteous Father, though the world has failed to recognize Thee, I have known Thee, and these have perceived that Thou didst send me.
B043C017V026	43	17	26	And I have made known Thy name to them and will make it known, that the love with which Thou hast loved me may be in them, and that I may be in them.«
B043C018V001	43	18	1	After offering this prayer Jesus went out with His disciples to a place on the further side of the Ravine of the Cedars, where there was a garden which He entered–Himself and His disciples.
B043C018V002	43	18	2	Now Judas also, who at that very time was betraying Him, knew the place, for Jesus had often resorted there with His disciples.
B043C018V003	43	18	3	So Judas, followed by the battalion and by a detachment of the Temple police sent by the High Priests and Pharisees, came there with torches and lamps and weapons.
B043C018V004	43	18	4	Jesus therefore, knowing all that was about to befall Him, went out to meet them. »Who are you looking for?« He asked them.
B043C018V005	43	18	5	»For Jesus the Nazarene,« was the answer. »I am he,« He replied. (Now Judas who was betraying Him was also standing with them.)
B043C018V006	43	18	6	As soon then as He said to them, »I am he,« they went backwards and fell to the ground.
B043C018V007	43	18	7	Again therefore He asked them, »Who are you looking for?«»For Jesus the Nazarene,« they said.
B043C018V008	43	18	8	»I have told you,« replied Jesus, »that I am he. If therefore you are looking for me, let these my disciples go their way.«
B043C018V009	43	18	9	He made this request in order that the words He had spoken might be fulfilled, »As for those whom Thou hast given me, I have not lost one.«
B043C018V010	43	18	10	Simon Peter, however, having a sword, drew it, and, aiming at the High Priest's servant, cut off his right ear. The servant's name was Malchus.
B043C018V011	43	18	11	Jesus therefore said to Peter, »Put back your sword. Shall I refuse to drink the cup of sorrow which the Father has given me to drink?«
B043C018V012	43	18	12	So the battalion and their tribune and the Jewish police closed in, and took Jesus and bound Him.
B043C018V013	43	18	13	They then brought Him to Annas first; for Annas was the father-in-law of Caiaphas who was High Priest that year.
B043C018V014	43	18	14	(It was this Caiaphas who had advised the Jews, saying, »It is to your interest that one man should die for the People.«)
B043C018V015	43	18	15	Meanwhile Simon Peter was following Jesus, and so also was another disciple. The latter was known to the High Priest, and went in with Jesus into the court of the High Priest's palace.
B043C018V016	43	18	16	But Peter remained standing outside the door, till the disciple who was acquainted with the High Priest came out and induced the portress to let Peter in.
B043C018V017	43	18	17	This led the girl, the portress, to ask Peter, »Are you also one of this man's disciples?«»No, I am not,« he replied.
B043C018V018	43	18	18	Now because it was cold the servants and the police had lighted a charcoal fire, and were standing and warming themselves; and Peter too remained with them, standing and warming himself.
B043C018V019	43	18	19	So the High Priest questioned Jesus about His disciples and His teaching.
B043C018V020	43	18	20	»As for me,« replied Jesus, »I have spoken openly to the world. I have continually taught in some synagogue or in the Temple where all the Jews are wont to assemble, and I have said nothing in secret.
B043C018V021	43	18	21	Why do you question me? Question those who heard what it was I said to them: these witnesses here know what I said.«
B043C018V022	43	18	22	Upon His saying this, one of the officers standing by struck Him with his open hand, asking Him as he did so, »Is that the way you answer the High Priest?«
B043C018V023	43	18	23	»If I have spoken wrongly,« replied Jesus, »bear witness to it as wrong; but if rightly, why that blow?«
B043C018V024	43	18	24	So Annas sent Him bound to Caiaphas the High Priest.
B043C018V025	43	18	25	But Simon Peter remained standing and warming himself, and this led to their asking him, »Are you also one of his disciples?« He denied it, and said, »No, I am not.«
B043C018V026	43	18	26	One of the High Priest's servants, a relative of the man whose ear Peter had cut off, said, »Did I not see you in the garden with him?«
B043C018V027	43	18	27	Once more Peter denied it, and immediately a cock crowed.
B043C018V028	43	18	28	So they brought Jesus from Caiaphas's house to the Praetorium. It was the early morning, and they would not enter the Praetorium themselves for fear of defilement, and in order that they might be able to eat the Passover.
B043C018V029	43	18	29	Accordingly Pilate came out to them and inquired, »What accusation have you to bring against this man?«
B043C018V030	43	18	30	»If the man were not a criminal,« they replied, »we would not have handed him over to you.«
B043C018V031	43	18	31	»Take him yourselves,« said Pilate, »and judge him by your Law.«»We have no power,« replied the Jews, »to put any man to death.«
B043C018V032	43	18	32	They said this that the words might be fulfilled in which Jesus predicted the kind of death He was to die.
B043C018V033	43	18	33	Re-entering the Praetorium, therefore, Pilate called Jesus and asked Him, »Are 
B043C018V034	43	18	34	»Do you say this of yourself, or have others told it you about me?« replied Jesus.
B043C018V035	43	18	35	»Am I a Jew?« exclaimed Pilate; »it is your own nation and the High Priests who have handed you over to me. What have you done?«
B043C018V036	43	18	36	»My kingdom,« replied Jesus, »does not belong to this world. If my kingdom did belong to this world, my subjects would have resolutely fought to save me from being delivered up to the Jews. But, as a matter of fact, my kingdom has not this origin.«
B043C018V037	43	18	37	»So then 
B043C018V038	43	18	38	»What is truth?« said Pilate. But no sooner had he spoken the words than he went out again to the Jews and told them, »I find no crime in him.
B043C018V039	43	18	39	But you have a custom that I should release one prisoner to you at the Passover. So shall I release to you the King of the Jews?«
B043C018V040	43	18	40	With a roar of voices they again cried out, saying, »Not this man, but Barabbas!« Now Barabbas was a robber.
B043C019V001	43	19	1	Then Pilate took Jesus and scourged Him.
B043C019V002	43	19	2	And the soldiers, twisting twigs of thorn into a wreath, put it on His head, and threw round Him a crimson cloak.
B043C019V003	43	19	3	Then they began to march up to Him, saying in a mocking voice, »Hail King of the Jews!« And they struck Him with the palms of their hands.
B043C019V004	43	19	4	Once more Pilate came out and said to the Jews, »See, I am bringing him out to you to let you clearly understand that I find no crime in him.«
B043C019V005	43	19	5	So Jesus came out, wearing the wreath of thorns and the crimson cloak. And Pilate said to them, »See, there is the man.«
B043C019V006	43	19	6	As soon then as the High Priests and the officers saw Him, they shouted »To the cross! To the cross!« »Take him yourselves and crucify him,« said Pilate; »for I, at any rate, find no crime in him.«
B043C019V007	43	19	7	»We,« replied the Jews, »have a Law, and in accordance with that Law he ought to die, for having claimed to be the Son of God.«
B043C019V008	43	19	8	More alarmed than ever, Pilate no sooner heard these words than he re-entered the Praetorium and began to question Jesus.
B043C019V009	43	19	9	»What is your origin?« he asked. But Jesus gave him no answer.
B043C019V010	43	19	10	»Do you refuse to speak even to me?« asked Pilate; »do you not know that I have it in my power either to release you or to crucify you?«
B043C019V011	43	19	11	»You would have had no power whatever over me,« replied Jesus, »had it not been granted you from above. On that account he who has delivered me up to you is more guilty than you are.«
B043C019V012	43	19	12	Upon receiving this answer, Pilate was for releasing Him. But the Jews kept shouting, »If you release this man, you are no friend of Caesar's. Every one who sets himself up as king declares himself a rebel against Caesar.«
B043C019V013	43	19	13	On hearing this, Pilate brought Jesus out, and sat down on the judge's seat in a place called the Pavement–or in Hebrew, Gabbatha.
B043C019V014	43	19	14	It was the day of Preparation for the Passover, about six o'clock in the morning. Then he said to the Jews, »There is your king!«
B043C019V015	43	19	15	This caused a storm of outcries, »Away with him! Away with him! Crucify him!«»Am I to crucify your king?« Pilate asked. »We have no king, except Caesar,« answered the High Priests.
B043C019V016	43	19	16	Then Pilate gave Him up to them to be crucified. Accordingly they took Jesus;
B043C019V017	43	19	17	and He went out carrying His own cross, to the place called Skull-place –or, in Hebrew, Golgotha–
B043C019V018	43	19	18	where they nailed Him to a cross, and two others at the same time, one on each side and Jesus in the middle.
B043C019V019	43	19	19	And Pilate wrote a notice and had it fastened to the top of the cross. It ran thus: JESUS THE NAZARENE, THE KING OF THE JEWS.
B043C019V020	43	19	20	Many of the Jews read this notice, for the place where Jesus was crucified was near the city, and the notice was in three languages–Hebrew, Latin, and Greek.
B043C019V021	43	19	21	This led the Jewish High Priests to remonstrate with Pilate. »You should not write `The King of the Jews,'« they said, »but that he claimed to be King of the Jews.«
B043C019V022	43	19	22	»What I have written I have written,« was Pilate's answer.
B043C019V023	43	19	23	So the soldiers, as soon as they had crucified Jesus, took His garments, including His tunic, and divided them into four parts–one part for each soldier. The tunic was without seam, woven from the top in one piece.
B043C019V024	43	19	24	So they said to one another, »Do not let us tear it. Let us draw lots for it.« This happened that the Scripture might be fulfilled which says, 
B043C019V025	43	19	25	Now standing close to the cross of Jesus were His mother and His mother's sister, Mary the wife of Clopas, and Mary of Magdala.
B043C019V026	43	19	26	So Jesus, seeing His mother, and seeing the disciple whom He loved standing near, said to His mother, »Behold, your son!«
B043C019V027	43	19	27	Then He said to the disciple, »Behold, your mother!« And from that time the disciple received her into his own home.
B043C019V028	43	19	28	After this, Jesus, knowing that everything was now brought to an end, said–that the Scripture might be fulfilled, »I am thirsty.«
B043C019V029	43	19	29	There was a jar of wine standing there. With this wine they filled a sponge, put it on the end of a stalk of hyssop, and lifted it to His mouth.
B043C019V030	43	19	30	As soon as Jesus had taken the wine, He said, »It is finished.« And then, bowing His head, He yielded up His spirit.
B043C019V031	43	19	31	Meanwhile the Jews, because it was the day of Preparation for the Passover, and in order that the bodies might not remain on the crosses during the Sabbath (for that Sabbath was one of special solemnity), requested Pilate to have the legs of the dying men broken, and the bodies removed.
B043C019V032	43	19	32	Accordingly the soldiers came and broke the legs of the first man and also of the other who had been crucified with Jesus.
B043C019V033	43	19	33	Then they came to Jesus Himself: but when they saw that He was already dead, they refrained from breaking His legs.
B043C019V034	43	19	34	One of the soldiers, however, made a thrust at His side with a lance, and immediately blood and water flowed out.
B043C019V035	43	19	35	This statement is the testimony of an eye-witness, and it is true. He knows that he is telling the truth–in order that you also may believe.
B043C019V036	43	19	36	For all this took place that the Scripture might be fulfilled which declares, 
B043C019V037	43	19	37	And again another Scripture says, 
B043C019V038	43	19	38	After this, Joseph of Arimathaea, who was a disciple of Jesus, but for fear of the Jews a secret disciple, asked Pilate's permission to carry away the body of Jesus; and Pilate gave him leave. So he came and removed the body.
B043C019V039	43	19	39	Nicodemus too –he who at first had visited Jesus by night– came bringing a mixture of myrrh and aloes, in weight about seventy or eighty pounds.
B043C019V040	43	19	40	Taking down the body they wrapped it in linen cloths along with the spices, in accordance with the Jewish mode of preparing for burial.
B043C019V041	43	19	41	There was a garden at the place where Jesus had been crucified, and in the garden a new tomb, in which no one had yet been buried.
B043C019V042	43	19	42	Therefore, because it was the day of Preparation for the Jewish Passover, and the tomb was close at hand, they put Jesus there.
B043C020V001	43	20	1	On the first day of the week, very early, while it was still dark, Mary of Magdala came to the tomb and saw that the stone had been removed from it.
B043C020V002	43	20	2	So she ran, as fast as she could, to find Simon Peter and the other disciple –the one who was dear to Jesus– and to tell them, »They have taken the Master out of the tomb, and we do not know where they have put Him.«
B043C020V003	43	20	3	Peter and the other disciple started at once to go to the tomb, both of them running,
B043C020V004	43	20	4	but the other disciple ran faster than Peter and reached it before he did.
B043C020V005	43	20	5	Stooping and looking in, he saw the linen cloths lying there on the ground, but he did not go in.
B043C020V006	43	20	6	Simon Peter, however, also came, following him, and entered the tomb. There on the ground he saw the cloths;
B043C020V007	43	20	7	and the towel, which had been placed over the face of Jesus, not lying with the cloths, but folded up and put by itself.
B043C020V008	43	20	8	Then the other disciple, who had been the first to come to the tomb, also went in and saw and was convinced.
B043C020V009	43	20	9	For until now they had not understood the inspired teaching, that He must rise again from among the dead.
B043C020V010	43	20	10	Then they went away and returned home.
B043C020V011	43	20	11	Meanwhile Mary remained standing near the tomb, weeping aloud. She did not enter the tomb, but as she wept she stooped and looked in,
B043C020V012	43	20	12	and saw two angels clothed in white raiment, sitting one at the head and one at the feet where the body of Jesus had been.
B043C020V013	43	20	13	They spoke to her. »Why are you weeping?« they asked. »Because,« she replied, »they have taken away my Lord, and I do not know where they have put him.«
B043C020V014	43	20	14	While she was speaking, she turned round and saw Jesus standing there, but did not recognize Him.
B043C020V015	43	20	15	»Why are you weeping?« He asked; »who are you looking for?« She, supposing that He was the gardener, replied, »Sir, if you have carried him away, tell me where you have put him and I will remove him.«
B043C020V016	43	20	16	»Mary!« said Jesus. She turned to Him. »Rabboni!« she cried in Hebrew: the word means `Teacher!'
B043C020V017	43	20	17	»Do not cling to me,« said Jesus, »for I have not yet ascended to the Father. But take this message to my brethren: `I am ascending to my Father and your Father, to my God and your God.'«
B043C020V018	43	20	18	Mary of Magdala came and brought word to the disciples. »I have seen the Master,« she said. And she told them that He had said these things to her.
B043C020V019	43	20	19	On that same first day of the week, when it was evening and, for fear of the Jews, the doors of the house where the disciples were, were locked, Jesus came and stood in their midst, and said to them, »Peace be to you!«
B043C020V020	43	20	20	Having said this He showed them His hands and also His side; and the disciples were filled with joy at seeing the Master.
B043C020V021	43	20	21	A second time, therefore, He said to them, »Peace be to you! As the Father sent me, I also now send you.«
B043C020V022	43	20	22	Having said this He breathed upon them and said, »Receive the Holy Spirit.
B043C020V023	43	20	23	If you remit the sins of any persons, they remain remitted to them. If you bind fast the sins of any, they remain bound.«
B043C020V024	43	20	24	Thomas, one of the twelve –surnamed `the Twin'– was not among them when Jesus came.
B043C020V025	43	20	25	So the rest of the disciples told him, »We have seen the Master!« His reply was, »Unless I see in his hands the wound made by the nails and put my finger into the wound, and put my hand into his side, I will never believe it.«
B043C020V026	43	20	26	A week later the disciples were again in the house, and Thomas was with them, when Jesus came –though the doors were locked– and stood in their midst, and said, »Peace be to you.«
B043C020V027	43	20	27	Then He said to Thomas, »Bring your finger here and feel my hands; bring you hand and put it into my side; and do not be ready to disbelieve but to believe.«
B043C020V028	43	20	28	»My Lord and my God!« replied Thomas.
B043C020V029	43	20	29	»Because you have seen me,« replied Jesus, »you have believed. Blessed are those who have not seen and yet have believed.«
B043C020V030	43	20	30	There were also a great number of other signs which Jesus performed in the presence of the disciples, which are not recorded in this book.
B043C020V031	43	20	31	But these have been recorded in order that you may believe that He is the Christ, the Son of God, and that, through believing, you may have Life through His name.
B043C021V001	43	21	1	After this, Jesus again showed Himself to the disciples. It was at the Lake of Tiberias. The circumstances were as follows.
B043C021V002	43	21	2	Simon Peter was with Thomas, called the Twin, Nathanael of Cana in Galilee, the sons of Zabdi, and two others of the Master's disciples.
B043C021V003	43	21	3	Simon Peter said to them, »I am going fishing.«»We will go too,« said they. So they set out and went on board their boat; but they caught nothing that night.
B043C021V004	43	21	4	When, however, day was now dawning, Jesus stood on the beach, though the disciples did not know that it was Jesus.
B043C021V005	43	21	5	He called to them. »Children,« He said, »have you any food there?«»No,« they answered.
B043C021V006	43	21	6	»Throw the net in on the right hand side,« He said, »and you will find fish.« So they threw the net in, and now they could scarcely drag it along for the quantity of fish.
B043C021V007	43	21	7	This made the disciple whom Jesus loved say to Peter, »It is the Master.« Simon Peter therefore, when he heard the words, »It is the Master,« drew on his fisherman's shirt –for he had not been wearing it– put on his girdle, and sprang into the water.
B043C021V008	43	21	8	But the rest of the disciples came in the small boat (for they were not far from land–only about a hundred yards off), dragging the net full of fish.
B043C021V009	43	21	9	As soon as they landed, they saw a charcoal fire burning there, with fish broiling on it, and bread close by.
B043C021V010	43	21	10	Jesus told them to fetch some of the fish which they had just caught.
B043C021V011	43	21	11	So Simon Peter went on board the boat and drew the net ashore full of large fish, 153 in number; and yet, although there were so many, the net had not broken.
B043C021V012	43	21	12	»Come this way and have breakfast,« said Jesus. But not one of the disciples ventured to question Him as to who He was, for they felt sure that it was the Master.
B043C021V013	43	21	13	Then Jesus came and took the bread and gave them some, and the fish in the same way.
B043C021V014	43	21	14	This was now the third occasion on which Jesus showed Himself to the disciples after He had risen from among the dead.
B043C021V015	43	21	15	When they had finished breakfast, Jesus asked Simon Peter, »Simon, son of John, do you love me more than these others do?«»Yes, Master,« was his answer; »you know that you are dear to me.« »Then feed my lambs,« replied Jesus.
B043C021V016	43	21	16	Again a second time He asked him, »Simon, son of John, do you love me?«»Yes, Master,« he said, »you know that you are dear to me.«»Then be a shepherd to my sheep,« He said.
B043C021V017	43	21	17	A third time Jesus put the question:»Simon, son of John, am I dear to you?« It grieved Peter that Jesus asked him the third time, »Am I dear to you?«»Master,« he replied, »you know everything, you can see that you are dear to me.«»Then feed my much-loved sheep,« said Jesus.
B043C021V018	43	21	18	»In most solemn truth I tell you that whereas, when you were young, you used to put on your girdle and walk whichever way you chose, when you have grown old you will stretch out your arms and some one else will put a girdle round you and carry you where you have no wish to go.«
B043C021V019	43	21	19	This He said to indicate the kind of death by which that disciple would bring glory to God; and after speaking thus He said to him, »Follow me.«
B043C021V020	43	21	20	Peter turned round and noticed the disciple whom Jesus loved following–the one who at the supper had leaned back on His breast and had asked, »Master, who is it that is betraying you?«
B043C021V021	43	21	21	On seeing him, Peter asked Jesus, »And, Master, what about him?«
B043C021V022	43	21	22	»If I desire him to remain till I come,« replied Jesus, »what concern is that of yours? You, yourself, must follow me.«
B043C021V023	43	21	23	Hence the report spread among the brethren that that disciple would never die. Yet Jesus did not say, »He is not to die,« but, »If I desire him to remain till I come, what concern is that of yours?«
B043C021V024	43	21	24	That is the disciple who gives his testimony as to these matters, and has written this history; and we know that his testimony is true.
B043C021V025	43	21	25	But there are also many other things which Jesus did–so vast a number indeed that if they were all described in detail, I suppose that the world itself could not contain the books that would have to be written.
B044C001V001	44	1	1	My former narrative, Theophilus, dealt with all that Jesus did and taught as a beginning, down to the day on which,
B044C001V002	44	1	2	after giving instruction through the Holy Spirit to the Apostles whom He had chosen, He was taken up to Heaven.
B044C001V003	44	1	3	He had also, after He suffered, shown Himself alive to them with many sure proofs, appearing to them at intervals during forty days, and speaking of the Kingdom of God.
B044C001V004	44	1	4	And while in their company He charged them not to leave Jerusalem, but to wait for the Father's promised gift. »This you have heard of,« He said, »from me.
B044C001V005	44	1	5	For John indeed baptized with water, but before many days have passed you shall be baptized with the Holy Spirit.«
B044C001V006	44	1	6	Once when they were with Him, they asked Him, »Master, is this the time at which you are about to restore the kingdom of Israel?«
B044C001V007	44	1	7	»It is not for you,« He replied, »to know times or epochs which the Father has reserved within His own authority;
B044C001V008	44	1	8	and yet you will receive power when the Holy Spirit has come upon you, and you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem and in all Judaea and Samaria and to the remotest parts of the earth.«
B044C001V009	44	1	9	When He had said this, and while they were looking at Him, He was carried up, and a cloud closing beneath Him hid Him from their sight.
B044C001V010	44	1	10	But, while they stood intently gazing into the sky as He went, suddenly there were two men in white garments standing by them,
B044C001V011	44	1	11	who said, »Galilaeans, why stand looking into the sky? This same Jesus who has been taken up from you into Heaven will come in just the same way as you have seen Him going into Heaven.«
B044C001V012	44	1	12	Then they returned to Jerusalem from the mountain called the Oliveyard, which is near Jerusalem, about a mile off.
B044C001V013	44	1	13	They entered the city, and they went up to the upper room which was now their fixed place for meeting. Their names were Peter and John, James and Andrew, Philip and Thomas, Bartholomew and Matthew, James the son of Alphaeus, Simon the Zealot, and Judas the brother of James.
B044C001V014	44	1	14	All of these with one mind continued earnest in prayer, together with some women, and Mary the mother of Jesus, and His brothers.
B044C001V015	44	1	15	It was on one of these days that Peter stood up in the midst of the brethren –the entire number of persons present being about 120– and said,
B044C001V016	44	1	16	»Brethren, it was necessary that the Scripture should be fulfilled–the prediction, I mean, which the Holy Spirit uttered by the lips of David, about Judas, who acted as guide to those who arrested Jesus.
B044C001V017	44	1	17	For Judas was reckoned as one of our number, and a share in this ministry was allotted to him.«
B044C001V018	44	1	18	(Now having bought a piece of ground with the money paid for his wickedness he fell there with his face downwards, and, his body bursting open, he became disembowelled.
B044C001V019	44	1	19	This fact became widely known to the people of Jerusalem, so that the place received the name, in their language, of Achel-damach, which means `The Field of Blood.')
B044C001V020	44	1	20	»For it is written in the Book of Psalms,« 
B044C001V021	44	1	21	»It is necessary, therefore, that of the men who have been with us all the time that the Lord Jesus went in and out among us–
B044C001V022	44	1	22	beginning from His baptism by John down to the day on which He was taken up again from us into Heaven–one should be appointed to become a witness with us as to His resurrection.«
B044C001V023	44	1	23	So two names were proposed, Joseph called Bar-sabbas –and surnamed Justus– and Matthias.
B044C001V024	44	1	24	And the brethren prayed, saying, »Thou, Lord, who knowest the hearts of all, show clearly which of these two Thou hast chosen
B044C001V025	44	1	25	to occupy the place in this ministry and Apostleship from which Judas through transgression fell, in order to go to his own place.«
B044C001V026	44	1	26	Then they drew lots between them. The lot fell on Matthias, and a place among the eleven Apostles was voted to him.
B044C002V001	44	2	1	At length, on the day of the Harvest Festival, they had all met in one place;
B044C002V002	44	2	2	when suddenly there came from the sky a sound as of a strong rushing blast of wind. This filled the whole house where they were sitting;
B044C002V003	44	2	3	and they saw tongues of what looked like fire distributing themselves over the assembly, and on the head of each person a tongue alighted.
B044C002V004	44	2	4	They were all filled with the Holy Spirit, and began to speak in foreign languages according as the Spirit gave them words to utter.
B044C002V005	44	2	5	Now there were Jews residing in Jerusalem, devout men from every part of the world.
B044C002V006	44	2	6	So when this noise was heard, they came crowding together, and were amazed because everyone heard his own language spoken.
B044C002V007	44	2	7	They were beside themselves with wonder, and exclaimed, »Are not all these speakers Galilaeans?
B044C002V008	44	2	8	How then does each of us hear his own native language spoken by them?
B044C002V009	44	2	9	Some of us are Parthians, Medes, Elamites. Some are inhabitants of Mesopotamia, of Judaea or Cappadocia, of Pontus or the Asian Province, of Phrygia or Pamphylia,
B044C002V010	44	2	10	of Egypt or of the parts of Africa towards Cyrene. Others are visitors from Rome –being either Jews or converts from heathenism– and others are Cretans or Arabians.
B044C002V011	44	2	11	Yet we all alike hear these Galilaeans speaking in our own language about the wonderful things which God has done.«
B044C002V012	44	2	12	They were all astounded and bewildered, and asked one another, »What can this mean?«
B044C002V013	44	2	13	But others, scornfully jeering, said, »They are brim-full of sweet wine.«
B044C002V014	44	2	14	Peter however, together with the Eleven, stood up and addressed them in a loud voice. »Men of Judaea, and all you inhabitants of Jerusalem,« he said, »be in no uncertainty about this matter but pay attention to what I say.
B044C002V015	44	2	15	For this is not intoxication, as you suppose, it being only the third hour of the day.
B044C002V016	44	2	16	But that which was predicted through the Prophet Joel has happened:
B044C002V017	44	2	17	And it shall come to pass in the last days, God says, that I will pour out My Spirit upon all mankind; and your sons and your daughters shall prophesy, and your young men shall see visions, and your old men shall have dreams;
B044C002V018	44	2	18	and even upon My bondservants, both men and women, at that time, I will pour out My Spirit, and they shall prophesy.
B044C002V019	44	2	19	I will display marvels in the sky above, and signs on the earth below, blood and fire, and pillars of smoke.
B044C002V020	44	2	20	The sun shall be turned into darkness and the moon into blood, to usher in the day of the Lord– that great and illustrious day;
B044C002V021	44	2	21	and every one who calls on the name of the Lord shall be saved.'–
B044C002V022	44	2	22	»Listen, Israelites, to what I say. Jesus, the Nazarene, a man accredited to you from God by miracles and marvels and signs which God did among you through Him, as you yourselves know, Him–«
B044C002V023	44	2	23	delivered up through God's settled purpose and foreknowledge–you by the hands of Gentiles have nailed to a cross and have put to death.
B044C002V024	44	2	24	But God has raised Him to life, having terminated the throes of death, for in fact it was not possible for Him to be held fast by death.
B044C002V025	44	2	25	For David says in reference to Him, 
B044C002V026	44	2	26	
        
B044C002V027	44	2	27	
        
B044C002V028	44	2	28	
        
B044C002V029	44	2	29	»As to the patriarch David, I need hardly remind you, brethren, that he died and was buried, and that we still have his tomb among us.«
B044C002V030	44	2	30	Being a Prophet, however, and knowing that God had solemnly sworn to him to seat a descendant of his upon his throne,
B044C002V031	44	2	31	with prophetic foresight he spoke of the resurrection of the Christ, to the effect that He was not left forsaken in the Unseen World, nor did His body undergo decay.
B044C002V032	44	2	32	This Jesus, God has raised to life– a fact to which all of us testify.
B044C002V033	44	2	33	»Being therefore lifted high by the mighty hand of God, He has received from the Father the promised Holy Spirit and has poured out this which you see and hear.«
B044C002V034	44	2	34	For David did not ascend into Heaven, but he says himself, 
B044C002V035	44	2	35	
        
B044C002V036	44	2	36	»Therefore let the whole House of Israel know beyond all doubt that God has made Him both LORD and CHRIST–this Jesus whom you crucified.«
B044C002V037	44	2	37	Stung to the heart by these words, they said to Peter and the rest of the Apostles, »Brethren, what are we to do?«
B044C002V038	44	2	38	»Repent,« replied Peter, »and be baptized, every one of you, in the name of Jesus Christ, with a view to the remission of your sins, and you shall receive the gift of the Holy Spirit.
B044C002V039	44	2	39	For to you belongs the promise, and to your children, and to all who are far off, whoever the Lord our God may call.«
B044C002V040	44	2	40	And with many more appeals he solemnly warned and entreated them, saying, »Escape from this crooked generation.«
B044C002V041	44	2	41	Those, therefore, who joyfully welcomed his Message were baptized; and on that one day about three thousand persons were added to them;
B044C002V042	44	2	42	and they were constant in listening to the teaching of the Apostles and in their attendance at the Communion, that is, the Breaking of the Bread, and at prayer.
B044C002V043	44	2	43	Fear came upon every one, and many marvels and signs were done by the Apostles.
B044C002V044	44	2	44	And all the believers kept together, and had everything in common.
B044C002V045	44	2	45	They sold their lands and other property, and distributed the proceeds among all, according to every one's necessities.
B044C002V046	44	2	46	And, day by day, attending constantly in the Temple with one accord, and breaking bread in private houses, they took their meals with great happiness and single-heartedness,
B044C002V047	44	2	47	praising God and being regarded with favour by all the people. Also, day by day, the Lord added to their number those whom He was saving.
B044C003V001	44	3	1	One day Peter and John were going up to the Temple for the hour of prayer –the ninth hour– and, just then,
B044C003V002	44	3	2	some men were carrying there one who had been lame from birth, whom they were wont to place every day close to the Beautiful Gate (as it was called) of the Temple, for him to beg from the people as they went in.
B044C003V003	44	3	3	Seeing Peter and John about to go into the Temple, he asked them for alms.
B044C003V004	44	3	4	Peter fixing his eyes on him, as John did also, said, »Look at us.«
B044C003V005	44	3	5	So he looked and waited, expecting to receive something from them.
B044C003V006	44	3	6	»I have no silver or gold,« Peter said, »but what I have, I give you. In the name of Jesus Christ, the Nazarene– walk!«
B044C003V007	44	3	7	Then taking his hand Peter lifted him up, and immediately his feet and ankles were strengthened.
B044C003V008	44	3	8	Leaping up, he stood upright and began to walk, and went into the Temple with them, walking, leaping, and praising God.
B044C003V009	44	3	9	All the people saw him walking and praising God;
B044C003V010	44	3	10	and recognizing him as the man who used to sit at the Beautiful Gate of the Temple asking for alms, they were filled with awe and amazement at what had happened to him.
B044C003V011	44	3	11	While he still clung to Peter and John, the people, awe-struck, ran up crowding round them in what was known as Solomon's Portico.
B044C003V012	44	3	12	Peter, seeing this, spoke to the people. »Israelites,« he said, »why do you wonder at this man? Or why gaze at us, as though by any power or piety of our own we had enabled him to walk?
B044C003V013	44	3	13	The God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, the God of our forefathers, has conferred this honour on His Servant Jesus, whom you delivered up and disowned in the presence of Pilate, when he had decided to let Him go.
B044C003V014	44	3	14	Yes, you disowned the holy and righteous One, and asked as a favour the release of a murderer.
B044C003V015	44	3	15	The Prince of Life you put to death; but God has raised Him from the dead, and we are witnesses as to that.
B044C003V016	44	3	16	It is His name – faith in that name being the condition– which has strengthened this man whom you behold and know; and the faith which He has given has made this man sound and strong again, as you can all see.
B044C003V017	44	3	17	»And now, brethren, I know that it was in ignorance that you did it, as was the case with your rulers also.«
B044C003V018	44	3	18	But in this way God has fulfilled the declarations He made through all the Prophets, that His Christ would suffer.
B044C003V019	44	3	19	Repent, therefore, and reform your lives, so that the record of your sins may be cancelled, and that there may come seasons of revival from the Lord,
B044C003V020	44	3	20	and that He may send the Christ appointed beforehand for you–even Jesus.
B044C003V021	44	3	21	Heaven must receive Him until those times of which God has spoken from the earliest ages through the lips of His holy Prophets–the times of the reconstitution of all things.
B044C003V022	44	3	22	Moses declared, 
B044C003V023	44	3	23	
        
B044C003V024	44	3	24	Yes, and all the Prophets, from Samuel onwards –all who have spoken– have also announced the coming of this present time.
B044C003V025	44	3	25	»You are the heirs of the Prophets, and of the Covenant which God made with your forefathers when He said to Abraham, 
B044C003V026	44	3	26	It is to you first that God, after raising His Servant from the grave, has sent Him to bless you, by causing every one of you to turn from your wickedness.«
B044C004V001	44	4	1	While they were saying this to the people, the Priests, the Commander of the Temple Guard, and the Sadducees came upon them,
B044C004V002	44	4	2	highly incensed at their teaching the people and proclaiming in the case of Jesus the Resurrection from among the dead.
B044C004V003	44	4	3	They arrested the two Apostles and lodged them in custody till the next day; for it was already evening.
B044C004V004	44	4	4	But many of those who had listened to their preaching believed; and the number of the adult men had now grown to be about 5,000.
B044C004V005	44	4	5	The next day a meeting was held in Jerusalem of their Rulers, Elders, and Scribes,
B044C004V006	44	4	6	with Annas the High Priest, Caiaphas, John, Alexander, and the other members of the high-priestly family.
B044C004V007	44	4	7	So they made the Apostles stand in the centre, and demanded of them, »By what power or in what name have you done this?«
B044C004V008	44	4	8	Then Peter was filled with the Holy Spirit, and he replied, »Rulers and Elders of the people,
B044C004V009	44	4	9	if we to-day are under examination concerning the benefit conferred on a man helplessly lame, as to how this man has been cured;
B044C004V010	44	4	10	be it known to you all, and to all the people of Israel, that through the name of Jesus the Anointed, the Nazarene, whom 
B044C004V011	44	4	11	This Jesus is 
B044C004V012	44	4	12	And in no other is the great salvation to be found; for, in fact, there is no second name under Heaven that has been given among men through which we are to be saved.«
B044C004V013	44	4	13	As they looked on Peter and John so fearlessly outspoken –and also discovered that they were illiterate persons, untrained in the schools– they were surprised; and now they recognized them as having been with Jesus.
B044C004V014	44	4	14	And seeing the man standing with them –the man who had been cured– they had no reply to make.
B044C004V015	44	4	15	So they ordered them to withdraw from the Sanhedrin while they conferred among themselves.
B044C004V016	44	4	16	»What are we to do with these men?« they asked one another; for the fact that a remarkable miracle has been performed by them is well known to every one in Jerusalem, and we cannot deny it.
B044C004V017	44	4	17	But to prevent the matter spreading any further among the people, let us stop them by threats from speaking in the future in this name to any one whatever.«
B044C004V018	44	4	18	So they recalled the Apostles, and ordered them altogether to give up speaking or teaching in the name of Jesus.
B044C004V019	44	4	19	But Peter and John replied, »Judge whether it is right in God's sight to listen to you instead of listening to God.
B044C004V020	44	4	20	As for us, what we have seen and heard we cannot help speaking about.«
B044C004V021	44	4	21	The Court added further threats and then let them go, being quite unable to find any way of punishing them on account of the people, because all gave God the glory for the thing that had happened.
B044C004V022	44	4	22	For the man was over forty years of age on whom this miracle of restoration to health had been performed.
B044C004V023	44	4	23	After their release the two Apostles went to their friends, and told them all that the High Priests and Elders had said.
B044C004V024	44	4	24	And they, upon hearing the story, all lifted up their voices to God and said, »O Sovereign Lord, it is Thou who didst make Heaven and earth and sea, and all that is in them,
B044C004V025	44	4	25	and didst say through the Holy Spirit by the lips of our forefather David Thy servant, 
B044C004V026	44	4	26	
        
B044C004V027	44	4	27	»They did indeed assemble in this city in hostility to Thy holy Servant Jesus whom Thou hadst anointed –Herod and Pontius Pilate with the Gentiles and also the tribes of Israel–«
B044C004V028	44	4	28	to do all that Thy power and Thy will had predetermined should be done.
B044C004V029	44	4	29	And now, Lord, listen to their threats, and enable Thy servants to proclaim Thy Message with fearless courage,
B044C004V030	44	4	30	whilst Thou stretchest out Thine arm to cure men, and to give signs and marvels through the name of Thy holy Servant Jesus.«
B044C004V031	44	4	31	When they had prayed, the place in which they were assembled shook, and they were, one and all, filled with the Holy Spirit, and proceeded to tell God's Message with boldness.
B044C004V032	44	4	32	Among all those who had embraced the faith there was but one heart and soul, so that none of them claimed any of his possessions as his own, but everything they had was common property;
B044C004V033	44	4	33	while the Apostles with great force of conviction delivered their testimony as to the resurrection of the Lord Jesus; and great grace was upon them all.
B044C004V034	44	4	34	And, in fact, there was not a needy man among them, for all who were possessors of lands or houses sold them, and brought the money which they realised,
B044C004V035	44	4	35	and gave it to the Apostles, and distribution was made to every one according to his wants.
B044C004V036	44	4	36	In this way Joseph, whom the Apostles gave the name of Bar-nabas –signifying `Son of Encouragement'– a Levite, a native of Cyprus,
B044C004V037	44	4	37	sold a farm which he had, and brought the money and gave it to the Apostles.
B044C005V001	44	5	1	There was a man of the name of Ananias who, with his wife Sapphira, sold some property but,
B044C005V002	44	5	2	with her full knowledge and consent, dishonestly kept back part of the price which he received for it, though he brought the rest and gave it to the Apostles.
B044C005V003	44	5	3	»Ananias,« said Peter, »why has Satan taken possession of your heart, that you should try to deceive the Holy Spirit and dishonestly keep back part of the price paid you for this land?
B044C005V004	44	5	4	While it remained unsold, was not the land your own? And when sold, was it not at your own disposal? How is it that you have cherished this design in your heart? It is not to men you have told this lie, but to God.«
B044C005V005	44	5	5	Upon hearing these words Ananias fell down dead, and all who heard the words were awe-struck.
B044C005V006	44	5	6	The younger men, however, rose, and wrapping the body up, carried it out and buried it.
B044C005V007	44	5	7	About three hours had passed, when his wife came in, knowing nothing of what had happened.
B044C005V008	44	5	8	Peter at once questioned her. »Tell me,« he said, »whether you sold the land for so much.«»Yes,« she replied, »for so much.«
B044C005V009	44	5	9	»How was it,« replied Peter, »that you two agreed to try an experiment upon the Spirit of the Lord? The men who have buried your husband are already at the door, and they will carry you out.«
B044C005V010	44	5	10	Instantly she fell down dead at his feet, and the young men came in and found her dead. So they carried her out and buried her by her husband's side.
B044C005V011	44	5	11	This incident struck terror into the whole Church, and into the hearts of all who heard of it.
B044C005V012	44	5	12	Many signs and marvels continued to be done among the people by the Apostles; and by common consent they all met in Solomon's Portico.
B044C005V013	44	5	13	But none of the others dared to attach themselves to them. Yet the people held them in high honour–
B044C005V014	44	5	14	and more and more believers in the Lord joined them, including great numbers both of men and women–
B044C005V015	44	5	15	so that they would even bring out their sick friends into the streets and lay them on light couches or mats, in order that when Peter came by, at least his shadow might fall on one or other of them.
B044C005V016	44	5	16	The inhabitants, too, of the towns in the neighbourhood of Jerusalem came in crowds, bringing sick persons and some who were harassed by foul spirits, and they were cured, one and all.
B044C005V017	44	5	17	This roused the High Priest. He and all his party –the sect of the Sadducees– were filled with angry jealousy
B044C005V018	44	5	18	and laid hands upon the Apostles, and put them into the public jail.
B044C005V019	44	5	19	But during the night an angel of the Lord opened the prison doors and brought them out, and said,
B044C005V020	44	5	20	»Go and stand in the Temple, and go on proclaiming to the people all this Message of Life.«
B044C005V021	44	5	21	Having received that command they went into the Temple, just before daybreak, and began to teach: So when the High Priest and his party came, and had called together the Sanhedrin as well as all the Elders of the descendants of Israel, they sent to the jail to fetch the Apostles.
B044C005V022	44	5	22	But the officers went and could not find them in the prison. So they came back and brought word,
B044C005V023	44	5	23	saying, »The jail we found quite safely locked, and the warders were on guard at the doors, but upon going in we found no one there.«
B044C005V024	44	5	24	When the Commander of the Temple Guards and the High Priests heard this statement, they were utterly at a loss with regard to it, wondering what would happen next.
B044C005V025	44	5	25	And some one came and brought them word, saying, »The men you put in prison are actually in the Temple, standing there, teaching the people.«
B044C005V026	44	5	26	Upon this the Commander went with the officers, and brought the Apostles; but without using violence; for they were afraid of being stoned by the people.
B044C005V027	44	5	27	So they brought them and made them stand in front of the Sanhedrin. And then the High Priest questioned them.
B044C005V028	44	5	28	»We strictly forbad you to teach in that name–did we not?« he said. »And see, you have filled Jerusalem with your teaching, and are trying to make us responsible for that man's death!«
B044C005V029	44	5	29	Peter and the other Apostles replied, »We must obey God rather than man.
B044C005V030	44	5	30	The God of our forefathers has raised Jesus to life, whom you crucified and put to death.
B044C005V031	44	5	31	God has exalted Him to His right hand as Chief Leader and as Saviour, to give Israel repentance and forgiveness of sins.
B044C005V032	44	5	32	And we –and the Holy Spirit whom God has given to those who obey Him– are witnesses as to these things.«
B044C005V033	44	5	33	Infuriated at getting this answer, they were disposed to kill the Apostles.
B044C005V034	44	5	34	But a Pharisee of the name of Gamaliel, a teacher of the Law, held in honour by all the people, rose from his seat and requested that they should be sent outside the court for a few minutes.
B044C005V035	44	5	35	»Israelites,« he said, »be careful what you are about to do in dealing with these men.
B044C005V036	44	5	36	Years ago Theudas appeared, professing to be a person of importance, and a body of men, some four hundred in number, joined him. He was killed, and all his followers were dispersed and annihilated.
B044C005V037	44	5	37	After him, at the time of the Census, came Judas, the Galilaean, and was the leader in a revolt. He too perished, and all his followers were scattered.
B044C005V038	44	5	38	And now I tell you to hold aloof from these men and leave them alone–for if this scheme or work is of human origin, it will come to nothing.
B044C005V039	44	5	39	But if it is really from God, you will be powerless to put them down–lest perhaps you find yourselves to be actually fighting against God.«
B044C005V040	44	5	40	His advice carried conviction. So they called the Apostles in, and –after flogging them– ordered them not to speak in the name of Jesus, and then let them go.
B044C005V041	44	5	41	They, therefore, left the Sanhedrin and went their way, rejoicing that they had been deemed worthy to suffer disgrace on behalf of the NAME.
B044C005V042	44	5	42	But they did not desist from teaching every day, in the Temple or in private houses, and telling the Good News about Jesus, the Christ.
B044C006V001	44	6	1	About this time, as the number of disciples was increasing, complaints were made by the Greek-speaking Jews against the Hebrews because their widows were habitually overlooked in the daily ministration.
B044C006V002	44	6	2	So the Twelve called together the general body of the disciples and said, »It does not seem fitting that we Apostles should neglect the delivery of God's Message and minister at tables.
B044C006V003	44	6	3	Therefore, brethren, pick out from among yourselves seven men of good repute, full of the Spirit and of wisdom, and we will appoint them to undertake this duty.
B044C006V004	44	6	4	But, as for us, we will devote ourselves to prayer and to the delivery of the Message.«
B044C006V005	44	6	5	The suggestion met with general approval, and they selected Stephen, a man full of faith and of the Holy Spirit, Philip, Prochorus, Nicanor, Timon, Parmenas, and Nicolas, a proselyte of Antioch.
B044C006V006	44	6	6	These men they brought to the Apostles, and, after prayer, they laid their hands upon them.
B044C006V007	44	6	7	Meanwhile God's Message continued to spread, and the number of the disciples in Jerusalem very greatly increased, and very many priests obeyed the faith.
B044C006V008	44	6	8	And Stephen, full of grace and power, performed great marvels and signs among the people.
B044C006V009	44	6	9	But some members of the so-called `Synagogue of the Freed-men,' together with some Cyrenaeans, Alexandrians, Cilicians and men from Roman Asia, were roused to encounter Stephen in debate.
B044C006V010	44	6	10	They were quite unable, however, to resist the wisdom and the Spirit with which he spoke.
B044C006V011	44	6	11	Then they privately put forward men who declared, »We have heard him speak blasphemous things against Moses and against God.«
B044C006V012	44	6	12	In this way they excited the people, the Elders, and the Scribes. At length they came upon him, seized him with violence, and took him before the Sanhedrin.
B044C006V013	44	6	13	Here they brought forward false witnesses who declared, »This fellow is incessantly speaking against the Holy Place and the Law.
B044C006V014	44	6	14	For we have heard him say that Jesus, the Nazarene, will pull this place down to the ground and will change the customs which Moses handed down to us.«
B044C006V015	44	6	15	At once the eyes of all who were sitting in the Sanhedrin were fastened on him, and they saw his face looking just like the face of an angel.
B044C007V001	44	7	1	Then the High Priest asked him, »Are these statements true?«
B044C007V002	44	7	2	The reply of Stephen was, »Sirs –brethren and fathers– listen to me. God Most Glorious appeared to our forefather Abraham when he was living in Mesopotamia, before he settled in Haran,
B044C007V003	44	7	3	and said to him, »`Leave your country and your relatives, and go into whatever land I point out to you.'
B044C007V004	44	7	4	»Thereupon he left Chaldaea and settled in Haran till after the death of his father, when God caused him to remove into this country where you now live.«
B044C007V005	44	7	5	But he gave him no inheritance in it, no, not a single square yard of ground. And yet He promised to bestow the land as a permanent possession on him and his posterity after him–and promised this at a time when Abraham was childless.
B044C007V006	44	7	6	And God declared that Abraham's posterity should for four hundred years make their home in a country not their own, and be reduced to slavery and be oppressed.
B044C007V007	44	7	7	»`And the nation, whichever it is, that enslaves them, I will judge,' said God; `and afterwards they shall come out, and they shall worship Me in this place.'«
B044C007V008	44	7	8	»Then He gave him the Covenant of circumcision, and under this Covenant he became the father of Isaac–whom he circumcised on the eighth day. Isaac became the father of Jacob, and Jacob became the father of the twelve Patriarchs.«
B044C007V009	44	7	9	»The Patriarchs were jealous of Joseph and sold him into slavery in Egypt. But God was with him
B044C007V010	44	7	10	and delivered him from all his afflictions, and gave him favour and wisdom when he stood before Pharaoh, king of Egypt, who appointed him governor over Egypt and all the royal household.«
B044C007V011	44	7	11	But there came a famine throughout the whole of Egypt and Canaan –and great distress– so that our forefathers could find no food.
B044C007V012	44	7	12	When, however, Jacob heard that there was wheat to be had, he sent our forefathers into Egypt; that was the first time.
B044C007V013	44	7	13	On their second visit Joseph made himself known to his brothers, and Pharaoh was informed of Joseph's parentage.
B044C007V014	44	7	14	Then Joseph sent and invited his father Jacob and all his family, numbering seventy-five persons, to come to him,
B044C007V015	44	7	15	and Jacob went down into Egypt. There he died, and so did our forefathers,
B044C007V016	44	7	16	and they were taken to Shechem and were laid in the tomb which Abraham had bought from the sons of Hamor at Shechem for a sum of money paid in silver.
B044C007V017	44	7	17	»But as the time drew near for the fulfilment of the promise which God had made to Abraham, the people became many times more numerous in Egypt,
B044C007V018	44	7	18	until there arose a foreign king over Egypt who knew nothing of Joseph.«
B044C007V019	44	7	19	He adopted a crafty policy towards our race, and oppressed our forefathers, making them cast out their infants so that they might not be permitted to live.
B044C007V020	44	7	20	At this time Moses was born–a wonderfully beautiful child; and for three months he was cared for in his father's house.
B044C007V021	44	7	21	At length he was cast out, but Pharaoh's daughter adopted him, and brought him up as her own son.
B044C007V022	44	7	22	So Moses was educated in all the learning of the Egyptians, and possessed great influence through his eloquence and his achievements.
B044C007V023	44	7	23	»And when he was just forty years old, it occurred to him to visit his brethren the descendants of Israel.«
B044C007V024	44	7	24	Seeing one of them wrongfully treated he took his part, and secured justice for the ill-treated man by striking down the Egyptian.
B044C007V025	44	7	25	He supposed his brethren to be aware that by him God was sending them deliverance; this, however, they did not understand.
B044C007V026	44	7	26	The next day, also, he came and found two of them fighting, and he endeavoured to make peace between them. »`Sirs,' he said, `you are brothers. Why are you wronging one another?'
B044C007V027	44	7	27	»But the man who was doing the wrong resented his interference, and asked,« `Who appointed you magistrate and judge over us?
B044C007V028	44	7	28	Do you mean to kill me as you killed the Egyptian yesterday?'
B044C007V029	44	7	29	»Alarmed at this question, Moses fled from the country and went to live in the land of Midian. There he became the father of two sons.«
B044C007V030	44	7	30	»But at the end of forty years there appeared to him in the Desert of Mount Sinai an angel in the middle of a flame of fire in a bush.«
B044C007V031	44	7	31	When Moses saw this he wondered at the sight; but on his going up to look further, the voice of the Lord was heard, saying,
B044C007V032	44	7	32	»`I am the God of your forefathers, the God of Abraham, of Isaac, and of Jacob.'« Quaking with fear Moses did not dare gaze.
B044C007V033	44	7	33	»`Take off your shoes,' said the Lord, `for the spot on which you are standing is holy ground.«
B044C007V034	44	7	34	I have seen, yes, I have seen the oppression of My people who are in Egypt and have heard their groans, and I have come down to deliver them. And now I will send you to Egypt.'
B044C007V035	44	7	35	»The Moses whom they rejected, asking him, `Who appointed you magistrate and judge?' –that same Moses we find God sending as a magistrate and a deliverer by the help of the angel who appeared to him in the bush.«
B044C007V036	44	7	36	This was he who brought them out, after performing marvels and signs in Egypt and at the Red Sea, and in the Desert for forty years.
B044C007V037	44	7	37	This is the Moses who said to the descendants of Israel, 
B044C007V038	44	7	38	`This is he who was among the Congregation in the Desert, together with the angel who spoke to him on Mount Sinai and with our forefathers, who received ever-living utterances to hand on to us.
B044C007V039	44	7	39	»Our forefathers, however, would not submit to him, but spurned his authority and in their hearts turned back to Egypt.«
B044C007V040	44	7	40	They said to Aaron, »`Make gods for us, to march in front of us; for as for this Moses who brought us out of the land of Egypt, we do not know what has become of him.'
B044C007V041	44	7	41	»Moreover they made a calf at that time, and offered a sacrifice to the idol and kept rejoicing in the gods which their own hands had made.«
B044C007V042	44	7	42	So God turned from them and gave them up to the worship of the Host of Heaven, as it is written in the Book of the Prophets, 
B044C007V043	44	7	43	
        
B044C007V044	44	7	44	»Our forefathers had the Tent of the Testimony in the Desert, built as He who spoke to Moses had instructed him to make it in imitation of the model which he had seen.«
B044C007V045	44	7	45	That Tent was bequeathed to the next generation of our forefathers. Under Joshua they brought it with them when they were taking possession of the land of the Gentile nations, whom God drove out before them. So it continued till David's time.
B044C007V046	44	7	46	David obtained favour with God, and asked leave to provide a dwelling-place for the God of Jacob.
B044C007V047	44	7	47	But it was Solomon who built a house for Him.
B044C007V048	44	7	48	Yet the Most High does not dwell in buildings erected by men's hands. But, as the Prophet declares,
B044C007V049	44	7	49	
        
B044C007V050	44	7	50	
        
B044C007V051	44	7	51	»O stiff-necked men, uncircumcised in heart and ears, you also are continually at strife with the Holy Spirit–just as your forefathers were.«
B044C007V052	44	7	52	Which of the Prophets did not your forefathers persecute? Yes, they killed those who announced beforehand the advent of the righteous One, whose betrayers and murderers you have now become–
B044C007V053	44	7	53	you who received the Law given through angels, and yet have not obeyed it.«
B044C007V054	44	7	54	As they listened to these words, they became infuriated and gnashed their teeth at him.
B044C007V055	44	7	55	But, full of the Holy Spirit and looking up to Heaven, Stephen saw the glory of God, and Jesus standing at God's right hand.
B044C007V056	44	7	56	»I can see Heaven wide open,« he said, »and the Son of Man standing at God's right hand.«
B044C007V057	44	7	57	Upon this, with a loud outcry they stopped their ears, rushed upon Stephen in a body,
B044C007V058	44	7	58	dragged him out of the city, and stoned him, the witnesses throwing off their outer garments and giving them into the care of a young man called Saul.
B044C007V059	44	7	59	So they stoned Stephen, while he prayed, »Lord Jesus, receive my spirit.«
B044C007V060	44	7	60	Then, rising on his knees, he cried aloud, »Lord, do not reckon this sin against them.« And with these words he fell asleep.
B044C008V001	44	8	1	And Saul fully approved of his murder. At this time a great persecution broke out against the Church in Jerusalem, and all except the Apostles were scattered throughout Judaea and Samaria.
B044C008V002	44	8	2	A party of devout men, however, buried Stephen, and made loud lamentation over him.
B044C008V003	44	8	3	But Saul cruelly harassed the Church. He went into house after house, and, dragging off both men and women, threw them into prison.
B044C008V004	44	8	4	Those, however, who were scattered abroad went from place to place spreading the Good News of God's Message;
B044C008V005	44	8	5	while Philip went down to the city of Samaria and proclaimed Christ there.
B044C008V006	44	8	6	Crowds of people, with one accord, gave attention to what they heard from him, listening, and witnessing the signs which he did.
B044C008V007	44	8	7	For, with a loud cry, foul spirits came out of many possessed by them, and many paralytics and lame persons were restored to health.
B044C008V008	44	8	8	And there was great joy in that city.
B044C008V009	44	8	9	Now for some time past there had been a man named Simon living there, who had been practising magic and astonishing the Samaritans, pretending that he was more than human.
B044C008V010	44	8	10	To him people of all classes paid attention, declaring, »This man is the Power of God, known as the great Power.«
B044C008V011	44	8	11	His influence over them arose from their having been, for a long time, bewildered by his sorceries.
B044C008V012	44	8	12	But when Philip began to tell the Good News about the Kingdom of God and about the Name of Jesus Christ, and they embraced the faith, they were baptized, men and women alike.
B044C008V013	44	8	13	Simon himself also believed, and after being baptized remained in close attendance on Philip, and was full of amazement at seeing such signs and such great miracles performed.
B044C008V014	44	8	14	When the Apostles in Jerusalem heard that the Samaritans had accepted God's Message, they sent Peter and John to visit them.
B044C008V015	44	8	15	They, when they came down, prayed for them that they might receive the Holy Spirit:
B044C008V016	44	8	16	for He had not as yet fallen upon any of them. They had only been baptized into the name of the Lord Jesus.
B044C008V017	44	8	17	Then the Apostles placed their hands upon them, and they received the Holy Spirit.
B044C008V018	44	8	18	When, however, Simon saw that it was through the laying on of the Apostles' hands that the Spirit was bestowed, he offered them money.
B044C008V019	44	8	19	»Give me too,« he said, »that power, so that every one on whom I place my hands will receive the Holy Spirit.«
B044C008V020	44	8	20	»Perish your money and yourself,« replied Peter, »because you have imagined that you can obtain God's free gift with money!
B044C008V021	44	8	21	No part or lot have you in this matter, for your heart is not right in God's sight.
B044C008V022	44	8	22	Repent, therefore, of this wickedness of yours, and pray to the Lord, in the hope that the purpose which is in your heart may perhaps be forgiven you.
B044C008V023	44	8	23	For I perceive that you have fallen into the bitterest bondage of unrighteousness.«
B044C008V024	44	8	24	»Pray, both of you, to the Lord for me,« answered Simon, »that nothing of what you have said may come upon me.«
B044C008V025	44	8	25	So the Apostles, after giving a solemn charge and delivering the Lord's Message, travelled back to Jerusalem, making known the Good News also in many of the Samaritan villages.
B044C008V026	44	8	26	And an angel of the Lord said to Philip, »Rise and proceed south to the road that runs down from Jerusalem to Gaza, crossing the Desert.«
B044C008V027	44	8	27	Upon this he rose and went. Now, as it happened, an Ethiopian eunuch who was in a position of high authority with Candace, queen of the Ethiopians, as her treasurer, had visited Jerusalem to worship there,
B044C008V028	44	8	28	and was now on his way home; and as he sat in his chariot he was reading the Prophet Isaiah.
B044C008V029	44	8	29	Then the Spirit said to Philip, »Go and enter that chariot.«
B044C008V030	44	8	30	So Philip ran up and heard the eunuch reading the Prophet Isaiah. »Do you understand what you are reading?« he asked.
B044C008V031	44	8	31	»Why, how can I,« replied the eunuch, »unless some one explains it to me?« And he earnestly invited Philip to come up and sit with him.
B044C008V032	44	8	32	The passage of Scripture which he was reading was this: 
B044C008V033	44	8	33	
        
B044C008V034	44	8	34	»Pray, of whom is the Prophet speaking?« inquired the eunuch; »of himself or of some one else?«
B044C008V035	44	8	35	Then Philip began to speak, and, commencing with that same portion of Scripture, told him the Good News about Jesus.
B044C008V036	44	8	36	So they proceeded on their way till they came to some water; and the eunuch exclaimed, »See, here is water; what is there to prevent my being baptized?«
B044C008V037	44	8	37	[]
B044C008V038	44	8	38	So he stopped the chariot; and both of them –Philip and the eunuch– went down into the water, and Philip baptized him.
B044C008V039	44	8	39	But no sooner had they come up out of the water than the Spirit of the Lord caught Philip away, and the eunuch did not see him again. With a glad heart he resumed his journey;
B044C008V040	44	8	40	but Philip found himself at Ashdod. Then visiting town after town he everywhere made known the Good News until he reached Caesarea.
B044C009V001	44	9	1	Now Saul, whose every breath was a threat of destruction for the disciples of the Lord,
B044C009V002	44	9	2	went to the High Priest and begged from him letters addressed to the synagogues in Damascus, in order that if he found any believers there, either men or women, he might bring them in chains to Jerusalem.
B044C009V003	44	9	3	But on the journey, as he was getting near Damascus, suddenly there flashed round him a light from Heaven;
B044C009V004	44	9	4	and falling to the ground he heard a voice which said to him, »Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting Me?«
B044C009V005	44	9	5	»Who art thou, Lord?« he asked. »I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting,« was the reply.
B044C009V006	44	9	6	»But rise and go to the city, and you will be told what you are to do.«
B044C009V007	44	9	7	Meanwhile the men who travelled with Saul were standing dumb with amazement, hearing a sound, but seeing no one.
B044C009V008	44	9	8	Then he rose from the ground, but when he had opened his eyes, he could not see, and they led him by the arm and brought him to Damascus.
B044C009V009	44	9	9	And for two days he remained without sight, and did not eat or drink anything.
B044C009V010	44	9	10	Now in Damascus there was a disciple of the name of Ananias. The Lord spoke to him in a vision, saying, »Ananias!«»I am here, Lord,« he answered.
B044C009V011	44	9	11	»Rise,« said the Lord, »and go to Straight Street, and inquire at the house of Judas for a man called Saul, from Tarsus, for he is actually praying.
B044C009V012	44	9	12	He has seen a man called Ananias come and lay his hands upon him so that he may recover his sight.«
B044C009V013	44	9	13	»Lord,« answered Ananias, »I have heard about that man from many, and I have heard of the great mischief he has done to Thy people in Jerusalem;
B044C009V014	44	9	14	and here he is authorized by the High Priests to arrest all who call upon Thy name.«
B044C009V015	44	9	15	»Go,« replied the Lord; »he is a chosen instrument of Mine to carry My name to the Gentiles and to kings and to the descendants of Israel.
B044C009V016	44	9	16	For I will let him know the great sufferings which he must pass through for My sake.«
B044C009V017	44	9	17	So Ananias went and entered the house; and, laying his two hands upon Saul, said, »Saul, brother, the Lord –even Jesus who appeared to you on your journey– has sent me, that you may recover your sight and be filled with the Holy Spirit.«
B044C009V018	44	9	18	Instantly there dropped from his eyes what seemed to be scales, and he could see once more. Upon this he rose and received baptism;
B044C009V019	44	9	19	after which he took food and regained his strength. Then he remained some little time with the disciples in Damascus.
B044C009V020	44	9	20	And in the synagogues he began at once to proclaim Jesus as the Son of God;
B044C009V021	44	9	21	and his hearers were all amazed, and began to ask one another, »Is not this the man who in Jerusalem tried to exterminate those who called upon that Name, and came here on purpose to carry them off in chains to the High Priests?«
B044C009V022	44	9	22	Saul, however, gained more and more influence, and as for the Jews living in Damascus, he bewildered them with his proofs that Jesus is the Christ.
B044C009V023	44	9	23	At length the Jews plotted to kill Saul;
B044C009V024	44	9	24	but information of their intention was given to him. They even watched the gates, day and night, in order to murder him;
B044C009V025	44	9	25	but his disciples took him by night and let him down through the wall, lowering him in a hamper.
B044C009V026	44	9	26	So he came to Jerusalem and made several attempts to associate with the disciples, but they were all afraid of him, being in doubt as to whether he himself was a disciple.
B044C009V027	44	9	27	Barnabas, however, came to his assistance. He brought Saul to the Apostles, and related to them how, on his journey, he had seen the Lord, and that the Lord had spoken to him, and how in Damascus he had fearlessly taught in the name of Jesus.
B044C009V028	44	9	28	Henceforth Saul was one of them, going in and out of the city,
B044C009V029	44	9	29	and speaking fearlessly in the name of the Lord. And he often talked with the Hellenists and had discussions with them.
B044C009V030	44	9	30	But they kept trying to take his life. On learning this, the brethren brought him down to Caesarea, and then sent him by sea to Tarsus.
B044C009V031	44	9	31	The Church, however, throughout the whole of Judaea, Galilee and Samaria, had peace and was spiritually built up; and grew in numbers, living in the fear of the Lord and receiving encouragement from the Holy Spirit.
B044C009V032	44	9	32	Now Peter, as he went to town after town, came down also to God's people at Lud.
B044C009V033	44	9	33	There he found a man of the name of Aeneas, who for eight years had kept his bed, through being paralysed.
B044C009V034	44	9	34	Peter said to him, »Aeneas, Jesus Christ cures you. Rise and make your own bed.« He at once rose to his feet.
B044C009V035	44	9	35	And all the people of Lud and Sharon saw him; and they turned to the Lord.
B044C009V036	44	9	36	Among the disciples at Jaffa was a woman called Tabitha, or, as the name may be translated, `Dorcas.' Her life was wholly devoted to the good and charitable actions which she was constantly doing.
B044C009V037	44	9	37	But, as it happened, just at that time she was taken ill and died. After washing her body they laid it out in a room upstairs.
B044C009V038	44	9	38	Lud, however, being near Jaffa, the disciples, who had heard that Peter was at Lud, sent two men to him with an urgent request that he would come across to them without delay.
B044C009V039	44	9	39	So Peter rose and went with them. On his arrival they took him upstairs, and the widow women all came and stood by his side, weeping and showing him the underclothing and cloaks and garments of all kinds which Dorcas used to make while she was still with them.
B044C009V040	44	9	40	Peter, however, putting every one out of the room, knelt down and prayed, and then turning to the body, he said, »Tabitha, rise.« Dorcas at once opened her eyes, and seeing Peter, sat up.
B044C009V041	44	9	41	Then, giving her his hand, he raised her to her feet and, calling to him God's people and the widows, he gave her back to them alive.
B044C009V042	44	9	42	This incident became known throughout Jaffa, and many believed in the Lord;
B044C009V043	44	9	43	and Peter remained for a considerable time at Jaffa, staying at the house of a man called Simon, a tanner.
B044C010V001	44	10	1	Now a Captain of the Italian Regiment, named Cornelius, was quartered at Caesarea.
B044C010V002	44	10	2	He was religious and God-fearing–and so was every member of his household. He was also liberal in his charities to the people, and continually offered prayer to God.
B044C010V003	44	10	3	About three o'clock one afternoon he had a vision, and distinctly saw an angel of God enter his house, who called him by name, saying, »Cornelius!«
B044C010V004	44	10	4	Looking steadily at him, and being much alarmed, he said, »What do you want, Sir?«»Your prayers and charities,« he replied, »have gone up and have been recorded before God.
B044C010V005	44	10	5	And now send to Jaffa and fetch Simon, surnamed Peter.
B044C010V006	44	10	6	He is staying as a guest with Simon, a tanner, who has a house close to the sea.«
B044C010V007	44	10	7	So when the angel who had been speaking to him was gone, Cornelius called two of his servants and a God-fearing soldier who was in constant attendance on him,
B044C010V008	44	10	8	and, after telling them everything, he sent them to Jaffa.
B044C010V009	44	10	9	The next day, while they were still on their journey and were getting near the town, about noon Peter went up on the house-top to pray.
B044C010V010	44	10	10	He had become unusually hungry and wished for food; but, while they were preparing it, he fell into a trance.
B044C010V011	44	10	11	The sky had opened to his view, and what seemed to be an enormous sail was descending, being let down to the earth by ropes at the four corners.
B044C010V012	44	10	12	In it were all kinds of quadrupeds, reptiles and birds,
B044C010V013	44	10	13	and a voice came to him which said, »Rise, Peter, kill and eat.«
B044C010V014	44	10	14	»On no account, Lord,« he replied; »for I have never yet eaten anything unholy and impure.«
B044C010V015	44	10	15	Again a second time a voice was heard which said, »What God has purified, you must not regard as unholy.«
B044C010V016	44	10	16	This was said three times, and immediately the sail was drawn up out of sight.
B044C010V017	44	10	17	While Peter was greatly perplexed as to the meaning of the vision which he had seen, just then the men sent by Cornelius, having by inquiry found out Simon's house,
B044C010V018	44	10	18	had come to the door and had called the servant, and were asking, »Is Simon, surnamed Peter, staying here?«
B044C010V019	44	10	19	And Peter was still earnestly thinking over the vision, when the Spirit said to him, »Three men are now inquiring for you.
B044C010V020	44	10	20	Rise, go down, and go with them without any misgivings; for it is I who have sent them to you.«
B044C010V021	44	10	21	So Peter went down and said to the men, »I am the Simon you are inquiring for. What is the reason of your coming?«
B044C010V022	44	10	22	Their reply was, »Cornelius, a Captain, an upright and God-fearing man, of whom the whole Jewish nation speaks well, has been divinely instructed by a holy angel to send for you to come to his house and listen to what you have to say.«
B044C010V023	44	10	23	Upon hearing this, Peter invited them in, and gave them a lodging. The next day he set out with them, some of the brethren from Jaffa going with him,
B044C010V024	44	10	24	and the day after that they reached Caesarea. There Cornelius was awaiting their arrival, and had invited all his relatives and intimate friends to be present.
B044C010V025	44	10	25	When Peter entered the house, Cornelius met him, and threw himself at his feet to do him homage.
B044C010V026	44	10	26	But Peter lifted him up. »Stand up,« he said; »I myself also am but a man.«
B044C010V027	44	10	27	So Peter went in and conversed with him, and found a large company assembled.
B044C010V028	44	10	28	He said to them, »You know better than most that a Jew is strictly forbidden to associate with a Gentile or visit him; but God has taught me to call no one unholy or unclean.
B044C010V029	44	10	29	So for this reason, when sent for, I came without raising any objection. I therefore ask why you sent for me.«
B044C010V030	44	10	30	»Just at this hour, three days ago,« replied Cornelius, »I was offering afternoon prayer in my house, when suddenly a man in shining raiment stood in front of me,
B044C010V031	44	10	31	who said, »`Cornelius, your prayer has been heard, and your charities have been put on record before God.
B044C010V032	44	10	32	Send therefore to Jaffa, and invite Simon, surnamed Peter, to come here. He is staying as a guest in the house of Simon, a tanner, close to the sea.'
B044C010V033	44	10	33	»Immediately, therefore, I sent to you, and I thank you heartily for having come. That is why all of us are now assembled here in God's presence, to listen to what the Lord has commanded you to say.«
B044C010V034	44	10	34	Then Peter began to speak. »I clearly see,« he said, »that God makes no distinctions between one man and another;
B044C010V035	44	10	35	but that in every nation those who fear Him and live good lives are acceptable to Him.
B044C010V036	44	10	36	The Message which He sent to the descendants of Israel, when He announced the Good News of peace through Jesus Christ –He is Lord of all– that Message you cannot but know;
B044C010V037	44	10	37	the story, I mean, which has spread through the length and breadth of Judaea, beginning in Galilee after the baptism which John proclaimed.
B044C010V038	44	10	38	It tells how God anointed Jesus of Nazareth with the Holy Spirit and with power, so that He went about everywhere doing acts of kindness, and curing all who were being continually oppressed by the Devil–for God was with Jesus.
B044C010V039	44	10	39	»And we are witnesses as to all that He did both in the country of the Jews and in Jerusalem. But they even put Him to death, by crucifixion.«
B044C010V040	44	10	40	That same Jesus God raised to life on the third day, and permitted Him to appear unmistakably,
B044C010V041	44	10	41	not to all the people, but to witnesses –men previously chosen by God– namely, to us, who ate and drank with Him after He rose from the dead.
B044C010V042	44	10	42	And He has commanded us to preach to the people and solemnly declare that this is He who has been appointed by God to be the Judge of the living and the dead.
B044C010V043	44	10	43	To Him all the Prophets bear witness, and testify that through His name all who believe in Him receive the forgiveness of their sins.«
B044C010V044	44	10	44	While Peter was speaking these words, the Holy Spirit fell on all who were listening to the Message.
B044C010V045	44	10	45	And all the Jewish believers who had come with Peter were astonished that on the Gentiles also the gift of the Holy Spirit was poured out.
B044C010V046	44	10	46	For they heard them speaking in tongues and extolling the majesty of God. Then Peter said,
B044C010V047	44	10	47	»Can any one forbid the use of water, and object to these persons being baptized–men who have received the Holy Spirit just as we did?«
B044C010V048	44	10	48	And he directed that they should be baptized in the name of Jesus Christ. Then they begged him to remain with them for a time.
B044C011V001	44	11	1	Now the Apostles, and the brethren in various parts of Judaea, heard that the Gentiles also had received God's Message;
B044C011V002	44	11	2	and, when Peter returned to Jerusalem, the champions of circumcision found fault with him.
B044C011V003	44	11	3	»You went into the houses of men who are not Jews,« they said, »and you ate with them.«
B044C011V004	44	11	4	Peter, however, explained the whole matter to them from the beginning.
B044C011V005	44	11	5	»While I was in the town of Jaffa, offering prayer,« he said, »in a trance I saw a vision. There descended what seemed to be an enormous sail, being let down from the sky by ropes at the four corners, and it came close to me.
B044C011V006	44	11	6	Fixing my eyes on it, I examined it closely, and saw various kinds of quadrupeds, wild beasts, reptiles and birds.
B044C011V007	44	11	7	I also heard a voice saying to me, »`Rise, Peter, kill and eat.'
B044C011V008	44	11	8	»`On no account, Lord,' I replied, `for nothing unholy or impure has ever gone into my mouth.'«
B044C011V009	44	11	9	»But a voice answered, speaking a second time from the sky,« `What God has purified, you must not regard as unholy.'
B044C011V010	44	11	10	»This was said three times, and then everything was drawn up again out of sight.«
B044C011V011	44	11	11	»Now at that very moment three men came to the house where we were, having been sent from Caesarea to find me.«
B044C011V012	44	11	12	And the Spirit told me to accompany them without any misgivings. There also went with me these six brethren who are now present, and we reached the Centurion's house.
B044C011V013	44	11	13	Then he described to us how he had seen the angel come and enter his house and say, »`Send to Jaffa and fetch Simon, surnamed Peter.
B044C011V014	44	11	14	He will teach you truths by which you and all your family will be saved.'«
B044C011V015	44	11	15	»And,« said Peter, »no sooner had I begun to speak than the Holy Spirit fell upon them, just as He fell upon us at the first.
B044C011V016	44	11	16	Then I remembered the Lord's words, how He used to say, »`John baptized with water, but you shall be baptized in the Holy Spirit.'
B044C011V017	44	11	17	»If therefore God gave them the same gift as He gave us when we first believed on the Lord Jesus Christ, why, who was I to be able to thwart God?«
B044C011V018	44	11	18	This statement of Peter's silenced his opponents. They extolled the goodness of God, and said, »So, then, to the Gentiles also God has given the repentance which leads to Life.«
B044C011V019	44	11	19	Those, however, who had been driven in various directions by the persecution which broke out on account of Stephen made their way to Phoenicia, Cyprus and Antioch, delivering the Message to none but Jews.
B044C011V020	44	11	20	But some of them were Cyprians and Cyrenaeans, who, on coming to Antioch, spoke to the Greeks also and told them the Good News concerning the Lord Jesus.
B044C011V021	44	11	21	The power of the Lord was with them, and there were a vast number who believed and turned to the Lord.
B044C011V022	44	11	22	When tidings of this reached the ears of the Church in Jerusalem, they sent Barnabas as far as Antioch.
B044C011V023	44	11	23	On getting there he was delighted to see the grace which God had bestowed; and he encouraged them all to remain, with fixed resolve, faithful to the Lord.
B044C011V024	44	11	24	For he was a good man, and was full of the Holy Spirit and of faith; and the number of believers in the Lord greatly increased.
B044C011V025	44	11	25	Then Barnabas paid a visit to Tarsus to try to find Saul.
B044C011V026	44	11	26	He succeeded, and brought him to Antioch; and for a whole year they attended the meetings of the Church, and taught a large number of people. And it was in Antioch that the disciples first received the name of `Christians.'
B044C011V027	44	11	27	At that time certain Prophets came down from Jerusalem to Antioch,
B044C011V028	44	11	28	one of whom, named Agabus, being instructed by the Spirit, publicly predicted the speedy coming of a great famine throughout the world. (It came in the reign of Claudius.)
B044C011V029	44	11	29	So the disciples decided to send relief, every one in proportion to his means, to the brethren living in Judaea.
B044C011V030	44	11	30	This they did, forwarding their contributions to the Elders by Barnabas and Saul.
B044C012V001	44	12	1	Now, about that time, King Herod arrested certain members of the Church, in order to ill-treat them;
B044C012V002	44	12	2	and James, John's brother, he beheaded.
B044C012V003	44	12	3	Finding that this gratified the Jews, he proceeded to seize Peter also; these being the days of Unleavened Bread.
B044C012V004	44	12	4	He had him arrested and lodged in jail, handing him over to the care of sixteen soldiers; and intended after the Passover to bring him out again to the people.
B044C012V005	44	12	5	So Peter was kept in prison; but long and fervent prayer was offered to God by the Church on his behalf.
B044C012V006	44	12	6	Now when Herod was on the point of taking him out of prison, that very night Peter was asleep between two soldiers, bound with two chains, and guards were on duty outside the door.
B044C012V007	44	12	7	Suddenly an angel of the Lord stood by him, and a light shone in the cell; and, striking Peter on the side, he woke him and said, »Rise quickly.« Instantly the chains dropped off his wrists.
B044C012V008	44	12	8	»Fasten your girdle,« said the angel, »and tie on your sandals.« He did so. Then the angel said, »Throw your cloak round you, and follow me.«
B044C012V009	44	12	9	So Peter went out, following him, yet could not believe that what the angel was doing was real, but supposed that he saw a vision.
B044C012V010	44	12	10	And passing through the first ward and the second, they came to the iron gate leading into the city. This opened to them of itself; and, going out, they passed on through one of the streets, and then suddenly the angel left him.
B044C012V011	44	12	11	Peter coming to himself said, »Now I know for certain that the Lord has sent His angel and has rescued me from the power of Herod and from all that the Jewish people were anticipating.«
B044C012V012	44	12	12	So, after thinking things over, he went to the house of Mary, the mother of John surnamed Mark, where a large number of people were assembled, praying.
B044C012V013	44	12	13	When he knocked at the wicket in the door, a maidservant named Rhoda came to answer the knock;
B044C012V014	44	12	14	and recognizing Peter's voice, for very joy she did not open the door, but ran in and told them that Peter was standing there.
B044C012V015	44	12	15	»You are mad,« they said. But she strenuously maintained that it was true. »It is his guardian angel,« they said.
B044C012V016	44	12	16	Meanwhile Peter went on knocking, until at last they opened the door and saw that it was really he, and were filled with amazement.
B044C012V017	44	12	17	But he motioned with his hand for silence, and then described to them how the Lord had brought him out of the prison. »Tell all this to James and the brethren,« he added. Then he left them, and went to another place.
B044C012V018	44	12	18	When morning came, there was no little commotion among the soldiers, as to what could possibly have become of Peter.
B044C012V019	44	12	19	And when Herod had had him searched for and could not find him, after sharply questioning the guards he ordered them away to execution. He then went down from Judaea to Caesarea and remained there.
B044C012V020	44	12	20	Now the people of Tyre and Sidon had incurred Herod's violent displeasure. So they sent a large deputation to wait on him; and having secured the good will of Blastus, his treasurer, they begged the king to be friendly with them again, because their country was dependent on his for its food supply.
B044C012V021	44	12	21	So, on an appointed day, Herod, having arrayed himself in royal robes, took his seat on the tribunal, and was haranguing them;
B044C012V022	44	12	22	and the assembled people kept shouting, »It is the voice of a god, and not of a man!«
B044C012V023	44	12	23	Instantly an angel of the Lord struck him, because he had not given the glory to God, and being eaten up by worms, he died.
B044C012V024	44	12	24	But God's Message prospered, and converts were multiplied.
B044C012V025	44	12	25	And Barnabas and Saul returned from Jerusalem, having discharged their mission, and they brought with them John, surnamed Mark.
B044C013V001	44	13	1	Now there were in Antioch, in the Church there –as Prophets and teachers– barnabas, Symeon surnamed `the black,' Lucius the Cyrenaean, Manaen (who was Herod the Tetrarch's foster-brother), and Saul.
B044C013V002	44	13	2	While they were worshipping the Lord and fasting, the Holy Spirit said, »Set apart for Me, now at once, Barnabas and Saul, for the work to which I have called them.«
B044C013V003	44	13	3	So, after fasting and prayer and the laying on of hands, they let them go.
B044C013V004	44	13	4	They therefore, being thus sent out by the Holy Spirit, went down to Seleuceia, and from there sailed to Cyprus.
B044C013V005	44	13	5	Having reached Salamis, they began to announce God's Message in the synagogues of the Jews. And they had John as their assistant.
B044C013V006	44	13	6	When they had gone through the whole length of the island as far as Paphos, they there met with a Jewish magician and false prophet, Bar-Jesus by name,
B044C013V007	44	13	7	who was a friend of the Proconsul Sergius Paulus. The Proconsul was a man of keen intelligence. He sent for Barnabas and Saul, and asked to be told God's Message.
B044C013V008	44	13	8	But Elymas (or `the Magician,' for such is the meaning of the name) opposed them, and tried to prevent the Proconsul from accepting the faith.
B044C013V009	44	13	9	Then Saul, who is also called Paul, was filled with the Holy Spirit, and, fixing his eyes on Elymas,
B044C013V010	44	13	10	said, »You who are full of every kind of craftiness and unscrupulous cunning –you son of the Devil and foe to all that is right– will you never cease to misrepresent the straight paths of the Lord?
B044C013V011	44	13	11	The Lord's hand is now upon you, and you will be blind for a time and unable to see the light of day.« Instantly there fell upon him a mist and a darkness, and, as he walked about, he begged people to lead him by the hand.
B044C013V012	44	13	12	Then the Proconsul, seeing what had happened, believed, being struck with amazement at the teaching of the Lord.
B044C013V013	44	13	13	From Paphos, Paul and his party put out to sea and sailed to Perga in Pamphylia. John, however, left them and returned to Jerusalem.
B044C013V014	44	13	14	But they themselves, passing through from Perga, came to Antioch in Pisidia. Here, on the Sabbath day, they went into the synagogue and sat down.
B044C013V015	44	13	15	After the reading of the Law and the Prophets, the Wardens of the synagogue sent word to them. »Brethren,« they said, »if you have anything encouraging to say to the people, speak.«
B044C013V016	44	13	16	So Paul rose, and motioning with his hand for silence, said, »Israelites, and you others who fear God, pay attention to me.
B044C013V017	44	13	17	The God of this people of Israel chose our forefathers, and made the people great during their stay in Egypt, until with wondrous power He brought them out from that land.
B044C013V018	44	13	18	For a period of about forty years, He fed them, like a nurse, in the Desert.
B044C013V019	44	13	19	Then, after overthrowing seven nations in the land of Canaan, He divided that country among them as their inheritance for about four hundred and fifty years;
B044C013V020	44	13	20	and afterwards He gave them judges down to the time of the Prophet Samuel.
B044C013V021	44	13	21	Next they asked for a king, and God gave them Saul the son of Kish, a Benjamite, who reigned forty years.
B044C013V022	44	13	22	After removing him, He raised up David to be their king, to whom He also bore witness when He said, »`I have found David the son of Jesse, a man I love, who will obey all My commands.'
B044C013V023	44	13	23	»It is from among David's descendants that God, in fulfilment of His promise, has raised up a Saviour for Israel, even Jesus.«
B044C013V024	44	13	24	Before the coming of Jesus, John had proclaimed to all the people of Israel a baptism of repentance.
B044C013V025	44	13	25	But John, towards the end of his career, repeatedly asked the people, »`What do you suppose me to be? I am not the Christ. But there is One coming after me whose sandal I am not worthy to unfasten.'
B044C013V026	44	13	26	»Brethren, descendants of the family of Abraham, and all among you who fear God, to us has this Message of salvation been sent.«
B044C013V027	44	13	27	For the people of Jerusalem and their rulers, by the judgement they pronounced on Jesus, have actually fulfilled the predictions of the Prophets which are read Sabbath after Sabbath, through ignorance of those predictions and of Him.
B044C013V028	44	13	28	Without having found Him guilty of any capital offence they urged Pilate to have Him put to death;
B044C013V029	44	13	29	and when they had carried out everything which had been written about Him, they took Him down from the cross and laid Him in a tomb.
B044C013V030	44	13	30	»But God raised Him from the dead.«
B044C013V031	44	13	31	And, after a few days, He appeared to the people who had gone up with Him from Galilee to Jerusalem and are now witnesses concerning Him to the Jews.
B044C013V032	44	13	32	And we bring you the Good News about the promise made to our forefathers,
B044C013V033	44	13	33	that God has amply fulfilled it to our children in raising up Jesus; as it is also written in the second Psalm, 
B044C013V034	44	13	34	And as to His having raised Him from among the dead, never again to be in the position of one soon to return to decay, He speaks thus: 
B044C013V035	44	13	35	Because in another Psalm also He says, 
B044C013V036	44	13	36	For David, after having been useful to his own generation in accordance with God's purpose, did fall asleep, was gathered to his forefathers, and did undergo decay.
B044C013V037	44	13	37	But He whom God raised to life underwent no decay.
B044C013V038	44	13	38	»Understand therefore, brethren, that through this Jesus forgiveness of sins is announced to you;
B044C013V039	44	13	39	and in Him every believer is absolved from all offences, from which you could not be absolved under the Law of Moses.«
B044C013V040	44	13	40	Beware, then, lest what is spoken in the Prophets should come true of you:
B044C013V041	44	13	41	
        
B044C013V042	44	13	42	As Paul and Barnabas were leaving the synagogue, the people earnestly begged to have all this repeated to them on the following Sabbath.
B044C013V043	44	13	43	And, when the congregation had broken up, many of the Jews and of the devout converts from heathenism continued with Paul and Barnabas, who talked to them and urged them to hold fast to the grace of God.
B044C013V044	44	13	44	On the next Sabbath almost the whole population of the city came together to hear the Lord's Message.
B044C013V045	44	13	45	Seeing the crowds, the Jews, filled with angry jealousy, opposed Paul's statements and abused him.
B044C013V046	44	13	46	Then, throwing off all reserve, Paul and Barnabas said, »We were bound to proclaim God's Message to you first. But since you spurn it and judge yourselves to be unworthy of the Life of the Ages–well, we turn to the Gentiles.
B044C013V047	44	13	47	For such is the Lord's command to us. 
B044C013V048	44	13	48	The Gentiles listened with delight and extolled the Lord's Message; and all who were pre-destined to the Life of the Ages believed.
B044C013V049	44	13	49	So the Lord's Message spread through the whole district.
B044C013V050	44	13	50	But the Jews influenced the gentlewomen of rank who worshipped with them, and also the leading men in the city, and stirred up persecution against Paul and Barnabas and drove them out of the district.
B044C013V051	44	13	51	But they shook off the dust from their feet as a protest against them and came to Iconium;
B044C013V052	44	13	52	and as for the disciples, they were more and more filled with joy and with the Holy Spirit.
B044C014V001	44	14	1	At Iconium the Apostles went together to the Jewish synagogue and preached, with the result that a great number both of Jews and Greeks believed.
B044C014V002	44	14	2	But the Jews who had refused obedience stirred up the Gentiles and embittered their minds against the brethren.
B044C014V003	44	14	3	Yet Paul and Barnabas remained there for a considerable time, speaking freely and relying on the Lord, while He bore witness to the Message of His grace by permitting signs and marvels to be done by them.
B044C014V004	44	14	4	At length the people of the city split into parties, some siding with the Jews and some with the Apostles.
B044C014V005	44	14	5	And when a hostile movement was made by both Gentiles and Jews, with the sanction of their magistrates, to maltreat and stone them,
B044C014V006	44	14	6	the Apostles, having become aware of it, made their escape into the Lycaonian towns of Lystra and Derbe, and the neighbouring country.
B044C014V007	44	14	7	And there they continued to tell the Good News.
B044C014V008	44	14	8	Now a man who had no power in his feet used to sit in the streets of Lystra. He had been lame from his birth and had never walked.
B044C014V009	44	14	9	After this man had listened to one of Paul's sermons, the Apostle, looking steadily at him and perceiving that he had faith to be cured,
B044C014V010	44	14	10	said in a loud voice, »Stand upright upon your feet!«
B044C014V011	44	14	11	So he sprang up and began to walk about. Then the crowds, seeing what Paul had done, rent the air with their shouts in the Lycaonian language, saying, »The gods have assumed human form and have come down to us.«
B044C014V012	44	14	12	They called Barnabas `Zeus,' and Paul, as being the principal speaker, `Hermes.'
B044C014V013	44	14	13	And the priest of Zeus –the temple of Zeus being at the entrance to the city– brought bullocks and garlands to the gates, and in company with the crowd was intending to offer sacrifices to them.
B044C014V014	44	14	14	But the Apostles, Barnabas and Paul, heard of it; and tearing their clothes they rushed out into the middle of the crowd, exclaiming, »Sirs, why are you doing all this?
B044C014V015	44	14	15	We also are but men, with natures kindred to your own; and we bring you the Good News that you are to turn from these unreal things, to worship the ever-living God, the Creator of earth and sky and sea and of everything that is in them.
B044C014V016	44	14	16	In times gone by He allowed all the nations to go their own ways;
B044C014V017	44	14	17	and yet by His beneficence He has not left His existence unattested–His beneficence, I mean, in sending you rain from Heaven and fruitful seasons, satisfying your hearts with food and joyfulness.«
B044C014V018	44	14	18	Even with words like these they had difficulty in preventing the thronging crowd from offering sacrifices to them.
B044C014V019	44	14	19	But now a party of Jews came from Antioch and Iconium, and, having won over the crowd, they stoned Paul and dragged him out of the town, believing him to be dead.
B044C014V020	44	14	20	When, however, the disciples had collected round him, he rose and went back into the town. The next day he went with Barnabas to Derbe;
B044C014V021	44	14	21	and, after proclaiming the Good News to the people there and gaining a large number of converts, they retraced their steps to Lystra, Iconium, and Antioch.
B044C014V022	44	14	22	Everywhere they strengthened the disciples by encouraging them to hold fast to the faith, and warned them saying, »It is through many afflictions that we must make our way into the Kingdom of God.«
B044C014V023	44	14	23	And in every Church, after prayer and fasting, they selected Elders by show of hands, and commended them to the Lord on whom their faith rested.
B044C014V024	44	14	24	Then passing through Pisidia they came into Pamphylia;
B044C014V025	44	14	25	and after telling the Message at Perga they came down to Attaleia.
B044C014V026	44	14	26	Thence they sailed to Antioch, where they had previously been commended to the grace of God in connexion with the work which they had now completed.
B044C014V027	44	14	27	Upon their arrival they called the Church together and proceeded to report in detail all that God, working with them, had done, and how He had opened for the Gentiles the door of faith.
B044C014V028	44	14	28	And they remained a considerable time in Antioch with the disciples.
B044C015V001	44	15	1	But certain persons who had come down from Judaea tried to convince the brethren, saying, »Unless you are circumcised in accordance with the Mosaic custom, you cannot be saved.«
B044C015V002	44	15	2	Between these new comers and Paul and Barnabas there was no little disagreement and controversy, until at last it was decided that Paul and Barnabas and some other brethren should go up to consult the Apostles and Elders in Jerusalem on this matter.
B044C015V003	44	15	3	So they set out, being accompanied for a short distance by some other members of the Church; and as they passed through Phoenicia and Samaria, they told the whole story of the conversion of the Gentiles and inspired all the brethren with great joy.
B044C015V004	44	15	4	Upon their arrival in Jerusalem they were cordially received by the Church, the Apostles, and the Elders; and they reported in detail all that God, working with them, had done.
B044C015V005	44	15	5	But certain men who had belonged to the sect of the Pharisees but were now believers, stood up in the assembly, and said, »Yes, Gentile believers ought to be circumcised and be ordered to keep the Law of Moses.«
B044C015V006	44	15	6	Then the Apostles and Elders met to consider the matter;
B044C015V007	44	15	7	and after there had been a long discussion Peter rose to his feet. »It is within your own knowledge,« he said, »that God originally made choice among you that from my lips the Gentiles were to hear the Message of the Good News, and believe.
B044C015V008	44	15	8	And God, who knows all hearts, gave His testimony in their favour by bestowing the Holy Spirit on them just as He did on us;
B044C015V009	44	15	9	and He made no difference between us and them, in that He cleansed their hearts by their faith.
B044C015V010	44	15	10	Now, therefore, why try an experiment upon God, by laying on the necks of these disciples a yoke which neither our forefathers nor we have been able to bear?
B044C015V011	44	15	11	On the contrary, we believe that it is by the grace of the Lord Jesus that we, as well as they, shall be saved.«
B044C015V012	44	15	12	Then the whole assembly remained silent while they listened to the statement made by Paul and Barnabas as to all the signs and marvels that God had done among the Gentiles through their instrumentality.
B044C015V013	44	15	13	When they had finished speaking, James said, »Brethren, listen to me.
B044C015V014	44	15	14	Symeon has related how God first looked graciously on the Gentiles to take from among them a People to be called by His name.
B044C015V015	44	15	15	And this is in harmony with the language of the Prophets, which says:
B044C015V016	44	15	16	`»Afterwards I will return, and will rebuild David's fallen tent. Its ruins I will rebuild, and I will set it up again;
B044C015V017	44	15	17	In order that the rest of mankind may earnestly seek the Lord–even all the nations which are called by My name,«
B044C015V018	44	15	18	Says the Lord, who has been making these things known from ages long past.'
B044C015V019	44	15	19	»My judgement, therefore, is against inflicting unexpected annoyance on those of the Gentiles who are turning to God.
B044C015V020	44	15	20	Yet let us send them written instructions to abstain from things polluted by connexion with idolatry, from fornication, from meat killed by strangling, and from blood.
B044C015V021	44	15	21	For Moses from the earliest times has had his preachers in every town, being read, as he is, Sabbath after Sabbath, in the various synagogues.«
B044C015V022	44	15	22	Thereupon it was decided by the Apostles and Elders, with the approval of the whole Church, to choose suitable persons from among themselves and send them to Antioch, with Paul and Barnabas. Judas, called Bar-sabbas, and Silas, leading men among the brethren, were selected,
B044C015V023	44	15	23	and they took with them the following letter: »The Apostles and the elder brethren send greeting to the Gentile brethren throughout Antioch, Syria and Cilicia.
B044C015V024	44	15	24	As we have been informed that certain persons who have gone out from among us have disturbed you by their teaching and have unsettled your minds, without having received any such instructions from us;
B044C015V025	44	15	25	we have unanimously decided to select certain men and send them to you in company with our dear friends Barnabas and Paul,
B044C015V026	44	15	26	who have endangered their very lives for the sake of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B044C015V027	44	15	27	We have therefore sent Judas and Silas, who are themselves bringing you the same message by word of mouth.
B044C015V028	44	15	28	For it has seemed good to the Holy Spirit and to us to lay upon you no burden heavier than these necessary requirements–
B044C015V029	44	15	29	You must abstain from things sacrificed to idols, from blood, from things strangled, and from fornication. Keep yourselves clear of these things, and it will be well with you. Farewell.«
B044C015V030	44	15	30	They, therefore, having been solemnly sent, came down to Antioch, where they called together the whole assembly and delivered the letter.
B044C015V031	44	15	31	The people read it, and were delighted with the comfort it brought them.
B044C015V032	44	15	32	And Judas and Silas, being themselves also Prophets, gave them a long and encouraging talk, and strengthened them in the faith.
B044C015V033	44	15	33	After spending some time there they received an affectionate farewell from the brethren to return to those who had sent them.
B044C015V034	44	15	34	[]
B044C015V035	44	15	35	But Paul and Barnabas remained in Antioch, teaching and, in company with many others, telling the Good News of the Lord's Message.
B044C015V036	44	15	36	After a while Paul said to Barnabas, »Suppose we now revisit the brethren in the various towns in which we have made known the Lord's Message–to see whether they are prospering!«
B044C015V037	44	15	37	Barnabas, however, was bent on taking with them John, whose other name was Mark,
B044C015V038	44	15	38	while Paul deemed it undesirable to have as their companion one who had deserted them in Pamphylia and had not gone on with them to the work.
B044C015V039	44	15	39	So there arose a serious disagreement between them, which resulted in their parting from one another, Barnabas taking Mark and setting sail for Cyprus.
B044C015V040	44	15	40	But Paul chose Silas as his travelling companion; and set out, after being commended by the brethren to the grace of the Lord;
B044C015V041	44	15	41	and he passed through Syria and Cilicia, strengthening the Churches.
B044C016V001	44	16	1	He also came to Derbe and to Lystra. At Lystra he found a disciple, Timothy by name–the son of a Christian Jewess, though he had a Greek father.
B044C016V002	44	16	2	Timothy was well spoken of by the brethren at Lystra and Iconium,
B044C016V003	44	16	3	and Paul desiring that he should accompany him on his journey, took him and circumcised him on account of the Jews in those parts, for they all knew that his father was a Greek.
B044C016V004	44	16	4	As they journeyed on from town to town, they handed to the brethren for their observance the decisions which had been arrived at by the Apostles and Elders in Jerusalem.
B044C016V005	44	16	5	So the Churches went on gaining a stronger faith and growing in numbers from day to day.
B044C016V006	44	16	6	Then Paul and his companions passed through Phrygia and Galatia, having been forbidden by the Holy Spirit to proclaim the Message in the province of Asia.
B044C016V007	44	16	7	When they reached the frontier of Mysia, they were about to enter Bithynia, but the Spirit of Jesus would not permit this.
B044C016V008	44	16	8	So, passing along Mysia, they came to Troas.
B044C016V009	44	16	9	Here, one night, Paul saw a vision. There was a Macedonian who was standing, entreating him and saying, »Come over into Macedonia and help us.«
B044C016V010	44	16	10	So when he had seen the vision, we immediately looked out for an opportunity of passing on into Macedonia, confidently inferring that God had called us to proclaim the Good News to the people there.
B044C016V011	44	16	11	Accordingly we put out to sea from Troas, and ran a straight course to Samothrace. The next day we came to Neapolis,
B044C016V012	44	16	12	and thence to Philippi, which is a city in Macedonia, the first in its district, a Roman colony. And there we stayed some little time.
B044C016V013	44	16	13	On the Sabbath we went beyond the city gate to the riverside, where we had reason to believe that there was a place for prayer; and sitting down we talked with the women who had come together.
B044C016V014	44	16	14	Among our hearers was one named Lydia, a dealer in purple goods. She belonged to the city of Thyateira, and was a worshipper of the true God. The Lord opened her heart, so that she gave attention to what Paul was saying.
B044C016V015	44	16	15	When she and her household had been baptized, she urged us, saying, »If in your judgement I am a believer in the Lord, come and stay at my house.« And she made us go there.
B044C016V016	44	16	16	One day, as we were on our way to the place of prayer, a slave girl met us who claimed to be inspired and was accustomed to bring her owners large profits by telling fortunes.
B044C016V017	44	16	17	She kept following close behind Paul and the rest of us, crying aloud, »These men are the bondservants of the Most High God, and are proclaiming to you the way of salvation.«
B044C016V018	44	16	18	This she persisted in for a considerable time, until Paul, wearied out, turned round and said to the spirit, »I command you in the name of Jesus Christ to come out of her.« And it came out immediately.
B044C016V019	44	16	19	But when her owners saw that their hopes of gain were gone, they seized Paul and Silas and dragged them off to the magistrates in the public square.
B044C016V020	44	16	20	Then they brought them before the praetors. »These men,« they said, »are creating a great disturbance in our city.
B044C016V021	44	16	21	They are Jews, and are teaching customs which we, as Romans, are not permitted to adopt or practise.«
B044C016V022	44	16	22	The crowd, too, joined in the outcry against them, till at length the praetors ordered them to be stripped and beaten with rods;
B044C016V023	44	16	23	and, after severely flogging them, they threw them into jail and bade the jailer keep them safely.
B044C016V024	44	16	24	He, having received an order like that, lodged them in the inner prison, and secured their feet in the stocks.
B044C016V025	44	16	25	About midnight Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns to God, and the prisoners were listening to them,
B044C016V026	44	16	26	when suddenly there was such a violent shock of earthquake that the prison shook to its foundations. Instantly the doors all flew open, and the chains fell off from every prisoner.
B044C016V027	44	16	27	Starting up from sleep and seeing the doors of the jail wide open, the jailer drew his sword and was on the point of killing himself, supposing that the prisoners had escaped.
B044C016V028	44	16	28	But Paul shouted loudly to him, saying, »Do yourself no injury: we are all here.
B044C016V029	44	16	29	Then, calling for lights, he sprang in and fell trembling at the feet of Paul and Silas;
B044C016V030	44	16	30	and, bringing them out of the prison, he exclaimed, »O sirs, what must I do to be saved?«
B044C016V031	44	16	31	»Believe on the Lord Jesus,« they replied, »and both you and your household will be saved.«
B044C016V032	44	16	32	And they told the Lord's Message to him as well as to all who were in his house.
B044C016V033	44	16	33	Then he took them, even at that time of night, washed their wounds, and he and all his household were immediately baptized;
B044C016V034	44	16	34	and bringing the Apostles up into his house, he spread a meal for them, and was filled with gladness, with his whole household, his faith resting on God.
B044C016V035	44	16	35	In the morning the praetors sent their lictors with the order, »Release those men.«
B044C016V036	44	16	36	So the jailer brought Paul word, saying, »The praetors have sent orders for you to be released. Now therefore you can go, and proceed on your way in peace.«
B044C016V037	44	16	37	But Paul said to them, »After cruelly beating us in public, without trial, Roman citizens though we are, they have thrown us into prison, and are they now going to send us away privately? No, indeed! Let them come in person and fetch us out.«
B044C016V038	44	16	38	This answer the lictors took back to the praetors, who were alarmed when they were told that Paul and Silas were Roman citizens.
B044C016V039	44	16	39	Accordingly they came and apologized to them; and, bringing them out, asked them to leave the city.
B044C016V040	44	16	40	Then Paul and Silas, having come out of the prison, went to Lydia's house; and, after seeing the brethren and encouraging them, they left Philippi.
B044C017V001	44	17	1	Then, passing through Amphipolis and Apollonia, they went to Thessalonica. Here there was a synagogue of the Jews.
B044C017V002	44	17	2	Paul –following his usual custom– betook himself to it, and for three successive Sabbaths reasoned with them from the Scriptures,
B044C017V003	44	17	3	which he clearly explained, pointing out that it had been necessary for the Christ to suffer and rise again from the dead, and insisting, »The Jesus whom I am announcing to you is the Christ.«
B044C017V004	44	17	4	Some of the people were won over, and attached themselves to Paul and Silas, including many God-fearing Greeks and not a few gentlewomen of high rank.
B044C017V005	44	17	5	But the jealousy of the Jews was aroused, and, calling to their aid some ill-conditioned and idle fellows, they got together a riotous mob and filled the city with uproar. They then attacked the house of Jason and searched for Paul and Silas, to bring them out before the assembly of people.
B044C017V006	44	17	6	But, failing to find them, they dragged Jason and some of the other brethren before the magistrates of the city, loudly accusing them. »These men,« they said, »who have raised a tumult throughout the Empire, have come here also.
B044C017V007	44	17	7	Jason has received them into his house; and they all set Caesar's authority at defiance, declaring that there is another Emperor– one called Jesus.«
B044C017V008	44	17	8	Great was the excitement among the crowd, and among the magistrates of the city, when they heard these charges.
B044C017V009	44	17	9	They required Jason and the rest to find substantial bail, and after that they let them go.
B044C017V010	44	17	10	The brethren at once sent Paul and Silas away by night to Beroea, and they, on their arrival, went to the synagogue of the Jews.
B044C017V011	44	17	11	The Jews at Beroea were of a nobler disposition than those in Thessalonica, for they very readily received the Message, and day after day searched the Scriptures to see whether it was as Paul stated.
B044C017V012	44	17	12	As the result many of them became believers, and so did not a few of the Greeks–gentlewomen of good position, and men.
B044C017V013	44	17	13	As soon, however, as the Jews of Thessalonica learnt that God's Message had been proclaimed by Paul at Beroea, they came there also, and incited the mob to a riot.
B044C017V014	44	17	14	Then the brethren promptly sent Paul down to the sea-coast, but Silas and Timothy remained behind.
B044C017V015	44	17	15	Those who were caring for Paul's safety went with him as far as Athens, and then left him, taking a message from him to Silas and Timothy, asking them to join him as speedily as possible.
B044C017V016	44	17	16	While Paul was waiting for them in Athens, his spirit was stirred within him when he noticed that the city was full of idols.
B044C017V017	44	17	17	So he had discussions in the synagogue with the Jews and the other worshippers, and in the market place, day after day, with those whom he happened to meet.
B044C017V018	44	17	18	A few of the Epicurean and Stoic philosophers also encountered him. Some of them asked, »What has this beggarly babbler to say?«»His business,« said others, »seems to be to cry up some foreign gods.« This was because he had been telling the Good News of Jesus and the Resurrection.
B044C017V019	44	17	19	Then they took him and brought him up to the Areopagus, asking him, »May we be told what this new teaching of yours is?
B044C017V020	44	17	20	For the things you are saying sound strange to us. We should therefore like to be told exactly what they mean.«
B044C017V021	44	17	21	(For all the Athenians and their foreign visitors used to devote their whole leisure to telling or hearing about something new.)
B044C017V022	44	17	22	So Paul, taking his stand in the centre of the Areopagus, spoke as follows: »Men of Athens, I perceive that you are in every respect remarkably religious.
B044C017V023	44	17	23	For as I passed along and observed the things you worship, I found also an altar bearing the inscription, `TO AN UNKNOWN GOD.' »The Being, therefore, whom you, without knowing Him, revere, Him I now proclaim to you.
B044C017V024	44	17	24	GOD who made the universe and everything in it–He, being Lord of Heaven and earth, does not dwell in sanctuaries built by men.
B044C017V025	44	17	25	Nor is He ministered to by human hands, as though He needed anything–but He Himself gives to all men life and breath and all things.
B044C017V026	44	17	26	He caused to spring from one forefather people of every race, for them to live on the whole surface of the earth, and marked out for them an appointed span of life and the boundaries of their homes;
B044C017V027	44	17	27	that they might seek God, if perhaps they could grope for Him and find Him. Yes, though He is not far from any one of us.
B044C017V028	44	17	28	For it is in closest union with Him that we live and move and have our being; as in fact some of the poets in repute among yourselves have said, `For we are also His offspring.'
B044C017V029	44	17	29	Since then we are God's offspring, we ought not to imagine that His nature resembles gold or silver or marble, or anything sculptured by the art and inventive faculty of man.
B044C017V030	44	17	30	Those times of ignorance God viewed with indulgence. But now He commands all men everywhere to repent,
B044C017V031	44	17	31	seeing that He has appointed a day on which, before long, He will judge the world in righteousness, through the instrumentality of a man whom He has pre-destined to this work, and has made the fact certain to every one by raising Him from the dead.«
B044C017V032	44	17	32	When they heard Paul speak of a resurrection of dead men, some began to scoff. But others said, »We will hear you again on that subject.«
B044C017V033	44	17	33	So Paul went away from them.
B044C017V034	44	17	34	A few, however, attached themselves to him and believed, among them being Dionysius a member of the Council, a gentlewoman named Damaris, and some others.
B044C018V001	44	18	1	After this he left Athens and came to Corinth.
B044C018V002	44	18	2	Here he found a Jew, a native of Pontus, of the name of Aquila. He and his wife Priscilla had recently come from Italy because of Claudius's edict expelling all the Jews from Rome. So Paul paid them a visit;
B044C018V003	44	18	3	and because he was of the same trade –that of tent-maker– he lodged with them and worked with them.
B044C018V004	44	18	4	But, Sabbath after Sabbath, he preached in the synagogue and tried to win over both Jews and Greeks.
B044C018V005	44	18	5	Now at the time when Silas and Timothy came down from Macedonia, Paul was preaching fervently and was solemnly telling the Jews that Jesus is the Christ.
B044C018V006	44	18	6	But upon their opposing him with abusive language, he shook his clothes by way of protest, and said to them, »Your ruin will be upon your own heads. I am not responsible: in future I will go among the Gentiles.«
B044C018V007	44	18	7	So he left the place and went to the house of a person called Titius Justus, a worshipper of the true God. His house was next door to the synagogue.
B044C018V008	44	18	8	And Crispus, the Warden of the synagogue, believed in the Lord, and so did all his household; and from time to time many of the Corinthians who heard Paul believed and received baptism.
B044C018V009	44	18	9	And, in a vision by night, the Lord said to Paul, »Dismiss your fears: go on speaking, and do not give up.
B044C018V010	44	18	10	I am with you, and no one shall attack you to injure you; for I have very many people in this city.«
B044C018V011	44	18	11	So Paul remained in Corinth for a year and six months, teaching among them the Message of God.
B044C018V012	44	18	12	But when Gallio became Proconsul of Greece, the Jews with one accord made a dead set at Paul, and brought him before the court.
B044C018V013	44	18	13	»This man,« they said, »is inducing people to offer unlawful worship to God.«
B044C018V014	44	18	14	But, when Paul was about to begin his defence, Gallio said to the Jews, »If it had been some wrongful act or piece of cunning knavery I might reasonably have listened to you Jews.
B044C018V015	44	18	15	But since these are questions about words and names and your Law, you yourselves must see to them. I refuse to be a judge in such matters.«
B044C018V016	44	18	16	So he ordered them out of court.
B044C018V017	44	18	17	Then the people all set upon Sosthenes, the Warden of the synagogue, and beat him severely in front of the court. Gallio did not concern himself in the least about this.
B044C018V018	44	18	18	After remaining a considerable time longer in Corinth, Paul took leave of the brethren and set sail for Syria; and Priscilla and Aquila were with him. He had shaved his head at Cenchreae, because he was bound by a vow.
B044C018V019	44	18	19	They put in at Ephesus, and there Paul left his companions behind. As for himself, he went to the synagogue and had a discussion with the Jews.
B044C018V020	44	18	20	When they asked him to remain longer he did not consent,
B044C018V021	44	18	21	but took leave of them with the promise, »I will return to you, God willing.« So he set sail from Ephesus.
B044C018V022	44	18	22	Landing at Caesarea, he went up to Jerusalem and inquired after the welfare of the Church, and then went down to Antioch.
B044C018V023	44	18	23	After spending some time in Antioch, Paul set out on a tour, visiting the whole of Galatia and Phrygia in order, and strengthening all the disciples.
B044C018V024	44	18	24	Meanwhile a Jew named Apollos came to Ephesus. He was a native of Alexandria, a man of great learning and well versed in the Scriptures.
B044C018V025	44	18	25	He had been instructed by word of mouth in the way of the Lord, and, being full of burning zeal, he used to speak and teach accurately the facts about Jesus, though he knew of no baptism but John's.
B044C018V026	44	18	26	He began to speak boldly in the synagogue, and Priscilla and Aquila, after hearing him, took him home and explained God's way to him more accurately.
B044C018V027	44	18	27	Then, as he had made up his mind to cross over into Greece, the brethren wrote to the disciples in Corinth begging them to give him a kindly welcome. Upon his arrival he rendered valuable help to those who through grace had believed;
B044C018V028	44	18	28	for he powerfully and in public overcame the Jews in argument, proving to them from the Scriptures that Jesus is the Christ.
B044C019V001	44	19	1	During the stay of Apollos in Corinth, Paul, after passing through the inland districts, came to Ephesus, where he found a few disciples.
B044C019V002	44	19	2	»Did you receive the Holy Spirit when you first believed?« he asked them. »No,« they replied, »we did not even hear that there is a Holy Spirit.«
B044C019V003	44	19	3	»Into what then were you baptized?« he asked. »Into John's baptism,« they replied.
B044C019V004	44	19	4	»John,« he said, »administered a baptism of repentance, bidding the people believe on One who was to come after him; namely, on Jesus.«
B044C019V005	44	19	5	On hearing this, they were baptized into the name of the Lord Jesus;
B044C019V006	44	19	6	and when Paul laid his hands upon them, the Holy Spirit came on them, and they began to speak in tongues and to prophesy.
B044C019V007	44	19	7	They numbered in all about twelve men.
B044C019V008	44	19	8	Afterwards he went into the synagogue. There for three months he continued to preach fearlessly, explaining in words which carried conviction the truths which concern the Kingdom of God.
B044C019V009	44	19	9	But some grew obstinate in unbelief and spoke evil of the new faith before all the congregation. So Paul left them, and, taking with him those who were disciples, held discussions daily in Tyrannus's lecture-hall.
B044C019V010	44	19	10	This went on for two years, so that all the inhabitants of the province of Asia, Jews as well as Greeks, heard the Lord's Message.
B044C019V011	44	19	11	God also brought about extraordinary miracles through Paul's instrumentality.
B044C019V012	44	19	12	Towels or aprons, for instance, which Paul had handled used to be carried to the sick, and they recovered from their ailments, or the evil spirits left them.
B044C019V013	44	19	13	But there were also some wandering Jewish exorcists who undertook to invoke the name of Jesus over those who had the evil spirits, saying, »I command you by that Jesus whom Paul preaches.«
B044C019V014	44	19	14	There were seven sons of one Sceva, a Jew of high-priestly family, who were doing this.
B044C019V015	44	19	15	»Jesus I know,« the evil spirit answered, »and Paul I have heard of, but who are you?«
B044C019V016	44	19	16	And the man in whom the evil spirit was sprang on two of them, over-mastered them both, and treated them with such violence, that they fled from the house stripped of their clothes and wounded.
B044C019V017	44	19	17	All the people of Ephesus, Jews as well as Greeks, came to know of this. There was widespread terror, and they began to hold the name of the Lord Jesus in high honour.
B044C019V018	44	19	18	Many also of those who believed came confessing without reserve what their conduct had been,
B044C019V019	44	19	19	and not a few of those who had practised magical arts brought their books together and burnt them in the presence of all. The total value was reckoned and found to be 50,000 silver coins.
B044C019V020	44	19	20	Thus mightily did the Lord's Message spread and triumph!
B044C019V021	44	19	21	When matters had reached this point, Paul decided in his own mind to travel through Macedonia and Greece, and go to Jerusalem. »After that,« he said, »I must also see Rome.«
B044C019V022	44	19	22	But he sent two of his assistants, Timothy and Erastus, to Macedonia, while he himself remained for a while in Roman Asia.
B044C019V023	44	19	23	Now just at that time there arose no small commotion about the new faith.
B044C019V024	44	19	24	There was a certain Demetrius, a silversmith, who made miniature silver sanctuaries of Diana, a business which brought great gain to the mechanics in his employ.
B044C019V025	44	19	25	He called his workmen together, and others who were engaged in similar trades, and said to them, »You men well know that our prosperity depends on this business of ours;
B044C019V026	44	19	26	and you see and hear that, not in Ephesus only but throughout almost the whole province of Asia, this fellow Paul has led away a vast number of people by inducing them to believe that they are not gods at all that are made by men's hands.
B044C019V027	44	19	27	There is danger, therefore, not only that this our trade will become of no account, but also that the temple of the great goddess Diana will fall into utter disrepute, and that before long she will be actually deposed from her majestic rank–she who is now worshipped by the whole province of Asia; nay, by the whole world.«
B044C019V028	44	19	28	After listening to this harangue, they became furiously angry and kept calling out, »Great is the Ephesian Diana!«
B044C019V029	44	19	29	The riot and uproar spread through the whole city, till at last with one accord they rushed into the Theatre, dragging with them Gaius and Aristarchus, two Macedonians who were fellow travellers with Paul.
B044C019V030	44	19	30	Then Paul would have liked to go in and address the people, but the disciples would not let him do so.
B044C019V031	44	19	31	A few of the public officials, too, who were friendly to him, sent repeated messages entreating him not to venture into the Theatre.
B044C019V032	44	19	32	The people, meanwhile, kept shouting, some one thing and some another; for the assembly was all uproar and confusion, and the greater part had no idea why they had come together.
B044C019V033	44	19	33	Then some of the people crowded round Alexander, whom the Jews had pushed forward; and Alexander, motioning with his hand to get silence, was prepared to make a defence to the people.
B044C019V034	44	19	34	No sooner, however, did they see that he was a Jew, than there arose from them all one roar of shouting, lasting about two hours. »Great is the Ephesian Diana,« they said.
B044C019V035	44	19	35	At length the Recorder quieted them down. »Men of Ephesus,« he said, »who is there of all mankind that needs to be told that the city of Ephesus is the guardian of the temple of the great Diana and of the image which fell down from Zeus?
B044C019V036	44	19	36	These facts, then, being unquestioned, it becomes you to maintain your self-control and not act recklessly.
B044C019V037	44	19	37	For you have brought these men here, who are neither robbers of temples nor blasphemers of our goddess.
B044C019V038	44	19	38	If, however, Demetrius and the mechanics who support his contention have a grievance against any one, there are Assize-days and there are Proconsuls: let the persons interested accuse one another.
B044C019V039	44	19	39	But if you desire anything further, it will have to be settled in the regular assembly.
B044C019V040	44	19	40	For in connexion with to-day's proceedings there is danger of our being charged with attempted insurrection, there having been no real reason for this riot; nor shall we be able to justify the behaviour of this disorderly mob.«
B044C019V041	44	19	41	With these words he dismissed the assembly.
B044C020V001	44	20	1	When the uproar had ceased, Paul sent for the disciples; and, after speaking words of encouragement to them, he took his leave, and started for Macedonia.
B044C020V002	44	20	2	Passing through those districts he encouraged the disciples in frequent addresses, and then came into Greece, and spent three months there.
B044C020V003	44	20	3	The Jews having planned to waylay him whenever he might be on the point of taking ship for Syria, he decided to travel back by way of Macedonia.
B044C020V004	44	20	4	He was accompanied as far as the province of Asia by Sopater the Beroean, the son of Pyrrhus; by the Thessalonians, Aristarchus and Secundus; by Gaius of Derbe, and Timothy; and by the Asians, Tychicus and Trophimus.
B044C020V005	44	20	5	These brethren had gone on and were waiting for us in the Troad.
B044C020V006	44	20	6	But we ourselves sailed from Philippi after the days of Unleavened Bread, and five days later joined them in the Troad, where we remained for a week.
B044C020V007	44	20	7	On the first day of the week, when we had met to break bread, Paul, who was going away the next morning, was preaching to them, and prolonged his discourse till midnight.
B044C020V008	44	20	8	Now there were a good many lamps in the room upstairs where we all were,
B044C020V009	44	20	9	and a youth of the name of Eutychus was sitting at the window. This lad, gradually sinking into deep sleep while Paul preached at unusual length, overcome at last by sleep, fell from the second floor and was taken up dead.
B044C020V010	44	20	10	Paul, however, went down, threw himself upon him, and folding him in his arms said, »Do not be alarmed; his life is still in him.«
B044C020V011	44	20	11	Then he went upstairs again, broke bread, and took some food; and after a long conversation which was continued till daybreak, at last he parted from them.
B044C020V012	44	20	12	They had taken the lad home alive, and were greatly comforted.
B044C020V013	44	20	13	The rest of us had already gone on board a ship, and now we set sail for Assos, intending to take Paul on board there; for so he had arranged, he himself intending to go by land.
B044C020V014	44	20	14	Accordingly, when he met us at Assos, we took him on board and came to Mitylene.
B044C020V015	44	20	15	Sailing from there, we arrived the next day off Chios. On the next we touched at Samos; and on the day following reached Miletus.
B044C020V016	44	20	16	For Paul's plan was to sail past Ephesus, so as not to spend much time in the province of Asia; since he was very desirous of being in Jerusalem, if possible, on the day of the Harvest Festival.
B044C020V017	44	20	17	From Miletus he sent to Ephesus for the Elders of the Church to come to him.
B044C020V018	44	20	18	Upon their arrival he said to them, »You Elders well know, from the first day of my setting foot in the province of Asia, the kind of life I lived among you the whole time,
B044C020V019	44	20	19	serving the Lord in all humility, and with tears, and amid trials which came upon me through the plotting of the Jews–
B044C020V020	44	20	20	and that I never shrank from declaring to you anything that was profitable, or from teaching you in public and in your homes,
B044C020V021	44	20	21	and urging upon both Jews and Greeks the necessity of turning to God and of believing in Jesus our Lord.
B044C020V022	44	20	22	»And now, impelled by a sense of duty, I am on my way to Jerusalem, not knowing what will happen to me there,
B044C020V023	44	20	23	except that the Holy Spirit, at town after town, testifies to me that imprisonment and suffering are awaiting me.«
B044C020V024	44	20	24	But even the sacrifice of my life I count as nothing, if only I may perfect my earthly course, and be faithful to the duty which the Lord Jesus has entrusted to me of proclaiming, as of supreme importance, the Good News of God's grace.
B044C020V025	44	20	25	»And now, I know that none of you among whom I have gone in and out proclaiming the coming of the Kingdom will any longer see my face.«
B044C020V026	44	20	26	Therefore I protest to you to-day that I am not responsible for the ruin of any one of you.
B044C020V027	44	20	27	For I have not shrunk from declaring to you God's whole truth.
B044C020V028	44	20	28	»Take heed to yourselves and to all the flock among which the Holy Spirit has placed you to take the oversight for Him and act as shepherds to the Church of God, which He has bought with His own blood.«
B044C020V029	44	20	29	I know that, when I am gone, cruel wolves will come among you and will not spare the flock;
B044C020V030	44	20	30	and that from among your own selves men will rise up who will seek with their perverse talk to draw away the disciples after them.
B044C020V031	44	20	31	Therefore be on the alert; and remember that, night and day, for three years, I never ceased admonishing every one, even with tears.
B044C020V032	44	20	32	»And now I commend you to God and to the word of His grace. He is able to build you up and to give you your inheritance among His people.«
B044C020V033	44	20	33	No one's silver or gold or clothing have I coveted.
B044C020V034	44	20	34	You yourselves know that these hands of mine have provided for my own necessities and for the people with me.
B044C020V035	44	20	35	In all things I have set you an example, showing you that, by working as I do, you ought to help the weak, and to bear in mind the words of the Lord Jesus, how He Himself said, »`It is more blessed to give than to receive.'«
B044C020V036	44	20	36	Having spoken thus, Paul knelt down and prayed with them all;
B044C020V037	44	20	37	and with loud lamentation they all threw their arms round his neck, and kissed him lovingly,
B044C020V038	44	20	38	grieved above all things at his having told them that after that day they were no longer to see his face. And they went with him to the ship.
B044C021V001	44	21	1	When, at last, we had torn ourselves away and had set sail, we ran in a straight course to Cos; the next day to Rhodes, and from there to Patara.
B044C021V002	44	21	2	Finding a ship bound for Phoenicia, we went on board and put to sea.
B044C021V003	44	21	3	After sighting Cyprus and leaving that island on our left, we continued our voyage to Syria and put in at Tyre; for there the ship was to unload her cargo.
B044C021V004	44	21	4	Having searched for the disciples and found them, we stayed at Tyre for seven days; and, taught by the Spirit, they repeatedly urged Paul not to proceed to Jerusalem.
B044C021V005	44	21	5	When, however, our time was up, we left and went on our way, all the disciples and their wives and children coming to see us off. Then, after kneeling down on the beach and praying,
B044C021V006	44	21	6	we took leave of one another; and we went on board, while they returned home.
B044C021V007	44	21	7	As for us, our voyage was over when having sailed from Tyre we reached Ptolemais. here we inquired after the welfare of the brethren, and remained a day with them.
B044C021V008	44	21	8	On the morrow we left Ptolemais and went on to Caesarea, where we came to the house of Philip the Evangelist, who was one of the seven, and stayed with him.
B044C021V009	44	21	9	Now Philip had four unmarried daughters who were prophetesses;
B044C021V010	44	21	10	and during our somewhat lengthy stay a Prophet of the name of Agabus came down from Judaea.
B044C021V011	44	21	11	When he arrived he took Paul's loincloth, and bound his own feet and arms with it, and said, »Thus says the Holy Spirit, `So will the Jews in Jerusalem bind the owner of this loincloth, and will hand him over to the Gentiles.'«
B044C021V012	44	21	12	As soon as we heard these words, both we and the brethren at Caesarea entreated Paul not to go up to Jerusalem.
B044C021V013	44	21	13	His reply was, »What can you mean by thus breaking my heart with your grief? Why, as for me, I am ready not only to go to Jerusalem and be put in chains, but even to die there for the sake of the Lord Jesus.«
B044C021V014	44	21	14	So when he was not to be dissuaded, we ceased remonstrating with him and said, »The Lord's will be done!«
B044C021V015	44	21	15	A few days afterwards we loaded our baggage-cattle and continued our journey to Jerusalem.
B044C021V016	44	21	16	Some of the disciples from Caesarea also joined our party, and brought with them Mnason, a Cyprian, one of the early disciples, at whose house we were to lodge.
B044C021V017	44	21	17	At length we reached Jerusalem, and there the brethren gave us a hearty welcome.
B044C021V018	44	21	18	On the following day we went with Paul to call on James, and all the Elders of the Church came also.
B044C021V019	44	21	19	After exchanging friendly greetings, Paul told in detail all that God had done among the Gentiles through his instrumentality.
B044C021V020	44	21	20	And they, when they had heard his statement, gave the glory to God. Then they said, »You see, brother, how many tens of thousands of Jews there are among those who have accepted the faith, and they are all zealous upholders of the Law.
B044C021V021	44	21	21	Now what they have been repeatedly told about you is that you teach all the Jews among the Gentiles to abandon Moses, and that you forbid them to circumcise their children or observe old-established customs.
B044C021V022	44	21	22	What then ought you to do? They are sure to hear that you have come to Jerusalem;
B044C021V023	44	21	23	so do this which we now tell you. We have four men here who have a vow resting on them.
B044C021V024	44	21	24	Associate with these men and purify yourself with them, and pay their expenses so that they can shave their heads. Then everybody will know that there is no truth in these stories about you, but that in your own actions you yourself scrupulously obey the Law.
B044C021V025	44	21	25	But as for the Gentiles who have accepted the faith, we have communicated to them our decision that they are carefully to abstain from anything sacrificed to an idol, from blood, from what is strangled, and from fornication.«
B044C021V026	44	21	26	So Paul associated with the men; and the next day, having purified himself with them, he went into the Temple, giving every one to understand that the days of their purification were finished, and there he remained until the sacrifice for each of them was offered.
B044C021V027	44	21	27	But, when the seven days were nearly over, the Jews from the province of Asia, having seen Paul in the Temple, set about rousing the fury of all the people against him.
B044C021V028	44	21	28	They laid hands on him, crying out, »Men of Israel, help! help! This is the man who goes everywhere preaching to everybody against the Jewish people and the Law and this place. And besides, he has even brought Gentiles into the Temple and has desecrated this holy place.«
B044C021V029	44	21	29	(For they had previously seen Trophimus the Ephesian with him in the city, and imagined that Paul had brought him into the Temple.)
B044C021V030	44	21	30	The excitement spread through the whole city, and the people rushed in crowds to the Temple, and there laid hold of Paul and began to drag him out; and the Temple gates were immediately closed.
B044C021V031	44	21	31	But while they were trying to kill Paul, word was taken up to the Tribune in command of the battalion, that all Jerusalem was in a ferment.
B044C021V032	44	21	32	He instantly sent for a few soldiers and their officers, and came down among the people with all speed. At the sight of the Tribune and the troops they ceased beating Paul.
B044C021V033	44	21	33	Then the Tribune, making his way to him, arrested him, and, having ordered him to be secured with two chains, proceeded to ask who he was and what he had been doing.
B044C021V034	44	21	34	Some of the crowd shouted one accusation against Paul and some another, until, as the uproar made it impossible for the truth to be ascertained with certainty, the Tribune ordered him to be brought into the barracks.
B044C021V035	44	21	35	When Paul was going up the steps, he had to be carried by the soldiers because of the violence of the mob;
B044C021V036	44	21	36	for the whole mass of the people pressed on in the rear, shouting, »Away with him!«
B044C021V037	44	21	37	When he was about to be taken into the barracks, Paul said to the Tribune, »May I speak to you?«»Do you know Greek?« the Tribune asked.
B044C021V038	44	21	38	»Are you not the Egyptian who some years ago excited the riot of the 4,000 cut-throats, and led them out into the Desert?«
B044C021V039	44	21	39	»I am a Jew,« replied Paul, »belonging to Tarsus in Cilicia, and am a citizen of no unimportant city. Give me leave, I pray you, to speak to the people.«
B044C021V040	44	21	40	So with his permission Paul stood on the steps and motioned with his hand to the people to be quiet; and when there was perfect silence he addressed them in Hebrew.
B044C022V001	44	22	1	»Brethren and fathers,« he said, »listen to my defence which I now make before you.«
B044C022V002	44	22	2	And on hearing him address them in Hebrew, they kept all the more quiet; and he said,
B044C022V003	44	22	3	»I am a Jew, born at Tarsus in Cilicia, but brought up in this city. I was carefully trained at the feet of Gamaliel in the Law of our forefathers, and, like all of you to-day, was zealous for God.«
B044C022V004	44	22	4	I persecuted to death this new faith, continually binding both men and women and throwing them into prison;
B044C022V005	44	22	5	as the High Priest also and all the Elders can bear me witness. It was, too, from them that I received letters to the brethren in Damascus, and I was already on my way to Damascus, intending to bring those also who had fled there, in chains to Jerusalem, to be punished.
B044C022V006	44	22	6	»But on my way, when I was now not far from Damascus, about noon a sudden blaze of light from Heaven shone round me.
B044C022V007	44	22	7	I fell to the ground and heard a voice say to me, »`Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting Me?'
B044C022V008	44	22	8	»`Who art thou, Lord?' I asked.« `I am Jesus, the Nazarene,' He replied, `whom you are persecuting.'
B044C022V009	44	22	9	»Now the men who were with me, though they saw the light, did not hear the words of Him who spoke to me.«
B044C022V010	44	22	10	And I asked, »`What am I to do, Lord?' «And the Lord said to me, »`Rise, and go into Damascus. There you shall be told of all that has been appointed for you to do.'
B044C022V011	44	22	11	»And as I could not see because the light had been so dazzling, those who were with me had to lead me by the arm, and so I came to Damascus.«
B044C022V012	44	22	12	»And a certain Ananias, a pious man who obeyed the Law and bore a good character with all the Jews of the city,
B044C022V013	44	22	13	came to me and standing at my side said, »`Brother Saul, recover your sight.'« I instantly regained my sight and looked up at him.
B044C022V014	44	22	14	Then he said, `The God of our forefathers has appointed you to know His will, and to see the righteous One and hear Him speak.
B044C022V015	44	22	15	For you shall be a witness for Him, to all men, of what you have seen and heard.
B044C022V016	44	22	16	And now why delay? Rise, get yourself baptized, and wash off your sins, calling upon His name.'
B044C022V017	44	22	17	»After my return to Jerusalem, and while praying in the Temple, I fell into a trance.«
B044C022V018	44	22	18	I saw Jesus, and He said to me, »`Make haste and leave Jerusalem quickly, because they will not accept your testimony about Me.'
B044C022V019	44	22	19	»`Lord,' I replied, `they themselves well know how active I was in imprisoning, and in flogging in synagogue after synagogue those who believe in Thee;«
B044C022V020	44	22	20	and when they were shedding the blood of Stephen, Thy witness, I was standing by, fully approving of it, and I held the clothes of those who were killing him.'
B044C022V021	44	22	21	»`Go,' He replied; `I will send you as an Apostle to nations far away.'«
B044C022V022	44	22	22	Until they heard this last statement the people listened to Paul, but now with a roar of disapproval they cried out, »Away with such a fellow from the earth! He ought not to be allowed to live.«
B044C022V023	44	22	23	And when they continued their furious shouts, throwing their clothes into the air and flinging dust about,
B044C022V024	44	22	24	the Tribune ordered him to be brought into the barracks, and be examined by flogging, in order to ascertain the reason why they thus cried out against him.
B044C022V025	44	22	25	But, when they had tied him up with the straps, Paul said to the Captain who stood by, »Does the Law permit you to flog a Roman citizen–and one too who is uncondemned?«
B044C022V026	44	22	26	On hearing this question, the Captain went to report the matter to the Tribune. »What are you intending to do?« he said. »This man is a Roman citizen.«
B044C022V027	44	22	27	So the Tribune came to Paul and asked him, »Tell me, are you a Roman citizen?«»Yes,« he said.
B044C022V028	44	22	28	»I paid a large sum for my citizenship,« said the Tribune. »But I was born free,« said Paul.
B044C022V029	44	22	29	So the men who had been on the point of putting him under torture immediately left him. And the Tribune, too, was frightened when he learnt that Paul was a Roman citizen, for he had had him bound.
B044C022V030	44	22	30	The next day, wishing to know exactly what charge was being brought against him by the Jews, the Tribune ordered his chains to be removed; and, having sent word to the High Priests and all the Sanhedrin to assemble, he brought Paul down and made him stand before them.
B044C023V001	44	23	1	Then Paul, fixing a steady gaze on the Sanhedrin, said, »Brethren, it is with a perfectly clear conscience that I have discharged my duties before God up to this day.«
B044C023V002	44	23	2	On hearing this the High Priest Ananias ordered those who were standing near Paul to strike him on the mouth.
B044C023V003	44	23	3	»Before long,« exclaimed Paul, »God will strike you, you white-washed wall! Are you sitting there to judge me in accordance with the Law, and do you yourself actually break the Law by ordering me to be struck?«
B044C023V004	44	23	4	»Do you rail at God's High Priest?« cried the men who stood by him.
B044C023V005	44	23	5	»I did not know, brethren,« replied Paul, »that he was the High Priest; for it is written, 
B044C023V006	44	23	6	Noticing, however, that the Sanhedrin consisted partly of Sadducees and partly of Pharisees, he called out loudly among them, »Brethren, I am a Pharisee, the son of Pharisees. It is because of my hope of a resurrection of the dead that I am on my trial.«
B044C023V007	44	23	7	These words of his caused an angry dispute between the Pharisees and the Sadducees, and the assembly took different sides.
B044C023V008	44	23	8	For the Sadducees maintain that there is no resurrection, and neither angel nor spirit; but the Pharisees acknowledge the existence of both.
B044C023V009	44	23	9	So there arose a great uproar; and some of the Scribes belonging to the sect of the Pharisees sprang to their feet and fiercely contended, saying, »We find no harm in the man. What if a spirit has spoken to him, or an angel–!«
B044C023V010	44	23	10	But when the struggle was becoming violent, the Tribune, fearing that Paul would be torn to pieces by the people, ordered the troops to go down and take him from among them by force and bring him into the barracks.
B044C023V011	44	23	11	The following night the Lord came and stood at Paul's side, and said, »Be of good courage, for as you have borne faithful witness about me in Jerusalem, so you must also bear witness in Rome.«
B044C023V012	44	23	12	Now, when daylight came, the Jews formed a conspiracy and solemnly swore not to eat or drink till they had killed Paul.
B044C023V013	44	23	13	There were more than forty of them who bound themselves by this oath.
B044C023V014	44	23	14	They went to the High Priests and Elders and said to them, »We have bound ourselves under a heavy curse to take no food till we have killed Paul.
B044C023V015	44	23	15	Now therefore you and the Sanhedrin should make representations to the Tribune for him to bring him down to you, under the impression that you intend to inquire more minutely about him; and we are prepared to assassinate him before he comes near the place.«
B044C023V016	44	23	16	But Paul's sister's son heard of the intended attack upon him. So he came and went into the barracks and told Paul about it;
B044C023V017	44	23	17	and Paul called one of the Captains and said, »Take this young man to the Tribune, for he has information to give him.«
B044C023V018	44	23	18	So he took him and brought him to the Tribune, and said, »Paul, the prisoner, called me to him and begged me to bring this youth to you, because he has something to say to you.«
B044C023V019	44	23	19	Then the Tribune, taking him by the arm, withdrew out of the hearing of others and asked him, »What have you to tell me?«
B044C023V020	44	23	20	»The Jews,« he replied, »have agreed to request you to bring Paul down to the Sanhedrin to-morrow for the purpose of making yourself more accurately acquainted with the case.
B044C023V021	44	23	21	I beg you not to comply; for more than forty men among them are lying in wait for him, who have solemnly vowed that they will neither eat nor drink till they have assassinated him; and even now they are ready, in anticipation of receiving that promise of you.«
B044C023V022	44	23	22	So the Tribune sent the youth home, cautioning him. »Do not let any one know that you have given me this information,« he said.
B044C023V023	44	23	23	Then, calling to him two of the Captains, he gave his orders. »Get ready two hundred men,« he said, »to march to Caesarea, with seventy cavalry and two hundred light infantry, starting at nine o'clock to-night.«
B044C023V024	44	23	24	He further told them to provide horses to mount Paul on, so as to bring him safely to Felix the Governor.
B044C023V025	44	23	25	He also wrote a letter of which these were the contents:
B044C023V026	44	23	26	»Claudius Lysias to his Excellency, Felix the Governor: all good wishes.
B044C023V027	44	23	27	This man Paul had been seized by the Jews, and they were on the point of killing him, when I came upon them with the troops and rescued him, for I had been informed that he was a Roman citizen.
B044C023V028	44	23	28	And, wishing to know with certainty the offense of which they were accusing him, I brought him down into their Sanhedrin,
B044C023V029	44	23	29	and I discovered that the charge had to do with questions of their Law, but that he was accused of nothing for which he deserves death or imprisonment.
B044C023V030	44	23	30	But now that I have received information of an intended attack upon him, I immediately send him to you, directing his accusers also to state before you the case they have against him.«
B044C023V031	44	23	31	So, in obedience to their orders, the soldiers took Paul and brought him by night as far as Antipatris.
B044C023V032	44	23	32	The next day the infantry returned to the barracks, leaving the cavalry to proceed with him;
B044C023V033	44	23	33	and, the cavalry having reached Caesarea and delivered the letter to the Governor, they brought Paul also to him.
B044C023V034	44	23	34	Felix, after reading the letter, inquired from what province he was; and being told »from Cilicia,«
B044C023V035	44	23	35	he said, »I will hear all you have to say, when your accusers also have come.« And he ordered him to be detained in custody in Herod's Palace.
B044C024V001	44	24	1	Five days after this, Ananias the High Priest came down to Caesarea with a number of Elders and a pleader called Tertullus. They stated to the Governor the case against Paul.
B044C024V002	44	24	2	So Paul was sent for, and Tertullus began to impeach him as follows:»Indebted as we are,« he said, »to you, most noble Felix, for the perfect peace which we enjoy, and for reforms which your wisdom has introduced to this nation,
B044C024V003	44	24	3	in every instance and in every place we accept them with profound gratitude.
B044C024V004	44	24	4	But –not to detain you too long– I beg you in your forbearance to listen to a brief statement from us.
B044C024V005	44	24	5	For we have found this man Paul a source of mischief and a disturber of the peace among all the Jews throughout the Empire, and a ringleader in the heresy of the Nazarenes.
B044C024V006	44	24	6	He even attempted to profane the Temple, but we arrested him.
B044C024V007	44	24	7	[]
B044C024V008	44	24	8	You, however, by examining him, will yourself be able to learn the truth as to all this which we allege against him.«
B044C024V009	44	24	9	The Jews also joined in the charge, maintaining that these were facts.
B044C024V010	44	24	10	Then, at a sign from the Governor, Paul answered, »Knowing, Sir, that for many years you have administered justice to this nation, I cheerfully make my defence.
B044C024V011	44	24	11	For you have it in your power to ascertain that it is not more than twelve days ago that I went up to worship in Jerusalem;
B044C024V012	44	24	12	and that neither in the Temple nor in the synagogues, nor anywhere in the city, did they find me disputing with any opponent or collecting a crowd about me.
B044C024V013	44	24	13	Nor can they prove the charges which they are now bringing against me.
B044C024V014	44	24	14	But this I confess to you–that in the way which they style a heresy, I worship the God of our forefathers, believing everything that is taught in the Law or is written in the Prophets,
B044C024V015	44	24	15	and having a hope directed towards God, which my accusers themselves also entertain, that before long there will be a resurrection both of the righteous and the unrighteous.
B044C024V016	44	24	16	This too is my own earnest endeavour–always to have a clear conscience in relation to God and man.
B044C024V017	44	24	17	»Now after an interval of several years I came to bring alms to my nation, and to offer sacrifices.«
B044C024V018	44	24	18	While I was busy about these, they found me in the Temple purified, with no crowd around me and no uproar; but there were certain Jews from the province of Asia.
B044C024V019	44	24	19	They ought to have been here before you, and to have been my prosecutors, if they have any charge to bring against me.
B044C024V020	44	24	20	Or let these men themselves say what misdemeanour they found me guilty of when I stood before the Sanhedrin,
B044C024V021	44	24	21	unless it was in that one expression which I made use of when I shouted out as I stood among them, »`The resurrection of the dead is the thing about which I am on my trial before you to-day.'«
B044C024V022	44	24	22	At this point Felix, who was fairly well informed about the new faith, adjourned the trial, saying to the Jews, »When the Tribune Lysias comes down, I will enter carefully into the matter.«
B044C024V023	44	24	23	And he gave orders to the Captain that Paul was to be kept in custody, but be treated with indulgence, and that his personal friends were not to be prevented from showing him kindness.
B044C024V024	44	24	24	Not long after this, Felix came with Drusilla his wife, a Jewess, and sending for Paul, listened to him as he spoke about faith in Christ Jesus.
B044C024V025	44	24	25	But when he dealt with the subjects of justice, self-control, and the judgement which was soon to come, Felix became alarmed and said, »For the present leave me, and when I can find a convenient opportunity I will send for you.«
B044C024V026	44	24	26	At the same time he hoped that Paul would give him money; and for this reason he sent for him the oftener to converse with him.
B044C024V027	44	24	27	But after the lapse of fully two years Felix was succeeded by Porcius Festus; and being desirous of gratifying the Jews, Felix left Paul still in prison.
B044C025V001	44	25	1	Festus, having entered on his duties as governor of the province, two days later went up from Caesarea to Jerusalem.
B044C025V002	44	25	2	The High Priests and the leading men among the Jews immediately made representations to him against Paul, and begged him–
B044C025V003	44	25	3	asking it as a favour, to Paul's prejudice–to have him brought to Jerusalem. They were planning an ambush to kill him on the way.
B044C025V004	44	25	4	Festus, however, replied that Paul was in custody in Caesarea, and that he was himself going there very soon.
B044C025V005	44	25	5	»Therefore let those of you,« he said, »who can come, go down with me, and impeach the man, if there is anything amiss in him.«
B044C025V006	44	25	6	After a stay of eight or ten days in Jerusalem –not more– he went down to Caesarea; and the next day, taking his seat on the tribunal, he ordered Paul to be brought in.
B044C025V007	44	25	7	Upon Paul's arrival, the Jews who had come down from Jerusalem stood round him, and brought many grave charges against him which they were unable to substantiate.
B044C025V008	44	25	8	But, in reply, Paul said, »Neither against the Jewish Law, nor against the Temple, nor against Caesar, have I committed any offence whatever.«
B044C025V009	44	25	9	Then Festus, being anxious to gratify the Jews, asked Paul, »Are you willing to go up to Jerusalem, and there stand your trial before me on these charges?«
B044C025V010	44	25	10	»I am standing before Caesar's tribunal,« replied Paul, »where alone I ought to be tried. The Jews have no real ground of complaint against me, as in fact you yourself are beginning to see more clearly.
B044C025V011	44	25	11	If, however, I have done wrong and have committed any offence for which I deserve to die, I do not ask to be excused that penalty. But if there is no truth in what these men allege against me, no one has the right to give me up to them as a favour. I appeal to Caesar.«
B044C025V012	44	25	12	Then, after conferring with the Council, Festus replied, »To Caesar you have appealed: to Caesar you shall go.«
B044C025V013	44	25	13	A short time after this, Agrippa the king and Bernice came to Caesarea to pay a complimentary visit to Festus;
B044C025V014	44	25	14	and, during their rather long stay, Festus laid Paul's case before the king. »There is a man here,« he said, »whom Felix left a prisoner,
B044C025V015	44	25	15	about whom, when I went to Jerusalem, the High Priests and the Elders of the Jews made representations to me, begging that sentence might be pronounced against him.
B044C025V016	44	25	16	My reply was that it is not the custom among the Romans to give up any one for punishment before the accused has had his accusers face to face, and has had an opportunity of defending himself against the charge which has been brought against him.
B044C025V017	44	25	17	»When, therefore, a number of them came here, the next day I took my seat on the tribunal, without any loss of time, and ordered the man to be brought in.«
B044C025V018	44	25	18	But, when his accusers stood up, they did not charge him with the misdemeanours of which I had been suspecting him.
B044C025V019	44	25	19	But they quarrelled with him about certain matters connected with their own religion, and about one Jesus who had died, but –so Paul persistently maintained– is now alive.
B044C025V020	44	25	20	I was at a loss how to investigate such questions, and asked Paul whether he would care to go to Jerusalem and there stand his trial on these matters.
B044C025V021	44	25	21	But when Paul appealed to have his case kept for the Emperor's decision, I ordered him to be kept in prison until I could send him up to Caesar.«
B044C025V022	44	25	22	»I should like to hear the man myself,« said Agrippa. »to-morrow,« replied Festus, »you shall.« Accordingly, the next day, Agrippa and Bernice came in state
B044C025V023	44	25	23	and took their seats in the Judgement Hall, attended by the Tribunes and the men of high rank in the city; and, at the command of Festus, Paul was brought in.
B044C025V024	44	25	24	Then Festus said, »King Agrippa and all who are present with us, you see here the man about whom the whole nation of the Jews made suit to me, both in Jerusalem and here, crying out that he ought not to live any longer.
B044C025V025	44	25	25	I could not discover that he had done anything for which he deserved to die; but as he has himself appealed to the Emperor, I have decided to send him to Rome.
B044C025V026	44	25	26	I have nothing very definite, however, to tell our Sovereign about him. So I have brought the man before you all –and especially before you, King Agrippa– that after he has been examined I may find something which I can put into writing.
B044C025V027	44	25	27	For, when sending a prisoner to Rome, it seems to me to be absurd not to state the charges against him.«
B044C026V001	44	26	1	Then Agrippa said to Paul, »You have permission to speak about yourself.« So Paul, with outstretched arm, proceeded to make his defence.
B044C026V002	44	26	2	»As regards all the accusations brought against me by the Jews,« he said, »I think myself fortunate, King Agrippa, in being about to defend myself to-day before you,
B044C026V003	44	26	3	who are so familiar with all the customs and speculations that prevail among the Jews; and for this reason, I pray you, give me a patient hearing.
B044C026V004	44	26	4	»The kind of life I have lived from my youth upwards, as exemplified in my early days among my nation and in Jerusalem, is known to all the Jews.«
B044C026V005	44	26	5	For they all know me of old –if they would but testify to the fact– how, being an adherent of the strictest sect of our religion, my life was that of a Pharisee.
B044C026V006	44	26	6	And now I stand here impeached because of my hope in the fulfilment of the promise made by God to our forefathers–
B044C026V007	44	26	7	the promise which our twelve tribes, worshipping day and night with intense devotedness, hope to have made good to them. It is on the subject of this hope, Sir, that I am accused by the Jews.
B044C026V008	44	26	8	Why is it deemed with all of you a thing past belief if God raises the dead to life?
B044C026V009	44	26	9	»I myself, however, thought it a duty to do many things in hostility to the name of Jesus, the Nazarene.«
B044C026V010	44	26	10	And that was how I acted in Jerusalem. Armed with authority received from the High Priests I shut up many of God's people in various prisons, and when they were about to be put to death I gave my vote against them.
B044C026V011	44	26	11	In all the synagogues also I punished them many a time, and tried to make them blaspheme; and in my wild fury I chased them even to foreign towns.
B044C026V012	44	26	12	»While thus engaged, I was travelling one day to Damascus armed with authority and a commission from the High Priests,
B044C026V013	44	26	13	and on the journey, at noon, Sir, I saw a light from Heaven –brighter than the brightness of the sun– shining around me and around those who were travelling with me.«
B044C026V014	44	26	14	We all fell to the ground; and I heard a voice which said to me in Hebrew, »`Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting Me? You are finding it painful to kick against the ox-goad.'
B044C026V015	44	26	15	»`Who art Thou, Lord?' I asked.« `I am Jesus whom you are persecuting,' the Lord replied.
B044C026V016	44	26	16	`But rise, and stand on your feet; for I have appeared to you for the very purpose of appointing you My servant and My witness both as to the things you have already seen and as to those in which I will appear to you.
B044C026V017	44	26	17	I will save you from the Jewish people and from the Gentiles, to whom I send you to open their eyes,
B044C026V018	44	26	18	that they may turn from darkness to light and from the obedience to Satan to God, in order to receive forgiveness of sins and an inheritance among those who are sanctified through faith in Me.'
B044C026V019	44	26	19	»Therefore, King Agrippa, I was not disobedient to the heavenly vision;«
B044C026V020	44	26	20	but I proceeded to preach first to the people in Damascus, and then to those in Jerusalem and in all Judaea, and to the Gentiles, that they must repent and turn to God, and live lives consistent with such repentance.
B044C026V021	44	26	21	»It was on this account that the Jews seized me in the Temple and tried to kill me.«
B044C026V022	44	26	22	Having, however, obtained the help which is from God, I have stood firm until now, and have solemnly exhorted rich and poor alike, saying nothing except what the Prophets and Moses predicted as soon to happen,
B044C026V023	44	26	23	since the Christ was to be a suffering Christ, and by coming back from the dead was then to be the first to proclaim a message of light both to the Jewish people and to the Gentiles.«
B044C026V024	44	26	24	As Paul thus made his defence, Festus exclaimed in a loud voice, »You are raving mad, Paul; and great learning is driving you mad.«
B044C026V025	44	26	25	»I am not mad, most noble Festus,« replied Paul; »I am speaking words of sober truth.
B044C026V026	44	26	26	For the King, to whom I speak freely, knows about these matters. I am not to be persuaded that any detail of them has escaped his notice; for these things have not been done in a corner.
B044C026V027	44	26	27	King Agrippa, do you believe the Prophets? I know that you believe them.«
B044C026V028	44	26	28	Agrippa answered, »In brief, you are doing your best to persuade me to become a Christian.«
B044C026V029	44	26	29	»My prayer to God, whether briefly or at length,« replied Paul, »would be that not only you but all who are my hearers to-day, might become such as I am–except these chains.«
B044C026V030	44	26	30	So the King rose, and the Governor, and Bernice, and those who were sitting with them;
B044C026V031	44	26	31	and, having withdrawn, they talked to one another and said, »This man is doing nothing for which he deserves death or imprisonment.«
B044C026V032	44	26	32	And Agrippa said to Festus, »He might have been set at liberty, if he had not appealed to Caesar.«
B044C027V001	44	27	1	Now when it was decided that we should sail for Italy, they handed over Paul and a few other prisoners into the custody of Julius, a Captain of the Augustan battalion;
B044C027V002	44	27	2	and going on board a ship of Adramyttium which was about to sail to the ports of the province of Asia, we put to sea; Aristarchus, the Macedonian, from Thessalonica, forming one of our party.
B044C027V003	44	27	3	The next day we put in at Sidon. There Julius treated Paul with thoughtful kindness and allowed him to visit his friends and profit by their generous care.
B044C027V004	44	27	4	Putting to sea again, we sailed under the lee of Cyprus, because the winds were against us;
B044C027V005	44	27	5	and, sailing the whole length of the sea that lies off Cilicia and Pamphylia, we reached Myra in Lycia.
B044C027V006	44	27	6	There Julius found an Alexandrian ship bound for Italy, and put us on board of her.
B044C027V007	44	27	7	It took several days of slow sailing for us to come with difficulty off Cnidus; from which point, as the wind did not allow us to get on in the direct course, we ran under the lee of Crete by Salmone.
B044C027V008	44	27	8	Then, coasting along with difficulty, we reached a place called `Fair Havens,' near the town of Lasea.
B044C027V009	44	27	9	Our voyage thus far had occupied a considerable time, and the navigation being now unsafe and the Fast also already over, Paul warned them.
B044C027V010	44	27	10	»Sirs,« he said, »I perceive that before long the voyage will be attended with danger and heavy loss, not only to the cargo and the ship but to our own lives also.«
B044C027V011	44	27	11	But Julius let himself be persuaded by the pilot and by the owner rather than by Paul's arguments;
B044C027V012	44	27	12	and as the harbour was inconvenient for wintering in, the majority were in favour of putting out to sea, to try whether they could get to Phoenix –a harbour on the coast of Crete facing north-east and south-east– to winter there.
B044C027V013	44	27	13	And a light breeze from the south sprang up, so that they supposed they were now sure of their purpose. So weighing anchor they ran along the coast of Crete, hugging the shore.
B044C027V014	44	27	14	But it was not long before a furious north-east wind, coming down from the mountains, burst upon us and carried the ship out of her course.
B044C027V015	44	27	15	She was unable to make headway against the gale; so we gave up and let her drive.
B044C027V016	44	27	16	Then we ran under the lee of a little island called Cauda, where we managed with great difficulty to secure the boat;
B044C027V017	44	27	17	and, after hoisting it on board, they used frapping-cables to undergird the ship, and, as they were afraid of being driven on the Syrtis quicksands, they lowered the gear and lay to.
B044C027V018	44	27	18	But, as the storm was still violent, the next day they began to lighten the ship;
B044C027V019	44	27	19	and, on the third day, with their own hands they threw the ship's spare gear overboard.
B044C027V020	44	27	20	Then, when for several days neither sun nor stars were seen and the terrific gale still harassed us, the last ray of hope was now vanishing.
B044C027V021	44	27	21	When for a long time they had taken but little food, Paul, standing up among them, said, »Sirs, you ought to have listened to me and not have sailed from Crete. You would then have escaped this suffering and loss.
B044C027V022	44	27	22	But now take courage, for there will be no destruction of life among you, but of the ship only.
B044C027V023	44	27	23	For there stood by my side, last night, an angel of the God to whom I belong, and whom also I worship,
B044C027V024	44	27	24	and he said, »`Dismiss all fear, Paul, for you must stand before Caesar; and God has granted you the lives of all who are sailing with you.'
B044C027V025	44	27	25	»Therefore, Sirs, take courage; for I believe God, and am convinced that things will happen exactly as I have been told.
B044C027V026	44	27	26	But we are to be stranded on a certain island.«
B044C027V027	44	27	27	It was now the fourteenth night, and we were drifting through the Sea of Adria, when, about midnight, the sailors suspected that land was close at hand.
B044C027V028	44	27	28	So they hove the lead and found twenty fathoms of water; and after a short time they hove again and found fifteen fathoms.
B044C027V029	44	27	29	Then for fear of possibly running on rocks, they threw out four anchors from the stern and waited impatiently for daylight.
B044C027V030	44	27	30	The sailors, however, wanted to make their escape from the ship, and had lowered the boat into the sea, pretending that they were going to lay out anchors from the bow.
B044C027V031	44	27	31	But Paul, addressing Julius and the soldiers, said, »Your lives will be sacrificed, unless these men remain on board.«
B044C027V032	44	27	32	Then the soldiers cut the ropes of the ship's boat and let her fall off.
B044C027V033	44	27	33	And continually, up till daybreak, Paul kept urging all on board to take some food. »This is the fourteenth day,« he said, »that you have been anxiously waiting for the storm to cease, and have fasted, eating little or nothing.
B044C027V034	44	27	34	I therefore strongly advise you to take some food. This is essential for your safety. For not a hair will perish from the head of any one of you.«
B044C027V035	44	27	35	Having said this he took some bread, and, after giving thanks to God for it before them all, he broke it in pieces and began to eat it.
B044C027V036	44	27	36	This raised the spirits of all, and they too took food.
B044C027V037	44	27	37	There were 276 of us, crew and passengers, all told.
B044C027V038	44	27	38	After eating a hearty meal they lightened the ship by throwing the wheat overboard.
B044C027V039	44	27	39	When daylight came, they tried in vain to recognise the coast. But an inlet with a sandy beach attracted their attention, and now their object was, if possible, to run the ship aground in this inlet.
B044C027V040	44	27	40	So they cut away the anchors and left them in the sea, unloosing at the same time the bands which secured the paddle-rudders. Then, hoisting the foresail to the wind, they made for the beach.
B044C027V041	44	27	41	But coming to a place where two seas met, they stranded the ship, and her bow sticking fast remained immovable, while the stern began to go to pieces under the heavy hammering of the sea.
B044C027V042	44	27	42	Now the soldiers recommended that the prisoners should be killed, for fear some one of them might swim ashore and effect his escape.
B044C027V043	44	27	43	But their Captain, bent on securing Paul's safety, kept them from their purpose and gave orders that those who could swim should first jump overboard and get to land;
B044C027V044	44	27	44	and that the rest should follow, some on planks, and others on various things from the ship. In this way they all got safely to land.
B044C028V001	44	28	1	Our lives having been thus preserved, we discovered that the island was called Malta.
B044C028V002	44	28	2	The strange-speaking natives showed us remarkable kindness, for they lighted a fire and made us all welcome because of the pelting rain and the cold.
B044C028V003	44	28	3	Now, when Paul had gathered a bundle of sticks and had thrown them on the fire, a viper, driven by the heat, came out and fastened itself on his hand.
B044C028V004	44	28	4	When the natives saw the creature hanging to his hand, they said to one another, »Beyond doubt this man is a murderer, for, though saved from the sea, unerring Justice does not permit him to live.«
B044C028V005	44	28	5	He, however, shook the reptile off into the fire and was unhurt.
B044C028V006	44	28	6	They expected him soon to swell with inflammation or suddenly fall down dead; but, after waiting a long time and seeing no harm come to him, they changed their minds and said that he was a god.
B044C028V007	44	28	7	Now in the same part of the island there were estates belonging to the Governor, whose name was Publius. He welcomed us to his house, and for three days generously made us his guests.
B044C028V008	44	28	8	It happened, however, that his father was lying ill of dysentery aggravated by attacks of fever; so Paul went to see him, and, after praying, laid his hands on him and cured him.
B044C028V009	44	28	9	After this, all the other sick people in the island came and were cured.
B044C028V010	44	28	10	They also loaded us with honours, and when at last we sailed they put supplies on board for us.
B044C028V011	44	28	11	Three months passed before we set sail in an Alexandrian vessel, called the `Twin Brothers,' which had wintered at the island.
B044C028V012	44	28	12	At Syracuse we put in and stayed for two days.
B044C028V013	44	28	13	From there we came round and reached Rhegium; and a day later, a south wind sprang up which brought us by the evening of the next day to Puteoli.
B044C028V014	44	28	14	Here we found brethren, who invited us to remain with them for a week; and so we reached Rome.
B044C028V015	44	28	15	Meanwhile the brethren there, hearing of our movements, came as far as the Market of Appius and the Three Huts to meet us; and when Paul saw them he thanked God and felt encouraged.
B044C028V016	44	28	16	Upon our arrival in Rome, Paul received permission to live by himself, guarded by a soldier.
B044C028V017	44	28	17	After one complete day he invited the leading men among the Jews to meet him; and, when they were come together, he said to them, »As for me, brethren, although I had done nothing prejudicial to our people or contrary to the customs of our forefathers, I was handed over as a prisoner from Jerusalem into the power of the Romans.
B044C028V018	44	28	18	They, after they had sharply questioned me, were willing to set me at liberty, because they found no offence in me for which I deserve to die.
B044C028V019	44	28	19	But, at last, the opposition of the Jews compelled me to appeal to Caesar; not however that I had any charge to bring against my nation.
B044C028V020	44	28	20	For these reasons, then, I have invited you here, that I might see you and speak to you; for it is for the sake of Him who is the hope of Israel that this chain hangs upon me.«
B044C028V021	44	28	21	»For our part,« they replied, »we have not received any letters from Judaea about you, nor have any of our countrymen come here and reported or stated anything to your disadvantage.
B044C028V022	44	28	22	But we should be glad to hear from you what it is that you believe; for as for this sect all we know is that it is everywhere spoken against.«
B044C028V023	44	28	23	So they arranged a day with him and came to him in considerable numbers at the house of the friends who were entertaining him. And then, with solemn earnestness, he explained to them the subject of the Kingdom of God, endeavouring from morning till evening to convince them about Jesus, both from the Law of Moses and from the Prophets.
B044C028V024	44	28	24	Some were convinced; others refused to believe.
B044C028V025	44	28	25	Unable to agree among themselves, they at last left him, but not before Paul had spoken a parting word to them, saying, »Right well did the Holy Spirit say to your forefathers through the Prophet Isaiah:
B044C028V026	44	28	26	
        
B044C028V027	44	28	27	
        
B044C028V028	44	28	28	»Be fully assured, therefore, that this salvation –God's salvation– has now been sent to the Gentiles, and that they, at any rate, will give heed.«
B044C028V029	44	28	29	[]
B044C028V030	44	28	30	After this Paul lived for fully two years in a hired house of his own, receiving all who came to see him.
B044C028V031	44	28	31	He announced the coming of the Kingdom of God, and taught concerning the Lord Jesus Christ without let or hindrance.
B045C001V001	45	1	1	Paul, a bondservant of Jesus Christ, called to be an Apostle, set apart to proclaim God's Good News,
B045C001V002	45	1	2	which God had already promised through His Prophets in Holy Writ, concerning His Son,
B045C001V003	45	1	3	who, as regards His human descent, belonged to the posterity of David,
B045C001V004	45	1	4	but as regards the holiness of His Spirit was decisively proved by His Resurrection to be the Son of God–I mean concerning Jesus Christ our Lord,
B045C001V005	45	1	5	through whom we have received grace and Apostleship in His service in order to win men to obedience to the faith, among all Gentile peoples,
B045C001V006	45	1	6	among whom you also, called, as you have been, to belong to Jesus Christ, are numbered:
B045C001V007	45	1	7	To all God's loved ones who are in Rome, called to be saints. May grace and peace be granted to you from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B045C001V008	45	1	8	First of all, I thank my God through Jesus Christ for what He has done for all of you; for the report of your faith is spreading through the whole world.
B045C001V009	45	1	9	I call God to witness –to whom I render priestly and spiritual service by telling the Good News about His Son– how unceasingly I make mention of you in His presence,
B045C001V010	45	1	10	always in my prayers entreating that now, at length, if such be His will, the way may by some means be made clear for me to come to you.
B045C001V011	45	1	11	For I am longing to see you, in order to convey to you some spiritual help, so that you may be strengthened;
B045C001V012	45	1	12	in other words that while I am among you we may be mutually encouraged by one another's faith, yours and mine.
B045C001V013	45	1	13	And I desire you to know, brethren, that I have many a time intended to come to you –though until now I have been disappointed– in order that among you also I might gather some fruit from my labours, as I have already done among the rest of the Gentile nations.
B045C001V014	45	1	14	I am already under obligations alike to Greek-speaking races and to others, to cultured and to uncultured people:
B045C001V015	45	1	15	so that for my part I am willing and eager to proclaim the Good News to you also who are in Rome.
B045C001V016	45	1	16	For I am not ashamed of the Good News. It is God's power which is at work for the salvation of every one who believes–the Jew first, and then the Gentile.
B045C001V017	45	1	17	For in the Good News a righteousness which comes from God is being revealed, depending on faith and tending to produce faith; as the Scripture has it, 
B045C001V018	45	1	18	For God's anger is being revealed from Heaven against all impiety and against the iniquity of men who through iniquity suppress the truth. God is angry:
B045C001V019	45	1	19	because what may be known about Him is plain to their inmost consciousness; for He Himself has made it plain to them.
B045C001V020	45	1	20	For, from the very creation of the world, His invisible perfections –namely His eternal power and divine nature– have been rendered intelligible and clearly visible by His works, so that these men are without excuse.
B045C001V021	45	1	21	For when they had come to know God, they did not give Him glory as God nor render Him thanks, but they became absorbed in useless discussions, and their senseless minds were darkened.
B045C001V022	45	1	22	While boasting of their wisdom they became utter fools,
B045C001V023	45	1	23	and, instead of worshipping the imperishable God, they worshipped images resembling perishable man or resembling birds or beasts or reptiles.
B045C001V024	45	1	24	For this reason, in accordance with their own depraved cravings, God gave them up to uncleanness, allowing them to dishonour their bodies among themselves with impurity.
B045C001V025	45	1	25	For they had bartered the reality of God for what is unreal, and had offered divine honours and religious service to created things, rather than to the Creator–He who is for ever blessed. Amen.
B045C001V026	45	1	26	This then is the reason why God gave them up to vile passions. For not only did the women among them exchange the natural use of their bodies for one which is contrary to nature, but the men also,
B045C001V027	45	1	27	in just the same way –neglecting that for which nature intends women– burned with passion towards one another, men practising shameful vice with men, and receiving in their own selves the reward which necessarily followed their misconduct.
B045C001V028	45	1	28	And just as they had refused to continue to have a full knowledge of God, so it was to utterly worthless minds that God gave them up, for them to do things which should not be done.
B045C001V029	45	1	29	Their hearts overflowed with all sorts of dishonesty, mischief, greed, malice. They were full of envy and murder, and were quarrelsome, crafty, and spiteful.
B045C001V030	45	1	30	They were secret backbiters, open slanderers; hateful to God, insolent, haughty, boastful; inventors of new forms of sin, disobedient to parents, destitute of common sense,
B045C001V031	45	1	31	faithless to their promises, without natural affection, without human pity.
B045C001V032	45	1	32	In short, though knowing full well the sentence which God pronounces against actions such as theirs, as things which deserve death, they not only practise them, but even encourage and applaud others who do them.
B045C002V001	45	2	1	You are therefore without excuse, O man, whoever you are who sit in judgement upon others. For when you pass judgement on your fellow man, you condemn yourself; for you who sit in judgement upon others are guilty of the same misdeeds;
B045C002V002	45	2	2	and we know that God's judgement against those who commit such sins is in accordance with the truth.
B045C002V003	45	2	3	And you who pronounce judgement upon those who do such things although your own conduct is the same as theirs–do you imagine that you yourself will escape unpunished when God judges?
B045C002V004	45	2	4	Or is it that you think slightingly of His infinite goodness, forbearance and patience, unaware that the goodness of God is gently drawing you to repentance?
B045C002V005	45	2	5	The fact is that in the stubbornness of your impenitent heart you are treasuring up against yourself anger on the day of Anger–the day when the righteousness of God's judgements will stand revealed.
B045C002V006	45	2	6	-To each man He will make an award corresponding to his actions;-
B045C002V007	45	2	7	to those on the one hand who, by lives of persistent right-doing, are striving for glory, honour and immortality, the Life of the Ages;
B045C002V008	45	2	8	while on the other hand upon the self-willed who disobey the truth and obey unrighteousness will fall anger and fury, affliction and awful distress,
B045C002V009	45	2	9	coming upon the soul of every man and woman who deliberately does wrong–upon the Jew first, and then upon the Gentile;
B045C002V010	45	2	10	whereas glory, honour and peace will be given to every one who does what is good and right–to the Jew first and then to the Gentile.
B045C002V011	45	2	11	For God pays no attention to this world's distinctions.
B045C002V012	45	2	12	For all who have sinned apart from the Law will also perish apart from the Law, and all who have sinned whilst living under the Law, will be judged by the Law.
B045C002V013	45	2	13	It is not those that merely hear the Law read who are righteous in the sight of God, but it is those that obey the Law who will be pronounced righteous.
B045C002V014	45	2	14	For when Gentiles who have no Law obey by natural instinct the commands of the Law, they, without having a Law, are a Law to themselves;
B045C002V015	45	2	15	since they exhibit proof that a knowledge of the conduct which the Law requires is engraven on their hearts, while their consciences also bear witness to the Law, and their thoughts, as if in mutual discussion, accuse them or perhaps maintain their innocence–
B045C002V016	45	2	16	on the day when God will judge the secrets of men's lives by Jesus Christ, as declared in the Good News as I have taught it.
B045C002V017	45	2	17	And since you claim the name of Jew, and find rest and satisfaction in the Law, and make your boast in God,
B045C002V018	45	2	18	and know the supreme will, and can test things that differ –being a man who receives instruction from the Law–
B045C002V019	45	2	19	and have persuaded yourself that, as for you, you are a guide to the blind, a light to those who are in darkness,
B045C002V020	45	2	20	a schoolmaster for the dull and ignorant, a teacher of the young, because in the Law you possess an outline of real knowledge and an outline of the truth:
B045C002V021	45	2	21	you then who teach your fellow man, do you refuse to teach yourself? You who cry out against stealing, are you yourself a thief?
B045C002V022	45	2	22	You who forbid adultery, do you commit adultery? You who loathe idols, do you plunder their temples?
B045C002V023	45	2	23	You who make your boast in the Law, do you offend against its commands and so dishonour God?
B045C002V024	45	2	24	-For the name of God is blasphemed among the Gentile nations because of you,- as Holy Writ declares.
B045C002V025	45	2	25	Circumcision does indeed profit, if you obey the Law; but if you are a Law-breaker, the fact that you have been circumcised counts for nothing.
B045C002V026	45	2	26	In the same way if an uncircumcised man pays attention to the just requirements of the Law, shall not his lack of circumcision be overlooked, and,
B045C002V027	45	2	27	although he is a Gentile by birth, if he scrupulously obeys the Law, shall he not sit in judgement upon you who, possessing, as you do, a written Law and circumcision, are yet a Law-breaker?
B045C002V028	45	2	28	For the true Jew is not the man who is simply a Jew outwardly, and true circumcision is not that which is outward and bodily.
B045C002V029	45	2	29	But the true Jew is one inwardly, and true circumcision is heart-circumcision–not literal, but spiritual; and such people receive praise not from men, but from God.
B045C003V001	45	3	1	What special privilege, then, has a Jew? Or what benefit is to be derived from circumcision?
B045C003V002	45	3	2	The privilege is great from every point of view. First of all, because the Jews were entrusted with God's truth.
B045C003V003	45	3	3	For what if some Jews have proved unfaithful? Shall their faithlessness render God's faithfulness worthless?
B045C003V004	45	3	4	No, indeed; let us hold God to be true, though every man should prove to be false. As it stands written, 
B045C003V005	45	3	5	But if our unrighteousness sets God's righteousness in a clearer light, what shall we say? (Is God unrighteous –I speak in our everyday language– when He inflicts punishment?
B045C003V006	45	3	6	No indeed; for in that case how shall He judge all mankind?)
B045C003V007	45	3	7	If, for instance, a falsehood of mine has made God's truthfulness more conspicuous, redounding to His glory, why am I judged all the same as a sinner?
B045C003V008	45	3	8	And why should we not say –for so they wickedly misrepresent us, and so some charge us with arguing– »Let us do evil that good may come«? The condemnation of those who would so argue is just.
B045C003V009	45	3	9	What then? Are we Jews more highly estimated than they? Not in the least; for we have already charged all Jews and Gentiles alike with being in thraldom to sin.
B045C003V010	45	3	10	Thus it stands written, »There is not one righteous man.
B045C003V011	45	3	11	There is not one who is really wise, nor one who is a diligent seeker after God.
B045C003V012	45	3	12	All have turned aside from the right path; they have every one of them become corrupt. There is no one who does what is right–no, not so much as one.«
B045C003V013	45	3	13	»Their throats resemble an opened grave; with their tongues they have been talking deceitfully.« »The venom of vipers lies hidden behind their lips.«
B045C003V014	45	3	14	»Their mouths are full of cursing and bitterness.«
B045C003V015	45	3	15	»Their feet move swiftly to shed blood.
B045C003V016	45	3	16	Ruin and misery mark their path;
B045C003V017	45	3	17	and the way to peace they have not known.«
B045C003V018	45	3	18	»There is no fear of God before their eyes.«
B045C003V019	45	3	19	But it cannot be denied that all that the Law says is addressed to those who are living under the Law, in order that every mouth may be stopped, and that the whole world may await sentence from God.
B045C003V020	45	3	20	For on the ground of obedience to Law no man living will be declared righteous before Him. Law simply brings a sure knowledge of sin.
B045C003V021	45	3	21	But now a righteousness coming from God has been brought to light apart from any Law, both Law and Prophets bearing witness to it–
B045C003V022	45	3	22	a righteousness coming from God, which depends on faith in Jesus Christ and extends to all who believe. No distinction is made;
B045C003V023	45	3	23	for all alike have sinned, and all consciously come short of the glory of God,
B045C003V024	45	3	24	gaining acquittal from guilt by His free unpurchased grace through the deliverance which is found in Christ Jesus.
B045C003V025	45	3	25	He it is whom God put forward as a Mercy-seat, rendered efficacious through faith in His blood, in order to demonstrate His righteousness – because of the passing over, in God's forbearance, of the sins previously committed–
B045C003V026	45	3	26	with a view to demonstrating, at the present time, His righteousness, that He may be shown to be righteous Himself, and the giver of righteousness to those who believe in Jesus.
B045C003V027	45	3	27	Where then is there room for your boasting? It is for ever shut out. On what principle? On the ground of merit? No, but on the ground of faith.
B045C003V028	45	3	28	For we maintain that it is as the result of faith that a man is held to be righteous, apart from actions done in obedience to Law.
B045C003V029	45	3	29	Is God simply the God of the Jews, and not of the Gentiles also? He is certainly the God of the Gentiles also,
B045C003V030	45	3	30	unless you can deny that it is one and the same God who will pronounce the circumcised to be acquitted on the ground of faith, and the uncircumcised to be acquitted through the same faith.
B045C003V031	45	3	31	Do we then by means of this faith abolish the Law? No, indeed; we give the Law a firmer footing.
B045C004V001	45	4	1	What then shall we say that Abraham, our earthly forefather, has gained?
B045C004V002	45	4	2	For if he was held to be righteous on the ground of his actions, he has something to boast of; but not in the presence of God.
B045C004V003	45	4	3	For what says the Scripture? 
B045C004V004	45	4	4	But in the case of a man who works, pay is not reckoned a favour but a debt;
B045C004V005	45	4	5	whereas in the case of a man who pleads no actions of his own, but simply believes in Him who declares the ungodly free from guilt, his faith is placed to his credit as righteousness.
B045C004V006	45	4	6	In this way David also tells of the blessedness of the man to whose credit God places righteousness, apart from his actions.
B045C004V007	45	4	7	
        
B045C004V008	45	4	8	
        
B045C004V009	45	4	9	This declaration of blessedness, then, does it come simply to the circumcised, or to the uncircumcised as well? For 
B045C004V010	45	4	10	What then were the circumstances under which this took place? Was it after he had been circumcised, or before?
B045C004V011	45	4	11	Before, not after. And he received circumcision as a sign, a mark attesting the reality of the faith-righteousness which was his while still uncircumcised, that he might be the forefather of all those who believe even though they are uncircumcised–in order that this righteousness might be placed to their credit;
B045C004V012	45	4	12	and the forefather of the circumcised, namely of those who not merely are circumcised, but also walk in the steps of the faith which our forefather Abraham had while he was as yet uncircumcised.
B045C004V013	45	4	13	Again, the promise that he should inherit the world did not come to Abraham or his posterity conditioned by Law, but by faith-righteousness.
B045C004V014	45	4	14	For if it is the righteous through Law who are heirs, then faith is useless and the promise counts for nothing.
B045C004V015	45	4	15	For the Law inflicts punishment; but where no Law exists, there can be no violation of Law.
B045C004V016	45	4	16	All depends on faith, and for this reason–that acceptance with God might be an act of pure grace,
B045C004V017	45	4	17	so that the promise should be made sure to all Abraham's true descendants; not merely to those who are righteous through the Law, but to those who are righteous through a faith like that of Abraham. Thus in the sight of God in whom he believed, who gives life to the dead and makes reference to things that do not exist, as though they did, Abraham is the forefather of all of us. As it is written, 
B045C004V018	45	4	18	Under utterly hopeless circumstances he hopefully believed, so that he might become the forefather of many nations, in agreement with the words 
B045C004V019	45	4	19	And, without growing weak in faith, he could contemplate his own vital powers which had now decayed –for he was nearly 100 years old– and Sarah's barrenness.
B045C004V020	45	4	20	Nor did he in unbelief stagger at God's promise, but became mighty in faith, giving glory to God,
B045C004V021	45	4	21	and being absolutely certain that whatever promise He is bound by He is able also to make good.
B045C004V022	45	4	22	For this reason also his faith 
B045C004V023	45	4	23	Nor was the fact of its being placed to his credit put on record for his sake only;
B045C004V024	45	4	24	it was for our sakes too. Faith, before long, will be placed to the credit of us also who are believers in Him who raised Jesus, our Lord, from the dead,
B045C004V025	45	4	25	who was surrendered to death because of the offences we had committed, and was raised to life because of the acquittal secured for us.
B045C005V001	45	5	1	Standing then acquitted as the result of faith, let us enjoy peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ,
B045C005V002	45	5	2	through whom also, as the result of faith, we have obtained an introduction into that state of favour with God in which we stand, and we exult in hope of some day sharing in God's glory.
B045C005V003	45	5	3	And not only so: we also exult in our sufferings, knowing as we do, that suffering produces fortitude;
B045C005V004	45	5	4	fortitude, ripeness of character; and ripeness of character, hope;
B045C005V005	45	5	5	and that this hope never disappoints, because God's love for us floods our hearts through the Holy Spirit who has been given to us.
B045C005V006	45	5	6	For already, while we were still helpless, Christ at the right moment died for the ungodly.
B045C005V007	45	5	7	Why, it is scarcely conceivable that any one would die for a simply just man, although for a good and lovable man perhaps some one, here and there, will have the courage even to lay down his life.
B045C005V008	45	5	8	But God gives proof of His love to us in Christ's dying for us while we were still sinners.
B045C005V009	45	5	9	If therefore we have now been pronounced free from guilt through His blood, much more shall we be delivered from God's anger through Him.
B045C005V010	45	5	10	For if while we were hostile to God we were reconciled to Him through the death of His Son, it is still more certain that now that we are reconciled, we shall obtain salvation through Christ's life.
B045C005V011	45	5	11	And not only so, but we also exult in God through our Lord Jesus Christ, through whom we have now obtained that reconciliation.
B045C005V012	45	5	12	What follows? This comparison. Through one man sin entered into the world, and through sin death, and so death passed to all mankind in turn, in that all sinned.
B045C005V013	45	5	13	For prior to the Law sin was already in the world; only it is not entered in the account against us when no Law exists.
B045C005V014	45	5	14	Yet Death reigned as king from Adam to Moses even over those who had not sinned, as Adam did, against Law. And in Adam we have a type of Him whose coming was still future.
B045C005V015	45	5	15	But God's free gift immeasurably outweighs the transgression. For if through the transgression of the one individual the mass of mankind have died, infinitely greater is the generosity with which God's grace, and the gift given in His grace which found expression in the one man Jesus Christ, have been bestowed on the mass of mankind.
B045C005V016	45	5	16	And it is not with the gift as it was with the results of one individual's sin; for the judgement which one individual provoked resulted in condemnation, whereas the free gift after a multitude of transgressions results in acquittal.
B045C005V017	45	5	17	For if, through the transgression of the one individual, Death made use of the one individual to seize the sovereignty, all the more shall those who receive God's overflowing grace and gift of righteousness reign as kings in Life through the one individual, Jesus Christ.
B045C005V018	45	5	18	It follows then that just as the result of a single transgression is a condemnation which extends to the whole race, so also the result of a single decree of righteousness is a life-giving acquittal which extends to the whole race.
B045C005V019	45	5	19	For as through the disobedience of the one individual the mass of mankind were constituted sinners, so also through the obedience of the One the mass of mankind will be constituted righteous.
B045C005V020	45	5	20	Now Law was brought in later on, so that transgression might increase. But where sin increased, grace has overflowed;
B045C005V021	45	5	21	in order that as sin has exercised kingly sway in inflicting death, so grace, too, may exercise kingly sway in bestowing a righteousness which results in the Life of the Ages through Jesus Christ our Lord.
B045C006V001	45	6	1	To what conclusion, then, shall we come? Are we to persist in sinning in order that the grace extended to us may be the greater?
B045C006V002	45	6	2	No, indeed; how shall we who have died to sin, live in it any longer?
B045C006V003	45	6	3	And do you not know that all of us who have been baptized into Christ Jesus were baptized into His death?
B045C006V004	45	6	4	Well, then, we by our baptism were buried with Him in death, in order that, just as Christ was raised from among the dead by the Father's glorious power, we also should live an entirely new life.
B045C006V005	45	6	5	For since we have become one with Him by sharing in His death, we shall also be one with Him by sharing in His resurrection.
B045C006V006	45	6	6	This we know–that our old self was nailed to the cross with Him, in order that our sinful nature might be deprived of its power, so that we should no longer be the slaves of sin;
B045C006V007	45	6	7	for he who has paid the penalty of death stands absolved from his sin.
B045C006V008	45	6	8	But, seeing that we have died with Christ, we believe that we shall also live with Him;
B045C006V009	45	6	9	because we know that Christ, having come back to life, is no longer liable to die.
B045C006V010	45	6	10	Death has no longer any power over Him. For by the death which He died He became, once for all, dead in relation to sin; but by the life which He now lives He is alive in relation to God.
B045C006V011	45	6	11	In the same way you also must regard yourselves as dead in relation to sin, but as alive in relation to God, because you are in Christ Jesus.
B045C006V012	45	6	12	Let not Sin therefore reign as king in your mortal bodies, causing you to be in subjection to their cravings;
B045C006V013	45	6	13	and no longer lend your faculties as unrighteous weapons for Sin to use. On the contrary surrender your very selves to God as living men who have risen from the dead, and surrender your several faculties to God, to be used as weapons to maintain the right.
B045C006V014	45	6	14	For Sin shall not be lord over you, since you are subjects not of Law, but of grace.
B045C006V015	45	6	15	Are we therefore to sin because we are no longer under the authority of Law, but under grace? No, indeed!
B045C006V016	45	6	16	Do you not know that if you surrender yourselves as bondservants to obey any one, you become the bondservants of him whom you obey, whether the bondservants of Sin (with death as the result) or of Duty (resulting in righteousness)?
B045C006V017	45	6	17	But thanks be to God that though you were once in thraldom to Sin, you have now yielded a hearty obedience to that system of truth in which you have been instructed.
B045C006V018	45	6	18	You were set free from the tyranny of Sin, and became the bondservants of Righteousness–
B045C006V019	45	6	19	your human infirmity leads me to employ these familiar figures–and just as you once surrendered your faculties into bondage to Impurity and ever-increasing disregard of Law, so you must now surrender them into bondage to Righteousness ever advancing towards perfect holiness.
B045C006V020	45	6	20	For when you were the bondservants of sin, you were under no sort of subjection to Righteousness.
B045C006V021	45	6	21	At that time, then, what benefit did you get from conduct which you now regard with shame? Why, such things finally result in death.
B045C006V022	45	6	22	But now that you have been set free from the tyranny of Sin, and have become the bondservants of God, you have your reward in being made holy, and you have the Life of the Ages as the final result.
B045C006V023	45	6	23	For the wages paid by Sin are death; but God's free gift is the Life of the Ages bestowed upon us in Christ Jesus our Lord.
B045C007V001	45	7	1	Brethren, do you not know –for I am writing to people acquainted with the Law– that it is during our lifetime that we are subject to the Law?
B045C007V002	45	7	2	A wife, for instance, whose husband is living is bound to him by the Law; but if her husband dies the law that bound her to him has now no hold over her.
B045C007V003	45	7	3	This accounts for the fact that if during her husband's life she lives with another man, she will be stigmatized as an adulteress; but that if her husband is dead she is no longer under the old prohibition, and even though she marries again, she is not an adulteress.
B045C007V004	45	7	4	So, my brethren, to you also the Law died through the incarnation of Christ, that you might be wedded to Another, namely to Him who rose from the dead in order that we might yield fruit to God.
B045C007V005	45	7	5	For whilst we were under the thraldom of our earthly natures, sinful passions – made sinful by the Law– were always being aroused to action in our bodily faculties that they might yield fruit to death.
B045C007V006	45	7	6	But seeing that we have died to that which once held us in bondage, the Law has now no hold over us, so that we render a service which, instead of being old and formal, is new and spiritual.
B045C007V007	45	7	7	What follows? Is the Law itself a sinful thing? No, indeed; on the contrary, unless I had been taught by the Law, I should have known nothing of sin as sin. For instance, I should not have known what covetousness is, if the Law had not repeatedly said, 
B045C007V008	45	7	8	Sin took advantage of this, and by means of the Commandment stirred up within me every kind of coveting; for apart from Law sin would be dead.
B045C007V009	45	7	9	Once, apart from Law, I was alive, but when the Commandment came, sin sprang into life, and I died;
B045C007V010	45	7	10	and, as it turned out, the very Commandment which was to bring me life, brought me death.
B045C007V011	45	7	11	For sin seized the advantage, and by means of the Commandment it completely deceived me, and also put me to death.
B045C007V012	45	7	12	So that the Law itself is holy, and the Commandment is holy, just and good.
B045C007V013	45	7	13	Did then a thing which is good become death to me? No, indeed, but sin did; so that through its bringing about death by means of what was good, it might be seen in its true light as sin, in order that by means of the Commandment the unspeakable sinfulness of sin might be plainly shown.
B045C007V014	45	7	14	For we know that the Law is a spiritual thing; but I am unspiritual–the slave, bought and sold, of sin.
B045C007V015	45	7	15	For what I do, I do not recognize as my own action. What I desire to do is not what I do, but what I am averse to is what I do.
B045C007V016	45	7	16	But if I do that which I do not desire to do, I admit the excellence of the Law,
B045C007V017	45	7	17	and now it is no longer I that do these things, but the sin which has its home within me does them.
B045C007V018	45	7	18	For I know that in me, that is, in my lower self, nothing good has its home; for while the will to do right is present with me, the power to carry it out is not.
B045C007V019	45	7	19	For what I do is not the good thing that I desire to do; but the evil thing that I desire not to do, is what I constantly do.
B045C007V020	45	7	20	But if I do that which I desire not to do, it can no longer be said that it is I who do it, but the sin which has its home within me does it.
B045C007V021	45	7	21	I find therefore the law of my nature to be that when I desire to do what is right, evil is lying in ambush for me.
B045C007V022	45	7	22	For in my inmost self all my sympathy is with the Law of God;
B045C007V023	45	7	23	but I discover within me a different Law at war with the Law of my understanding, and leading me captive to the Law which is everywhere at work in my body–the Law of sin.
B045C007V024	45	7	24	(Unhappy man that I am! who will rescue me from this death-burdened body?
B045C007V025	45	7	25	Thanks be to God through Jesus Christ our Lord!) To sum up then, with my understanding, I –my true self– am in servitude to the Law of God, but with my lower nature I am in servitude to the Law of sin.
B045C008V001	45	8	1	There is therefore now no condemnation to those who are in Christ Jesus;
B045C008V002	45	8	2	for the Spirit's Law – telling of Life in Christ Jesus– has set me free from the Law that deals only with sin and death.
B045C008V003	45	8	3	For what was impossible to the Law –powerless as it was because it acted through frail humanity– God effected. Sending His own Son in a body like that of sinful human nature and as a sacrifice for sin, He pronounced sentence upon sin in human nature;
B045C008V004	45	8	4	in order that in our case the requirements of the Law might be fully met. For our lives are regulated not by our earthly, but by our spiritual natures.
B045C008V005	45	8	5	For if men are controlled by their earthly natures, they give their minds to earthly things. If they are controlled by their spiritual natures, they give their minds to spiritual things.
B045C008V006	45	8	6	Because for the mind to be given up to earthly things means death; but for it to be given up to spiritual things means Life and peace.
B045C008V007	45	8	7	Abandonment to earthly things is a state of enmity to God. Such a mind does not submit to God's Law, and indeed cannot do so.
B045C008V008	45	8	8	And those whose hearts are absorbed in earthly things cannot please God.
B045C008V009	45	8	9	You, however, are not devoted to earthly, but to spiritual things, if the Spirit of God is really dwelling in you; whereas if any man has not the Spirit of Christ, such a one does not belong to Him.
B045C008V010	45	8	10	But if Christ is in you, though your body must die because of sin, yet your spirit has Life because of righteousness.
B045C008V011	45	8	11	And if the Spirit of Him who raised up Jesus from the dead is dwelling in you, He who raised up Christ from the dead will give Life also to your mortal bodies because of His Spirit who dwells in you.
B045C008V012	45	8	12	Therefore, brethren, it is not to our lower natures that we are under obligation that we should live by their rule.
B045C008V013	45	8	13	For if you so live, death is near; but if, through being under the sway of the spirit, you are putting your old bodily habits to death, you will live.
