B045C015V021	45	15	21	But, as Scripture says, 
B045C015V022	45	15	22	And it is really this which has again and again prevented my coming to you.
B045C015V023	45	15	23	But now, as there is no more unoccupied ground in this part of the world, and I have for years past been eager to pay you a visit,
B045C015V024	45	15	24	I hope, as soon as ever I extend my travels into Spain, to see you on my way and be helped forward by you on my journey, when I have first enjoyed being with you for a time.
B045C015V025	45	15	25	But at present I am going to Jerusalem to serve God's people,
B045C015V026	45	15	26	for Macedonia and Greece have kindly contributed a certain sum in relief of the poor among God's people, in Jerusalem.
B045C015V027	45	15	27	Yes, they have kindly done this, and, in fact, it was a debt they owed them. For seeing that the Gentiles have been admitted in to partnership with the Jews in their spiritual blessings, they in turn are under an obligation to render sacred service to the Jews in temporal things.
B045C015V028	45	15	28	So after discharging this duty, and making sure that these kind gifts reach those for whom they are intended, I shall start for Spain, passing through Rome on my way there;
B045C015V029	45	15	29	and I know that when I come to you it will be with a vast amount of blessing from Christ.
B045C015V030	45	15	30	But I entreat you, brethren, in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ and by the love which His Spirit inspires, to help me by wrestling in prayer to God on my behalf,
B045C015V031	45	15	31	asking that I may escape unhurt from those in Judaea who are disobedient, and that the service which I am going to Jerusalem to render may be well received by the Church there,
B045C015V032	45	15	32	in order that if God be willing I may come to you with a glad heart, and may enjoy a time of rest with you.
B045C015V033	45	15	33	May God, who gives peace be with you all! Amen.
B045C016V001	45	16	1	Herewith I introduce our sister Phoebe to you, who is a servant of the Church at Cenchreae,
B045C016V002	45	16	2	that you may receive her as a fellow Christian in a manner worthy of God's people, and may assist her in any matter in which she may need help. For she has indeed been a kind friend to many, including myself.
B045C016V003	45	16	3	Greetings to Prisca and Aquila my fellow labourers in the work of Christ Jesus–
B045C016V004	45	16	4	friends who have endangered their own lives for mine. I am grateful to them, and not I alone, but all the Gentile Churches also.
B045C016V005	45	16	5	Greetings, too, to the Church that meets at their house. Greetings to my dear Epaenetus, who was the earliest convert to Christ in the province of Asia;
B045C016V006	45	16	6	to Mary who has laboured strenuously among you;
B045C016V007	45	16	7	and to Andronicus and Junia, my countrymen, who once shared my imprisonment. They are of note among the Apostles, and are Christians of longer standing than myself.
B045C016V008	45	16	8	Greetings to Ampliatus, dear to me in the Lord;
B045C016V009	45	16	9	to Urban, our fellow labourer in Christ, and to my dear Stachys.
B045C016V010	45	16	10	Greetings to Apella, that veteran believer; and to the members of the household of Aristobulus.
B045C016V011	45	16	11	Greetings to my countryman, Herodion; and to the believing members of the household of Narcissus.
B045C016V012	45	16	12	Greetings to those Christian workers, Tryphaena and Tryphosa; also to dear Persis, who has laboured strenuously in the Lord's work.
B045C016V013	45	16	13	Greetings to Rufus, who is one of the Lord's chosen people; and to his mother, who has also been a mother to me.
B045C016V014	45	16	14	Greetings to Asyncritus, Phlegon, Hermes, Patrobas, Hermas, and to the brethren associated with them;
B045C016V015	45	16	15	to Philologus and Julia, Nereus and his sister and Olympas, and to all God's people associated with them.
B045C016V016	45	16	16	Salute one another with a holy kiss. All the Churches of Christ send greetings to you.
B045C016V017	45	16	17	But I beseech you, brethren, to keep a watch on those who are causing the divisions among you, and are leading others into sin, in defiance of the instruction which you have received; and habitually to shun them.
B045C016V018	45	16	18	For men of that stamp are not bondservants of Christ our Lord, but are slaves to their own appetites; and by their plausible words and their flattery they utterly deceive the minds of the simple.
B045C016V019	45	16	19	Your fidelity to the truth is everywhere known. I rejoice over you, therefore, but I wish you to be wise as to what is good, and simple-minded as to what is evil.
B045C016V020	45	16	20	And before long, God the giver of peace will crush Satan under your feet. The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you!
B045C016V021	45	16	21	Timothy, my fellow worker, sends you greetings, and so do my countrymen Lucius, Jason and Sosipater.
B045C016V022	45	16	22	I, Tertius, who write this letter, send you Christian greetings.
B045C016V023	45	16	23	Gaius, my host, who is also the host of the whole Church, greets you. So do Erastus, the treasurer of the city, and Quartus our brother.
B045C016V024	45	16	24	[]
B045C016V025	45	16	25	To Him who has it in His power to make you strong, as declared in the Good News which I am spreading, and the proclamation concerning Jesus Christ, in harmony with the unveiling of the Truth which in the periods of past Ages remained unuttered,
B045C016V026	45	16	26	but has now been brought fully to light, and by the command of the God of the Ages has been made known by the writings of the Prophets among all the Gentiles to win them to obedience to the faith–
B045C016V027	45	16	27	to God, the only wise, through Jesus Christ, even to Him be the glory through all the Ages! Amen.
B046C001V001	46	1	1	Paul, called to be an Apostle of Christ Jesus through the will of God–and our brother Sosthenes:
B046C001V002	46	1	2	To the Church of God in Corinth, men and women consecrated in Christ Jesus, called to be saints, with all in every place who call on the name of our Lord Jesus Christ– their Lord as well as ours.
B046C001V003	46	1	3	May grace and peace be granted to you from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B046C001V004	46	1	4	I thank my God continually on your behalf for the grace of God bestowed on you in Christ Jesus–
B046C001V005	46	1	5	that you have been so richly blessed in Him, with readiness of speech and fulness of knowledge.
B046C001V006	46	1	6	Thus my testimony as to the Christ has been confirmed in your experience,
B046C001V007	46	1	7	so that there is no gift of God in which you consciously come short while patiently waiting for the reappearing of our Lord Jesus Christ,
B046C001V008	46	1	8	who will also keep you stedfast to the very End, so that you will be free from reproach on the day of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B046C001V009	46	1	9	God is ever true to His promises, and it was by Him that you were, one and all, called into fellowship with his Son Jesus Christ, our Lord.
B046C001V010	46	1	10	Now I entreat you, brethren, in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ, to cultivate a spirit of harmony –all of you– and that there be no divisions among you, but rather a perfect union through your having one mind and one judgement.
B046C001V011	46	1	11	For I have been distinctly informed, my brethren, about you by Chloe's people, that there are dissensions among you.
B046C001V012	46	1	12	What I mean is that each of you is a partisan. One man says »I belong to Paul;« another »I belong to Apollos;« a third »I belong to Peter;« a fourth »I belong to Christ.«
B046C001V013	46	1	13	Is the Christ in fragments? Is it Paul who was crucified on your behalf? Or were you baptized to be Paul's adherents?
B046C001V014	46	1	14	I thank God that I did not baptize any of you except Crispus and Gaius–
B046C001V015	46	1	15	for fear people should say that you were baptized to be my adherents.
B046C001V016	46	1	16	I did, however, baptize Stephanas' household also: but I do not think that I baptized any one else.
B046C001V017	46	1	17	Christ did not send me to baptize, but to proclaim the Good News; and not in merely wise words–lest the Cross of Christ should be deprived of its power.
B046C001V018	46	1	18	For the Message of the Cross is foolishness to those who are on the way to perdition, but it is the power of God to those whom He is saving.
B046C001V019	46	1	19	For so it stands written, 
B046C001V020	46	1	20	Where is your wise man? Where your expounder of the Law? Where your investigator of the questions of this present age? Has not God shown the world's wisdom to be utter foolishness?
B046C001V021	46	1	21	For after the world by its wisdom –as God in His wisdom had ordained– had failed to gain the knowledge of God, God was pleased, by the apparent foolishness of the Message which we preach, to save those who accepted it.
B046C001V022	46	1	22	Seeing that Jews demand miracles, and Greeks go in search of wisdom,
B046C001V023	46	1	23	while we proclaim a Christ who has been crucified–to the Jews a stumbling-block, to Gentiles foolishness,
B046C001V024	46	1	24	but to those who have received the Call, whether Jews or Greeks, Christ the power of God and the wisdom of God.
B046C001V025	46	1	25	Because that which the world deems foolish in God is wiser than men's wisdom, and that which it deems feeble in God is mightier than men's might.
B046C001V026	46	1	26	For consider, brethren, God's call to you. Not many who are wise with merely human wisdom, not many of position and influence, not many of noble birth have been called.
B046C001V027	46	1	27	But God has chosen the things which the world regards as foolish, in order to put its wise men to shame; and God has chosen the things which the world regards as destitute of influence, in order to put its powerful things to shame;
B046C001V028	46	1	28	and the things which the world regards as base, and those which it sets utterly at nought –things that have no existence– God has chosen in order to reduce to nothing things that do exist;
B046C001V029	46	1	29	to prevent any mortal man from boasting in the presence of God.
B046C001V030	46	1	30	But you –and it is all God's doing– are in Christ Jesus: He has become for us a wisdom which is from God, consisting of righteousness and sanctification and deliverance;
B046C001V031	46	1	31	in order that it may be as Scripture says, 
B046C002V001	46	2	1	And as for myself, brethren, when I came to you, it was not with surpassing power of eloquence or earthly wisdom that I came, announcing to you that which God had commanded me to bear witness to.
B046C002V002	46	2	2	For I determined to be utterly ignorant, when among you, of everything except of Jesus Christ, and of Him as having been crucified.
B046C002V003	46	2	3	And so far as I myself was concerned, I came to you in conscious feebleness and in fear and in deep anxiety.
B046C002V004	46	2	4	And my language and the Message that I proclaimed were not adorned with persuasive words of earthly wisdom, but depended upon truths which the Spirit taught and mightily carried home;
B046C002V005	46	2	5	so that your trust might rest not on the wisdom of man but on the power of God.
B046C002V006	46	2	6	Yet when we are among mature believers we do speak words of wisdom; a wisdom not belonging, however, to the present age nor to the leaders of the present age who are soon to pass away.
B046C002V007	46	2	7	But in dealing with truths hitherto kept secret we speak of God's wisdom–that hidden wisdom which, before the world began, God pre-destined, so that it should result in glory to us;
B046C002V008	46	2	8	a wisdom which not one of the leaders of the present age possesses, for if they had possessed it, they would never have crucified the Lord of glory.
B046C002V009	46	2	9	But –to use the words of Scripture– we speak of 
B046C002V010	46	2	10	For us, however, God has drawn aside the veil through the teaching of the Spirit; for the Spirit searches everything, including the depths of the divine nature.
B046C002V011	46	2	11	For, among human beings, who knows a man's inner thoughts except the man's own spirit within him? In the same way, also, only God's Spirit is acquainted with God's inner thoughts.
B046C002V012	46	2	12	But we have not received the spirit of the world, but the Spirit which comes forth from God, that we may know the blessings that have been so freely given to us by God.
B046C002V013	46	2	13	Of these we speak –not in language which man's wisdom teaches us, but in that which the Spirit teaches– adapting, as we do, spiritual words to spiritual truths.
B046C002V014	46	2	14	The unspiritual man rejects the things of the Spirit of God, and cannot attain to the knowledge of them, because they are spiritually judged.
B046C002V015	46	2	15	But the spiritual man judges of everything, although he is himself judged by no one.
B046C002V016	46	2	16	For 
B046C003V001	46	3	1	And as for myself, brethren, I found it impossible to speak to you as spiritual men. It had to be as to worldlings–mere babes in Christ.
B046C003V002	46	3	2	I fed you with milk and not with solid food, since for this you were not yet strong enough. And even now you are not strong enough:
B046C003V003	46	3	3	you are still unspiritual. For so long as jealousy and strife continue among you, can it be denied that you are unspiritual and are living and acting like mere men of the world?
B046C003V004	46	3	4	For when some one says, »I belong to Paul,« and another says, »I belong to Apollos,« is not this the way men of the world speak?
B046C003V005	46	3	5	What then is Apollos? And what is Paul? They are just God's servants, through whose efforts, and as the Lord granted power to each, you accepted the faith.
B046C003V006	46	3	6	I planted and Apollos watered; but it was God who was, all the time, giving the increase.
B046C003V007	46	3	7	So that neither the planter nor the waterer is of any importance. God who gives the increase is all in all.
B046C003V008	46	3	8	Now in aim and purpose the planter and the waterer are one; and yet each will receive his own special reward, answering to his own special work.
B046C003V009	46	3	9	Apollos and I are simply fellow workers for and with God, and you are 
B046C003V010	46	3	10	In discharge of the task which God graciously entrusted to me, I –like a competent master-builder– have laid a foundation, and others are building upon it. But let every one be careful how and what he builds.
B046C003V011	46	3	11	For no one can lay any other foundation in addition to that which is already laid, namely Jesus Christ.
B046C003V012	46	3	12	And whether the building which any one is erecting on that foundation be of gold or silver or costly stones, of timber or hay or straw–
B046C003V013	46	3	13	the true character of each individual's work will become manifest. For the day of Christ will disclose it, because that day is soon to come upon us clothed in fire, and as for the quality of every one's work– the fire is the thing which will test it.
B046C003V014	46	3	14	If any one's work –the building which he has erected– stands the test, he will be rewarded.
B046C003V015	46	3	15	If any one's work is burnt up, he will suffer the loss of it; yet he will himself be rescued, but only, as it were, by passing through the fire.
B046C003V016	46	3	16	Do you not know that you are God's Sanctuary, and that the Spirit of God has His home within you?
B046C003V017	46	3	17	If any one is marring the Sanctuary of God, him will God mar; for the Sanctuary of God is holy, which you all are.
B046C003V018	46	3	18	Let no one deceive himself. If any man imagines that he is wise, compared with the rest of you, with the wisdom of the present age, let him become »foolish« so that he may be wise.
B046C003V019	46	3	19	This world's wisdom is »foolishness« in God's sight; for it is written, 
B046C003V020	46	3	20	And again, 
B046C003V021	46	3	21	Therefore let no one boast about his human teachers.
B046C003V022	46	3	22	For everything belongs to you –be it Paul or Apollos or Peter, the world or life or death, things present or future– everything belongs to you;
B046C003V023	46	3	23	and you belong to Christ, and Christ belongs to God.
B046C004V001	46	4	1	As for us Apostles, let any one take this view of us–we are Christ's officers, and stewards of God's secret truths.
B046C004V002	46	4	2	This being so, it follows that fidelity is what is required in stewards.
B046C004V003	46	4	3	I however am very little concerned at undergoing your scrutiny, or that of other men; in fact I do not even scrutinize myself.
B046C004V004	46	4	4	Though I am not conscious of having been in any way unfaithful, yet I do not for that reason stand acquitted; but He whose scrutiny I must undergo is the Lord.
B046C004V005	46	4	5	Therefore form no premature judgements, but wait until the Lord returns. He will both bring to light the secrets of darkness and will openly disclose the motives that have been in people's hearts; and then the praise which each man deserves will come to him from God.
B046C004V006	46	4	6	In writing this much, brethren, with special reference to Apollos and myself, I have done so for your sakes, in order to teach you by our example what those words mean, which say, »Nothing beyond what is written!« –so that you may cease to take sides in boastful rivalry, for one teacher against another.
B046C004V007	46	4	7	Why, who gives you your superiority, my brother? Or what have you that you did not receive? And if you really did receive it, why boast as if this were not so?
B046C004V008	46	4	8	Every one of you already has all that heart can desire; already you have grown rich; without waiting for us, you have ascended your thrones! Yes indeed, would to God that you had ascended your thrones, that we also might reign with you!
B046C004V009	46	4	9	God, it seems to me, has exhibited us Apostles last of all, as men condemned to death; for we have come to be a spectacle to all creation–alike to angels and to men.
B046C004V010	46	4	10	We, for Christ's sake, are labeled as »foolish«; you, as Christians, are men of shrewd intelligence. We are mere weaklings: you are strong. You are in high repute: we are outcasts.
B046C004V011	46	4	11	To this very moment we endure both hunger and thirst, with scanty clothing and many a blow.
B046C004V012	46	4	12	Homes we have none. Wearily we toil, working with our own hands. When reviled, we bless; when persecuted, we bear it patiently;
B046C004V013	46	4	13	when slandered, we try to conciliate. We have come to be regarded as the mere dirt and filth of the world–the refuse of the universe, even to this hour.
B046C004V014	46	4	14	I am not writing all this to shame you, but I am offering you advice as my dearly-loved children.
B046C004V015	46	4	15	For even if you were to have ten thousand spiritual instructors–for all that you could not have several fathers. It is I who in Christ Jesus became your father through the Good News.
B046C004V016	46	4	16	I entreat you therefore to become like me.
B046C004V017	46	4	17	For this reason I have sent Timothy to you. Spiritually he is my dearly-loved and faithful child. He will remind you of my habits as a Christian teacher–the manner in which I teach everywhere in every Church.
B046C004V018	46	4	18	But some of you have been puffed up through getting the idea that I am not coming to Corinth.
B046C004V019	46	4	19	But, if the Lord is willing, I shall come to you without delay; and then I shall know not the fine speeches of these conceited people, but their power.
B046C004V020	46	4	20	For Apostolic authority is not a thing of words, but of power.
B046C004V021	46	4	21	Which shall it be? Shall I come to you with a rod, or in a loving and tender spirit?
B046C005V001	46	5	1	It is actually reported that there is fornication among you, and of a kind unheard of even among the Gentiles–a man has his father's wife!
B046C005V002	46	5	2	And you, instead of mourning and removing from among you the man who has done this deed of shame, are filled with self-complacency!
B046C005V003	46	5	3	I for my part, present with you in spirit although absent in body, have already, as though I were present, judged him who has so acted.
B046C005V004	46	5	4	In the name of our Lord Jesus, when you are all assembled and my spirit is with you, together with the power of our Lord Jesus,
B046C005V005	46	5	5	I have handed over such a man to Satan for the destruction of his body, that his spirit may be saved on the day of the Lord Jesus.
B046C005V006	46	5	6	It is no good thing–this which you make the ground of your boasting. Do you not know that a little yeast corrupts the whole of the dough?
B046C005V007	46	5	7	Get rid of the old yeast so that you may be dough of a new kind; for in fact you 
B046C005V008	46	5	8	Therefore let us keep our festival not with old yeast nor with the yeast of what is evil and mischievous, but with bread free from yeast–the bread of transparent sincerity and of truth.
B046C005V009	46	5	9	I wrote to you in that letter that you were not to associate with fornicators;
B046C005V010	46	5	10	not that in this world you are to keep wholly aloof from such as they, any more than from people who are avaricious and greedy of gain, or from worshippers of idols. For that would mean that you would be compelled to go out of the world altogether.
B046C005V011	46	5	11	But what I meant was that you were not to associate with any one bearing the name of »brother,« if he was addicted to fornication or avarice or idol-worship or abusive language or hard-drinking or greed of gain. With such a man you ought not even to eat.
B046C005V012	46	5	12	For what business of mine is it to judge outsiders? Is it not for you to judge those who are within the Church
B046C005V013	46	5	13	while you leave to God's judgement those who are outside? Remove the wicked man from among you.
B046C006V001	46	6	1	If one of you has a grievance against an opponent, does he dare to go to law before irreligious men and not before God's people?
B046C006V002	46	6	2	Do you not know that God's people will sit in judgement upon the world? And if you are the court before which the world is to be judged, are you unfit to deal with these petty matters?
B046C006V003	46	6	3	Do you not know that we are to sit in judgement upon angels–to say nothing of things belonging to this life?
B046C006V004	46	6	4	If therefore you have things belonging to this life which need to be decided, is it men who are absolutely nothing in the Church–is it 
B046C006V005	46	6	5	I say this to put you to shame. Has it come to this, that there does not exist among you a single wise man competent to decide between a man and his brother,
B046C006V006	46	6	6	but brother goes to law with brother, and that before unbelievers?
B046C006V007	46	6	7	To say no more, then, it is altogether a defect in you that you have law-suits with one another. Why not rather endure injustice? Why not rather submit to being defrauded?
B046C006V008	46	6	8	On the contrary you yourselves inflict injustice and fraud, and upon brethren too.
B046C006V009	46	6	9	Do you not know that unrighteous men will not inherit God's Kingdom? Cherish no delusion here. Neither fornicators, nor idolaters, nor adulterers, nor any who are guilty of unnatural crime,
B046C006V010	46	6	10	nor theives, nor avaricious people, nor any who are addicted to hard drinking, to abusive language or to greed of gain, will inherit God's Kingdom.
B046C006V011	46	6	11	And all this describes what some of you were. But now you have had every stain washed off: now you have been set apart as holy: now you have been pronounced free from guilt; in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ and through the Spirit of our God.
B046C006V012	46	6	12	Everything is allowable to me, but not everything is profitable. Everything is allowable to me, but to nothing will I become a slave.
B046C006V013	46	6	13	Food of all kinds is meant for the stomach, and the stomach is meant for food, and God will cause both of them to perish. Yet the body does not exist for the purpose of fornication, but for the Master's service, and the Master exists for the body;
B046C006V014	46	6	14	and as God by His power raised the Master to life, so He will also raise us up.
B046C006V015	46	6	15	Do you not know that your bodies are members of Christ? Shall I then take away the members of Christ and make them the members of a prostitute? No, indeed.
B046C006V016	46	6	16	Or do you not know that a man who has to do with a prostitute is one with her in body? For God says, 
B046C006V017	46	6	17	But he who is in union with the Master is one with Him in spirit.
B046C006V018	46	6	18	Flee from fornication. Any other sin that a human being commits lies outside the body; but he who commits fornication sins against his own body.
B046C006V019	46	6	19	Or do you not know that your bodies are a sanctuary of the Holy Spirit who is within you–the Spirit whom you have from God?
B046C006V020	46	6	20	And you are not your own, for you have been redeemed at infinite cost. Therefore glorify God in your bodies.
B046C007V001	46	7	1	I now deal with the subjects mentioned in your letter. It is well for a man to abstain altogether from marriage.
B046C007V002	46	7	2	But because there is so much fornication every man should have a wife of his own, and every woman should have a husband.
B046C007V003	46	7	3	Let a man pay his wife her due, and let a woman also pay her husband his.
B046C007V004	46	7	4	A married woman is not mistress of her own person: her husband has certain rights. In the same way a married man is not master of his own person: his wife has certain rights.
B046C007V005	46	7	5	Do not refuse one another, unless perhaps it is just for a time and by mutual consent, so that you may devote yourselves to prayer and may then associate again; lest the Adversary begin to tempt you because of your deficiency in self-control.
B046C007V006	46	7	6	Thus much in the way of concession, not of command.
B046C007V007	46	7	7	Yet I would that everybody lived as I do; but each of us has his own special gift from God–one in one direction and one in another.
B046C007V008	46	7	8	But I tell the unmarried, and women who are widows, that it is well for them to remain as I am.
B046C007V009	46	7	9	If, however, they cannot maintain self-control, by all means let them marry; for marriage is better than the fever of passion.
B046C007V010	46	7	10	But to those already married my instructions are –yet not mine, but the Lord's– that a wife is not to leave her husband;
B046C007V011	46	7	11	or if she has already left him, let her either remain as she is or be reconciled to him; and that a husband is not to send away his wife.
B046C007V012	46	7	12	To the rest it is I who speak–not the Lord. If a brother has a wife who is an unbeliever, and she consents to live with him, let him not send her away.
B046C007V013	46	7	13	And a woman who has an unbelieving husband–if he consents to live with her, let her not separate from him.
B046C007V014	46	7	14	For, in such cases, the unbelieving husband has become –and is– holy through union with a Christian woman, and the unbelieving wife is holy through union with a Christian brother. Otherwise your children would be unholy, but in reality they have a place among God's people.
B046C007V015	46	7	15	If, however, the unbeliever is determined to leave, let him or her do so. Under such circumstances the Christian man or woman is no slave; God has called us to live lives of peace.
B046C007V016	46	7	16	For what assurance have you, O woman, as to whether you will save your husband? Or what assurance have you, O man, as to whether you will save your wife?
B046C007V017	46	7	17	Only, whatever be the condition in life which the Lord has assigned to each individual –and whatever the condition in which he was living when God called him– in that let him continue.
B046C007V018	46	7	18	This is what I command in all the Churches. Was any one already circumcised when called? Let him not have recourse to the surgeons. Was any one uncircumcised when called? Let him remain uncircumcised.
B046C007V019	46	7	19	Circumcision is nothing, and uncircumcision is nothing: obedience to God's commandments is everything.
B046C007V020	46	7	20	Whatever be the condition in life in which a man was, when he was called, in that let him continue.
B046C007V021	46	7	21	Were you a slave when God called you? Let not that weigh on your mind. And yet if you can get your freedom, take advantage of the opportunity.
B046C007V022	46	7	22	For a Christian, if he was a slave when called, is the Lord's freed man, and in the same way a free man, if called, becomes the slave of Christ.
B046C007V023	46	7	23	You have all been redeemed at infinite cost: do not become slaves to men.
B046C007V024	46	7	24	Where each one stood when he was called, there, brethren, let him still stand–close to God.
B046C007V025	46	7	25	Concerning unmarried women I have no command to give you from the Lord; but I offer you my opinion, which is that of a man who, through the Lord's mercy, is deserving of your confidence.
B046C007V026	46	7	26	I think then that, taking into consideration the distress which is now upon us, it is well for a man to remain as he is.
B046C007V027	46	7	27	Are you bound to a wife? Do not seek to get free. Are you free from the marriage bond? Do not seek for a wife.
B046C007V028	46	7	28	Yet if you marry, you have not sinned; and if a maiden marries, she has not sinned. Such people, however, will have outward trouble. But I am for sparing you.
B046C007V029	46	7	29	Yet of this I warn you, brethren: the time has been shortened–so that henceforth those who have wives should be as though they had none,
B046C007V030	46	7	30	those who weep as though they did not weep, those who rejoice as though they did not rejoice, those who buy as though they did not possess,
B046C007V031	46	7	31	and those who use the world as not using it to the full. For the world as it now exists is passing away.
B046C007V032	46	7	32	And I would have you free from worldly anxiety. An unmarried man concerns himself with the Lord's business–how he shall please the Lord;
B046C007V033	46	7	33	but a married man concerns himself with the business of the world–how he shall please his wife.
B046C007V034	46	7	34	There is a difference too between a married and an unmarried woman. She who is unmarried concerns herself with the Lord's business –that she may be holy both in body and spirit; but the married woman concerns herself with the business of the world– how she shall please her husband.
B046C007V035	46	7	35	Thus much I say in your own interest; not to lay a trap for you, but to help towards what is becoming, and enable you to wait on the Lord without distraction.
B046C007V036	46	7	36	If, however, a father thinks he is acting unbecomingly towards his still unmarried daughter if she be past the bloom of her youth, and so the matter is urgent, let him do what she desires; he commits no sin; she and her suitor should be allowed to marry.
B046C007V037	46	7	37	But if a father stands firm in his resolve, being free from all external constraint and having a legal right to act as he pleases, and in his own mind has come to the decision to keep his daughter unmarried, he will do well.
B046C007V038	46	7	38	So that he who gives his daughter in marriage does well, and yet he who does not give her in marriage will do better.
B046C007V039	46	7	39	A woman is bound to her husband during the whole period that he lives; but if her husband dies, she is at liberty to marry whom she will, provided that he is a Christian.
B046C007V040	46	7	40	But in my judgement, her state is a more enviable one if she remains as she is; and I also think that I have the Spirit of God.
B046C008V001	46	8	1	Now as to things which have been sacrificed to idols. This is a subject which we already understand–because we all have knowledge of it. Knowledge, however, tends to make people conceited; it is love that builds us up.
B046C008V002	46	8	2	If any one imagines that he already possesses any true knowledge, he has as yet attained to no knowledge of the kind to which he ought to have attained;
B046C008V003	46	8	3	but if any one loves God, that man is known by God.
B046C008V004	46	8	4	As to eating things which have been sacrificed to idols, we are fully aware that an idol is nothing in the world, and that there is no God but One.
B046C008V005	46	8	5	For if so-called gods do exist, either in Heaven or on earth –and in fact there are many such gods and many such lords–
B046C008V006	46	8	6	yet 
B046C008V007	46	8	7	But all believers do not recognize these facts. Some, from force of habit in relation to the idol, even now eat idol sacrifices as such, and their consciences, being but weak, are polluted.
B046C008V008	46	8	8	It is true that a particular kind of food will not bring us into God's presence; we are neither inferior to others if we abstain from it, nor superior to them if we eat it.
B046C008V009	46	8	9	But take care lest this liberty of yours should prove a hindrance to the progress of weak believers.
B046C008V010	46	8	10	For if any one were to see you, who know the real truth of this matter, reclining at table in an idol's temple, would not his conscience (supposing him to be a weak believer) be emboldened to eat the food which has been sacrificed to the idol?
B046C008V011	46	8	11	Why, your knowledge becomes the ruin of the weak believer–your brother, for whom Christ died!
B046C008V012	46	8	12	Moreover when you thus sin against the brethren and wound their weak consciences, you are, in reality, sinning against Christ.
B046C008V013	46	8	13	Therefore if what I eat causes my brother to fall, never again to the end of my days will I touch any kind of animal food, for fear I should cause my brother to fall.
B046C009V001	46	9	1	Am I not free? Am I not an Apostle? Can it be denied that I have seen Jesus, our Lord? Are not you yourselves my work in the Lord?
B046C009V002	46	9	2	If to other men I am not an Apostle, yet at any rate I am one to you; for your very existence as a Christian Church is the seal of my Apostleship.
B046C009V003	46	9	3	That is how I vindicate myself to those who criticize me.
B046C009V004	46	9	4	Have we not a right to claim food and drink?
B046C009V005	46	9	5	Have we not a right to take with us on our journeys a Christian sister as our wife, as the rest of the Apostles do–and the Lord's brothers and Peter?
B046C009V006	46	9	6	Or again, is it only Barnabas and myself who are not at liberty to give up working with our hands?
B046C009V007	46	9	7	What soldier ever serves at his own cost? Who plants a vineyard and yet does not eat any of the grapes? Or who tends a herd of cattle and yet does not taste their milk?
B046C009V008	46	9	8	Am I making use of merely worldly illustrations? Does not the Law speak in the same tone?
B046C009V009	46	9	9	For in the Law of Moses it is written, 
B046C009V010	46	9	10	Is God simply thinking about the oxen? Or is it really in our interest that He speaks? Of course, it was written in our interest, because it is His will that when a plough-man ploughs, and a thresher threshes, it should be in the hope of sharing that which comes as the result.
B046C009V011	46	9	11	If it is we who sowed the spiritual grain in you, is it a great thing that we should reap a temporal harvest from you?
B046C009V012	46	9	12	If other teachers possess that right over you, do not we possess it much more? Yet we have not availed ourselves of the right, but we patiently endure all things rather than hinder in the least degree the progress of the Good News of the Christ.
B046C009V013	46	9	13	Do you not know that those who perform the sacred rites have their food from the sacred place, and that those who serve at the altar all alike share with the altar?
B046C009V014	46	9	14	In the same way the Lord also directed those who proclaim the Good News to maintain themselves by the Good News.
B046C009V015	46	9	15	But I, for my part, have not used, and do not use, my full rights in any of these things. Nor do I now write with that object so far as I myself am concerned, for I would rather die than have anybody make this boast of mine an empty one.
B046C009V016	46	9	16	If I go on preaching the Good News, that is nothing for me to boast of; for the necessity is imposed upon me; and alas for me, if I fail to preach it!
B046C009V017	46	9	17	And if I preach willingly, I receive my wages; but if against my will, a stewardship has nevertheless been entrusted to me.
B046C009V018	46	9	18	What are my wages then? The very fact that the Good News which I preach will cost my hearers nothing, so that I cannot be charged with abuse of my privileges as a Christian preacher.
B046C009V019	46	9	19	Though free from all human control, I have made myself the slave of all in the hope of winning as many converts as possible.
B046C009V020	46	9	20	To the Jews I have become like a Jew in order to win Jews; to men under the Law as if I were under the Law –although I am not– in order to win those who are under the Law;
B046C009V021	46	9	21	to men without Law as if I were without Law –although I am not without Law in relation to God but am abiding in Christ's Law– in order to win those who are without Law.
B046C009V022	46	9	22	To the weak I have become weak, so as to gain the weak. To all men I have become all things, in the hope that in every one of these ways I may save some.
B046C009V023	46	9	23	And I do everything for the sake of the Good News, that I may share with my hearers in its benefits.
B046C009V024	46	9	24	Do you not know that in the foot-race the runners all run, but that only one gets the prize? You must run like him, in order to win with certainty.
B046C009V025	46	9	25	But every competitor in an athletic contest practices abstemiousness in all directions. They indeed do this for the sake of securing a perishable wreath, but we for the sake of securing one that will not perish.
B046C009V026	46	9	26	That is how I run, not being in any doubt as to my goal. I am a boxer who does not inflict blows on the air,
B046C009V027	46	9	27	but I hit hard and straight at my own body and lead it off into slavery, lest possibly, after I have been a herald to others, I should myself be rejected.
B046C010V001	46	10	1	For I would have you remember, brethren, how our forefathers were all of them sheltered by the cloud, and all got safely through the Red Sea.
B046C010V002	46	10	2	All were baptized in the cloud and in the sea to be followers of Moses.
B046C010V003	46	10	3	All ate the same spiritual food,
B046C010V004	46	10	4	and all drank the same spiritual drink; for they long drank the water that flowed from the spiritual rock that went with them–and that rock was the Christ.
B046C010V005	46	10	5	But with most of them God was not well pleased; for they were laid low in the Desert.
B046C010V006	46	10	6	And in this they became a warning to us, to teach us not to be eager, as they were eager, in pursuit of what is evil.
B046C010V007	46	10	7	And you must not be worshippers of idols, as some of them were. For it is written, 
B046C010V008	46	10	8	Nor may we be fornicators, like some of them who committed fornication and on a single day 23,000 of them fell dead.
B046C010V009	46	10	9	And do not let us test the Lord too far, as some of them tested Him and were destroyed by the serpents.
B046C010V010	46	10	10	And do not be discontented, as some of them were, and they were destroyed by the Destroyer.
B046C010V011	46	10	11	All this kept happening to them with a figurative meaning; but it was put on record by way of admonition to us upon whom the ends of the Ages have come.
B046C010V012	46	10	12	So then let him who thinks he is standing securely beware of falling.
B046C010V013	46	10	13	No temptation has you in its power but such as is common to human nature; and God is faithful and will not allow you to be tempted beyond your strength. But, when the temptation comes, He will also provide the way of escape; so that you may be able to bear it.
B046C010V014	46	10	14	Therefore, my dear friends, avoid all connection with the worship of idols.
B046C010V015	46	10	15	I speak as to men of sense: judge for yourselves of what I say.
B046C010V016	46	10	16	The cup of blessing, which we bless, does it not mean a joint-participation in the blood of Christ? The loaf of bread which we break, does it not mean a joint-participation in the body of Christ?
B046C010V017	46	10	17	Since there is one loaf, we who are many are one body; we, all of us, share in that one loaf.
B046C010V018	46	10	18	Look at the Israelites–the nation and their ritual. Are not those who eat the sacrifices joint-partakers in the altar?
B046C010V019	46	10	19	Do I mean that a thing sacrificed to an idol is what it claims to be, or that an idol is a real thing?
B046C010V020	46	10	20	No, but that which the Gentiles sacrifice, they sacrifice to demons, not to God; and I would not have you have fellowship with one another through the demons.
B046C010V021	46	10	21	You cannot drink the Lord's cup and the cup of demons: you cannot be joint-partakers both in the table of the Lord and in the table of demons.
B046C010V022	46	10	22	Or are we actually arousing the Lord to jealousy. Are we stronger than He is?
B046C010V023	46	10	23	Everything is allowable, but not everything is profitable. Everything is allowable, but everything does not build others up.
B046C010V024	46	10	24	Let no one be for ever seeking his own good, but let each seek that of his fellow man.
B046C010V025	46	10	25	Anything that is for sale in the meat market, eat, and ask no questions for conscience' sake;
B046C010V026	46	10	26	for 
B046C010V027	46	10	27	If an unbeliever gives you an invitation and you are disposed to accept it, eat whatever is put before you, and ask no questions for conscience' sake.
B046C010V028	46	10	28	But if any one tells you, »This food has been offered in sacrifice;« abstain from eating it–out of respect for him who warned you, and, as before, for conscience' sake.
B046C010V029	46	10	29	But now I mean his conscience, not your own. »Why, on what ground,« you may object, »is the question of my liberty of action to be decided by a conscience not my own?
B046C010V030	46	10	30	If, so far as I am concerned, I partake with a grateful heart, why am I to be found fault with in regard to a thing for which I give thanks?«
B046C010V031	46	10	31	Whether, then, you are eating or drinking, or whatever you are doing, let everything be done to the glory of God.
B046C010V032	46	10	32	Do not be causes of stumbling either to Jews or to Gentiles, nor to the Church of God.
B046C010V033	46	10	33	That is the way that I also seek in everything the approval of all men, not aiming at my own profit, but at that of the many, in the hope that they may be saved.
B046C011V001	46	11	1	Be imitators of me, in so far as I in turn am an imitator of Christ.
B046C011V002	46	11	2	Now I commend you for remembering me in everything, and because you hold fast truths and practices precisely as I have taught them to you.
B046C011V003	46	11	3	I would have you know, however, that of every man, Christ is the Head, that of a woman her husband is the Head, and that God is Christ's Head.
B046C011V004	46	11	4	A man who wears a veil when praying or prophesying dishonors his Head;
B046C011V005	46	11	5	but a woman who prays or prophesies with her head uncovered dishonors her Head, for it is exactly the same as if she had her hair cut short.
B046C011V006	46	11	6	If a woman will not wear a veil, let her also cut off her hair. But since it is a dishonor to a woman to have her hair cut off or her head shaved, let her wear a veil.
B046C011V007	46	11	7	For a man ought not to have a veil on his head, since he is the image and glory of God; while woman is the glory of man.
B046C011V008	46	11	8	Man does not take his origin from woman, but woman takes hers from man.
B046C011V009	46	11	9	For man was not created for woman's sake, but woman for man's.
B046C011V010	46	11	10	That is why a woman ought to have on her head a symbol of subjection, because of the angels.
B046C011V011	46	11	11	Yet, in the Lord, woman is not independent of man nor man independent of woman.
B046C011V012	46	11	12	For just as woman originates from man, so also man comes into existence through woman, but everything springs originally from God.
B046C011V013	46	11	13	Judge of this for your own selves: is it seemly for a woman to pray to God when she is unveiled?
B046C011V014	46	11	14	Does not Nature itself teach you that if a man has long hair it is a dishonor to him,
B046C011V015	46	11	15	but that if a woman has long hair it is her glory, because her hair was given her for a covering?
B046C011V016	46	11	16	But if any one is inclined to be contentious on the point, we have no such custom, nor have the Churches of God.
B046C011V017	46	11	17	But while giving you these instructions, there is one thing I cannot praise–your meeting together, with bad rather than good results.
B046C011V018	46	11	18	for, in the first place, when you meet as a Church, there are divisions among you. This is what I am told, and I believe that there is some truth in it.
B046C011V019	46	11	19	For there must of necessity be differences of opinion among you, in order that it may be plainly seen who are the men of sterling worth among you.
B046C011V020	46	11	20	When, however, you meet in one place, there is no eating the Supper of the Lord;
B046C011V021	46	11	21	for it is his own supper of which each of you is in a hurry to partake, and one eats like a hungry man, while another has already drunk to excess.
B046C011V022	46	11	22	Why, have you no homes in which to eat and drink? Or do you wish to show your contempt for the Church of God and make those who have no homes feel ashamed? What shall I say to you? Shall I praise you? In this matter I certainly do not praise you.
B046C011V023	46	11	23	For it was from the Lord that I received the facts which, in turn, I handed on to you; how that the Lord Jesus, on the night He was to be betrayed, took some bread,
B046C011V024	46	11	24	and after giving thanks He broke it and said, »This is my body which is about to be broken for you. Do this in memory of me.«
B046C011V025	46	11	25	In the same way, when the meal was over, He also took the cup. »This cup,« He said, »is the new Covenant of which my blood is the pledge. Do this, every time that you drink it, in memory of me.«
B046C011V026	46	11	26	For every time that you eat this bread and drink from the cup, you are proclaiming the Lord's death–until He returns.
B046C011V027	46	11	27	Whoever, therefore, in an unworthy manner, eats the bread or drinks from the cup of the Lord sins against the body and blood of the Lord.
B046C011V028	46	11	28	But let a man examine himself, and, having done that, then let him eat the bread and drink from the cup.
B046C011V029	46	11	29	For any one who eats and drinks, eats and drinks judgement to himself, if he fails to estimate the body aright.
B046C011V030	46	11	30	That is why many among you are sickly and out of health, and why not a few die.
B046C011V031	46	11	31	If, however, we estimated ourselves aright, we should not be judged.
B046C011V032	46	11	32	But when we are judged by the Lord, chastisement follows, to save us from being condemned along with the world.
B046C011V033	46	11	33	Therefore, brethren, when you come together for this meal, wait for one another.
B046C011V034	46	11	34	If any one is hungry, let him eat at home; so that your coming together may not lead to judgement. The other matters I will deal with whenever I come.
B046C012V001	46	12	1	It is important, brethren, that you should have clear knowledge on the subject of spiritual gifts.
B046C012V002	46	12	2	You know that when you were heathens you went astray after dumb idols, wherever you happened to be led.
B046C012V003	46	12	3	For this reason I would have you understand that no one speaking under the influence of The Spirit of God ever says, »Jesus is accursed,« and that no one is able to say, »Jesus is Lord,« except under the influence of the Holy Spirit.
B046C012V004	46	12	4	Now there are various kinds of gifts, but there is one and the same Spirit;
B046C012V005	46	12	5	various forms of official service, and yet one and the same Lord;
B046C012V006	46	12	6	diversities in work, and yet one and the same God–He who in each person brings about the whole result.
B046C012V007	46	12	7	But to each of us a manifestation of the Spirit has been granted for the common good.
B046C012V008	46	12	8	To one the utterance of wisdom has been granted through the Spirit; to another the utterance of knowledge in accordance with the will of the same Spirit;
B046C012V009	46	12	9	to a third man, by means of the same Spirit, special faith; to another various gifts of healing, by means of the one Spirit;
B046C012V010	46	12	10	to another the exercise of miraculous powers; to another the gift of prophecy; to another the power of discriminating between prophetic utterances; to another varieties of the gift of `tongues;' to another the interpretation of tongues.
B046C012V011	46	12	11	But these results are all brought about by one and the same Spirit, who bestows His gifts upon each of us in accordance with His own will.
B046C012V012	46	12	12	For just as the human body is one and yet has many parts, and all its parts, many as they are, constitute but one body, so it is with the Church of Christ.
B046C012V013	46	12	13	For, in fact, in one Spirit all of us –whether we are Jews or Gentiles, slaves or free men– were baptized to form but one body; and we were all nourished by that one Spirit.
B046C012V014	46	12	14	For the human body does not consist of one part, but of many.
B046C012V015	46	12	15	Were the foot to say, »Because I am not a hand I am not a part of the body,« that would not make it any the less a part of the body.
B046C012V016	46	12	16	Or were the ear to say, »Because I am not an eye, I am not a part of the body,« that would not make it any the less a part of the body.
B046C012V017	46	12	17	If the whole body were an eye, where would the hearing be? If the whole body were an ear, where would the nostrils be?
B046C012V018	46	12	18	But, as a matter of fact, God has arranged the parts in the body –every one of them– as He has seen fit.
B046C012V019	46	12	19	If they were all one part, where would the body be?
B046C012V020	46	12	20	But, as a matter of fact, there are many parts and but one body.
B046C012V021	46	12	21	It is also impossible for the eye to say to the hand, »I do not need you;« or again for the head to say to the feet, »I do not need you.«
B046C012V022	46	12	22	No, it is quite otherwise. Even those parts of the body which are apparently somewhat feeble are yet indispensable;
B046C012V023	46	12	23	and those which we deem less honorable we clothe with more abundant honor; and so our ungraceful parts come to have a more abundant grace, while our graceful parts have everything they need.
B046C012V024	46	12	24	But it was God who built up the body, and bestowed more abundant honor on the part that felt the need,
B046C012V025	46	12	25	that there might be no disunion in the body, but that all the members might entertain the same anxious care for one another's welfare.
B046C012V026	46	12	26	And if one part is suffering, every other part suffers with it; or if one part is receiving special honor, every other part shares in the joy.
B046C012V027	46	12	27	As for you, you are the body of Christ, and individually you are members of it.
B046C012V028	46	12	28	And by God's appointment there are in the Church–first Apostles, secondly Prophets, thirdly teachers. Then come miraculous powers, and then ability to cure diseases or render loving service, or powers of organization, or varieties of the gift of `tongues.'
B046C012V029	46	12	29	Are all Apostles? Are all Prophets? Are all teachers?
B046C012V030	46	12	30	Have all miraculous powers? Have all ability to cure diseases? Do all speak in `tongues'? Do all interpret?
B046C012V031	46	12	31	But always seek to excel in the greater gifts. And now I will point out to you a way of life which transcends all others.
B046C013V001	46	13	1	If I can speak with the tongues of men and of angels, but am destitute of Love, I have but become a loud-sounding trumpet or a clanging cymbal.
B046C013V002	46	13	2	If I possess the gift of prophecy and am versed in all mysteries and all knowledge, and have such absolute faith that I can remove mountains, but am destitute of Love, I am nothing.
B046C013V003	46	13	3	And if I distribute all my possessions to the poor, and give up my body to be burned, but am destitute of Love, it profits me nothing.
B046C013V004	46	13	4	Love is patient and kind. Love knows neither envy nor jealousy. Love is not forward and self-assertive, nor boastful and conceited.
B046C013V005	46	13	5	She does not behave unbecomingly, nor seek to aggrandize herself, nor blaze out in passionate anger, nor brood over wrongs.
B046C013V006	46	13	6	She finds no pleasure in injustice done to others, but joyfully sides with the truth.
B046C013V007	46	13	7	She knows how to be silent. She is full of trust, full of hope, full of patient endurance.
B046C013V008	46	13	8	Love never fails. But if there are prophecies, they will be done away with; if there are languages, they will cease; if there is knowledge, it will be brought to an end.
B046C013V009	46	13	9	For our knowledge is imperfect, and so is our prophesying;
B046C013V010	46	13	10	but when the perfect state of things is come, all that is imperfect will be brought to an end.
B046C013V011	46	13	11	When I was a child, I talked like a child, felt like a child, reasoned like a child: when I became a man, I put from me childish ways.
B046C013V012	46	13	12	For the present we see things as if in a mirror, and are puzzled; but then we shall see them face to face. For the present the knowledge I gain is imperfect; but then I shall know fully, even as I am fully known.
B046C013V013	46	13	13	And so there remain Faith, Hope, Love–these three; and of these the greatest is Love.
B046C014V001	46	14	1	Be eager in your pursuit of this Love, and be earnestly ambitious for spiritual gifts, but let it be chiefly so in order that you may prophesy.
B046C014V002	46	14	2	For he who speaks in an unknown tongue is not speaking to men, but to God; for no one understands him. Yet in the Spirit he is speaking secret truths.
B046C014V003	46	14	3	But he who prophesies speaks to men words of edification, encouragement and comfort.
B046C014V004	46	14	4	He who speaks in an unknown tongue does good to himself, but he who prophesies does good to the Church.
B046C014V005	46	14	5	I should be right glad were you all to speak in `tongues,' but yet more glad were you all to prophesy. And, in fact, the man who prophesies is superior to him who speaks in `tongues,' except when the latter can interpret in order that the Church may get a blessing.
B046C014V006	46	14	6	But, brethren, as things are, if I come to you speaking in `tongues,' what benefit shall I confer on you, if the utterance is neither in the form of a revelation nor of additional knowledge nor of prophecy nor of teaching?
B046C014V007	46	14	7	Even inanimate things –flutes or harps, for instance– when yielding a sound, if they make no distinction in the notes, how shall the tune which is played on the flute or the harp be known?
B046C014V008	46	14	8	If the bugle –to take another example– gives an uncertain sound, who will prepare for battle?
B046C014V009	46	14	9	And so with you; if with the living voice you fail to utter intelligible words, how will people know what you are saying? You will be talking to the winds.
B046C014V010	46	14	10	There are, we will suppose, a great number of languages in the world, and no creature is without a language.
B046C014V011	46	14	11	If, however, I do not know the meaning of the particular language, I shall seem to the speaker of it, and he to me, to be merely talking some foreign tongue.
B046C014V012	46	14	12	Therefore, seeing that you are ambitious for spiritual gifts, seek to excel in them so as to benefit the Church.
B046C014V013	46	14	13	Therefore let a man who has the gift of tongues pray for the power of interpreting them.
B046C014V014	46	14	14	For if I pray in an unknown tongue, my spirit prays, but my understanding is barren.
B046C014V015	46	14	15	How then does the matter stand? I will pray in spirit, and I will pray with my understanding also. I will praise God in spirit, and I will praise Him with my understanding also.
B046C014V016	46	14	16	Otherwise, if you bless God in spirit only, how shall he who is in the position of an ungifted man say the `Amen' to your giving of thanks, when he does not know what your words mean?
B046C014V017	46	14	17	Rightly enough you are giving thanks, and yet your neighbor is not benefited.
B046C014V018	46	14	18	I speak in a tongue, thank God, more than all of you;
B046C014V019	46	14	19	but in the Church I would rather speak five words with my understanding –so as to instruct others also– than ten thousand words in an unknown tongue.
B046C014V020	46	14	20	Brethren, do not prove yourselves to be children in your minds. As regards evil, indeed, be utter babes, but as regards your minds prove yourselves to be men of ripe years.
B046C014V021	46	14	21	In the Law it stands written, 
B046C014V022	46	14	22	This shows that the gift of tongues is intended as a sign not to those who believe but to unbelievers, but prophecy is intended not for unbelievers but for those who believe.
B046C014V023	46	14	23	Accordingly if the whole Church has assembled and all are speaking in `tongues,' and there come in ungifted men, or unbelievers, will they not say that you are all mad?
B046C014V024	46	14	24	If, on the other hand, every one is prophesying and an unbeliever or an ungifted man comes in, he is convicted by all and closely examined by all,
B046C014V025	46	14	25	and the hidden evils of his heart are brought to light. And, as the result, he will fall on his face and worship God, and will report to others that of a truth God is among you.
B046C014V026	46	14	26	What then, brethren? Whenever you assemble, there is not one of you who is not ready either with a song of praise, a sermon, a revelation, a `tongue,' or an interpretation. Let everything be done with a view to the building up of faith and character.
B046C014V027	46	14	27	If there is speaking in an unknown tongue, only two or at the most three should speak, and they should do so one at a time, and one should interpret;
B046C014V028	46	14	28	or if there is no interpreter, let the man with the gift be silent in the Church, speaking to himself and to God.
B046C014V029	46	14	29	But if there are Prophets, let two or three speak and let the rest judge.
B046C014V030	46	14	30	And if anything is revealed to some one else who is seated there, let the first be silent.
B046C014V031	46	14	31	For you can all prophesy one by one, so that all may learn and all be encouraged:
B046C014V032	46	14	32	and the spirits of Prophets yield submission to Prophets.
B046C014V033	46	14	33	For God is not a God of disorder, but of peace, as He is in all the Churches of His people.
B046C014V034	46	14	34	Let married women be silent in the Churches, for they are not permitted to speak. They must be content with a subordinate place, as the Law also says;
B046C014V035	46	14	35	and if they wish to ask questions, they should ask their own husbands at home. For it is disgraceful for a married woman to speak at a Church assembly.
B046C014V036	46	14	36	Was it from you that God's Message first went forth, or is it to you only that it has come?
B046C014V037	46	14	37	If any one deems himself to be a Prophet or a man with spiritual gifts, let him recognize as the Lord's command all that I am now writing to you.
B046C014V038	46	14	38	But if any one is ignorant, let him be ignorant.
B046C014V039	46	14	39	The conclusion, my brethren, is this. Be earnestly ambitious to prophesy, and do not check speaking with tongues;
B046C014V040	46	14	40	only let everything be done in a becoming and orderly manner.
B046C015V001	46	15	1	But let me recall to you, brethren, the Good News which I brought you, which you accepted, and on which you are standing,
B046C015V002	46	15	2	through which also you are obtaining salvation, if you bear in mind the words in which I proclaimed it–unless indeed your faith has been unreal from the very first.
B046C015V003	46	15	3	For I repeated to you the all-important fact which also I had been taught, that Christ died for our sins in accordance with the Scriptures;
B046C015V004	46	15	4	that He was buried; that He rose to life again on the third day in accordance with the Scriptures,
B046C015V005	46	15	5	and was seen by Peter, and then by the Twelve.
B046C015V006	46	15	6	Afterwards He was seen by more than five hundred brethren at once, most of whom are still alive, although some of them have now fallen asleep.
B046C015V007	46	15	7	Afterwards He was seen by James, and then by all the Apostles.
B046C015V008	46	15	8	And last of all, as to one of untimely birth, He appeared to me also.
B046C015V009	46	15	9	For I am the least of the Apostles, and am not fit to be called an Apostle–because I persecuted the Church of God.
B046C015V010	46	15	10	But what I am I am by the grace of God, and His grace bestowed upon me did not prove ineffectual. But I labored more strenuously than all the rest–yet it was not I, but God's grace working with me.
B046C015V011	46	15	11	But whether it is I or they, this is the way we preach and the way that you came to believe.
B046C015V012	46	15	12	But if Christ is preached as having risen from the dead, how is it that some of you say that there is no such thing as a resurrection of the dead?
B046C015V013	46	15	13	If there is no such thing as a resurrection of the dead, then Christ Himself has not risen to life.
B046C015V014	46	15	14	And if Christ has not risen, it follows that what we preach is a delusion, and that your faith also is a delusion.
B046C015V015	46	15	15	Nay more, we are actually being discovered to be bearing false witness about God, because we have testified that God raised Christ to life, whom He did not raise, if in reality none of the dead are raised.
B046C015V016	46	15	16	For if none of the dead are raised to life, then Christ has not risen;
B046C015V017	46	15	17	and if Christ has not risen, your faith is a vain thing–you are still in your sins.
B046C015V018	46	15	18	It follows also that those who have fallen asleep in Christ have perished.
B046C015V019	46	15	19	If in this present life we have a 
B046C015V020	46	15	20	But, in reality, Christ 
B046C015V021	46	15	21	For seeing that death came through man, through man comes also the resurrection of the dead.
B046C015V022	46	15	22	For just as through Adam all die, so also through Christ all will be made alive again.
B046C015V023	46	15	23	But this will happen to each in the right order–Christ having been the first to rise, and afterwards Christ's people rising at His return.
B046C015V024	46	15	24	Later on, comes the End, when He is to surrender the Kingship to God, the Father, when He shall have overthrown all other government and all other authority and power.
B046C015V025	46	15	25	For He must continue King until He shall have put all His enemies under His feet.
B046C015V026	46	15	26	The last enemy that is to be overthrown is Death;
B046C015V027	46	15	27	for He will have put all things in subjection under His feet. And when He shall have declared that »All things are in subjection,« it will be with the manifest exception of Him who has reduced them all to subjection to Him.
B046C015V028	46	15	28	But when the whole universe has been made subject to Him, then the Son Himself will also become subject to Him who has made the universe subject to Him, in order that GOD may be all in all.
B046C015V029	46	15	29	Otherwise what will become of those who got themselves baptized for the dead? If the dead do not rise at all, why are these baptized for them?
B046C015V030	46	15	30	Why also do we Apostles expose ourselves to danger every hour?
B046C015V031	46	15	31	I protest, brethren, as surely as I glory over you –which I may justly do in Christ Jesus our Lord– that I die day by day.
B046C015V032	46	15	32	If from merely human motives I have fought with wild beasts in Ephesus, what profit is it to me? If the dead do not rise, let us eat and drink, for tomorrow we are to die.
B046C015V033	46	15	33	Do not deceive yourselves:»Evil companionships corrupt good morals.«
B046C015V034	46	15	34	Wake from this drunken fit; live righteous lives, and cease to sin; for some have no knowledge of God: I speak thus in order to move you to shame.
B046C015V035	46	15	35	But some one will say, »How can the dead rise? And with what kind of body do they come back?«
B046C015V036	46	15	36	Foolish man! the seed you yourself sow has no life given to it unless it first dies;
B046C015V037	46	15	37	and as for what you sow, it is not the plant which is to be that you are sowing, but a bare grain, of wheat (it may be) or of something else, and God gives it a body as He has seen fit,
B046C015V038	46	15	38	and to each kind of seed a body of its own.
B046C015V039	46	15	39	All flesh is not the same: there is human flesh, and flesh of cattle, of birds, and of fishes.
B046C015V040	46	15	40	There are bodies which are celestial and there are bodies which are earthly, but the glory of the celestial ones is one thing, and that of the earthly ones is another.
B046C015V041	46	15	41	There is one glory of the sun, another of the moon, and another of the stars; for star differs from star in glory.
B046C015V042	46	15	42	It is the same with the resurrection of the dead. The body is sown in a state of decay, it is raised free from decay;
B046C015V043	46	15	43	it is sown in dishonor, it is raised in glory; it is sown in weakness, it is raised in power;
B046C015V044	46	15	44	an animal body is sown, a spiritual body is raised. As surely as there is an animal body, so there is also a spiritual body.
B046C015V045	46	15	45	In the same way also it is written, 
B046C015V046	46	15	46	Nevertheless, it is not what is spiritual that came first, but what is animal; what is spiritual came afterwards.
B046C015V047	46	15	47	The first man is a man of earth, earthy; the second man is from Heaven.
B046C015V048	46	15	48	What the earthy one is, that also are those who are earthy; and what the heavenly One is, that also are those who are heavenly.
B046C015V049	46	15	49	And as we have borne a resemblance to the earthy one, let us see to it that we also bear a resemblance to the heavenly One.
B046C015V050	46	15	50	But this I tell you, brethren: our mortal bodies cannot inherit the Kingdom of God, nor will what is perishable inherit what is imperishable.
B046C015V051	46	15	51	I tell you a truth hitherto kept secret: we shall not all sleep, but we shall all be changed,
B046C015V052	46	15	52	in a moment, in the twinkling of an eye, at the sounding of the last trumpet; for the trumpet will sound, and the dead will be raised incapable of decay, and 
B046C015V053	46	15	53	For so it must be: this perishable nature must clothe itself with what is imperishable, and this mortality must clothe itself with immortality.
B046C015V054	46	15	54	But when this perishable nature has put on what is imperishable, and this mortality has put on immortality, then will the words of Scripture be fulfilled, 
B046C015V055	46	15	55	
        
B046C015V056	46	15	56	Now sin is the sting of death, and sin derives its power from the Law;
B046C015V057	46	15	57	but God be thanked who gives us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ!
B046C015V058	46	15	58	Therefore, my dear brethren, be firm, unmovable, busily occupied at all times in the Lord's work, knowing that your toil is not fruitless in the Lord.
B046C016V001	46	16	1	As to the collection for God's people, what I have directed the Churches of Galatia to do, you must do also.
B046C016V002	46	16	2	On the first day of every week let each of you put on one side and store up at his home whatever gain has been granted to him; so that whenever I come, there may then be no collections going on.
B046C016V003	46	16	3	And when I am with you, whatever brethren you accredit by letter I will send to carry your kind gift to Jerusalem.
B046C016V004	46	16	4	And if it is worth while for me also to make the journey, they shall go as my companions.
B046C016V005	46	16	5	I shall come to you after passing through Macedonia; for my plan will be to pass through Macedonia;
B046C016V006	46	16	6	and I shall make some stay with you perhaps, or even spend the winter with you, in order that you may help me forward, whichever way I travel.
B046C016V007	46	16	7	For I do not wish to see you on this occasion merely in passing; but if the Lord permits, I hope to remain some time with you.
B046C016V008	46	16	8	I shall remain in Ephesus, however, until the time of the Harvest Festival,
B046C016V009	46	16	9	for a wide door stands open before me which demands great efforts, and we have many opponents.
B046C016V010	46	16	10	If Timothy pays you a visit, see that he is free from fear in his relations with you; for he is engaged in the Master's work just as I am.
B046C016V011	46	16	11	Therefore let no one slight him, but all of you should help him forward in peace to join me; for I am waiting for him and others of the brethren.
B046C016V012	46	16	12	As for our brother Apollos, I have repeatedly urged him to accompany the brethren who are coming to you: but he is quite resolved not to do so at present. He will come, however, when he has a good opportunity.
B046C016V013	46	16	13	Be on the alert; stand firm in the faith; acquit yourselves like men; be strong.
B046C016V014	46	16	14	Let all that you do be done from motives of love.
B046C016V015	46	16	15	And I beseech you, brethren –you know the household of Stephanas, how they were the earliest Greek converts to Christ, and have devoted themselves to the service of God's people–
B046C016V016	46	16	16	I beseech you, on your part, to show deference to such men, and to every one who participates in their work and toils hard.
B046C016V017	46	16	17	It is a joy to me that Stephanas, Fortunatus and Achaicus have now arrived, because what was wanting so far as you are concerned they have supplied.
B046C016V018	46	16	18	They have refreshed my spirit, and yours. Acknowledge such men as these.
B046C016V019	46	16	19	The Churches in the province of Asia send you greetings; and Aquila and Prisca, in hearty Christian love, do the same, together with the Church which meets at their house.
B046C016V020	46	16	20	The brethren all send greetings to you. Greet one another with a holy kiss.
B046C016V021	46	16	21	The final greeting of me –Paul– with my own hand.
B046C016V022	46	16	22	If any one is destitute of love to the Lord, let him be accursed. OUR LORD IS COMING.
B046C016V023	46	16	23	The grace of the Lord Jesus be with you.
B046C016V024	46	16	24	My love in Christ Jesus be with you all.
B047C001V001	47	1	1	Paul, an Apostle of Christ Jesus by the will of God–and our brother Timothy: To the Church of God in Corinth, with all God's people throughout Greece.
B047C001V002	47	1	2	May grace and peace be granted to you from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B047C001V003	47	1	3	Heartfelt thanks be to the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ–the Father who is full of compassion and the God who gives all comfort.
B047C001V004	47	1	4	He comforts us in our every affliction so that we may be able to comfort those who are in any kind of affliction by means of the comfort with which we ourselves are comforted by God.
B047C001V005	47	1	5	For just as we have more than our share of suffering for the Christ, so also through the Christ we have more than our share of comfort.
B047C001V006	47	1	6	But if, on the one hand, we are enduring affliction, it is for your comfort and salvation; and if, on the other hand, we are receiving comfort, it is for your comfort which is produced within you through your patient fortitude under the same sufferings as those which we also are enduring.
B047C001V007	47	1	7	And our hope for you is stedfast; for we know that as you are partners with us in the sufferings, so you are also partners in the comfort.
B047C001V008	47	1	8	For as for our troubles which came upon us in the province of Asia, we would have you know, brethren, that we were exceedingly weighed down, and felt overwhelmed, so that we renounced all hope even of life.
B047C001V009	47	1	9	Nay, we had, as we still have, the sentence of death within our own selves, in order that our confidence may repose, not on ourselves, but on God who raised the dead to life.
B047C001V010	47	1	10	He it is who rescued us from so imminent a death, and will do so again; and we have a firm hope in Him that He will also rescue us in all the future,
B047C001V011	47	1	11	while you on your part lend us your aid in entreaty for us, so that from many lips thanksgivings may rise on our behalf for the boon granted to us at the intercession of many.
B047C001V012	47	1	12	For the reason for our boasting is this–the testimony of our own conscience that it was in holiness and with pure motives before God, and in reliance not on worldly wisdom but on the gracious help of God, that we have conducted ourselves in the world, and above all in our relations with you.
B047C001V013	47	1	13	For we are writing to you nothing different from what we have written before, or from what indeed you already recognize as truth and will, I trust, recognize as such to the very end;
B047C001V014	47	1	14	just as some few of you have recognized us as your reason for boasting, even as you will be ours, on the day of Jesus our Lord.
B047C001V015	47	1	15	It was because I entertained this confidence that I intended to visit you before going elsewhere –so that you might receive a twofold proof of God's favour–
B047C001V016	47	1	16	and to pass by way of Corinth into Macedonia. Then my plan was to return from Macedonia to you, and be helped forward by you to Judaea.
B047C001V017	47	1	17	Did I display any vacillation or caprice in this? Or the purposes which I form–do I form them on worldly principles, now crying »Yes, yes,« and now »No, no«?
B047C001V018	47	1	18	As certainly as God is faithful, our language to you is not now »Yes« and now »No.«
B047C001V019	47	1	19	For Jesus Christ the Son of God –He who was proclaimed among you by us, that is by Silas and Timothy and myself– did not show Himself a waverer between »Yes« and »No.« But it was and always is »Yes« with Him.
B047C001V020	47	1	20	For all the promises of God, whatever their number, have their confirmation in Him; and for this reason through Him also our »Amen« acknowledges their truth and promotes the glory of God through our faith.
B047C001V021	47	1	21	But He who is making us as well as you stedfast through union with the Anointed One, and has anointed us, is God,
B047C001V022	47	1	22	and He has also set His seal upon us, and has put His Spirit into our hearts as a pledge and foretaste of future blessing.
B047C001V023	47	1	23	But as for me, as my soul shall answer for it, I appeal to God as my witness, that it was to spare you pain that I gave up my visit to Corinth.
B047C001V024	47	1	24	Not that we want to lord it over you in respect of your faith –we do, however, desire to help your joy– for in the matter of your faith you are standing firm.
B047C002V001	47	2	1	But, so far as I am concerned, I have resolved not to have a painful visit the next time I come to see you.
B047C002V002	47	2	2	For if I of all men give you pain, who then is there to gladden my heart, but the very persons to whom I give pain?
B047C002V003	47	2	3	And I write this to you in order that when I come I may not receive pain from those who ought to give me joy, confident as I am as to all of you that my joy is the joy of you all.
B047C002V004	47	2	4	For with many tears I write to you, and in deep suffering and depression of spirit, not in order to grieve you, but in the hope of showing you how brimful my heart is with love for you.
B047C002V005	47	2	5	Now if any one has caused sorrow, it has been caused not so much to me, as in some degree –for I have no wish to exaggerate– to all of you.
B047C002V006	47	2	6	In the case of such a person the punishment which was inflicted by the majority of you is enough.
B047C002V007	47	2	7	So that you may now take the opposite course, and forgive him rather and comfort him, for fear he should perhaps be driven to despair by his excess of grief.
B047C002V008	47	2	8	I beg you therefore fully to reinstate him in your love.
B047C002V009	47	2	9	For in writing to you I have also this object in view–to discover by experience whether you are prepared to be obedient in every respect.
B047C002V010	47	2	10	When you forgive a man an offence I also forgive it; for in fact what I have forgiven, if I have forgiven anything, has always been for your sakes in the presence of Christ,
B047C002V011	47	2	11	for fear Satan should gain an advantage over us. For we are not ignorant of his devices.
B047C002V012	47	2	12	Now when I came into the Troad to spread there the Good News about the Christ, even though in the Lord's providence a door stood open before me,
B047C002V013	47	2	13	yet, obtaining no relief for my spirit because I did not find our brother Titus, I bade them farewell and went on into Macedonia.
B047C002V014	47	2	14	But to God be the thanks who in Christ ever heads our triumphal procession, and by our hands waves in every place that sweet incense, the knowledge of Him.
B047C002V015	47	2	15	For we are a fragrance of Christ grateful to God in those whom He is saving and in those who are perishing;
B047C002V016	47	2	16	to the last-named an odor of death predictive of death, and to the others an odor of life predictive of life. And for such service as this who is competent?
B047C002V017	47	2	17	We are; for, unlike most teachers, we are not fraudulent hucksters of God's Message; but with transparent motives, as commissioned by God, in God's presence and in communion with Christ, so we speak.
B047C003V001	47	3	1	Do you say that this is self-recommendation once more? Or do we need, as some do, letters of recommendation to you or from you?
B047C003V002	47	3	2	Our letter of recommendation is yourselves–a letter written on our hearts and everywhere known and read.
B047C003V003	47	3	3	For all can see that you are a letter of Christ entrusted to our care, and written not with ink, but with the Spirit of the ever-living God–and not on tablets of stone, but on human hearts as tablets.
B047C003V004	47	3	4	Such is the confidence which we have through Christ in the presence of God;
B047C003V005	47	3	5	not that of ourselves we are competent to decide anything by our own reasonings, but our competency comes from God.
B047C003V006	47	3	6	It is He also who has made us competent to serve Him in connexion with a new Covenant, which is not a written code but a Spirit; for the written code inflicts death, but the Spirit gives Life.
B047C003V007	47	3	7	If, however, the service that proclaims death –its code being engraved in writing upon stones– came with glory, so that the children of Israel could not look steadily on the face of Moses because of the brightness of his face–a vanishing brightness;
B047C003V008	47	3	8	will not the service of the Spirit be far more glorious?
B047C003V009	47	3	9	For if the service which pronounces doom had glory, far more glorious still is the service which tells of righteousness.
B047C003V010	47	3	10	For, in fact, that which was once resplendent in glory has no glory at all in this respect, that it pales before the glory which surpasses it.
B047C003V011	47	3	11	For if that which was to be abolished came with glory, much more is that which is permanent arrayed in glory.
B047C003V012	47	3	12	Therefore, cherishing a hope like this, we speak without reserve, and we do not imitate Moses,
B047C003V013	47	3	13	who used to throw a veil over his face to hide from the gaze of the children of Israel the passing away of what was but transitory.
B047C003V014	47	3	14	Nay, their minds were made dull; for to this very day during the reading of the book of the ancient Covenant, the same veil remains unlifted, because it is only in Christ that it is to be abolished.
B047C003V015	47	3	15	Yes, to this day, whenever Moses is read, a veil lies upon their hearts.
B047C003V016	47	3	16	But whenever the heart of the nation shall have returned to the Lord, the veil will be withdrawn.
B047C003V017	47	3	17	Now by »the Lord« is meant the Spirit; and where the Spirit of the Lord is, freedom is enjoyed.
B047C003V018	47	3	18	And all of us, with unveiled faces, reflecting like bright mirrors the glory of the Lord, are being transformed into the same likeness, from one degree of radiant holiness to another, even as derived from the Lord the Spirit.
B047C004V001	47	4	1	Therefore, being engaged in this service and being mindful of the mercy which has been shown us, we are not cowards.
B047C004V002	47	4	2	Nay, we have renounced the secrecy which marks a feeling of shame. We practice no cunning tricks, nor do we adulterate God's Message. But by a full clear statement of the truth we strive to commend ourselves in the presence of God to every human conscience.
B047C004V003	47	4	3	If, however, the meaning of our Good News has been veiled, the veil has been on the hearts of those who are on the way to perdition,
B047C004V004	47	4	4	in whom the god of this present age has blinded their unbelieving minds so as to shut out the sunshine of the Good News of the glory of the Christ, who is the image of God.
B047C004V005	47	4	5	(For we do not proclaim ourselves, but we proclaim Christ Jesus as Lord, and ourselves as your bondservants for the sake of Jesus.)
B047C004V006	47	4	6	For God who said, »Out of darkness let light shine,« is He who has shone in our hearts to give us the light of the knowledge of God's glory, which is radiant on the face of Christ.
B047C004V007	47	4	7	But we have this treasure in a fragile vase of clay, in order that the surpassing greatness of the power may be seen to belong to God, and not to originate in us.
B047C004V008	47	4	8	We are hard pressed, yet never in absolute distress; perplexed, yet never utterly baffled;
B047C004V009	47	4	9	pursued, yet never left unsuccoured; struck to the ground, yet never slain;
B047C004V010	47	4	10	always, wherever we go, carrying with us in our bodies the putting to death of Jesus, so that in our bodies it may also be clearly shown that Jesus lives.
B047C004V011	47	4	11	For we, alive though we are, are continually surrendering ourselves to death for the sake of Jesus, so that in this mortal nature of ours it may also be clearly shown that Jesus lives.
B047C004V012	47	4	12	Thus we are constantly dying, while you are in full enjoyment of Life.
B047C004V013	47	4	13	But possessing the same Spirit of faith as he who wrote, 
B047C004V014	47	4	14	For we know that He who raised the Lord Jesus from the dead will raise us also to be with Jesus, and will cause both us and you to stand in His own presence.
B047C004V015	47	4	15	For everything is for your sakes, in order that grace, being more richly bestowed because of the thanksgivings of the increased number, may more and more promote the glory of God.
B047C004V016	47	4	16	Therefore we are not cowards. Nay, even though our outward man is wasting away, yet our inward man is being renewed day by day.
B047C004V017	47	4	17	For this our light and transitory burden of suffering is achieving for us a preponderating, yes, a vastly preponderating, and eternal weight of glory;
B047C004V018	47	4	18	while we look not at things seen, but things unseen; for things seen are temporary, but things unseen are eternal.
B047C005V001	47	5	1	For we know that if this poor tent, our earthly house, is taken down, we have in Heaven a building which God has provided, a house not built by human hands, but eternal.
B047C005V002	47	5	2	For in this one we sigh, because we long to put on over it our dwelling which comes from Heaven–
B047C005V003	47	5	3	if indeed having really put on a robe we shall not be found to be unclothed.
B047C005V004	47	5	4	Yes, we who are in this tent certainly do sigh under our burdens, for we do not wish to lay aside that with which we are now clothed, but to put on more, so that our mortality may be absorbed in Life.
B047C005V005	47	5	5	And He who formed us with this very end in view is God, who has given us His Spirit as a pledge and foretaste of that bliss.
B047C005V006	47	5	6	We have therefore a cheerful confidence. We know that while we are at home in the body we are banished from the Lord;
B047C005V007	47	5	7	for we are living a life of faith, and not one of sight.
B047C005V008	47	5	8	So we have a cheerful confidence, and we anticipate with greater delight being banished from the body and going home to the Lord.
B047C005V009	47	5	9	And for this reason also we make it our ambition, whether at home or in exile, to please Him perfectly.
B047C005V010	47	5	10	For we must all of us appear before Christ's judgement-seat in our true characters, in order that each may then receive an award for his actions in this life, in accordance with what he has done, whether it be good or whether it be worthless.
B047C005V011	47	5	11	Therefore, because we realize how greatly the Lord is to be feared, we are endeavouring to win men over, and God recognizes what our motives are, and I hope that you, in your hearts, recognize them too.
B047C005V012	47	5	12	We are not again commending ourselves to your favour, but are furnishing you with a ground of boasting on our behalf, so that you may have a reply ready for those with whom superficial appearances are everything and sincerity of heart counts for nothing.
B047C005V013	47	5	13	For if we have been beside ourselves, it has been for God's glory; or if we are now in our right senses, it is in order to be of service to you.
B047C005V014	47	5	14	For the love of Christ overmasters us, the conclusion at which we have arrived being this–that One having died for all, His death was their death,
B047C005V015	47	5	15	and that He died for all in order that the living may no longer live to themselves, but to Him who died for them and rose again.
B047C005V016	47	5	16	Therefore for the future we know no one simply as a man. Even if we have known Christ as a man, yet now we do so no longer.
B047C005V017	47	5	17	So that if any one is in Christ, he is a new creature: the old state of things has passed away; a new state of things has come into existence.
B047C005V018	47	5	18	And all this is from God, who has reconciled us to Himself through Christ, and has appointed us to serve in the ministry of reconciliation.
B047C005V019	47	5	19	We are to tell how God was in Christ reconciling the world to Himself, not charging men's transgressions to their account, and that He has entrusted to us the Message of this reconciliation.
B047C005V020	47	5	20	On Christ's behalf therefore we come as ambassadors, God, as it were, making entreaty through our lips: we, on Christ's behalf, beseech men to be reconciled to God.
B047C005V021	47	5	21	He has made Him who knew nothing of sin to be sin for us, in order that in Him we may become the righteousness of God.
B047C006V001	47	6	1	And you also we, as God's fellow workers, entreat not to be found to have received His grace to no purpose.
B047C006V002	47	6	2	For He says, 
B047C006V003	47	6	3	We endeavour to give people no cause for stumbling in anything, lest the work we are doing should fall into discredit.
B047C006V004	47	6	4	On the contrary, as God's servants, we seek their full approval–by unwearied endurance, by afflictions, by distress, by helplessness;
B047C006V005	47	6	5	by floggings, by imprisonments; by facing riots, by toil, by sleepless watching, by hunger and thirst;
B047C006V006	47	6	6	by purity of life, by knowledge, by patience, by kindness, by the Holy Spirit, by sincere love;
B047C006V007	47	6	7	by the proclamation of the truth, by the power of God; by the weapons of righteousness, wielded in both hands;
B047C006V008	47	6	8	through honour and ignominy, through calumny and praise. We are looked upon as impostors and yet are true men;
B047C006V009	47	6	9	as obscure persons, and yet are well known; as on the point of death, and yet, strange to tell, we live; as under God's discipline, and yet we are not deprived of life;
B047C006V010	47	6	10	as sad, but we are always joyful; as poor, but we bestow wealth on many; as having nothing, and yet we securely possess all things.
B047C006V011	47	6	11	O Corinthians, our lips are unsealed to you: our heart is expanded.
B047C006V012	47	6	12	There is no narrowness in our love to you: the narrowness is in your own feelings.
B047C006V013	47	6	13	And in just requital –I speak as to my children– let your hearts expand also.
B047C006V014	47	6	14	Do not come into close association with unbelievers, like oxen yoked with asses. For what is there in common between righteousness and lawlessness? Or what partnership has light with darkness?
B047C006V015	47	6	15	Where can harmony between Christ and Belial be found? Or what participation has a believer with an unbeliever?
B047C006V016	47	6	16	And what compact has the Temple of God with idols? For 
B047C006V017	47	6	17	Therefore, 
B047C006V018	47	6	18	
        
B047C007V001	47	7	1	Having therefore these promises, beloved friends, let us purify ourselves from all defilement of body and of spirit, and secure perfect holiness through the fear of God.
B047C007V002	47	7	2	Make room for us in your hearts. There is not one of you whom we have wronged, not one to whom we have done harm, not one over whom we have gained any selfish advantage.
B047C007V003	47	7	3	I do not say this to imply blame, for, as I have already said, you have such a place in our hearts that we would die with you or live with you.
B047C007V004	47	7	4	I have great confidence in you: very loudly do I boast of you. I am filled with comfort: my heart overflows with joy amid all our affliction.
B047C007V005	47	7	5	For even after our arrival in Macedonia we could get no relief such as human nature craves. We were greatly harassed; there were conflicts without and fears within.
B047C007V006	47	7	6	But He who comforts the depressed –even God– comforted us by the coming of Titus, and not by his coming only,
B047C007V007	47	7	7	but also by the fact that he had felt comforted on your account, and by the report which he brought of your eager affection, of your grief, and of your jealousy on my behalf, so that I rejoiced more than ever.
B047C007V008	47	7	8	For if I gave you pain by that letter, I do not regret it, though I did regret it then. I see that that letter, even though for a time it gave you pain, had a salutary effect.
B047C007V009	47	7	9	Now I rejoice, not in your grief, but because the grief led to repentance; for you sorrowed with a godly sorrow, which prevented you from receiving injury from us in any respect.
B047C007V010	47	7	10	For godly sorrow produces repentance leading to salvation, a repentance not to be regretted; but the sorrow of the world finally produces death.
B047C007V011	47	7	11	For mark the effects of this very thing –your having sorrowed with a godly sorrow– what earnestness it has called forth in you, what eagerness to clear yourselves, what indignation, what alarm, what longing affection, what jealousy, what meting out of justice! You have completely wiped away reproach from yourselves in the matter.
B047C007V012	47	7	12	Therefore, though I wrote to you, it was not to punish the offender, nor to secure justice for him who had suffered the wrong, but it was chiefly in order that your earnest feeling on our behalf might become manifest to yourselves in the sight of God.
B047C007V013	47	7	13	For this reason we feel comforted; and –in addition to this our comfort– we have been filled with all the deeper joy at Titus's joy, because his spirit has been set at rest by you all.
B047C007V014	47	7	14	For however I may have boasted to him about you, I have no reason to feel ashamed; but as we have in all respects spoken the truth to you, so also our boasting to Titus about you has turned out to be the truth.
B047C007V015	47	7	15	And his strong and tender affection is all the more drawn out towards you when he recalls to mind the obedience which all of you manifested by the timidity and nervous anxiety with which you welcomed him.
B047C007V016	47	7	16	I rejoice that I have absolute confidence in you.
B047C008V001	47	8	1	But we desire to let you know, brethren, of the grace of God which has been bestowed on the Churches of Macedonia;
B047C008V002	47	8	2	how, while passing through great trouble, their boundless joy even amid their deep poverty has overflowed to increase their generous liberality.
B047C008V003	47	8	3	For I can testify that to the utmost of their power, and even beyond their power, they have of their own free will given help.
B047C008V004	47	8	4	With earnest entreaty they begged from us the favour of being allowed to share in the service now being rendered to God's people.
B047C008V005	47	8	5	They not only did this, as we had expected, but first of all in obedience to God's will they gave their own selves to the Lord and to us.
B047C008V006	47	8	6	This led us to urge Titus that, as he had previously been the one who commenced the work, so he should now go and complete among you this act of beneficence also.
B047C008V007	47	8	7	Yes, just as you are already very rich in faith, readiness of speech, knowledge, unwearied zeal, and in the love that is in you, implanted by us, see to it that this grace of liberal giving also flourishes in you.
B047C008V008	47	8	8	I am not saying this by way of command, but to test by the standard of other men's earnestness the genuineness of your love also.
B047C008V009	47	8	9	For you know the condescending goodness of our Lord Jesus Christ–how for your sakes He became poor, though He was rich, in order that you through His poverty might grow rich.
B047C008V010	47	8	10	But in this matter I give you an opinion; for my doing this helps forward your own intentions, seeing that not only have you begun operations, but a year ago you already had the desire to do so.
B047C008V011	47	8	11	And now complete the doing also, in order that, just as there was then the eagerness in desiring, there may now be the accomplishment in proportion to your means.
B047C008V012	47	8	12	For, assuming the earnest willingness, the gift is acceptable according to whatever a man has, and not according to what he has not.
B047C008V013	47	8	13	I do not urge you to give in order that others may have relief while you are unduly pressed,
B047C008V014	47	8	14	but that, by equalization of burdens, your superfluity having in the present emergency supplied their deficiency, their superfluity may in turn be a supply for your deficiency later on, so that there may be equalization of burdens.
B047C008V015	47	8	15	Even as it is written, 
B047C008V016	47	8	16	But thanks be to God that He inspires the heart of Titus with the same deep interest in you;
B047C008V017	47	8	17	for Titus welcomed our request, and, being thoroughly in earnest, comes to you of his own free will.
B047C008V018	47	8	18	And we send with him the brother whose praises for his earnestness in proclaiming the Good News are heard throughout all the Churches.
B047C008V019	47	8	19	And more than that, he is the one who was chosen by the vote of the Churches to travel with us, sharing our commission in the administration of this generous gift to promote the Lord's glory and gratify our own strong desire.
B047C008V020	47	8	20	For against one thing we are on our guard–I mean against blame being thrown upon us in respect to these large and liberal contributions which are under our charge.
B047C008V021	47	8	21	For we seek not only God's approval of our integrity, but man's also.
B047C008V022	47	8	22	And we send with them our brother, of whose zeal we have had frequent proof in many matters, and who is now more zealous than ever through the strong confidence which he has in you.
B047C008V023	47	8	23	As for Titus, remember that he is a partner with me, and is my comrade in my labours for you. And as for our brethren, remember that they are delegates from the Churches, and are men in whom Christ is glorified.
B047C008V024	47	8	24	Exhibit therefore to the Churches a proof of your love, and a justification of our boasting to these brethren about you.
B047C009V001	47	9	1	As to the services which are being rendered to God's people, it is really unnecessary for me to write to you.
B047C009V002	47	9	2	For I know your earnest willingness, on account of which I habitually boast of you to the Macedonians, pointing out to them that for a whole year you in Greece have been ready; and the greater number of them have been spurred on by your ardour.
B047C009V003	47	9	3	Still I send the brethren in order that in this matter our boast about you may not turn out to have been an idle one; so that, as I have said, you may be ready;
B047C009V004	47	9	4	for fear that, if any Macedonians come with me and find you unprepared, we –not to say you yourselves– should be put to the blush in respect to this confidence.
B047C009V005	47	9	5	I have thought it absolutely necessary therefore to request these brethren to visit you before I myself come, and to make sure beforehand that the gift of love which you have already promised may be ready as a gift of love, and may not seem to have been something which I have extorted from you.
B047C009V006	47	9	6	But do not forget that he who sows with a niggardly hand will also reap a niggardly crop, and that he who sows bountifully will also reap bountifully.
B047C009V007	47	9	7	Let each contribute what he has decided upon in his own mind, and not do it reluctantly or under compulsion. 
B047C009V008	47	9	8	And God is able to bestow every blessing on you in abundance, so that richly enjoying all sufficiency at all times, you may have ample means for all good works.
B047C009V009	47	9	9	As it is written, 
B047C009V010	47	9	10	And God who continually supplies seed for the sower and bread for eating, will supply you with seed and multiply it, and will cause your almsgiving to yield a plentiful harvest.
B047C009V011	47	9	11	May you be abundantly enriched so as to show all liberality, such as through our instrumentality brings thanksgiving to God.
B047C009V012	47	9	12	For the service rendered in this sacred gift not only helps to relieve the wants of God's people, but it is also rich in its results and awakens a chorus of thanksgiving to God.
B047C009V013	47	9	13	For, by the practical proof of it which you exhibit in this service, you cause God to be extolled for your fidelity to your professed adherence to the Good News of the Christ, and for the liberality of your contributions for them and for all who are in need,
B047C009V014	47	9	14	while they themselves also in supplications on your behalf pour out their longing love towards you because of God's surpassing grace which is resting upon you.
B047C009V015	47	9	15	Thanks be to God for His unspeakably precious gift!
B047C010V001	47	10	1	But as for me Paul, I entreat you by the gentleness and self-forgetfulness of Christ–I who when among you have not an imposing personal presence, but when absent am fearlessly outspoken in dealing with you.
B047C010V002	47	10	2	I beseech you not to compel me when present to make a bold display of the confidence with which I reckon I shall show my `courage' against some who reckon that we are guided by worldly principles.
B047C010V003	47	10	3	For, though we are still living in the world, it is no worldly warfare that we are waging.
B047C010V004	47	10	4	The weapons with which we fight are not human weapons, but are mighty for God in overthrowing strong fortresses.
B047C010V005	47	10	5	For we overthrow arrogant `reckonings,' and every stronghold that towers high in defiance of the knowledge of God, and we carry off every thought as if into slavery–into subjection to Christ;
B047C010V006	47	10	6	while we hold ourselves in readiness to punish every act of disobedience, as soon as ever you as a Church have fully shown your obedience.
B047C010V007	47	10	7	Is it outward appearances you look to? If any man is confident as regards himself that he specially belongs to Christ, let him consider again and reflect that just as he belongs to Christ, so also do we.
B047C010V008	47	10	8	If, however, I were to boast more loudly of our Apostolic authority, which the Lord has given us that we may build you up, not pull you down, I should have no reason to feel ashamed.
B047C010V009	47	10	9	Let it not seem as if I wanted to frighten you by my letters.
B047C010V010	47	10	10	For they say »His letters are authoritative and forcible, but his personal presence is unimpressive, and as for eloquence, he has none.«
B047C010V011	47	10	11	Let such people take this into their reckoning, that whatever we are in word by our letters when absent, the same are we also in act when present.
B047C010V012	47	10	12	For we have not the `courage' to rank ourselves among, or compare ourselves with, certain persons distinguished by their self-commendation. Yet they are not wise, measuring themselves, as they do, by one another and comparing themselves with one another.
B047C010V013	47	10	13	We, however, will not exceed due limits in our boasting, but will keep within the limits of the sphere which God has assigned to us as a limit, which reaches even to you.
B047C010V014	47	10	14	For there is no undue stretch of authority on our part, as though it did not extend to you. We pressed on even to Corinth, and were the first to proclaim to you the Good News of the Christ.
B047C010V015	47	10	15	We do not exceed our due limits, and take credit for other men's labours; but we entertain the hope that, as your faith grows, we shall gain promotion among you –still keeping within our own sphere– promotion to a larger field of labour,
B047C010V016	47	10	16	and shall tell the Good News in the districts beyond you, not boasting in another man's sphere about work already done by him.
B047C010V017	47	10	17	But 
B047C010V018	47	10	18	For it is not the man that commends himself who is really approved, but he whom the Lord commends.
B047C011V001	47	11	1	I wish you could have borne with a little foolish boasting on my part. Nay, do bear with me.
B047C011V002	47	11	2	I am jealous over you with God's own jealousy. For I have betrothed you to Christ to present you to Him like a faithful bride to her one husband.
B047C011V003	47	11	3	But I am afraid that, as the serpent in his craftiness deceived Eve, so your minds may be led astray from their single-heartedness and their fidelity to Christ.
B047C011V004	47	11	4	If indeed some visitor is proclaiming among you another Jesus whom we did not proclaim, or if you are receiving a Spirit different from the One you have already received or a Good News different from that which you have already welcomed, your toleration is admirable!
B047C011V005	47	11	5	Why, I reckon myself in no respect inferior to those superlatively great Apostles.
B047C011V006	47	11	6	And if in the matter of speech I am no orator, yet in knowledge I am not deficient. Nay, we have in every way made that fully evident to you.
B047C011V007	47	11	7	Is it a sin that I abased myself in order for you to be exalted, in that I proclaimed God's Good News to you without fee or reward?
B047C011V008	47	11	8	Other Churches I robbed, receiving pay from them in order to do you service.
B047C011V009	47	11	9	And when I was with you and my resources failed, there was no one to whom I became a burden –for the brethren when they came from Macedonia fully supplied my wants– and I kept myself from being in the least a burden to you, and will do so still.
B047C011V010	47	11	10	Christ knows that it is true when I say that I will not be stopped from boasting of this anywhere in Greece.
B047C011V011	47	11	11	And why? Because I do not love you? God knows that I do.
B047C011V012	47	11	12	But I will persist in the same line of conduct in order to cut the ground from under the feet of those who desire an opportunity of getting themselves recognized as being on a level with us in the matters about which they boast.
B047C011V013	47	11	13	For men of this stamp are sham apostles, dishonest workmen, assuming the garb of Apostles of Christ.
B047C011V014	47	11	14	And no wonder. Satan, their master, can disguise himself as an angel of light.
B047C011V015	47	11	15	It is therefore no great thing for his servants also to disguise themselves as servants of righteousness. Their end will be in accordance with their actions.
B047C011V016	47	11	16	To return to what I was saying. Let no one suppose that I am foolish. Or if you must, at any rate make allowance for me as being foolish, in order that I, as well as they, may boast a little.
B047C011V017	47	11	17	What I am now saying, I do not say by the Lord's command, but as a fool in his folly might, in this reckless boasting.
B047C011V018	47	11	18	Since many boast for merely human reasons, I too will boast.
B047C011V019	47	11	19	Wise as you yourselves are, you find pleasure in tolerating fools.
B047C011V020	47	11	20	For you tolerate it, if any one enslaves you, lives at your expense, makes off with your property, gives himself airs, or strikes you on the face.
B047C011V021	47	11	21	I use the language of self-disparagement, as though I were admitting our own feebleness. Yet for whatever reason any one is `courageous' –I speak in mere folly– I also am courageous.
B047C011V022	47	11	22	Are they Hebrews? So am I. Are they Israelites? So am I. Are they descendants of Abraham? So am I.
B047C011V023	47	11	23	Are they servants of Christ? (I speak as if I were out of my mind.) Much more am I His servant; serving Him more thoroughly than they by my labours, and more thoroughly also by my imprisonments, by excessively cruel floggings, and with risk of life many a time.
B047C011V024	47	11	24	From the Jews I five times have received forty lashes all but one.
B047C011V025	47	11	25	Three times I have been beaten with Roman rods, once I have been stoned, three times I have been shipwrecked, once for full four and twenty hours I was floating on the open sea.
B047C011V026	47	11	26	I have served Him by frequent travelling, amid dangers in crossing rivers, dangers from robbers; dangers from my own countrymen, dangers from the Gentiles; dangers in the city, dangers in the Desert, dangers by sea, dangers from spies in our midst;
B047C011V027	47	11	27	with labour and toil, with many a sleepless night, in hunger and thirst, in frequent fastings, in cold, and with insufficient clothing.
B047C011V028	47	11	28	And besides other things, which I pass over, there is that which presses on me daily–my anxiety for all the Churches.
B047C011V029	47	11	29	Who is weak, and I am not weak? Who is led astray into sin, and I am not aflame with indignation?
B047C011V030	47	11	30	If boast I must, it shall be of things which display my weakness.
B047C011V031	47	11	31	The God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ –He who is blessed throughout the Ages– knows that I am speaking the truth.
B047C011V032	47	11	32	In Damascus the governor under King Aretas kept guards at the gates of the city in order to apprehend me,
B047C011V033	47	11	33	but through an opening in the wall I was let down in a basket, and so escaped his hands.
B047C012V001	47	12	1	I am compelled to boast. It is not a profitable employment, but I will proceed to visions and revelations granted me by the Lord.
B047C012V002	47	12	2	I know a Christian man who fourteen years ago – whether in the body I do not know, or out of the body I do not know; God knows– was caught up (this man of whom I am speaking) even to the highest Heaven.
B047C012V003	47	12	3	And I know that this man– whether in the body or apart from the body I do not know;
B047C012V004	47	12	4	God knows–was caught up into Paradise and heard unspeakable things which no human being is permitted to repeat.
B047C012V005	47	12	5	Of such a one I will boast; but of myself I will not boast, except in my weaknesses.
B047C012V006	47	12	6	If however I should choose to boast, I should not be a fool for so doing, for I should be speaking the truth. But I forbear, lest any one should be led to estimate me more highly than what his own eyes attest, or more highly than what he hears from my lips.
B047C012V007	47	12	7	And judging by the stupendous grandeur of the revelations–therefore lest I should be over-elated there has been sent to me, like the agony of impalement, Satan's angel dealing blow after blow, lest I should be over-elated.
B047C012V008	47	12	8	As for this, three times have I besought the Lord to rid me of him;
B047C012V009	47	12	9	but His reply has been, »My grace suffices for you, for power matures in weakness.« Most gladly therefore will I boast of my infirmities rather than complain of them–in order that Christ's power may overshadow me.
B047C012V010	47	12	10	In fact I take pleasure in infirmities, in the bearing of insults, in distress, in persecutions, in grievous difficulties–for Christ's sake; for when I am weak, then I am strong.
B047C012V011	47	12	11	It is foolish of me to write all this, but you have compelled me to do so. Why, you ought to have been my vindicators; for in no respect have I been inferior to these superlatively great Apostles, even though in myself I am nothing.
B047C012V012	47	12	12	The signs that characterize the true Apostle have been done among you, accompanied by unwearied fortitude, and by tokens and marvels and displays of power.
B047C012V013	47	12	13	In what respect, therefore, have you been worse dealt with than other Churches, except that I myself never hung as a dead weight upon you? Forgive the injustice I thus did you!
B047C012V014	47	12	14	See, I am now for the third time prepared to visit you, but I will not be a dead weight to you. I desire not your money, but yourselves; for children ought not to put by for their parents, but parents for their children.
B047C012V015	47	12	15	And as for me, most gladly will I spend all I have and be utterly spent for your salvation.
B047C012V016	47	12	16	If I love you so intensely, am I the less to be loved? Be that as it may: I was not a burden to you. But being by no means scrupulous, I entrapped you, they say!
B047C012V017	47	12	17	Have I gained any selfish advantage over you through any one of the messengers I have sent to you?
B047C012V018	47	12	18	I begged Titus to visit you, and sent our other brother with him. Did Titus gain any selfish advantage over you? Were not he and I guided by one and the same Spirit, and did we not walk in the same steps?
B047C012V019	47	12	19	You are imagining, all this time, that we are making our defense at your bar. In reality it is as in God's presence and in communion with Christ that we speak; but, dear friends, it is all with a view to your progress in goodness.
B047C012V020	47	12	20	For I am afraid that perhaps when I come I may not find you to be what I desire, and that you may find me to be what you do not desire; that perhaps there may be contention, jealousy, bitter feeling, party spirit, ill-natured talk, backbiting, undue eulogy, unrest;
B047C012V021	47	12	21	and that upon re-visiting you I may be humbled by my God in your presence, and may have to mourn over many whose hearts still cling to their old sins, and who have not repented of the impurity, fornication, and gross sensuality, of which they have been guilty.
B047C013V001	47	13	1	This intended visit of mine is my third visit to you. 
B047C013V002	47	13	2	Those who cling to their old sins, and indeed all of you, I have forewarned and still forewarn (as I did on my second visit when present, so I do now, though absent) that, when I come again, I shall not spare you;
B047C013V003	47	13	3	since you want a practical proof of the fact that Christ speaks by my lips–He who is not feeble towards you, but powerful among you.
B047C013V004	47	13	4	For though it is true that He was crucified through weakness, yet He now lives through the power of God. We also are weak, sharing His weakness, but with Him we shall be full of life to deal with you through the power of God.
B047C013V005	47	13	5	Test yourselves to discover whether you are true believers: put your own selves under examination. Or do you not know that Jesus Christ is within you, unless you are insincere?
B047C013V006	47	13	6	But I trust that you will recognize that we are not insincere.
B047C013V007	47	13	7	And our prayer to God is that you may do nothing wrong; not in order that our sincerity may be demonstrated, but that you may do what is right, even though our sincerity may seem to be doubtful.
B047C013V008	47	13	8	For we have no power against the truth, but only for the furtherance of the truth;
B047C013V009	47	13	9	and it is a joy to us when we are powerless, but you are strong. This we also pray for–the perfecting of your characters.
B047C013V010	47	13	10	For this reason I write thus while absent, that when present I may not have to act severely in the exercise of the authority which the Lord has given me for building up, and not for pulling down.
B047C013V011	47	13	11	Finally, brethren, be joyful, secure perfection of character, take courage, be of one mind, live in peace. And then God who gives love and peace will be with you.
B047C013V012	47	13	12	Salute one another with a holy kiss.
B047C013V013	47	13	13	All God's people here send greetings to you.
B047C013V014	47	13	14	May the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ, the love of God, and the fellowship of the Holy Spirit, be with you all.
B048C001V001	48	1	1	Paul, an Apostle sent not from men nor by any man, but by Jesus Christ and by God the Father, who raised Jesus from among the dead–
B048C001V002	48	1	2	and all the brethren who are with me: To the Churches of Galatia.
B048C001V003	48	1	3	May grace and peace be granted to you from God the Father, and from our Lord Jesus Christ,
B048C001V004	48	1	4	who gave Himself to suffer for our sins in order to rescue us from the present wicked age in accordance with the will of our God and Father.
B048C001V005	48	1	5	To Him be the glory to the Ages of the Ages! Amen.
B048C001V006	48	1	6	I marvel that you are so readily leaving Him who called you by the grace of Christ, and are adhering to a different Good News.
B048C001V007	48	1	7	For other »Good News« there is none; but there are some persons who are troubling you, and are seeking to distort the Good News concerning Christ.
B048C001V008	48	1	8	But if even we or an angel from Heaven should bring you a Good News different from that which we have already brought you, let him be accursed.
B048C001V009	48	1	9	What I have just said I repeat–if any one is preaching to you a Good News other than that which you originally received, let him be accursed.
B048C001V010	48	1	10	For is it man's favour or God's that I aspire to? Or am I seeking to please men? If I were still a man-pleaser, I should not be Christ's bondservant.
B048C001V011	48	1	11	For I must tell you, brethren, that the Good News which was proclaimed by me is not such as man approves of.
B048C001V012	48	1	12	For, in fact, it was not from man that I received or learnt it, but by a revelation from Jesus Christ.
B048C001V013	48	1	13	For you have heard of my early career in Judaism–how I furiously persecuted the Church of God, and made havoc of it;
B048C001V014	48	1	14	and how in devotion to Judaism I outstripped many men of my own age among my people, being far more zealous than they on behalf of the traditions of my forefathers.
B048C001V015	48	1	15	But when He who set me apart even from my birth, and called me by His grace,
B048C001V016	48	1	16	saw fit to reveal His Son within me in order that I might tell among the Gentiles the Good News concerning Him, at once I did not confer with any human being,
B048C001V017	48	1	17	nor did I go up to Jerusalem to those who were my seniors in the Apostleship, but I went away into Arabia, and afterwards came back to Damascus.
B048C001V018	48	1	18	Then, three years later, I went up to Jerusalem to inquire for Peter, and I spent a fortnight with him.
B048C001V019	48	1	19	I saw none of the other Apostles, except James, the Lord's brother.
B048C001V020	48	1	20	In making these assertions I am speaking the truth, as in the sight of God.
B048C001V021	48	1	21	Afterwards I visited Syria and Cilicia.
B048C001V022	48	1	22	But to the Christian Churches in Judaea I was personally unknown.
B048C001V023	48	1	23	They only heard it said, »He who was once our persecutor is now telling the Good News of the faith of which he formerly made havoc.«
B048C001V024	48	1	24	And they gave glory to God on my account.
B048C002V001	48	2	1	Later still, after an interval of fourteen years, I again went up to Jerusalem in company with Barnabas, taking Titus also with me.
B048C002V002	48	2	2	I went up in obedience to a revelation of God's will; and I explained to them the Good News which I proclaim among the Gentiles. To the leaders of the Church this explanation was made in private, lest by any means I should be running, or should already have run, in vain.
B048C002V003	48	2	3	But although my companion Titus was a Greek they did not insist upon even his being circumcised.
B048C002V004	48	2	4	Yet there was danger of this through the false brethren secretly introduced into the Church, who had stolen in to spy out the freedom which is ours in Christ Jesus, in order to rob us of it.
B048C002V005	48	2	5	But not for an hour did we give way and submit to them; in order that the Good News might continue with you in its integrity.
B048C002V006	48	2	6	From those leaders I gained nothing new. Whether they were men of importance or not, matters nothing to me–God recognizes no external distinctions. To me, at any rate, the leaders imparted nothing new.
B048C002V007	48	2	7	Indeed, when they saw that I was entrusted with the preaching of the Good News to the Gentiles as Peter had been with that to the Jews–
B048C002V008	48	2	8	for He who had been at work within Peter with a view to his Apostleship to the Jews had also been at work within me with a view to my Apostleship to the Gentiles–
B048C002V009	48	2	9	and when they perceived the mission which was graciously entrusted to me, they (that is to say, James, Peter, and John, who were considered to be the pillars of the Church) welcomed Barnabas and me to their fellowship on the understanding that we were to go to the Gentiles and they to the Jews.
B048C002V010	48	2	10	Only they urged that we should remember their poor–a thing which was uppermost in my own mind.
B048C002V011	48	2	11	Now when Peter visited Antioch, I remonstrated with him to his face, because he had incurred just censure.
B048C002V012	48	2	12	For until certain persons came from James he had been accustomed to eat with Gentiles; but as soon as these persons came, he withdrew and separated himself for fear of the Circumcision party.
B048C002V013	48	2	13	And along with him the other Jews also concealed their real opinions, so that even Barnabas was carried away by their lack of straightforwardness.
B048C002V014	48	2	14	As soon as I saw that they were not walking uprightly in the spirit of the Good News, I said to Peter, before them all, »If you, though you are a Jew, live as a Gentile does, and not as a Jew, how can you make the Gentiles follow Jewish customs?
B048C002V015	48	2	15	You and I, though we are Jews by birth and not Gentile sinners,
B048C002V016	48	2	16	know that it is not through obedience to Law that a man can be declared free from guilt, but only through faith in Jesus Christ. We have therefore believed in Christ Jesus, for the purpose of being declared free from guilt, through faith in Christ and not through obedience to Law. For through obedience to Law no human being shall be declared free from guilt.
B048C002V017	48	2	17	But if while we are seeking in Christ acquittal from guilt we ourselves are convicted of sin, Christ then encourages us to sin! No, indeed.
B048C002V018	48	2	18	Why, if I am now rebuilding that structure of sin which I had demolished, I am thereby constituting myself a transgressor;
B048C002V019	48	2	19	for it is by the Law that I have died to the Law, in order that I may live to God.
B048C002V020	48	2	20	I have been crucified with Christ, and it is no longer I that live, but Christ that lives in me; and the life which I now live in the body I live through faith in the Son of God who loved me and gave Himself up to death on my behalf.
B048C002V021	48	2	21	I do not nullify the grace of God; for if acquittal from guilt is obtainable through the Law, then Christ has died in vain.«
B048C003V001	48	3	1	You foolish Galatians! Whose sophistry has bewitched you–you to whom Jesus Christ has been vividly portrayed as on the Cross?
B048C003V002	48	3	2	Answer me this one question, »Is it on the ground of your obedience to the Law that you received the Spirit, or is it because, when you heard, you believed?«
B048C003V003	48	3	3	Are you so foolish? Having begun by the Spirit, are you now going to reach perfection through what is external?
B048C003V004	48	3	4	Have you endured such sufferings to no purpose–if indeed it has been to no purpose?
B048C003V005	48	3	5	He who gives you His Spirit and works miracles among you–does He do so on the ground of your obedience to the Law, or is it the result of your having heard and believed:
B048C003V006	48	3	6	even as 
B048C003V007	48	3	7	Notice therefore that those who possess faith are true sons of Abraham.
B048C003V008	48	3	8	And the Scripture, foreseeing that in consequence of faith God would declare the nations to be free from guilt, sent beforehand the Good News to Abraham, saying, 
B048C003V009	48	3	9	So we see that it is those who possess faith that are blessed with believing Abraham.
B048C003V010	48	3	10	All who are depending upon their own obedience to the Law are under a curse, for it is written, 
B048C003V011	48	3	11	It is evident, too, that no one can find acceptance with God simply by obeying the Law, because 
B048C003V012	48	3	12	and the Law has nothing to do with faith. It teaches that 
B048C003V013	48	3	13	Christ has purchased our freedom from the curse of the Law by becoming accursed for us–because 
B048C003V014	48	3	14	Our freedom has been thus purchased in order that in Christ Jesus the blessing belonging to Abraham may come upon the nations, so that through faith we may receive the promised Spirit.
B048C003V015	48	3	15	Brethren, even a covenant made by a man –to borrow an illustration from daily life– when once formally sanctioned is not liable to be set aside or added to.
B048C003V016	48	3	16	(Now the promises were given to Abraham and to his seed. God did not say »and to seeds,« as if speaking of many, but »and to your seed,« since He spoke of only one–and this is Christ.)
B048C003V017	48	3	17	I mean that the Covenant which God had already formally made is not abrogated by the Law which was given four hundred and thirty years later–so as to annul the promise.
B048C003V018	48	3	18	For if the inheritance comes through obedience to Law, it no longer comes because of a promise. But, as a matter of fact, God has granted it to Abraham in fulfilment of a promise.
B048C003V019	48	3	19	Why then was the Law given? It was imposed later on for the sake of defining sin, until the seed should come to whom God had made the promise; and its details were laid down by a mediator with the help of angels.
B048C003V020	48	3	20	But there cannot be a mediator where only one individual is concerned.
B048C003V021	48	3	21	God, however, is only one. Is the Law then opposed to the promises of God? No, indeed; for if a Law had been given which could have conferred Life, righteousness would certainly have come by the Law.
B048C003V022	48	3	22	But Scripture has shown that all mankind are the prisoners of sin, in order that the promised blessing, which depends on faith in Jesus Christ, may be given to those who believe.
B048C003V023	48	3	23	Before this faith came, we Jews were perpetual prisoners under the Law, living under restraints and limitations in preparation for the faith which was soon to be revealed.
B048C003V024	48	3	24	So that the Law has acted the part of a tutor-slave to lead us to Christ, in order that through faith we may be declared to be free from guilt.
B048C003V025	48	3	25	But now that this faith has come, we are no longer under a tutor-slave.
B048C003V026	48	3	26	You are all sons of God through faith in Christ Jesus;
B048C003V027	48	3	27	for all of you who have been baptized into Christ, have clothed yourselves with Christ.
B048C003V028	48	3	28	In Him the distinctions between Jew and Gentile, slave and free man, male and female, disappear; you are all one in Christ Jesus.
B048C003V029	48	3	29	And if you belong to Christ, then you are indeed true descendants of Abraham, and are heirs in fulfilment of the promise.
B048C004V001	48	4	1	Now I say that so long as an heir is a child, he in no respect differs from a slave, although he is the owner of everything,
B048C004V002	48	4	2	but he is under the control of guardians and trustees until the time his father has appointed.
B048C004V003	48	4	3	So we also, when spiritually we were children, were subject to the world's rudimentary notions, and were enslaved.
B048C004V004	48	4	4	But, when the time was fully come, God sent forth His Son, born of a woman, born subject to Law,
B048C004V005	48	4	5	in order to purchase the freedom of all who were subject to Law, so that we might receive recognition as sons.
B048C004V006	48	4	6	And because you are sons, God has sent out the Spirit of His Son to enter your hearts and cry »Abba! our Father!«
B048C004V007	48	4	7	Therefore you are no longer a slave, but a son; and if a son, then an heir also through God's own act.
B048C004V008	48	4	8	But at one time, you Gentiles, having no knowledge of God, were slaves to gods which in reality do not exist.
B048C004V009	48	4	9	Now, however, having come to know God –or rather to be known by Him– how is it you are again turning back to weak and worthless rudimentary notions to which you are once more willing to be enslaved?
B048C004V010	48	4	10	You scrupulously observe days and months, special seasons, and years.
B048C004V011	48	4	11	I am alarmed about you, and am afraid that I have perhaps bestowed labour upon you to no purpose.
B048C004V012	48	4	12	Brethren, become as I am, I beseech you; for I have also become like you. In no respect did you behave badly to me.
B048C004V013	48	4	13	And you know that in those early days it was on account of bodily infirmity that I proclaimed the Good News to you,
B048C004V014	48	4	14	and yet the bodily infirmity which was such a trial to you, you did not regard with contempt or loathing, but you received me as if I had been an angel of God or Christ Jesus Himself!
B048C004V015	48	4	15	I ask you, then, what has become of your self-congratulations? For I bear you witness that had it been possible you would have torn out your own eyes and have given them to me.
B048C004V016	48	4	16	Can it be that I have become your enemy through speaking the truth to you?
B048C004V017	48	4	17	These men pay court to you, but not with honourable motives. They want to exclude you, so that you may pay court to them.
B048C004V018	48	4	18	It is always an honourable thing to be courted in an honourable cause; always, and not only when I am with you, my children–
B048C004V019	48	4	19	you for whom I am again, as it were, undergoing the pains of childbirth, until Christ is fully formed within you.
B048C004V020	48	4	20	Would that I were with you and could change my tone, for I am perplexed about you.
B048C004V021	48	4	21	Tell me –you who want to continue to be subject to Law– will you not listen to the Law?
B048C004V022	48	4	22	For it is written that Abraham had two sons, one by the slave-girl and one by the free woman.
B048C004V023	48	4	23	But we see that the child of the slave-girl was born in the common course of nature; but the child of the free woman in fulfilment of the promise.
B048C004V024	48	4	24	All this is allegorical; for the women represent two Covenants. One has its origin on Mount Sinai, and bears children destined for slavery.
B048C004V025	48	4	25	This is Hagar; for the name Hagar stands for Mount Sinai in Arabia, and corresponds to the present Jerusalem, which is in bondage together with her children.
B048C004V026	48	4	26	But the Jerusalem which is above is free, and 
B048C004V027	48	4	27	For it is written, 
B048C004V028	48	4	28	But you, brethren, like Isaac, are children born in fulfilment of a promise.
B048C004V029	48	4	29	Yet just as, at that time, the child born in the common course of nature persecuted the one whose birth was due to the power of the Spirit, so it is now.
B048C004V030	48	4	30	But what says the Scripture? 
B048C004V031	48	4	31	Therefore, brethren, since we are not the children of a slave-girl, but of the free woman–
B048C005V001	48	5	1	Christ having made us gloriously free–stand fast and do not again be hampered with the yoke of slavery.
B048C005V002	48	5	2	Remember that it is I Paul who tell you that if you receive circumcision Christ will avail you nothing.
B048C005V003	48	5	3	I once more protest to every man who receives circumcision that he is under obligation to obey the whole Law of Moses.
B048C005V004	48	5	4	Christ has become nothing to any of you who are seeking acceptance with God through the Law: you have fallen away from grace.
B048C005V005	48	5	5	
        
B048C005V006	48	5	6	For in Christ Jesus neither circumcision nor uncircumcision is of any importance; but only faith working through love.
B048C005V007	48	5	7	You were running the race nobly! Who has interfered and caused you to swerve from the truth?
B048C005V008	48	5	8	No such teaching ever proceeded from Him who is calling you.
B048C005V009	48	5	9	A little yeast corrupts the whole of the dough.
B048C005V010	48	5	10	For my part I have strong confidence in you in the Lord that you will adopt my view of the matter. But the man –be he who he may– who is troubling you, will have to bear the full weight of the judgement to be pronounced on him.
B048C005V011	48	5	11	As for me, brethren, if I am still a preacher of circumcision, how is it that I am still suffering persecution? In that case the Cross has ceased to be a stumbling-block!
B048C005V012	48	5	12	Would to God that those who are unsettling your faith would even mutilate themselves.
B048C005V013	48	5	13	You however, brethren, were called to freedom. Only do not turn your freedom into an excuse for giving way to your lower natures; but become bondservants to one another in a spirit of love.
B048C005V014	48	5	14	For the entire Law has been obeyed when you have kept the single precept, which says, 
B048C005V015	48	5	15	But if you are perpetually snarling and snapping at one another, beware lest you are destroyed by one another.
B048C005V016	48	5	16	This then is what I mean. Let your lives be guided by the Spirit, and then you will certainly not indulge the cravings of your lower natures.
B048C005V017	48	5	17	For the cravings of the lower nature are opposed to those of the Spirit, and the cravings of the Spirit are opposed to those of the lower nature; because these are antagonistic to each other, so that you cannot do everything to which you are inclined.
B048C005V018	48	5	18	But if the Spirit is leading you, you are not subject to Law.
B048C005V019	48	5	19	Now you know full well the doings of our lower natures. Fornication, impurity, indecency, idol-worship, sorcery;
B048C005V020	48	5	20	enmity, strife, jealousy, outbursts of passion, intrigues, dissensions, factions, envyings;
B048C005V021	48	5	21	hard drinking, riotous feasting, and the like. And as to these I forewarn you, as I have already forewarned you, that those who are guilty of such things will have no share in the Kingdom of God.
B048C005V022	48	5	22	The Spirit, on the other hand, brings a harvest of love, joy, peace; patience towards others, kindness, benevolence;
B048C005V023	48	5	23	good faith, meekness, self-restraint.
B048C005V024	48	5	24	Against such things as these there is no law. Now those who belong to Christ Jesus have crucified their lower nature with its passions and appetites.
B048C005V025	48	5	25	If we are living by the Spirit's power, let our conduct also be governed by the Spirit's power.
B048C005V026	48	5	26	Let us not become vain-glorious, challenging one another, envying one another.
B048C006V001	48	6	1	Brethren, if anybody be detected in any misconduct, you who are spiritual should restore such a one in a spirit of meekness. And let each of you keep watch over himself, lest he also fall into temptation.
B048C006V002	48	6	2	Always carry one another's burdens, and so obey the whole of Christ's Law.
B048C006V003	48	6	3	For if there is any one who thinks himself to be somebody when he is nobody, he is deluding himself.
B048C006V004	48	6	4	But let every man scrutinize his own conduct, and then he will find out, not with reference to another but with reference to himself, what he has to boast of.
B048C006V005	48	6	5	For every man will have to carry his own load.
B048C006V006	48	6	6	But let those who receive instruction in Christian truth share with their instructors all temporal blessings.
B048C006V007	48	6	7	Do not deceive yourselves. God is not to be scoffed at. For whatever a man sows, that he will also reap.
B048C006V008	48	6	8	He who sows in the field of his lower nature, will from that nature reap destruction; but he who sows to serve the Spirit will from the Spirit reap the Life of the Ages.
B048C006V009	48	6	9	Let us not abate our courage in doing what is right; for in due time we shall reap a reward, if we do not faint.
B048C006V010	48	6	10	So then, as we have opportunity, let us labour for the good of all, and especially of those who belong to the household of the faith.
B048C006V011	48	6	11	See in what large letters I am writing to you with my own hand.
B048C006V012	48	6	12	All who desire to display their zeal for external observances try to compel you to receive circumcision, but their real object is simply to escape being persecuted for the Cross of Christ.
B048C006V013	48	6	13	For these very men do not really keep the Law of Moses, but they would have you receive circumcision in order that they may glory in 
B048C006V014	48	6	14	But as for me, God forbid that I should glory in anything except the Cross of our Lord Jesus Christ, upon which the world is crucified to me, and I am crucified to the world.
B048C006V015	48	6	15	For neither circumcision nor uncircumcision is of any importance; but only a renewed nature.
B048C006V016	48	6	16	And all who shall regulate their lives by this principle –may peace and mercy be given to them– and to the true Israel of God.
B048C006V017	48	6	17	From this time onward let no one trouble me; for, as for me, I bear, branded on my body, the scars of Jesus as my Master.
B048C006V018	48	6	18	May the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with your spirits, brethren. Amen.
B049C001V001	49	1	1	Paul, an Apostle of Christ Jesus by the will of God: To God's people who are in Ephesus–believers in Christ Jesus.
B049C001V002	49	1	2	May grace and peace be granted to you from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B049C001V003	49	1	3	Blessed be the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, who has crowned us with every spiritual blessing in the heavenly realms in Christ;
B049C001V004	49	1	4	even as, in His love, He chose us as His own in Christ before the creation of the world, that we might be holy and without blemish in His presence.
B049C001V005	49	1	5	For He pre-destined us to be adopted by Himself as sons through Jesus Christ –such being His gracious will and pleasure–
B049C001V006	49	1	6	to the praise of the splendour of His grace with which He has enriched us in the beloved One.
B049C001V007	49	1	7	It is in Him, and through the shedding of His blood, that we have our deliverance –the forgiveness of our offences– so abundant was God's grace,
B049C001V008	49	1	8	the grace which He, the possessor of all wisdom and understanding, lavished upon us,
B049C001V009	49	1	9	when He made known to us the secret of His will. And this is in harmony with God's merciful purpose
B049C001V010	49	1	10	for the government of the world when the times are ripe for it–the purpose which He has cherished in His own mind of restoring the whole creation to find its one Head in Christ; yes, things in Heaven and things on earth, to find their one Head in Him.
B049C001V011	49	1	11	In Him we Jews have been made heirs, having been chosen beforehand in accordance with the intention of Him whose might carries out in everything the design of His own will,
B049C001V012	49	1	12	so that we should be devoted to the extolling of His glorious attributes–we who were the first to fix our hopes on Christ.
B049C001V013	49	1	13	And in Him you Gentiles also, after listening to the Message of the truth, the Good News of your salvation –having believed in Him– were sealed with the promised Holy Spirit;
B049C001V014	49	1	14	that Spirit being a pledge and foretaste of our inheritance, in anticipation of its full redemption–the inheritance which He has purchased to be specially His for the extolling of His glory.
B049C001V015	49	1	15	For this reason I too, having heard of the faith in the Lord Jesus which prevails among you, and of your love for all God's people,
B049C001V016	49	1	16	offer never ceasing thanks on your behalf while I make mention of you in my prayers.
B049C001V017	49	1	17	For I always beseech the God of our Lord Jesus Christ –the Father most glorious– to give you a spirit of wisdom and penetration through an intimate knowledge of Him,
B049C001V018	49	1	18	the eyes of your understanding being enlightened so that you may know what is the hope which His call to you inspires, what the wealth of the glory of His inheritance in God's people,
B049C001V019	49	1	19	and what the transcendent greatness of His power in us believers as seen in the working of His infinite might
B049C001V020	49	1	20	when He displayed it in Christ by raising Him from the dead and seating Him at His own right hand in the heavenly realms,
B049C001V021	49	1	21	high above all other government and authority and power and dominion, and every title of sovereignty used either in this Age or in the Age to come.
B049C001V022	49	1	22	God has put all things under His feet, and has appointed Him universal and supreme Head of the Church, which is His Body,
B049C001V023	49	1	23	the completeness of Him who everywhere fills the universe with Himself.
B049C002V001	49	2	1	To you Gentiles also, who were dead through your offences and sins,
B049C002V002	49	2	2	which were once habitual to you while you walked in the ways of this world and obeyed the Prince of the powers of the air, the spirits that are now at work in the hearts of the sons of disobedience–to you God has given Life.
B049C002V003	49	2	3	Among them all of us also formerly passed our lives, governed by the inclinations of our lower natures, indulging the cravings of those natures and of our own thoughts, and were in our original state deserving of anger like all others.
B049C002V004	49	2	4	But God, being rich in mercy, because of the intense love which He bestowed on us,
B049C002V005	49	2	5	caused us, dead though we were through our offences, to live with Christ –it is by grace that you have been saved–
B049C002V006	49	2	6	raised us with Him from the dead, and enthroned us with Him in the heavenly realms as being in Christ Jesus,
B049C002V007	49	2	7	in order that, by His goodness to us in Christ Jesus, He might display in the Ages to come the transcendent riches of His grace.
B049C002V008	49	2	8	For it is by grace that you have been saved through faith; and that not of yourselves. It is God's gift, and is not on the ground of merit–
B049C002V009	49	2	9	so that it may be impossible for any one to boast.
B049C002V010	49	2	10	For we are God's own handiwork, created in Christ Jesus for good works which He has pre-destined us to practise.
B049C002V011	49	2	11	Therefore, do not forget that formerly you were Gentiles as to your bodily condition. You were called the Uncircumcision by those who style themselves the Circumcised–their circumcision being one which the knife has effected.
B049C002V012	49	2	12	At that time you were living apart from Christ, estranged from the Commonwealth of Israel, with no share by birth in the Covenants which are based on the Promises, and you had no hope and no God, in all the world.
B049C002V013	49	2	13	But now in Christ Jesus you who once were so far away have been brought near through the death of Christ.
B049C002V014	49	2	14	For He is our peace–He who has made Jews and Gentiles one, and in His own human nature has broken down the hostile dividing wall,
B049C002V015	49	2	15	by setting aside the Law with its commandments, expressed, as they were, in definite decrees. His design was to unite the two sections of humanity in Himself so as to form one new man,
B049C002V016	49	2	16	thus effecting peace, and to reconcile Jews and Gentiles in one body to God, by means of His cross–slaying by it their mutual enmity.
B049C002V017	49	2	17	So He came and proclaimed good news of peace to you who were so far away, and peace to those who were near;
B049C002V018	49	2	18	because it is through Him that Jews and Gentiles alike have access through one Spirit to the Father.
B049C002V019	49	2	19	You are therefore no longer mere foreigners or persons excluded from civil rights. On the contrary you share citizenship with God's people and are members of His family.
B049C002V020	49	2	20	You are a building which has been reared on the foundation of the Apostles and Prophets, the cornerstone being Christ Jesus Himself,
B049C002V021	49	2	21	in union with whom the whole fabric, fitted and closely joined together, is growing so as to form a holy sanctuary in the Lord;
B049C002V022	49	2	22	in whom you also are being built up together to become a fixed abode for God through the Spirit.
B049C003V001	49	3	1	For this reason I Paul, the prisoner of Christ Jesus on behalf of you Gentiles–
B049C003V002	49	3	2	if, that is, you have heard of the work which God has graciously entrusted to me for your benefit,
B049C003V003	49	3	3	and that by a revelation the truth hitherto kept secret was made known to me as I have already briefly explained it to you.
B049C003V004	49	3	4	By means of that explanation, as you read it, you can judge of my insight into the truth of Christ
B049C003V005	49	3	5	which in earlier ages was not made known to the human race, as it has now been revealed to His holy Apostles and Prophets through the Spirit–
B049C003V006	49	3	6	I mean the truth that the Gentiles are joint heirs with us Jews, and that they form one body with us, and have the same interest as we have in the promise which has been made good in Christ Jesus through the Good News,
B049C003V007	49	3	7	in which I have been appointed to serve, in virtue of the work which God, in the exercise of His power within me, has graciously entrusted to me.
B049C003V008	49	3	8	To me who am less than the least of all God's people has this work been graciously entrusted–to proclaim to the Gentiles the Good News of the exhaustless wealth of Christ,
B049C003V009	49	3	9	and to show all men in a clear light what my stewardship is. It is the stewardship of the truth which from all the Ages lay concealed in the mind of God, the Creator of all things–
B049C003V010	49	3	10	concealed in order that the Church might now be used to display to the powers and authorities in the heavenly realms the innumerable aspects of God's wisdom.
B049C003V011	49	3	11	Such was the eternal purpose which He had formed in Christ Jesus our Lord,
B049C003V012	49	3	12	in whom we have this bold and confident access through our faith in Him.
B049C003V013	49	3	13	Therefore I entreat you not to lose heart in the midst of my sufferings on your behalf, for they bring you honour.
B049C003V014	49	3	14	For this reason, on bended knee I beseech the Father,
B049C003V015	49	3	15	from whom the whole family in Heaven and on earth derives its name,
B049C003V016	49	3	16	to grant you –in accordance with the wealth of His glorious perfections– to be strengthened by His Spirit with power penetrating to your inmost being.
B049C003V017	49	3	17	I pray that Christ may make His home in your hearts through your faith; so that having your roots deep and your foundations strong, in love, you may become mighty to grasp the idea,
B049C003V018	49	3	18	as it is grasped by all God's people, of the breadth and length, the height and depth–
B049C003V019	49	3	19	yes, to attain to a knowledge of the knowledge-surpassing love of Christ, so that you may be made complete in accordance with God's own standard of completeness.
B049C003V020	49	3	20	Now to Him who, in exercise of His power that is at work within us, is able to do infinitely beyond all our highest prayers or thoughts–
B049C003V021	49	3	21	to Him be the glory in the Church and in Christ Jesus to all generations, world without end! Amen.
B049C004V001	49	4	1	I, then, the prisoner for the Master's sake, entreat you to live and act as becomes those who have received the call that you have received–
B049C004V002	49	4	2	with all lowliness of mind and unselfishness, and with patience, bearing with one another lovingly, and earnestly striving to maintain,
B049C004V003	49	4	3	in the uniting bond of peace, the unity given by the Spirit.
B049C004V004	49	4	4	There is but one body and but one Spirit, as also when you were called you had one and the same hope held out to you.
B049C004V005	49	4	5	There is but one Lord, one faith, one baptism,
B049C004V006	49	4	6	and one God and Father of all, who rules over all, acts through all, and dwells in all.
B049C004V007	49	4	7	Yet to each of us individually grace was given, measured out with the munificence of Christ.
B049C004V008	49	4	8	For this reason Scripture says: 
B049C004V009	49	4	9	(Now this »re-ascended« –what does it mean but that He had first descended into the lower regions of the earth?
B049C004V010	49	4	10	He who descended is the same as He who ascended again far above all the Heavens in order to fill the universe.)
B049C004V011	49	4	11	And He Himself appointed some to be Apostles, some to be Prophets, some to be evangelists, some to be pastors and teachers,
B049C004V012	49	4	12	in order fully to equip His people for the work of serving –for the building up of Christ's body–
B049C004V013	49	4	13	till we all of us arrive at oneness in faith and in the knowledge of the Son of God, and at mature manhood and the stature of full-grown men in Christ.
B049C004V014	49	4	14	So we shall no longer be babes nor shall we resemble mariners tossed on the waves and carried about with every changing wind of doctrine according to men's cleverness and unscrupulous cunning, making use of every shifting device to mislead.
B049C004V015	49	4	15	But we shall lovingly hold to the truth, and shall in all respects grow up into union with Him who is our Head, even Christ.
B049C004V016	49	4	16	Dependent on Him, the whole body –its various parts closely fitting and firmly adhering to one another– grows by the aid of every contributory link, with power proportioned to the need of each individual part, so as to build itself up in a spirit of love.
B049C004V017	49	4	17	Therefore I warn you, and I implore you in the name of the Master, no longer to live as the Gentiles in their perverseness live,
B049C004V018	49	4	18	with darkened understandings, having by reason of the ignorance which is deep-seated in them and the insensibility of their moral nature, no share in the Life which God gives.
B049C004V019	49	4	19	Such men being past feeling have abandoned themselves to impurity, greedily indulging in every kind of profligacy.
B049C004V020	49	4	20	But these are not the lessons which you have learned from Christ;
B049C004V021	49	4	21	if at least you have heard His voice and in Him have been taught –and this is true Christian teaching–
B049C004V022	49	4	22	to put away, in regard to your former mode of life, your original evil nature which is doomed to perish as befits its misleading impulses,
B049C004V023	49	4	23	and to get yourselves renewed in the temper of your minds and clothe yourselves
B049C004V024	49	4	24	with that new and better self which has been created to resemble God in the righteousness and holiness which come from the truth.
B049C004V025	49	4	25	For this reason, laying aside falsehood, every one of you should speak the truth to his fellow man; for we are, as it were, parts of one another.
B049C004V026	49	4	26	If angry, beware of sinning. Let not your irritation last until the sun goes down;
B049C004V027	49	4	27	and do not leave room for the Devil.
B049C004V028	49	4	28	He who has been a thief must steal no more, but, instead of that, should work with his own hands in honest industry, so that he may have something of which he can give the needy a share.
B049C004V029	49	4	29	Let no unwholesome words ever pass your lips, but let all your words be good for benefiting others according to the need of the moment, so that they may be a means of blessing to the hearers.
B049C004V030	49	4	30	And beware of grieving the Holy Spirit of God, in whom you have been sealed in preparation for the day of Redemption.
B049C004V031	49	4	31	Let all bitterness and all passionate feeling, all anger and loud insulting language, be unknown among you–and also every kind of malice.
B049C004V032	49	4	32	On the contrary learn to be kind to one another, tender-hearted, forgiving one another, just as God in Christ has also forgiven you.
B049C005V001	49	5	1	Therefore be imitators of God, as His dear children.
B049C005V002	49	5	2	And live and act lovingly, as Christ also loved you and gave Himself up to death on our behalf as an offering and sacrifice to God, yielding a fragrant odor.
B049C005V003	49	5	3	But fornication and every kind of impurity, or covetousness, let them not even be mentioned among you, for they ought not to be named among God's people.
B049C005V004	49	5	4	Avoid shameful and foolish talk and low jesting –they are all alike discreditable– and in place of these give thanks.
B049C005V005	49	5	5	For be well assured that no fornicator or immoral person and no money-grubber –or in other words idol-worshipper– has any share awaiting him in the Kingdom of Christ and of God.
B049C005V006	49	5	6	Let no one deceive you with empty words, for it is on account of these very sins that God's anger is coming upon the disobedient.
B049C005V007	49	5	7	Therefore do not become sharers with them.
B049C005V008	49	5	8	There was a time when you were nothing but darkness. Now, as Christians, you are Light itself.
B049C005V009	49	5	9	Live and act as sons of Light –for the effect of the Light is seen in every kind of goodness, uprightness and truth–
B049C005V010	49	5	10	and learn in your own experiences what is fully pleasing to the Lord.
B049C005V011	49	5	11	Have nothing to do with the barren unprofitable deeds of darkness, but, instead of that, set your faces against them;
B049C005V012	49	5	12	for the things which are done by these people in secret it is disgraceful even to speak of.
B049C005V013	49	5	13	But everything can be tested by the light and thus be shown in its true colors; for whatever shines of itself is light.
B049C005V014	49	5	14	For this reason it is said, »Rise, sleeper; rise from among the dead, and Christ will shed light upon you.«
B049C005V015	49	5	15	Therefore be very careful how you live and act. Let it not be as unwise men, but as wise.
B049C005V016	49	5	16	Buy up your opportunities, for these are evil times.
B049C005V017	49	5	17	On this account do not prove yourselves wanting in sense, but try to understand what the Lord's will is.
B049C005V018	49	5	18	Do not over-indulge in wine –a thing in which excess is so easy–
B049C005V019	49	5	19	but drink deeply of God's Spirit. Speak to one another with psalms and hymns and spiritual songs. Sing and offer praise in your hearts to the Lord.
B049C005V020	49	5	20	Always and for everything let your thanks to God the Father be presented in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ;
B049C005V021	49	5	21	and submit to one another out of reverence for Christ.
B049C005V022	49	5	22	Married women, submit to your own husbands as if to the Lord;
B049C005V023	49	5	23	because a husband is the Head of his wife as Christ also is the Head of the Church, being indeed the Saviour of this His Body.
B049C005V024	49	5	24	And just as the Church submits to Christ, so also married women should be entirely submissive to their husbands.
B049C005V025	49	5	25	Married men, love your wives, as Christ also loved the Church and gave Himself up to death for her;
B049C005V026	49	5	26	in order to make her holy, cleansing her with the baptismal water by the word,
B049C005V027	49	5	27	that He might present the Church to Himself a glorious bride, without spot or wrinkle or any other defect, but to be holy and unblemished.
B049C005V028	49	5	28	So too married men ought to love their wives as much as they love themselves. He who loves his wife loves himself.
B049C005V029	49	5	29	For never yet has a man hated his own body. On the contrary he feeds and cherishes it, just as Christ feeds and cherishes the Church;
B049C005V030	49	5	30	because we are, as it were, parts of His Body.
B049C005V031	49	5	31	
        
B049C005V032	49	5	32	That is a great truth hitherto kept secret: I mean the truth concerning Christ and the Church.
B049C005V033	49	5	33	Yet I insist that among you also, each man is to love his own wife as much as he loves himself, and let a married woman see to it that she treats her husband with respect.
B049C006V001	49	6	1	Children, be obedient to your parents as a Christian duty, for it is a duty.
B049C006V002	49	6	2	
        
B049C006V003	49	6	3	
        
B049C006V004	49	6	4	And you, fathers, do not irritate your children, but bring them up tenderly with true Christian training and advice.
B049C006V005	49	6	5	Slaves, be obedient to your earthly masters, with respect and eager anxiety to please and with simplicity of motive as if you were obeying Christ.
B049C006V006	49	6	6	Let it not be in acts of eye-service as if you had but to please men, but as Christ's bondservants who are doing God's will from the heart.
B049C006V007	49	6	7	With right good will, be faithful to your duty as service rendered to the Lord and not to man.
B049C006V008	49	6	8	You well know that whatever right thing any one does, he will receive a requital for it from the Lord, whether he is a slave or a free man.
B049C006V009	49	6	9	And you masters, act towards your slaves on the same principles, and refrain from threats. For you know that in Heaven there is One who is your Master as well as theirs, and that merely earthly distinctions there are none with Him.
B049C006V010	49	6	10	In conclusion, strengthen yourselves in the Lord and in the power which His supreme might imparts.
B049C006V011	49	6	11	Put on the complete armour of God, so as to be able to stand firm against all the stratagems of the Devil.
B049C006V012	49	6	12	For ours is not a conflict with mere flesh and blood, but with the despotisms, the empires, the forces that control and govern this dark world–the spiritual hosts of evil arrayed against us in the heavenly warfare.
B049C006V013	49	6	13	Therefore put on the complete armour of God, so that you may be able to stand your ground on the day of battle, and, having fought to the end, to remain victors on the field.
B049C006V014	49	6	14	Stand therefore, first fastening round you the girdle of truth and putting on the breastplate of uprightness
B049C006V015	49	6	15	as well as the shoes of the Good News of peace– a firm foundation for your feet.
B049C006V016	49	6	16	And besides all these take the great shield of faith, on which you will be able to quench all the flaming darts of the Wicked one;
B049C006V017	49	6	17	and take the helmet of salvation, and the sword of the Spirit which is the word of God.
B049C006V018	49	6	18	Pray with unceasing prayer and entreaty on every fitting occasion in the Spirit, and be always on the alert to seize opportunities for doing so, with unwearied persistence and entreaty on behalf of all God's people,
B049C006V019	49	6	19	and ask on my behalf that words may be given to me so that, outspoken and fearless, I may make known the truths (hitherto kept secret) of the Good News–
B049C006V020	49	6	20	to spread which I am an ambassador in chains–so that when telling them I may speak out boldly as I ought.
B049C006V021	49	6	21	But in order that you also may know how I am doing, Tychicus our dearly-loved brother and faithful helper in the Lord's service will tell you everything.
B049C006V022	49	6	22	I have sent him to you for the very purpose–that you may know about us and that he may encourage you.
B049C006V023	49	6	23	Peace be to the brethren, and love combined with faith, from God the Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B049C006V024	49	6	24	May grace be with all who love our Lord Jesus Christ with perfect sincerity.
B050C001V001	50	1	1	Paul and Timothy, bondservants of Christ Jesus: To all God's people in Christ Jesus who are at Philippi, with the ministers of the Church and their assistants.
B050C001V002	50	1	2	May grace and peace be granted to you from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B050C001V003	50	1	3	I thank my God at my every remembrance of you–
B050C001V004	50	1	4	always when offering any prayer on behalf of you all, finding a joy in offering it.
B050C001V005	50	1	5	I thank my God, I say, for your cooperation in spreading the Good News, from the time it first came to you even until now.
B050C001V006	50	1	6	For of this I am confident, that He who has begun a good work within you will go on to perfect it in preparation for the day of Jesus Christ.
B050C001V007	50	1	7	And I am justified in having this confidence about you all, because, both during my imprisonment and when I stand up in defence of the Good News or to confirm its truth, I have you in my heart, sharers as you all are in the same grace as myself.
B050C001V008	50	1	8	For God is my witness how I yearn over all of you with tender Christian affection.
B050C001V009	50	1	9	And it is my prayer that your love may be more and more accompanied by clear knowledge and keen perception, for testing things that differ,
B050C001V010	50	1	10	so that you may be men of transparent character, and may be blameless, in preparation for the day of Christ,
B050C001V011	50	1	11	being filled with these fruits of righteousness which come through Jesus Christ– to the glory and praise of God.
B050C001V012	50	1	12	Now I would have you know, brethren, that what I have gone through has turned out to the furtherance of the Good News rather than otherwise.
B050C001V013	50	1	13	And thus it has become notorious among all the Imperial Guards, and everywhere, that it is for the sake of Christ that I am a prisoner;
B050C001V014	50	1	14	and the greater part of the brethren, made confident in the Lord through my imprisonment, now speak of God's Message without fear, more boldly than ever.
B050C001V015	50	1	15	Some indeed actually preach Christ out of envy and contentiousness but there are also others who do it from good will.
B050C001V016	50	1	16	These latter preach Him from love to me, knowing that I am here for the defence of the Good News;
B050C001V017	50	1	17	while the others proclaim Him from motives of rivalry, and insincerely, supposing that by this they are embittering my imprisonment.
B050C001V018	50	1	18	What does it matter, however? In any case Christ is preached–either perversely or in honest truth; and in that I rejoice, yes, and will rejoice.
B050C001V019	50	1	19	For I know that it will result in my salvation through your prayers and a bountiful supply of the Spirit of Jesus Christ,
B050C001V020	50	1	20	in fulfilment of my eager expectation and hope that I shall never have reason to feel ashamed, but that by my perfect freedom of speech Christ will be glorified in me, now as always, either by my life or by my death.
B050C001V021	50	1	21	For, with me, to live is Christ and to die is gain.
B050C001V022	50	1	22	But since to live means a longer stay on earth, that implies more labour for me–and not unsuccessful labour; and which I am to choose I cannot tell.
B050C001V023	50	1	23	I am in a dilemma, my earnest desire being to depart and be with Christ, for that is far, far better.
B050C001V024	50	1	24	But for your sakes it is more important that I should still remain in the body.
B050C001V025	50	1	25	I am convinced of this, and I know that I shall remain, and shall go on working side by side with you all, to promote your progress and joy in the faith;
B050C001V026	50	1	26	so that, as Christians, you may have additional reason for glorying about me as the result of my being with you again.
B050C001V027	50	1	27	Only let the lives you live be worthy of the Good News of the Christ, in order that, whether I come and see you or, being absent, only hear of you, I may know that you are standing fast in one spirit and with one mind, fighting shoulder to shoulder for the faith of the Good News.
B050C001V028	50	1	28	Never for a moment quail before your antagonists. Your fearlessness will be to them a sure token of impending destruction, but to you it will be a sure token of your salvation–a token coming from God.
B050C001V029	50	1	29	For you have had the privilege granted you on behalf of Christ–not only to believe in Him, but also to suffer on His behalf;
B050C001V030	50	1	30	maintaining, as you do, the same kind of conflict that you once saw in me and which you still hear that I am engaged in.
B050C002V001	50	2	1	If then I can appeal to you as the followers of Christ, if there is any persuasive power in love and any common sharing of the Spirit, or if you have any tender-heartedness and compassion, make my joy complete by being of one mind,
B050C002V002	50	2	2	united by mutual love, with harmony of feeling giving your minds to one and the same object.
B050C002V003	50	2	3	Do nothing in a spirit of factiousness or of vainglory, but, with true humility, let every one regard the rest as being of more account than himself;
B050C002V004	50	2	4	each fixing his attention, not simply on his own interests, but on those of others also.
B050C002V005	50	2	5	Let the same disposition be in you which was in Christ Jesus.
B050C002V006	50	2	6	Although from the beginning He had the nature of God He did not reckon His equality with God a treasure to be tightly grasped.
B050C002V007	50	2	7	Nay, He stripped Himself of His glory, and took on Him the nature of a bondservant by becoming a man like other men.
B050C002V008	50	2	8	And being recognized as truly human, He humbled Himself and even stooped to die; yes, to die on a cross.
B050C002V009	50	2	9	It is in consequence of this that God has also so highly exalted Him, and has conferred on Him the Name which is supreme above every other,
B050C002V010	50	2	10	in order that in the Name of JESUS every knee should bow, of beings in Heaven, of those on the earth, and of those in the underworld,
B050C002V011	50	2	11	and that every tongue should confess that JESUS CHRIST is LORD, to the glory of God the Father.
B050C002V012	50	2	12	Therefore, my dearly-loved friends, as I have always found you obedient, labour earnestly with fear and trembling –not merely as though I were present with you, but much more now since I am absent from you– labour earnestly, I say, to make sure of your own salvation.
B050C002V013	50	2	13	For it is God Himself whose power creates within you the desire to do His gracious will and also brings about the accomplishment of the desire.
B050C002V014	50	2	14	Be ever on your guard against a grudging and contentious spirit,
B050C002V015	50	2	15	so that you may always prove yourselves to be blameless and spotless–irreproachable children of God in the midst of a crooked and perverse generation, among whom you are seen as heavenly lights in the world,
B050C002V016	50	2	16	holding out to them a Message of Life. It will then be my glory on the day of Christ that I did not run my race in vain nor toil in vain.
B050C002V017	50	2	17	Nay, even if my life is to be poured as a libation upon the sacrificial offering of your faith, I rejoice, and I congratulate you all.
B050C002V018	50	2	18	And I bid you also share my gladness, and congratulate me.
B050C002V019	50	2	19	But, if the Lord permits it, I hope before long to send Timothy to you, that I, in turn, may be cheered by getting news of you.
B050C002V020	50	2	20	For I have no one likeminded with him, who will cherish a genuine care for you.
B050C002V021	50	2	21	Everybody concerns himself about his own interests, not about those of Jesus Christ.
B050C002V022	50	2	22	But you know Timothy's approved worth–how, like a child working with his father, he has served with me in furtherance of the Good News.
B050C002V023	50	2	23	So it is he that I hope to send as soon as ever I see how things go with me;
B050C002V024	50	2	24	but trusting, as I do, in the Lord, I believe that I shall myself also come to you before long.
B050C002V025	50	2	25	Yet I deem it important to send Epaphroditus to you now–he is my brother and comrade both in labour and in arms, and is your messenger who has ministered to my needs.
B050C002V026	50	2	26	I send him because he is longing to see you all and is distressed at your having heard of his illness.
B050C002V027	50	2	27	For it is true that he has been ill, and was apparently at the point of death; but God had pity on him, and not only on him, but also on me, to save me from having sorrow upon sorrow.
B050C002V028	50	2	28	I am therefore all the more eager to send him, in the hope that when you see him again you may be glad and I may have the less sorrow.
B050C002V029	50	2	29	Receive him therefore with heartfelt Christian joy, and hold in honour men like him;
B050C002V030	50	2	30	because it was for the sake of Christ's work that he came so near death, hazarding, as he did, his very life in endeavouring to make good any deficiency that there might be in your gifts to me.
B050C003V001	50	3	1	In conclusion, my brethren, be joyful in the Lord. For me to give you the same warnings as before is not irksome to me, while so far as you are concerned it is a safe precaution.
B050C003V002	50	3	2	Beware of `the dogs,' the bad workmen, the self-mutilators.
B050C003V003	50	3	3	For we are the true circumcision–we who render to God a spiritual worship and make our boast in Christ Jesus and have no confidence in outward ceremonies:
B050C003V004	50	3	4	although I myself might have some excuse for confidence in outward ceremonies. If any one else claims a right to trust in them, far more may I:
B050C003V005	50	3	5	circumcised, as I was, on the eighth day, a member of the race of Israel and of the tribe of Benjamin, a Hebrew sprung from Hebrews; as to the Law a Pharisee;
B050C003V006	50	3	6	as to zeal, a persecutor of the Church; as to the righteousness which comes through Law, blameless.
B050C003V007	50	3	7	Yet all that was gain to me–for Christ's sake I have reckoned it loss.
B050C003V008	50	3	8	Nay, I even reckon all things as pure loss because of the priceless privilege of knowing Christ Jesus my Lord. And for His sake I have suffered the loss of everything, and reckon it all as mere refuse, in order that I may win Christ and be found in union with Him,
B050C003V009	50	3	9	not having a righteousness of my own, derived from the Law, but that which arises from faith in Christ–the righteousness which comes from God through faith.
B050C003V010	50	3	10	I long to know Christ and the power which is in His resurrection, and to share in His sufferings and die even as He died;
B050C003V011	50	3	11	in the hope that I may attain to the resurrection from among the dead.
B050C003V012	50	3	12	I do not say that I have already won the race or have already reached perfection. But I am pressing on, striving to lay hold of the prize for which also Christ has laid hold of me.
B050C003V013	50	3	13	Brethren, I do not imagine that I have yet laid hold of it. But this one thing I do–forgetting everything which is past and stretching forward to what lies in front of me,
B050C003V014	50	3	14	with my eyes fixed on the goal I push on to secure the prize of God's heavenward call in Christ Jesus.
B050C003V015	50	3	15	Therefore let all of us who are mature believers cherish these thoughts; and if in any respect you think differently, that also God will make clear to you.
B050C003V016	50	3	16	But whatever be the point that we have already reached, let us persevere in the same course.
B050C003V017	50	3	17	Brethren, vie with one another in imitating me, and carefully observe those who follow the example which we have set you.
B050C003V018	50	3	18	For there are many whom I have often described to you, and I now even with tears describe them, as being enemies to the Cross of Christ.
B050C003V019	50	3	19	Their end is destruction, their bellies are their God, their glory is in their shame, and their minds are devoted to earthly things.
B050C003V020	50	3	20	We, however, are free citizens of Heaven, and we are waiting with longing expectation for the coming from Heaven of a Saviour, the Lord Jesus Christ,
B050C003V021	50	3	21	who, in the exercise of the power which He has even to subject all things to Himself, will transform this body of our humiliation until it resembles His own glorious body.
B050C004V001	50	4	1	Therefore, my brethren, dearly loved and longed for, my joy and crown, so stand firm in the Lord, my dearly-loved ones.
B050C004V002	50	4	2	I entreat Euodia, and I entreat Syntyche, to be of one mind, as sisters in Christ.
B050C004V003	50	4	3	Yes, and I beg you also, my faithful yoke-fellow, to help these women who have shared my toil in connection with the Good News, together with Clement and the rest of my fellow labourers, whose names are recorded in the Book of Life.
B050C004V004	50	4	4	Always be glad in the Lord: I will repeat it, be glad.
B050C004V005	50	4	5	Let your forbearing spirit be known to every one–the Lord is near.
B050C004V006	50	4	6	Do not be over-anxious about anything, but by prayer and earnest pleading, together with thanksgiving, let your request be unreservedly made known in the presence of God.
B050C004V007	50	4	7	And then the peace of God, which transcends all our powers of thought, will be a garrison to guard your hearts and minds in union with Christ Jesus.
B050C004V008	50	4	8	Finally, brethren, whatever is true, whatever wins respect, whatever is just, whatever is pure, whatever is lovable, whatever is of good repute –if there is any virtue or anything deemed worthy of praise– cherish the thought of these things.
B050C004V009	50	4	9	The doctrines and the line of conduct which I taught you –both what you heard and what you saw in me– hold fast to them; and God who gives peace will be with you.
B050C004V010	50	4	10	But I rejoice with a deep and holy joy that now at length you have revived your thoughtfulness for my welfare. Indeed you have always been thoughtful for me, although opportunity failed you.
B050C004V011	50	4	11	I do not refer to this through fear of privation, for (for my part) I have learned, whatever be my outward experiences, to be content.
B050C004V012	50	4	12	I know both how to live in humble circumstances and how to live amid abundance. I am fully initiated into all the mysteries both of fulness and of hunger, of abundance and of want.
B050C004V013	50	4	13	I have strength for anything through Him who gives me power.
B050C004V014	50	4	14	Yet I thank you for taking your share in my troubles.
B050C004V015	50	4	15	And you men and women of Philippi also know that at the first preaching of the Good News, when I had left Macedonia, no other Church except yourselves held communication with me about giving and receiving;
B050C004V016	50	4	16	because even in Thessalonica you sent several times to minister to my needs.
B050C004V017	50	4	17	Not that I crave for gifts from you, but I do want to see abundant fruit bring you honour.
B050C004V018	50	4	18	I have enough of everything –and more than enough. My wants are fully satisfied now that I have received from the hands of Epaphroditus the generous gifts which you sent me– they are a fragrant odor, an acceptable sacrifice, truly pleasing to God.
B050C004V019	50	4	19	But my God –so great is His wealth of glory in Christ Jesus– will fully supply every need of yours.
B050C004V020	50	4	20	And to our God and Father be the glory throughout the Ages of the Ages! Amen.
B050C004V021	50	4	21	My Christian greetings to every one of God's people. The brethren who are with me send their greetings.
B050C004V022	50	4	22	All God's people here greet you–especially the members of Caesar's household.
B050C004V023	50	4	23	May the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with your spirits.
B051C001V001	51	1	1	Paul, an Apostle of Christ Jesus by the will of God–and Timothy our brother:
B051C001V002	51	1	2	To the people of God and the believing brethren at Colossae who are in Christ. May grace and peace be granted to you from God our Father.
B051C001V003	51	1	3	We give thanks to God, the Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, constantly praying for you as we do,
B051C001V004	51	1	4	because we have heard of your faith in Christ Jesus and of the love which you cherish towards all God's people,
B051C001V005	51	1	5	on account of the hope treasured up for you in Heaven. Of this hope you have already heard in the Message of the truth of the Good News.
B051C001V006	51	1	6	For it has reached you, and remains with you, just as it has also spread through the whole world, yielding fruit there and increasing, as it has done among you from the day when first you heard it and came really to know the grace of God,
B051C001V007	51	1	7	as you learned it from Epaphras our dearly-loved fellow servant. He is to you a faithful minister of Christ in our stead,
B051C001V008	51	1	8	and moreover he has informed us of your love, which is inspired by the Spirit.
B051C001V009	51	1	9	For this reason we also, from the day we first received these tidings, have never ceased to pray for you and to entreat that you may be filled with a clear knowledge of His will accompanied by thorough wisdom and discernment in spiritual things;
B051C001V010	51	1	10	so that your lives may be worthy of the Lord and perfectly pleasing to Him, while you exhibit the results of right action of every sort and grow into a fuller knowledge of God.
B051C001V011	51	1	11	Since His power is so glorious, may you be strengthened with strength of every kind, and be prepared for cheerfully enduring all things with patience and long-suffering;
B051C001V012	51	1	12	and give thanks to the Father who has made us fit to receive our share of the inheritance of God's people in Light.
B051C001V013	51	1	13	It is God who has delivered us out of the dominion of darkness, and has transferred us into the Kingdom of His dearly-loved Son,
B051C001V014	51	1	14	in whom we have our redemption–the forgiveness of our sins.
B051C001V015	51	1	15	Christ is the visible representation of the invisible God, the Firstborn and Lord of all creation.
B051C001V016	51	1	16	For in Him was created the universe of things in heaven and on earth, things seen and things unseen, thrones, dominions, princedoms, powers–all were created, and exist through and for Him.
B051C001V017	51	1	17	And HE IS before all things and in and through Him the universe is a harmonious whole.
B051C001V018	51	1	18	Moreover He is the Head of His Body, the Church. He is the Beginning, the Firstborn from among the dead, in order that He Himself may in all things occupy the foremost place.
B051C001V019	51	1	19	For it was the Father's gracious will that the whole of the divine perfections should dwell in Him.
B051C001V020	51	1	20	And God purposed through Him to reconcile the universe to Himself, making peace through His blood, which was shed upon the Cross–to reconcile to Himself through Him, I say, things on earth and things in Heaven.
B051C001V021	51	1	21	And you, estranged as you once were and even hostile in your minds, amidst your evil deeds,
B051C001V022	51	1	22	He has now, in His human body, reconciled to God by His death, to bring you, holy and faultless and irreproachable, into His presence;
B051C001V023	51	1	23	if, indeed, you are still firmly holding to faith as your foundation, without ever shifting from your hope that rests on the Good News that you have heard, which has been proclaimed in the whole creation under Heaven, and in which I Paul have been appointed to serve.
B051C001V024	51	1	24	Now I can find joy amid my sufferings for you, and I fill up in my own person whatever is lacking in Christ's afflictions on behalf of His Body, the Church.
B051C001V025	51	1	25	I have been appointed to serve the Church in the position of responsibility entrusted to me by God for your benefit, so that I may fully deliver God's Message–
B051C001V026	51	1	26	the truth which has been kept secret from all ages and generations, but has now been revealed to His people,
B051C001V027	51	1	27	to whom it was His will to make known how vast a wealth of glory for the Gentile world is implied in this truth–the truth that `Christ is in you, the hope of glory.'
B051C001V028	51	1	28	Him we preach, admonishing every one and instructing every one, with all possible wisdom, so that we may bring every one into God's presence, made perfect through Christ.
B051C001V029	51	1	29	To this end, like an earnest wrestler, I exert all my strength in reliance upon the power of Him who is mightily at work within me.
B051C002V001	51	2	1	For I would have you know in how severe a struggle I am engaged on behalf of you and the brethren in Laodicea and of all who have not known me personally,
B051C002V002	51	2	2	in order that their hearts may be cheered, they themselves being welded together in love and enjoying all the advantages of a reasonable certainty, till at last they attain the full knowledge of God's truth, which is Christ Himself.
B051C002V003	51	2	3	In Him all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge are stored up, hidden from view.
B051C002V004	51	2	4	I say this to prevent your being misled by any one's plausible sophistry.
B051C002V005	51	2	5	For although, as you say, I am absent from you in body, yet in spirit I am present with you and am delighted to witness your good discipline and the solid front presented by your faith in Christ.
B051C002V006	51	2	6	As therefore you have received the Christ, even Jesus our Lord, live and act in vital union with Him;
B051C002V007	51	2	7	having the roots of your being firmly planted in Him, and continually building yourselves up in Him, and always being increasingly confirmed in the faith as you were taught it, and abounding in it with thanksgiving.
B051C002V008	51	2	8	Take care lest there be some one who leads you away as prisoners by means of his philosophy and idle fancies, following human traditions and the world's crude notions instead of following Christ.
B051C002V009	51	2	9	For it is in Christ that the fulness of God's nature dwells embodied, and in Him you are made complete,
B051C002V010	51	2	10	and He is the Lord of all princes and rulers.
B051C002V011	51	2	11	In Him also you were circumcised with a circumcision not performed by hand, when you threw off your sinful nature in true Christian circumcision;
B051C002V012	51	2	12	having been buried with Him in your baptism, in which you were also raised with Him through faith produced within you by God who raised Him from among the dead.
B051C002V013	51	2	13	And to you –dead as you once were in your transgressions and in the uncircumcision of your natural state– He has nevertheless given Life with Himself, having forgiven us all our transgressions.
B051C002V014	51	2	14	The bond, with its requirements, which was in force against us and was hostile to us, He cancelled, and cleared it out of the way, nailing it to His Cross.
B051C002V015	51	2	15	And the hostile princes and rulers He shook off from Himself, and boldly displayed them as His conquests, when by the Cross He triumphed over them.
B051C002V016	51	2	16	Therefore suffer no one to sit in judgement on you as to eating or drinking or with regard to a festival, a new moon or a sabbath.
B051C002V017	51	2	17	These were a shadow of things that were soon to come, but the substance belongs to Christ.
B051C002V018	51	2	18	Let no one defraud you of your prize, priding himself on his humility and on his worship of the angels, and taking his stand on the visions he has seen, and idly puffed up with his unspiritual thoughts.
B051C002V019	51	2	19	Such a one does not keep his hold upon Christ, the Head, from whom the Body, in all its parts nourished and strengthened by its points of contact and its connections, grows with a divine growth.
B051C002V020	51	2	20	If you have died with Christ and have escaped from the world's rudimentary notions, why, as though your life still belonged to the world, do you submit to such precepts as
B051C002V021	51	2	21	»Do not handle this;« »Do not taste that;«»Do not touch that other thing« –
B051C002V022	51	2	22	referring to things which are all intended to be used up and perish–in obedience to mere human injunctions and teachings?
B051C002V023	51	2	23	These rules have indeed an appearance of wisdom where self-imposed worship exists, and an affectation of humility and an ascetic severity. But not one of them is of any value in combating the indulgence of our lower natures.
B051C003V001	51	3	1	If however you have risen with Christ, seek the things that are above, where Christ is, enthroned at God's right hand.
B051C003V002	51	3	2	Give your minds to the things that are above, not to the things that are on the earth.
B051C003V003	51	3	3	For you have died, and your life is hidden with Christ in God.
B051C003V004	51	3	4	When Christ appears –He is our true Life– then you also will appear with Him in glory.
B051C003V005	51	3	5	Therefore put to death your earthward inclinations–fornication, impurity, sensual passion, unholy desire, and all greed, for that is a form of idolatry.
B051C003V006	51	3	6	It is on account of these very sins that God's anger is coming,
B051C003V007	51	3	7	and you also were once addicted to them, while you were living under their power.
B051C003V008	51	3	8	But now you must rid yourselves of every kind of sin –angry and passionate outbreaks, ill-will, evil speaking, foul-mouthed abuse– so that these may never soil your lips.
B051C003V009	51	3	9	Do not speak falsehoods to one another, for you have stripped off the old self with its doings,
B051C003V010	51	3	10	and have clothed yourselves with the new self which is being remoulded into full knowledge so as to become like Him who created it.
B051C003V011	51	3	11	In that new creation there is neither Greek nor Jew, circumcision nor uncircumcision, barbarian, Scythian, slave nor free man, but Christ is everything and is in all of us.
B051C003V012	51	3	12	Clothe yourselves therefore, as God's own people holy and dearly loved, with tender-heartedness, kindness, lowliness of mind, meekness, long-suffering;
B051C003V013	51	3	13	bearing with one another and readily forgiving each other, if any one has a grievance against another. Just as the Lord has forgiven you, you also must forgive.
B051C003V014	51	3	14	And over all these put on love, which is the perfect bond of union;
B051C003V015	51	3	15	and let the peace which Christ gives settle all questionings in your hearts, to which peace indeed you were called as belonging to His one Body; and be thankful.
B051C003V016	51	3	16	Let the teaching concerning Christ remain as a rich treasure in your hearts. In all wisdom teach and admonish one another with psalms, hymns, and spiritual songs, and sing with grace in your hearts to God.
B051C003V017	51	3	17	And whatever you do, in word or in deed, do everything in the name of the Lord Jesus, and let it be through Him that you give thanks to God the Father.
B051C003V018	51	3	18	Married women, be submissive to your husbands, as is fitting in the Lord.
B051C003V019	51	3	19	Married men, be affectionate to your wives, and do not treat them harshly.
B051C003V020	51	3	20	Children be obedient to your parents in everything; for that is right for Christians.
B051C003V021	51	3	21	Fathers, do not fret and harass your children, or you may make them sullen and morose.
B051C003V022	51	3	22	Slaves, be obedient in everything to your earthly masters; not in acts of eye service, as aiming only to please men, but with simplicity of purpose, because you fear the Lord.
B051C003V023	51	3	23	Whatever you are doing, let your hearts be in your work, as a thing done for the Lord and not for men.
B051C003V024	51	3	24	For you know that it is from the Lord you will receive the inheritance as your reward. Christ is the Master whose bondservants you are.
B051C003V025	51	3	25	The man who perpetrates a wrong will find the wrong repaid to him; and with God there are no merely earthly distinctions.
B051C004V001	51	4	1	Masters, deal justly and equitably with your slaves, knowing that you too have a Master in Heaven.
B051C004V002	51	4	2	Be earnest and unwearied in prayer, being on the alert in it and in your giving of thanks.
B051C004V003	51	4	3	And pray at the same time for us also, that God may open for us a door for preaching, for us to tell the truth concerning Christ for the sake of which I am even a prisoner.
B051C004V004	51	4	4	Then I shall proclaim it fully, as it is my duty to do.
B051C004V005	51	4	5	Behave wisely in relation to the outside world, buying up your opportunities.
B051C004V006	51	4	6	Let your language be always seasoned with the salt of grace, so that you may know how to give every man a fitting answer.
B051C004V007	51	4	7	Tychicus, our much-loved brother, a trusty assistant and fellow servant with us in the Lord's work, will give you every information about me.
B051C004V008	51	4	8	And for this very purpose I send him to you that you may know how we are faring; and that he may cheer your hearts.
B051C004V009	51	4	9	And with him I send our dear and trusty brother Onesimus, who is one of yourselves. They will inform you of everything here.
B051C004V010	51	4	10	Aristarchus my fellow prisoner sends greeting to you, and so does Barnabas's cousin Mark. You have received instructions as to him; if he comes to you, give him a welcome.
B051C004V011	51	4	11	Jesus, called Justus, also sends greeting. These three are Hebrew converts. They alone among such have worked loyally with me for the Kingdom of God–they are men who have been a comfort to me.
B051C004V012	51	4	12	Epaphras, who is one of yourselves, a bondservant of Jesus Christ, sends greetings to you, always wrestling on your behalf in his prayers, that you may stand firm–Christians of ripe character and of clear conviction as to everything which is God's will.
B051C004V013	51	4	13	For I can bear witness to the deep interest he takes in you and in the brethren at Laodicea and in those at Hierapolis.
B051C004V014	51	4	14	Luke, the dearly-loved physician, salutes you, and so does Demas.
B051C004V015	51	4	15	Christian greetings to the brethren at Laodicea, especially to Nymphas, and to the Church that meets at their house.
B051C004V016	51	4	16	And when this Letter has been read among you, let it be read also in the Church of the Laodiceans, and you in turn must read the one I am sending to Laodicea.
B051C004V017	51	4	17	And tell Archippus to discharge carefully the duties devolving upon him as a servant of the Lord.
B051C004V018	51	4	18	I Paul add with my own hand this final greeting. Be mindful of me in my imprisonment. Grace be with you.
B052C001V001	52	1	1	Paul, Silas, and Timothy: To the Church of the Thessalonians which is in God the Father and the Lord Jesus Christ. May grace and peace be granted to you.
B052C001V002	52	1	2	We continually give thanks to God because of you all, while we make mention of you in our prayers.
B052C001V003	52	1	3	For we never fail to remember your works of faith and labours of love and your persistent and unwavering hope in our Lord Jesus Christ in the presence of our God and Father;
B052C001V004	52	1	4	knowing as we do, brethren, that you are beloved by God and that He has chosen you.
B052C001V005	52	1	5	The Good News that we brought you did not come to you in words only, but also with power and with the Holy Spirit and with much certainty, for you know the sort of men we became among you, as examples for your sakes.
B052C001V006	52	1	6	And you followed the pattern set you by us and by the Master, after you had received the Message amid severe persecution, and yet with the joy which the Holy Spirit gives,
B052C001V007	52	1	7	so that you became a pattern to all the believers throughout Macedonia and Greece.
B052C001V008	52	1	8	For it was not only from you that the Master's Message sounded forth throughout Macedonia and Greece; but everywhere your faith in God has become known, so that it is unnecessary for us to say anything about it.
B052C001V009	52	1	9	For when others speak of us they report the reception we had from you, and how you turned from your idols to God, to be bondservants of the true and ever-living God,
B052C001V010	52	1	10	and to await the return from Heaven of His Son, whom He raised from among the dead–even Jesus, our Deliverer from God's coming anger.
B052C002V001	52	2	1	For you yourselves, brethren, know that our visit to you did not fail of its purpose.
B052C002V002	52	2	2	But, as you will remember, after we had already met with suffering and outrage at Philippi, we summoned up boldness, by the help of our God, to tell you God's Good News amid much opposition.
B052C002V003	52	2	3	For our preaching was not grounded on a delusion, nor prompted by mingled motives, nor was there fraud in it.
B052C002V004	52	2	4	But as God tested and approved us before entrusting us with His Good News, so in what we say we are seeking not to please men but to please God, who tests and approves our motives.
B052C002V005	52	2	5	For, as you are well aware, we have never used the language of flattery nor have we found pretexts for enriching ourselves–God is our witness;
B052C002V006	52	2	6	nor did we seek glory either from you or from any other mere men, although we might have stood on our dignity as Christ's Apostles.
B052C002V007	52	2	7	On the contrary, in our relations to you we showed ourselves as gentle as a mother is when she tenderly nurses her own children.
B052C002V008	52	2	8	Seeing that we were thus drawn affectionately towards you, it would have been a joy to us to have imparted to you not only God's Good News, but to have given our very lives also, because you had become very dear to us.
B052C002V009	52	2	9	For you remember, brethren, our labour and toil: how, working night and day so as not to become a burden to any one of you, we came and proclaimed among you God's Good News.
B052C002V010	52	2	10	You yourselves are witnesses –and God is witness– how holy and upright and blameless our dealings with you believers were.
B052C002V011	52	2	11	For you know that we acted towards every one of you as a father does towards his own children, encouraging and cheering you,
B052C002V012	52	2	12	and imploring you to live lives worthy of fellowship with God who is inviting you to share His own Kingship and glory.
B052C002V013	52	2	13	And for this further reason we render unceasing thanks to God, that when you received God's Message from our lips, it was as no mere message from men that you embraced it, but as –what it really is– God's Message, which also does its work in the hearts of you who believe.
B052C002V014	52	2	14	For you, brethren, followed the example of the Churches of God in Christ Jesus which are in Judaea; seeing that you endured the same ill-treatment at the hands of your countrymen, as they did at the hands of the Jews.
B052C002V015	52	2	15	Those Jewish persecutors killed both the Lord Jesus and the Prophets, and drove us out of their midst. They are displeasing to God, and are the enemies of all mankind;
B052C002V016	52	2	16	for they still try to prevent our preaching to the Gentiles so that they may find salvation. They thus continually fill up the measure of their own sins, and God's anger in its severest form has overtaken them.
B052C002V017	52	2	17	But we, brethren, having been for a short time separated from you in bodily presence, though not in heart, endeavoured all the more earnestly, with intense longing, to see you face to face.
B052C002V018	52	2	18	On this account we wanted to come to you –at least I Paul wanted again and again to do so– but Satan hindered us.
B052C002V019	52	2	19	For what is our hope or joy, or the crown of which we boast? Is it not you yourselves in the presence of our Lord Jesus at His Coming?
B052C002V020	52	2	20	Yes, you are our glory and our joy.
B052C003V001	52	3	1	So when we could endure it no longer, we decided to remain behind in Athens alone;
B052C003V002	52	3	2	and sent Timothy our brother and God's minister in the service of Christ's Good News, that he might help you spiritually and encourage you in your faith;
B052C003V003	52	3	3	that none of you might be unnerved by your present trials: for you yourselves know that they are our appointed lot.
B052C003V004	52	3	4	For even when we were with you, we forewarned you, saying, »We are soon to suffer affliction;« and this actually happened, as you well know.
B052C003V005	52	3	5	For this reason I also, when I could no longer endure the uncertainty, sent to know the condition of your faith, lest perchance the Tempter might have tempted you and our labour have been lost.
B052C003V006	52	3	6	But now that Timothy has recently come back to us from you, and has brought us the happy tidings of your faith and love, and has told us how you still cherish a constant and affectionate recollection of us, and are longing to see us as we also long to see you–
B052C003V007	52	3	7	for this reason in our distress and trouble we have been comforted about you, brethren, by your faith.
B052C003V008	52	3	8	For now life is for us life indeed, since you are standing fast in the Lord.
B052C003V009	52	3	9	For what thanksgiving on your behalf can we possibly offer to God in return for all the joy which fills our souls before our God for you,
B052C003V010	52	3	10	while night and day, with intense earnestness, we pray that we may see your faces, and may bring to perfection whatever may be still lacking in your faith?
B052C003V011	52	3	11	But may our God and Father Himself –and our Lord Jesus– guide us on our way to you;
B052C003V012	52	3	12	and as for you, may the Lord teach you to love one another and all men, with a growing and a glowing love, resembling our love for you.
B052C003V013	52	3	13	Thus He will build up your characters, so that you will be faultlessly holy in the presence of our God and Father at the Coming of our Lord Jesus with all His holy ones.
B052C004V001	52	4	1	Moreover, brethren, as you learnt from our lips the lives which you ought to live, and do live, so as to please God, we beg and exhort you in the name of the Lord Jesus to live them more and more truly.
B052C004V002	52	4	2	For you know the commands which we laid upon you by the authority of the Lord Jesus.
B052C004V003	52	4	3	For this is God's will–your purity of life, that you abstain from fornication;
B052C004V004	52	4	4	that each man among you shall know how to procure a wife who shall be his own in purity and honour;
B052C004V005	52	4	5	that you be not overmastered by lustful cravings, like the Gentiles who have no knowledge of God;
B052C004V006	52	4	6	and that in this matter there be no encroaching on the rights of a brother Christian and no overreaching him. For the Lord is an avenger in all such cases, as we have already taught you and solemnly warned you.
B052C004V007	52	4	7	God has not called us to an unclean life, but to one of purity.
B052C004V008	52	4	8	Therefore a defiant spirit in such a case provokes not man but God, who puts His Holy Spirit into your hearts.
B052C004V009	52	4	9	But on the subject of love for the brotherhood it is unnecessary for me to write to you, for you yourselves have been taught by God to love one another;
B052C004V010	52	4	10	and indeed you do love all the brethren throughout Macedonia. And we exhort you to do so more and more,
B052C004V011	52	4	11	and to vie with one another in eagerness for peace, every one minding his own business and working with his hands, as we ordered you to do:
B052C004V012	52	4	12	so as to live worthy lives in relation to outsiders, and not be a burden to any one.
B052C004V013	52	4	13	Now, concerning those who from time to time pass away, we would not have you to be ignorant, brethren, lest you should mourn as others do who have no hope.
B052C004V014	52	4	14	For if we believe that Jesus has died and risen again, we also believe that, through Jesus, God will bring with Him those who shall have passed away.
B052C004V015	52	4	15	For this we declare to you on the Lord's own authority–that we who are alive and continue on earth until the Coming of the Lord, shall certainly not forestall those who shall have previously passed away.
B052C004V016	52	4	16	For the Lord Himself will come down from Heaven with a loud word of command, and with an archangel's voice and the trumpet of God, and the dead in Christ will rise first.
B052C004V017	52	4	17	Afterwards we who are alive and are still on earth will be caught up in their company amid clouds to meet the Lord in the air.
B052C004V018	52	4	18	And so we shall be with the Lord for ever. Therefore encourage one another with these words.
B052C005V001	52	5	1	But as to times and dates it is unnecessary that anything be written to you.
B052C005V002	52	5	2	For you yourselves know perfectly well that the day of the Lord comes like a thief in the night.
B052C005V003	52	5	3	While they are saying »Peace and safety!« then in a moment destruction falls upon them, like birth-pains on a woman who is with child; and escape there is none.
B052C005V004	52	5	4	But you, brethren, are not in darkness, that daylight should surprise you like a thief;
B052C005V005	52	5	5	for all of you are sons of Light and sons of the day. We belong neither to the night nor to darkness.
B052C005V006	52	5	6	So then let us not sleep, like the rest of the world, but let us keep awake and be sober.
B052C005V007	52	5	7	For those who sleep, sleep at night, and those who drink freely, drink at night.
B052C005V008	52	5	8	But let us, belonging –as we do– to the day, be sober, putting on the breastplate of faith and love, and for a helmet the hope of salvation.
B052C005V009	52	5	9	For God has not pre-destined us to meet His anger, but to obtain salvation through our Lord Jesus Christ;
B052C005V010	52	5	10	who died on our behalf, so that whether we are awake or are sleeping we may share His Life.
B052C005V011	52	5	11	Therefore encourage one another, and let each one help to strengthen his friend, as in fact you do.
B052C005V012	52	5	12	Now we beg you, brethren, to show respect for those who labour among you and are your leaders in Christian work, and are your advisers;
B052C005V013	52	5	13	and to esteem them very highly in love for their work's sake. Be at peace among yourselves.
B052C005V014	52	5	14	And we exhort you, brethren, admonish the unruly, comfort the timid, sustain the weak, and be patient towards all.
B052C005V015	52	5	15	See to it that no one ever repays another with evil for evil; but always seek opportunities of doing good both to one another and to all the world.
B052C005V016	52	5	16	Be always joyful.
B052C005V017	52	5	17	Be unceasing in prayer.
B052C005V018	52	5	18	In every circumstance of life be thankful; for this is God's will in Christ Jesus respecting you.
B052C005V019	52	5	19	Do not quench the Spirit.
B052C005V020	52	5	20	Do not think meanly of utterances of prophecy;
B052C005V021	52	5	21	but test all such, and retain hold of the good.
B052C005V022	52	5	22	Hold yourselves aloof from every form of evil.
B052C005V023	52	5	23	And may God Himself who gives peace, make you entirely holy; and may your spirits, souls and bodies be preserved complete and be found blameless at the Coming of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B052C005V024	52	5	24	Faithful is He who calls you, and He will also perfect His work.
B052C005V025	52	5	25	Brethren, pray for us.
B052C005V026	52	5	26	Greet all the brethren with a holy kiss.
B052C005V027	52	5	27	I solemnly charge you in the Lord's name to have this Letter read to all the brethren.
B052C005V028	52	5	28	May the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you.
B053C001V001	53	1	1	Paul, Silas, and Timothy: To the Church of the Thessalonians which is in God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B053C001V002	53	1	2	May grace and peace be granted to you from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B053C001V003	53	1	3	Unceasing thanks are due from us to God on your behalf, brethren. They are appropriate because your faith is growing greatly, and the love of every one of you for all the others goes on increasing.
B053C001V004	53	1	4	It so increases that we ourselves make honourable mention of you among the Churches of God because of your patience and faith amid all your persecutions and amid the afflictions which you are enduring.
B053C001V005	53	1	5	For these are a plain token of God's righteous judgement, which has in view your being deemed worthy of admission to God's Kingdom, for the sake of which, indeed, you are sufferers.
B053C001V006	53	1	6	A plain token of God's righteous judgement, I say, since it is a righteous thing for Him to requite with affliction those who are now afflicting you;
B053C001V007	53	1	7	and to requite with rest you who are suffering affliction now–rest with us at the re-appearing of the Lord Jesus from Heaven, attended by His mighty angels.
B053C001V008	53	1	8	He will come in flames of fire to take vengeance on those who have no knowledge of God, and do not obey the Good News as to Jesus, our Lord.
B053C001V009	53	1	9	They will pay the penalty of eternal destruction, being banished from the presence of the Lord and from His glorious majesty,
B053C001V010	53	1	10	when He comes on that day to be glorified in His people and to be wondered at among all who have believed, including you–because you believed the testimony which we brought for your acceptance.
B053C001V011	53	1	11	It is with this view also that we continually pray to our God for you, asking that He will count you worthy of His call, and by His mighty power fully gratify your every desire for what is truly good and make your work of faith complete;
B053C001V012	53	1	12	in order that the name of our Lord Jesus may be glorified in you, and that you may be glorified in Him–so wonderful is the grace of our God and of the Lord Jesus Christ!
B053C002V001	53	2	1	But with respect to the Coming of our Lord Jesus Christ and our being gathered to meet Him, we entreat you, brethren,
B053C002V002	53	2	2	not readily to become unsettled in mind or troubled –either by any pretended spiritual revelation or by any message or letter claiming to have been sent by us– through fancying that the day of the Lord is now here.
B053C002V003	53	2	3	Let no one in any way deceive you, for that day cannot come without the coming of the apostasy first, and the appearing of the man of sin, the son of perdition, who sets himself against,
B053C002V004	53	2	4	and exalts himself above, every so-called `god' or object of worship, and goes the length of taking his seat in the very temple of God, giving it out that he himself is God.
B053C002V005	53	2	5	Do you not remember that while I was still with you I used to tell you all this?
B053C002V006	53	2	6	And now you know what restrains him, in order that his true character may be revealed at his appointed time.
B053C002V007	53	2	7	For lawlessness is already at work in secret; but only until the man who is now exercising a restraining influence is removed,
B053C002V008	53	2	8	and then the Lawless one will be revealed, whom the Lord Jesus will sweep away with the tempest of His anger, and utterly overwhelm by the awful splendour of His Coming.
B053C002V009	53	2	9	The appearing of the Lawless one will be attended by various miracles and tokens and delusive marvels –for so Satan works–
B053C002V010	53	2	10	and by every kind of wicked deception for those who are on the way to perdition because they did not welcome into their hearts the love of the truth, so that they might be saved.
B053C002V011	53	2	11	And for this reason God sends them a misleading influence that they may believe the lie;
B053C002V012	53	2	12	in order that all may come under judgement who have refused to believe the truth and have taken pleasure in unrighteousness.
B053C002V013	53	2	13	And from us thanks are always due to God on your behalf –brethren whom the Lord loves– because God from the beginning has chosen you for salvation through the Spirit's sanctifying influence and your belief in the truth.
B053C002V014	53	2	14	To this blessing God has called you by our Good News, so that you may have a share in the glory of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B053C002V015	53	2	15	So then, brethren, stand your ground, and hold fast to the teachings which you have received from us, whether by word of mouth or by letter.
B053C002V016	53	2	16	And may our Lord Jesus Christ Himself –and God our Father who has loved us and has given us in His grace eternal consolation and a bright hope–
B053C002V017	53	2	17	comfort your hearts and make you stedfast in every good work and word.
B053C003V001	53	3	1	Finally, brethren, pray for us, asking that the Lord's Message may be spread rapidly and its glory be displayed, as it was displayed among you;
B053C003V002	53	3	2	and that we may be delivered from wrong-headed and wicked men; for it is not everybody who has faith.
B053C003V003	53	3	3	But the Lord is faithful, and He will make you stedfast and will guard you from the Evil one.
B053C003V004	53	3	4	And we have confidence in the Lord in regard to you that you are doing, and will do, what we command.
B053C003V005	53	3	5	And may the Lord guide your hearts into the love of God and into the patience of Christ.
B053C003V006	53	3	6	But, by the authority of the Lord, we command you, brethren, to stand aloof from every brother whose life is disorderly and not in accordance with the teaching which all received from us.
B053C003V007	53	3	7	For you yourselves know that it is your duty to follow our example. There was no disorder in our lives among you,
B053C003V008	53	3	8	nor did we eat any one's bread without paying for it, but we laboured and toiled, working hard night and day in order not to be a burden to any of you.
B053C003V009	53	3	9	This was not because we had not a claim upon you, but it arose from a desire to set you an example–for you to imitate us.
B053C003V010	53	3	10	For even when we were with you, we laid down this rule for you:»If a man does not choose to work, neither shall he eat.«
B053C003V011	53	3	11	For we hear that there are some of you who live disorderly lives and are mere idle busybodies.
B053C003V012	53	3	12	To persons of that sort our injunction –and our command by the authority of the Lord Jesus Christ– is that they are to work quietly and eat their own honestly-earned bread.
B053C003V013	53	3	13	But you, brethren, must not grow weary in the path of duty;
B053C003V014	53	3	14	and if any one refuses to obey these our written instructions, mark that man and hold no communication with him–so that he may be made to feel ashamed.
B053C003V015	53	3	15	And yet do not regard him as an enemy, but caution him as a brother.
B053C003V016	53	3	16	And may the Lord of peace Himself continually grant you peace in every sense. The Lord be with you all.
B053C003V017	53	3	17	I Paul add the greeting with my own hand, which is the credential in every letter of mine.
B053C003V018	53	3	18	This is my handwriting. May the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you all.
B054C001V001	54	1	1	Paul, an Apostle of Christ Jesus by the will of God our Saviour and Christ Jesus our hope:
B054C001V002	54	1	2	To Timothy, my own true son in the faith. May grace, mercy and peace be granted to you from God the Father and Christ Jesus our Lord.
B054C001V003	54	1	3	When I was on my journey to Macedonia I begged you to remain on in Ephesus that you might remonstrate with certain persons because of their erroneous teaching
B054C001V004	54	1	4	and the attention they bestow on mere fables and endless pedigrees, such as lead to controversy rather than to a true stewardship for God, which only exists where there is faith. And I make the same request now.
B054C001V005	54	1	5	But the end sought to be secured by exhortation is the love which springs from a pure heart, a clear conscience and a sincere faith.
B054C001V006	54	1	6	From these some have drifted away, and have wandered into empty words.
B054C001V007	54	1	7	They are ambitious to be teachers of the Law, although they do not understand either their own words or what the things are about which they make such confident assertions.
B054C001V008	54	1	8	Now we know that the Law is good, if a man uses it in the way it should be used,
B054C001V009	54	1	9	and remembers that a law is not enacted to control a righteous man, but for the lawless and rebellious, the irreligious and sinful, the godless and profane–for those who strike their fathers or their mothers, for murderers,
B054C001V010	54	1	10	fornicators, sodomites, slave-dealers, liars and false witnesses; and for whatever else is opposed to wholesome teaching
B054C001V011	54	1	11	and is not in accordance with the Good News of the blessed God with which I have been entrusted.
B054C001V012	54	1	12	I am thankful to Him who made me strong –even Christ Jesus our Lord– because He has judged me to be faithful and has put me into His service,
B054C001V013	54	1	13	though I was previously a blasphemer and a persecutor and had been insolent in outrage. Yet mercy was shown me, because I had acted ignorantly, not having as yet believed;
B054C001V014	54	1	14	and the grace of our Lord came to me in overflowing fulness, conferring faith on me and the love which is in Christ Jesus.
B054C001V015	54	1	15	Faithful is the saying, and deserving of universal acceptance, that Christ Jesus came into the world to save sinners; among whom I stand foremost.
B054C001V016	54	1	16	But mercy was shown me in order that in me as the foremost of sinners Christ Jesus might display the fulness of His long-suffering patience as an example to encourage those who would afterwards be resting their faith on Him with a view to the Life of the Ages.
B054C001V017	54	1	17	Now to the immortal and invisible King of the Ages, who alone is God, be honour and glory to the Ages of the Ages! Amen.
B054C001V018	54	1	18	This is the charge which I entrust to you, my son Timothy, in accordance with the inspired instructions concerning you which were given me long ago, that being equipped with them as your armour you may be continually fighting the good fight,
B054C001V019	54	1	19	holding fast to faith and a clear conscience, which some have cast aside and have made shipwreck of their faith.
B054C001V020	54	1	20	Among these are Hymenaeus and Alexander, whom I have delivered to Satan so that they may be taught not to blaspheme.
B054C002V001	54	2	1	I exhort then, first of all, that supplications, prayers, intercessions and thanksgivings be offered on behalf of all men;
B054C002V002	54	2	2	including kings and all who are in high station, in order that we may live peaceful and tranquil lives with all godliness and gravity.
B054C002V003	54	2	3	This is right, and is pleasing in the sight of God our Saviour,
B054C002V004	54	2	4	who is willing for all mankind to be saved and come to a full knowledge of the truth.
B054C002V005	54	2	5	For there is but one God and but one Mediator between God and men–Christ Jesus, Himself man;
B054C002V006	54	2	6	who gave Himself as the redemption price for all–a fact testified to at its own appointed time,
B054C002V007	54	2	7	and of which I have been appointed a herald and an Apostle (I am speaking the truth: it is not a fiction), a teacher of the Gentiles in faith and truth.
B054C002V008	54	2	8	So then I would have the men everywhere pray, lifting to God holy hands which are unstained with anger or strife;
B054C002V009	54	2	9	and I would have the women dress becomingly, with modesty and self-control, not with plaited hair or gold or pearls or costly clothes,
B054C002V010	54	2	10	but –as befits women making a claim to godliness– with the ornament of good works.
B054C002V011	54	2	11	A woman should quietly learn from others with entire submissiveness.
B054C002V012	54	2	12	I do not permit a woman to teach, nor have authority over a man, but she must remain silent.
B054C002V013	54	2	13	For Adam was formed first, and then Eve;
B054C002V014	54	2	14	and Adam was not deceived, but his wife was thoroughly deceived, and so became involved in transgression.
B054C002V015	54	2	15	Yet a woman will be brought safely through childbirth if she and her husband continue to live in faith and love and growing holiness, with habitual self-restraint.
B054C003V001	54	3	1	Faithful is the saying, »If any one is eager to have the oversight of a Church, he desires a noble work.«
B054C003V002	54	3	2	A minister then must be a man of irreproachable character, true to his one wife, temperate, sober-minded, well-behaved, hospitable to strangers, and with a gift for teaching;
B054C003V003	54	3	3	not a hard drinker nor given to blows; not selfish or quarrelsome or covetous;
B054C003V004	54	3	4	but ruling his own household wisely and well, with children kept under control with true dignity.
B054C003V005	54	3	5	(If a man does not know how to rule his own household, how shall he have the Church of God given into his care?)
B054C003V006	54	3	6	He ought not to be a new convert, for fear he should be blinded with pride and come under the same condemnation as the Devil.
B054C003V007	54	3	7	It is needful also that he bear a good character with people outside the Church, lest he fall into reproach or a snare of the Devil.
B054C003V008	54	3	8	Deacons, in the same way, must be men of serious demeanour, not double-tongued, nor addicted to much wine, nor greedy of base gain,
B054C003V009	54	3	9	but holding the secret truths of the faith with a clear conscience.
B054C003V010	54	3	10	And they must also be well-tried men, and when found to be of unblemished character then let them serve as deacons.
B054C003V011	54	3	11	Deaconesses, in the same way, must be sober-minded women, not slanderers, but in every way temperate and trustworthy.
B054C003V012	54	3	12	A deacon must be true to his one wife, and rule his children and his own household wisely and well.
B054C003V013	54	3	13	For those who have filled the deacon's office wisely and well, are already gaining for themselves an honourable standing, and are acquiring great freedom of speech in proclaiming the faith which rests on Christ Jesus.
B054C003V014	54	3	14	All this I write to you, though I am hoping before long to come to see you.
B054C003V015	54	3	15	But, for fear I may be hindered, I now write, so that you may have rules to guide you in dealing with God's household. For this is what the Church of the ever-living God is, and it is the pillar and foundation-stone of the truth.
B054C003V016	54	3	16	And, beyond controversy, great is the mystery of our religion– that Christ appeared in human form, and His claims justified by the Spirit, was seen by angels and proclaimed among Gentile nations, was believed on in the world, and received up again into glory.
B054C004V001	54	4	1	Now the Spirit expressly declares that in later times some will fall away from the faith, giving heed to deceiving spirits and the teachings of demons;
B054C004V002	54	4	2	through the hypocrisy of men who teach falsely and have their own consciences seared as with a hot iron;
B054C004V003	54	4	3	forbidding people to marry, and insisting on abstinence from foods which God has created to be partaken of, with thankfulness, by those who believe and have a clear knowledge of the truth.
B054C004V004	54	4	4	For everything that God has created is good, and nothing is to be cast aside, if only it is received with thanksgiving.
B054C004V005	54	4	5	For it is made holy by the word of God and by prayer.
B054C004V006	54	4	6	If you warn the brethren of these dangers you will be a good and faithful servant of Christ Jesus, inwardly feeding on the lessons of the faith and of the sound teaching of which you have been, and are, so close a follower.
B054C004V007	54	4	7	But worldly stories, fit only for credulous old women, have nothing to do with.
B054C004V008	54	4	8	Train yourself in godliness. Exercise for the body is not useless, but godliness is useful in every respect, possessing, as it does, the promise of Life now and of the Life which is soon coming.
B054C004V009	54	4	9	Faithful is this saying and deserving of universal acceptance:
B054C004V010	54	4	10	and here is the motive of our toiling and wrestling, because we have our hopes fixed on the ever-living God, who is the Saviour of all mankind, and especially of believers.
B054C004V011	54	4	11	Command this and teach this.
B054C004V012	54	4	12	Let no one think slightingly of you because you are a young man; but in speech, conduct, love, faith and purity, be an example for your fellow Christians to imitate.
B054C004V013	54	4	13	Till I come, bestow your attention on reading, exhortation and teaching.
B054C004V014	54	4	14	Do not be careless about the gifts with which you are endowed, which were conferred on you through a divine revelation when the hands of the elders were placed upon you.
B054C004V015	54	4	15	Habitually practise these duties, and be absorbed in them; so that your growing proficiency in them may be evident to all.
B054C004V016	54	4	16	Be on your guard as to yourself and your teaching. Persevere in these things; for by doing this you will make certain your own salvation and that of your hearers.
B054C005V001	54	5	1	Never administer a sharp reprimand to a man older than yourself; but entreat him as if he were your father, and the younger men as brothers;
B054C005V002	54	5	2	the elder women too as mothers, and the younger women as sisters, with perfect modesty.
B054C005V003	54	5	3	Honour widows who are really in need.
B054C005V004	54	5	4	But if a widow has children or grandchildren, let these learn first to show piety towards their own homes and to prove their gratitude to their parents; for this is well pleasing in the sight of God.
B054C005V005	54	5	5	A widow who is really in need, friendless and desolate, has her hopes fixed on God, and continues at her supplications and prayers, night and day;
B054C005V006	54	5	6	but a pleasure-loving widow is dead even while still alive.
B054C005V007	54	5	7	Press these facts upon them, so that they may live lives free from reproach.
B054C005V008	54	5	8	But if a man makes no provision for those dependent on him, and especially for his own family, he has disowned the faith and is behaving worse than an unbeliever.
B054C005V009	54	5	9	No widow is to be put on the roll who is under sixty years of age.
B054C005V010	54	5	10	She must have been true to her one husband, and well reported of for good deeds, as having brought up children, received strangers hospitably, washed the feet of God's people, given relief to the distressed, and devoted herself to good works of every kind.
B054C005V011	54	5	11	But the younger widows you must not enrol; for as soon as they begin to chafe against the yoke of Christ, they want to marry,
B054C005V012	54	5	12	and they incur disapproval for having broken their original vow.
B054C005V013	54	5	13	And at the same time they also learn to be idle as they go round from house to house; and they are not only idle, but are gossips also and busybodies, speaking of things that ought not to be spoken of.
B054C005V014	54	5	14	I would therefore have the younger women marry, bear children, rule in domestic matters, and furnish the Adversary with no excuse for slander.
B054C005V015	54	5	15	For already some of them have gone astray, following Satan.
B054C005V016	54	5	16	If a believing woman has widows dependent on her, she should relieve their wants, and save the Church from being burdened–so that the Church may relieve the widows who are really in need.
B054C005V017	54	5	17	Let the Elders who perform their duties wisely and well be held worthy of double honour, especially those who labour in preaching and teaching.
B054C005V018	54	5	18	For the Scripture says, 
B054C005V019	54	5	19	Never entertain an accusation against an Elder except on the evidence of two of three witnesses.
B054C005V020	54	5	20	Those who persist in sin reprove in the presence of all, so that it may also be a warning to the rest.
B054C005V021	54	5	21	I solemnly call upon you, in the presence of God and of Christ Jesus and of the elect angels, to carry out these instructions of mine without prejudice, and to do nothing from partiality.
B054C005V022	54	5	22	Do not ordain any one hastily; and do not be a partaker in the sins of others; keep 
B054C005V023	54	5	23	(No longer be a water-drinker; but take a little wine for the sake of your digestion and your frequent ailments.)
B054C005V024	54	5	24	The sins of some men are evident to the world, leading the way to your estimate of their characters, but the sins of others lag behind.
B054C005V025	54	5	25	So also the right actions of some are evident to the world, and those that are not cannot remain for ever out of sight.
B054C006V001	54	6	1	Let all who are under the yoke of slavery hold their own masters to be deserving of honour, so that the name of God and the Christian teaching may not be spoken against.
B054C006V002	54	6	2	And those who have believing masters should not be wanting in respect towards them because they are their brethren, but should serve them all the more willingly because those who profit by the faithful service rendered are believers and are friends.
B054C006V003	54	6	3	So teach and exhort. If any one is a teacher of any other kind of doctrine, and refuses assent to wholesome instructions –those of our Lord Jesus Christ– and the teaching that harmonizes with true godliness,
B054C006V004	54	6	4	he is puffed up with pride and has no true knowledge, but is crazy over discussions and controversies about words which give rise to envy, quarrelling, revilings, ill-natured suspicions,
B054C006V005	54	6	5	and persistent wranglings on the part of people whose intellects are disordered and they themselves blinded to all knowledge of the truth; who imagine that godliness means gain.
B054C006V006	54	6	6	And godliness 
B054C006V007	54	6	7	for we brought nothing into the world, nor can we carry anything out of it;
B054C006V008	54	6	8	and if we have food and clothing, with these we will be satisfied.
B054C006V009	54	6	9	But people who are determined to be rich fall into temptation and a snare, and into many unwise and pernicious ways which sink mankind in destruction and ruin.
B054C006V010	54	6	10	For from love of money all sorts of evils arise; and some have so hankered after money as to be led astray from the faith and be pierced through with countless sorrows.
B054C006V011	54	6	11	But you, O man of God, must flee from these things; and strive for uprightness, godliness, good faith, love, fortitude, and a forgiving temper.
B054C006V012	54	6	12	Exert all your strength in the honourable struggle for the faith; lay hold of the Life of the Ages, to which you were called, when you made your noble profession of faith before many witnesses.
B054C006V013	54	6	13	I charge you –as in the presence of God who gives life to all creatures, and of Christ Jesus who at the bar of Pontius Pilate made a noble profession of faith–
B054C006V014	54	6	14	that you keep God's commandments stainlessly and without reproach till the Appearing of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B054C006V015	54	6	15	For, as its appointed time, this will be brought about by the blessed and only Sovereign, the King of kings and Lord of lords,
B054C006V016	54	6	16	who alone possesses immortality, dwelling in unapproachable light, and whom no man has seen or can see. To Him be eternal honour and power! Amen.
B054C006V017	54	6	17	Impress on those who are rich in the present age that they must not be haughty nor set their hopes on riches –that unstable foundation– but on God who provides us richly with all things for our enjoyment.
B054C006V018	54	6	18	They must be beneficent, rich in noble deeds, open-handed and liberal;
B054C006V019	54	6	19	storing up for themselves that which shall be a solid foundation for the future, that they may lay hold of the Life which is life indeed.
B054C006V020	54	6	20	O Timothy, guard the truths entrusted to you, shunning irreligious and frivolous talk, and controversy with what is falsely called `knowledge';
B054C006V021	54	6	21	of which some have spoken boastfully in connexion with the true faith, and have erred. Grace be with you all.
B055C001V001	55	1	1	Paul, an Apostle of Christ Jesus, by the will of God, for proclaiming the promise of the Life which is in Christ Jesus:
B055C001V002	55	1	2	To Timothy my dearly-loved child. May grace, mercy and peace be granted to you from God the Father and Christ Jesus our Lord.
B055C001V003	55	1	3	I thank God, whom I serve with a pure conscience –as my forefathers did– that night and day I unceasingly remember you in my prayers,
B055C001V004	55	1	4	being always mindful of your tears, and longing to see you that I may be filled with joy.
B055C001V005	55	1	5	For I recall the sincere faith which is in your heart–a faith which dwelt first in your grandmother Lois and then in your mother Eunice, and, I am fully convinced, now dwells in you also.
B055C001V006	55	1	6	For this reason let me remind you to rekindle God's gift which is yours through the laying on of my hands.
B055C001V007	55	1	7	For the Spirit which God has given us is not a spirit of cowardice, but one of power and of love and of sound judgement.
B055C001V008	55	1	8	Do not be ashamed then to bear witness for our Lord and for me His prisoner; but rather share suffering with me in the service of the Good News, strengthened by the power of God.
B055C001V009	55	1	9	For He saved us and called us with a holy call, not in accordance with our desserts, but in accordance with His own purpose and the free grace which He bestowed on us in Christ Jesus before the commencement of the Ages,
B055C001V010	55	1	10	but which has now been plainly revealed through the Appearing of our Saviour, Christ Jesus. He has put an end to death and has brought Life and Immortality to light through the Good News,
B055C001V011	55	1	11	of which I have been appointed a preacher, Apostle and teacher, to the Gentiles.
B055C001V012	55	1	12	That indeed is the reason why I suffer as I do. But I am not ashamed, for I know in whom my trust reposes, and I am confident that He has it in His power to keep what I have entrusted to Him safe until that day.
B055C001V013	55	1	13	Provide yourself with an outline of the sound teaching which you have heard from my lips, and be true to the faith and love which are in Christ Jesus.
B055C001V014	55	1	14	That precious treasure which is in your charge, guard through the Holy Spirit who has His home in our hearts.
B055C001V015	55	1	15	Of this you are aware, that all the Christians in Roman Asia have deserted me: and among them Phygelus and Hermogenes.
B055C001V016	55	1	16	May the Lord show mercy to the household of Onesiphorus; for many a time he cheered me and he was not ashamed of my chain.
B055C001V017	55	1	17	Nay, when he was here in Rome, he took great pains to inquire where I was living, and at last he found me.
B055C001V018	55	1	18	(The Lord grant that he may obtain mercy at His hands on that day!) And you yourself well know all the services which he rendered me in Ephesus.
B055C002V001	55	2	1	You then, my child, must be strong in the grace that is in Christ Jesus.
B055C002V002	55	2	2	All that you have been taught by me in the hearing of many witnesses, you must hand on to trusty men who shall themselves, in turn, be competent to instruct others also.
B055C002V003	55	2	3	As a good soldier of Christ Jesus accept your share of suffering.
B055C002V004	55	2	4	Every one who serves as a soldier keeps himself from becoming entangled in the world's business–so that he may satisfy the officer who enlisted him.
B055C002V005	55	2	5	And if any one takes part in an athletic contest, he gets no prize unless he obeys the rules.
B055C002V006	55	2	6	The harvestman who labours in the field must be the first to get a share of the crop.
B055C002V007	55	2	7	Mark well what I am saying: the Lord will give you discernment in everything.
B055C002V008	55	2	8	Never forget that Jesus Christ has risen from among the dead and is a descendant of David, as is declared in the Good News which I preach.
B055C002V009	55	2	9	For preaching the Good News I suffer, and am even put in chains, as if I were a criminal: yet the word of God is not imprisoned.
B055C002V010	55	2	10	For this reason I endure all things for the sake of God's own people; so that they also may obtain salvation –even the salvation which is in Christ Jesus– and with it eternal glory.
B055C002V011	55	2	11	Faithful is the saying: »If we died with Him, we shall also live with Him;
B055C002V012	55	2	12	»If we patiently endure pain, we shall also share His Kingship;« If we disown Him, He will also disown us;
B055C002V013	55	2	13	»And even if 
B055C002V014	55	2	14	Bring all this to men's remembrances, solemnly charging them in the presence of God not to waste time in wrangling about mere words, a course which is altogether unprofitable and tends only to the ruin of the hearers.
B055C002V015	55	2	15	Earnestly seek to commend yourself to God as a servant who, because of his straightforward dealing with the word of truth, has no reason to feel any shame.
B055C002V016	55	2	16	But from irreligious and frivolous talk hold aloof, for those who indulge in it will proceed from bad to worse in impiety,
B055C002V017	55	2	17	and their teaching will spread like a running sore. Hymenaeus and Philetus are men of that stamp.
B055C002V018	55	2	18	In the matter of the truth they have gone astray, saying that the Resurrection is already past, and so they are overthrowing the faith of some.
B055C002V019	55	2	19	Yet God's solid foundation stands unmoved, bearing this inscription, 
B055C002V020	55	2	20	Now in a great house there are not only articles of gold and silver, but also others of wood and of earthenware; and some are for specially honourable, and others for common use.
B055C002V021	55	2	21	If therefore a man keeps himself clear of these latter, he himself will be for specially honourable use, consecrated, fit for the Master's service, and fully equipped for every good work.
B055C002V022	55	2	22	Keep a strong curb, however, on your youthful cravings; and strive for integrity, good faith, love, peace, in company with all who pray to the Lord with pure hearts.
B055C002V023	55	2	23	But avoid foolish discussions with ignorant men, knowing –as you do– that these lead to quarrels;
B055C002V024	55	2	24	and a bondservant of the Lord must not quarrel, but must be inoffensive towards all men, a skilful teacher, and patient under wrongs.
B055C002V025	55	2	25	He must speak in a gentle tone when correcting the errors of opponents, in the hope that God will at last give them repentance, for them to come to a full knowledge of the truth
B055C002V026	55	2	26	and recover sober-mindedness and freedom from the Devil's snare, though they are now entrapped by him to do his will.
B055C003V001	55	3	1	But of this be assured: in the last days grievous times will set in.
B055C003V002	55	3	2	For men will be lovers of self, lovers of money, boastful, haughty, profane. They will be disobedient to parents, thankless, irreligious,
B055C003V003	55	3	3	destitute of natural affection, unforgiving, slanderers. They will have no self-control, but will be brutal, opposed to goodness,
B055C003V004	55	3	4	treacherous, headstrong, self-important. They will love pleasure instead of loving God,
B055C003V005	55	3	5	and will keep up a make-believe of piety and yet live in defiance of its power. Turn away from people of this sort.
B055C003V006	55	3	6	Among them are included the men who make their way into private houses and carry off weak women as their prisoners–women who, weighed down by the burden of their sins, are led by ever-changing caprice,
B055C003V007	55	3	7	and are always learning something new, and yet are never able to arrive at real knowledge of the truth.
B055C003V008	55	3	8	And just as Jannes and Jambres withstood Moses, so also these false teachers withstand the truth–being, as they are, men of debased intellects, and of no real worth so far as faith is concerned.
B055C003V009	55	3	9	But they will have no further success; for their folly will be as clearly manifest to all men, as that of the opponents of Moses came to be.
B055C003V010	55	3	10	But you have intimately known my teaching, life, aims, faith, patience, love, resignation,
B055C003V011	55	3	11	and the persecutions and sufferings which I have endured; the things which happened to me in Antioch, Iconium and Lystra. You know the persecutions I endured, and how the Lord delivered me out of them all.
B055C003V012	55	3	12	And indeed every one who is determined to live a godly life as a follower of Christ Jesus will be persecuted.
B055C003V013	55	3	13	But bad men and impostors will go on from bad to worse, misleading and being misled.
B055C003V014	55	3	14	But you must cling to the things which you have learnt and have been taught to believe, knowing who your teachers were,
B055C003V015	55	3	15	and that from infancy you have known the sacred writings which are able to make you wise to obtain salvation through faith in Christ Jesus.
B055C003V016	55	3	16	Every Scripture is inspired by God and is useful for teaching, for convincing, for correction of error, and for instruction in right doing;
B055C003V017	55	3	17	so that the man of God may himself be complete and may be perfectly equipped for every good work.
B055C004V001	55	4	1	I solemnly implore you, in the presence of God and of Christ Jesus who is about to judge the living and the dead, and by His Appearing and His Kingship:
B055C004V002	55	4	2	proclaim God's message, be zealous in season and out of season; convince, rebuke, encourage, with the utmost patience as a teacher.
B055C004V003	55	4	3	For a time is coming when they will not tolerate wholesome instruction, but, wanting to have their ears tickled, they will find a multitude of teachers to satisfy their own fancies;
B055C004V004	55	4	4	and will turn away from listening to the truth and will turn aside to fables.
B055C004V005	55	4	5	But as for you, you must exercise habitual self-control, and not live a self-indulgent life, but do the duty of an evangelist and fully discharge the obligations of your office.
B055C004V006	55	4	6	I for my part am like a drink-offering which is already being poured out; and the time for my departure is now close at hand.
B055C004V007	55	4	7	I have gone through the glorious contest; I have run the race; I have guarded the faith.
B055C004V008	55	4	8	From this time onward there is reserved for me the crown of righteousness which the Lord, the righteous Judge, will award to me on that day, and not only to me, but also to all who love the thought of His Appearing.
B055C004V009	55	4	9	Make an effort to come to me speedily.
B055C004V010	55	4	10	For Demas has deserted me –loving, as he does, the present age– and has gone to Thessalonica; Crescens has gone to Galatia, and Titus to Dalmatia.
B055C004V011	55	4	11	Luke is the only friend I now have with me. Call for Mark on your way and bring him with you, for he is a great help to me in my ministry.
B055C004V012	55	4	12	Tychicus I have sent to Ephesus.
B055C004V013	55	4	13	When you come, bring with you the cloak which I left behind at Troas at the house of Carpus, and the books, but especially the parchments.
B055C004V014	55	4	14	Alexander the metal-worker showed bitter hostility towards me: the Lord will requite him according to his doings.
B055C004V015	55	4	15	You also should beware of him; for he has violently opposed our preaching.
B055C004V016	55	4	16	At my first defence I had no one at my side, but all deserted me. May it not be laid to their charge.
B055C004V017	55	4	17	The Lord, however, stood by me and filled me with inward strength, that through me the Message might be fully proclaimed and that all the Gentiles might hear it; and I was rescued from the lion's jaws.
B055C004V018	55	4	18	The Lord will deliver me from every cruel attack and will keep me safe in preparation for His heavenly Kingdom. To Him be the glory until the Ages of the Ages! Amen.
B055C004V019	55	4	19	Greet Prisca and Aquila, and the household of Onesiphorus.
B055C004V020	55	4	20	Erastus stayed in Corinth; Trophimus I left behind me at Miletus, ill.
B055C004V021	55	4	21	Make an effort to come before winter. Eubulus greets you, and so do Pudens, Linus, Claudia, and all the brethren.
B055C004V022	55	4	22	The Lord be with your spirit. Grace be with you all.
B056C001V001	56	1	1	Paul, a bondservant of God and an Apostle of Jesus Christ for building up the faith of God's own people and spreading a full knowledge of the truths of religion,
B056C001V002	56	1	2	in hope of the Life of the Ages which God, who is never false to His word, promised before the commencement of the Ages.
B056C001V003	56	1	3	And at the appointed time He clearly made known His Message in the preaching with which I was entrusted by the command of God our Saviour:
B056C001V004	56	1	4	To Titus my own true child in our common faith. May grace and peace be granted to you from God the Father and Christ Jesus our Saviour.
B056C001V005	56	1	5	I have left you behind in Crete in order that you may set right the things which still require attention, and appoint Elders in every town, as I directed you to do;
B056C001V006	56	1	6	wherever there is a man of blameless life, true to his one wife, having children who are themselves believers and are free from every reproach of profligacy or of stubborn self-will.
B056C001V007	56	1	7	For, as God's steward, a minister must be of blameless life, not over-fond of having his own way, not a man of a passionate temper nor a hard drinker, not given to blows nor greedy of gain,
B056C001V008	56	1	8	but hospitable to strangers, a lover of goodness, sober-minded, upright, saintly, self-controlled;
B056C001V009	56	1	9	holding fast to the faithful Message which he has received, so that he may be well qualified both to encourage others with sound teaching and to reply successfully to opponents.
B056C001V010	56	1	10	For there are many that spurn authority–idle, talkative and deceitful persons, who, for the most part, are adherents of the Circumcision.
B056C001V011	56	1	11	You must stop the mouths of such men, for they overthrow the faith of whole families, teaching what they ought not, just for the sake of making money.
B056C001V012	56	1	12	One of their own number –a Prophet who is a countryman of theirs– has said, »Cretans are always liars, dangerous animals, idle gluttons.«
B056C001V013	56	1	13	This testimony is true. Therefore sternly denounce them, that they may be robust in their faith,
B056C001V014	56	1	14	and not give attention to Jewish legends and the maxims of men who turn their backs on the truth.
B056C001V015	56	1	15	To the pure everything is pure; but to the polluted and unbelieving nothing is pure, but on the contrary their very minds and consciences are polluted.
B056C001V016	56	1	16	They profess to know God; but in their actions they disown Him, and are detestable and disobedient men, and for any good work are utterly useless.
B056C002V001	56	2	1	But as for you, you must speak in a manner that befits wholesome teaching.
B056C002V002	56	2	2	Exhort aged men to be temperate, grave, sober-minded, robust in their faith, their love and their patience.
B056C002V003	56	2	3	In the same way exhort aged women to let their conduct be such as becomes consecrated persons. They must not be slanderers nor enslaved to wine-drinking. They must be teachers of what is right.
B056C002V004	56	2	4	They should school the young women to be affectionate to their husbands and to their children, to be sober-minded, pure in their lives,
B056C002V005	56	2	5	industrious in their homes, kind, submissive to their husbands, so that the Christian teaching may not be exposed to reproach.
B056C002V006	56	2	6	In the same way exhort the younger men to be discreet,
B056C002V007	56	2	7	and above all make your own life a pattern of right conduct, having in your teaching no taint of insincerity, but a serious tone,
B056C002V008	56	2	8	and healthy language which no one can censure, so that our opponents may feel ashamed at having nothing evil to say against us.
B056C002V009	56	2	9	Exhort slaves to be always obedient to their owners, and to give them satisfaction in everything, not contradicting and not pilfering,
B056C002V010	56	2	10	but manifesting perfect fidelity and kind feeling, in order to bring honour to the teaching of our Saviour, God, in all things.
B056C002V011	56	2	11	For the grace of God has displayed itself with healing power to all mankind,
B056C002V012	56	2	12	training us to renounce ungodliness and all the pleasures of this world, and to live sober, upright, and pious lives at the present time,
B056C002V013	56	2	13	in expectation of the fulfilment of our blessed hope–the Appearing in glory of our great God and Saviour Jesus Christ;
B056C002V014	56	2	14	who gave Himself for us to purchase our freedom from all iniquity, and purify for Himself a people who should be specially His own, zealous for doing good works.
B056C002V015	56	2	15	Thus speak, exhort, reprove, with all impressiveness. Let no one make light of your authority.
B056C003V001	56	3	1	Remind people that they must submit to the rulers who are in authority over them; that they must obey the magistrates, be prepared for every right action,
B056C003V002	56	3	2	not speak evil of any one, nor be contentious, but yield unselfishly to others and constantly manifest a forgiving spirit towards all men.
B056C003V003	56	3	3	For there was a time when we also were deficient in understanding, obstinate, deluded, the slaves of various cravings and pleasures, spending our lives in malice and envy, hateful ourselves and hating one another.
B056C003V004	56	3	4	But when the goodness of God our Saviour, and His love to man, dawned upon us, not in consequence of things which we,
B056C003V005	56	3	5	as righteous men, had done, but as the result of His own mercy He saved us by means of the bath of regeneration and the renewal of our natures by the Holy Spirit,
B056C003V006	56	3	6	which He poured out on us richly through Jesus Christ our Saviour;
B056C003V007	56	3	7	in order that having been declared righteous through His grace we might become heirs to the Life of the Ages in fulfilment of our hopes.
B056C003V008	56	3	8	This is a faithful saying, and on these various points I would have you insist strenuously, in order that those who have their faith fixed on God may be careful to set an example of good actions. For these are not only good in themselves, but are also useful to mankind.
B056C003V009	56	3	9	But hold yourself aloof from foolish controversies and pedigrees and discussions and wrangling about the Law, for they are useless and vain.
B056C003V010	56	3	10	After a first and second admonition, have nothing further to do with any one who will not be taught;
B056C003V011	56	3	11	for, as you know, a man of that description has turned aside from the right path and is a sinner self-condemned.
B056C003V012	56	3	12	After I have sent Artemas or Tychicus to you, lose no time in joining me at Nicopolis; for I have decided to pass the winter there.
B056C003V013	56	3	13	Help Zenas the lawyer forward on his journey with special care, and Apollos, so that they may have all they require.
B056C003V014	56	3	14	And let our people too learn to set a good example in following honest occupations for the supply of their necessities, so that they may not live useless lives.
B056C003V015	56	3	15	Every one here sends you greeting. Greet the believers who hold us dear. May grace be with you all.
B057C001V001	57	1	1	Paul, a prisoner for Christ Jesus, and Timothy our brother: To Philemon our dearly-loved fellow labourer–
B057C001V002	57	1	2	and to our sister Apphia and our comrade Archippus–as well as to the Church in your house.
B057C001V003	57	1	3	May grace be granted to you all, and peace, from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B057C001V004	57	1	4	I give continual thanks to my God while making mention of you, my brother, in my prayers,
B057C001V005	57	1	5	because I hear of your love and of the faith which you have towards the Lord Jesus and which you manifest towards all God's people;
B057C001V006	57	1	6	praying as I do, that their participation in your faith may result in others fully recognizing all the right affection that is in us toward Christ.
B057C001V007	57	1	7	For I have found great joy and comfort in your love, because the hearts of God's people have been, and are, refreshed through you, my brother.
B057C001V008	57	1	8	Therefore, though I might with Christ's authority speak very freely and order you to do what is fitting,
B057C001V009	57	1	9	it is for love's sake that –instead of that– although I am none other than Paul the aged, and am now also a prisoner for Christ Jesus,
B057C001V010	57	1	10	I entreat you on behalf of my own child whose father I have become while in my chains–I mean Onesimus.
B057C001V011	57	1	11	Formerly he was useless to you, but now –true to his name– he is of great use to you and to me.
B057C001V012	57	1	12	I am sending him back to you, though in so doing I send part of myself.
B057C001V013	57	1	13	It was my wish to keep him at my side for him to attend to my wants, as your representative, during my imprisonment for the Good News.
B057C001V014	57	1	14	Only I wished to do nothing without your consent, so that his kind action of yours might not be done under pressure, but might be a voluntary one.
B057C001V015	57	1	15	For perhaps it was for this reason he was parted from you for a time, that you might receive him back wholly and for ever yours;
B057C001V016	57	1	16	no longer as a slave, but as something better than a slave–a brother peculiarly dear to me, and even dearer to you, both as a servant and as a fellow Christian.
B057C001V017	57	1	17	If therefore you regard me as a comrade, receive him as if he were I myself.
B057C001V018	57	1	18	And if he was ever dishonest or is in your debt, debit me with the amount.
B057C001V019	57	1	19	I Paul write this with my own hand–I will pay you in full. (I say nothing of the fact that you owe me even your own self.)
B057C001V020	57	1	20	Yes, brother, do me this favour for the Lord's sake. Refresh my heart in Christ.
B057C001V021	57	1	21	I write to you in the full confidence that you will meet my wishes, for I know you will do even more than I say.
B057C001V022	57	1	22	And at the same time provide accommodation for me; for I hope that through your prayers I shall be permitted to come to you.
B057C001V023	57	1	23	Greetings to you, my brother, from Epaphras my fellow prisoner for the sake of Christ Jesus;
B057C001V024	57	1	24	and from Mark, Aristarchus, Demas, and Luke, my fellow workers.
B057C001V025	57	1	25	May the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with the spirit of every one of you.
B058C001V001	58	1	1	God, who in ancient days spoke to our forefathers in many distinct messages and by various methods through the Prophets,
B058C001V002	58	1	2	has at the end of these days spoken to us through a Son, who is the pre-destined Lord of the universe, and through whom He made the Ages.
B058C001V003	58	1	3	He brightly reflects God's glory and is the exact representation of His being, and upholds the universe by His all-powerful word. After securing man's purification from sin He took His seat at the right hand of the Majesty on high,
B058C001V004	58	1	4	having become as far superior to the angels as the Name He possesses by inheritance is more excellent than theirs.
B058C001V005	58	1	5	For to which of the angels did God ever say, 
