B058C001V011	58	1	11	
        
B058C001V012	58	1	12	
        
B058C001V013	58	1	13	To which of the angels has He ever said, 
B058C001V014	58	1	14	Are not all angels spirits that serve Him–whom He sends out to render service for the benefit of those who, before long, will inherit salvation?
B058C002V001	58	2	1	For this reason we ought to pay the more earnest heed to the things which we have heard, for fear we should drift away from them.
B058C002V002	58	2	2	For if the message delivered through angels proved to be true, and every transgression and act of disobedience met with just retribution,
B058C002V003	58	2	3	how shall 
B058C002V004	58	2	4	while God corroborated their testimony by signs and marvels and various miracles, and by gifts of the Holy Spirit distributed in accordance with His own will.
B058C002V005	58	2	5	It is not to angels that God has assigned the sovereignty of that coming world, of which we speak.
B058C002V006	58	2	6	But, as we know, a writer has solemnly said, How poor a creature is man, and yet Thou dost remember him, and a son of man, and yet Thou dost come to him!
B058C002V007	58	2	7	Thou hast made him only a little inferior to the angels; with glory and honour Thou hast crowned him, and hast set him to govern the works of Thy hands.
B058C002V008	58	2	8	Thou hast put everything in subjection under his feet. - For this subjecting of the universe to man implies the leaving nothing not subject to him. But we do not as yet see the universe subject to him.
B058C002V009	58	2	9	But Jesus –who was made a little inferior to the angels in order that through God's grace He might taste death for every human being– we already see wearing a crown of glory and honour because of His having suffered death.
B058C002V010	58	2	10	For it was fitting that He for whom, and through whom, all things exist, after He had brought many sons to glory, should perfect by suffering the Prince Leader who had saved them.
B058C002V011	58	2	11	For both He who sanctifies and those whom He is sanctifying have all one Father; and for this reason He is not ashamed to speak of them as His brothers;
B058C002V012	58	2	12	as when He says: 
B058C002V013	58	2	13	and again, 
B058C002V014	58	2	14	Since then the children referred to are all alike sharers in perishable human nature, He Himself also, in the same way, took on Him a share of it, in order that through death He might render powerless him who had authority over death, that is, the Devil,
B058C002V015	58	2	15	and might set at liberty all those who through fear of death had been subject to lifelong slavery.
B058C002V016	58	2	16	For assuredly it is not to angels that He is continually reaching a helping hand, but it is to the descendants of Abraham.
B058C002V017	58	2	17	And for this purpose it was necessary that in all respects He should be made to resemble His brothers, so that He might become a compassionate and faithful High Priest in things relating to God, in order to atone for the sins of the people.
B058C002V018	58	2	18	For inasmuch as He has Himself felt the pain of temptation and trial, He is also able instantly to help those who are tempted and tried.
B058C003V001	58	3	1	Therefore, holy brethren, sharers with others in a heavenly invitation, fix your thoughts on Jesus, the Apostle and High Priest whose followers we profess to be.
B058C003V002	58	3	2	How faithful He was to Him who appointed Him, just as Moses also was faithful in all God's house!
B058C003V003	58	3	3	For Jesus has been counted worthy of greater glory than Moses, in so far as he who has built a house has higher honour than the house itself.
B058C003V004	58	3	4	For every house has had a builder, and the builder of all things is God.
B058C003V005	58	3	5	Moreover, Moses was faithful in all God's house as a servant in delivering the message given him to speak;
B058C003V006	58	3	6	but Christ was faithful as a Son having authority over God's house, and we are that house, if we hold firm to the End the boldness and the hope which we boast of as ours.
B058C003V007	58	3	7	For this reason–as the Holy Spirit warns us, »To-day, if you hear His voice,
B058C003V008	58	3	8	do not harden your hearts as your forefathers did in the time of the provocation on the day of the temptation in the Desert,
B058C003V009	58	3	9	where your forefathers so sorely tried My patience and saw all that I did during forty years.
B058C003V010	58	3	10	Therefore I was greatly grieved with that generation, and I said, `They are ever going astray in heart, and have not learnt to know My paths.'
B058C003V011	58	3	11	As I swore in My anger, they shall not be admitted to My rest« –
B058C003V012	58	3	12	see to it, brethren, that there is never in any one of you –as perhaps there may be– a sinful and unbelieving heart, manifesting itself in revolt from the ever-living God.
B058C003V013	58	3	13	On the contrary encourage one another, day after day, so long as To-day lasts, so that not one of you may be hardened through the deceitful character of sin.
B058C003V014	58	3	14	For we have, all alike, become sharers with Christ, if we really hold our first confidence firm to the End;
B058C003V015	58	3	15	seeing that the warning still comes to us, 
B058C003V016	58	3	16	For who were they that heard, and yet provoked God? Was it not the whole of the people who had come out of Egypt under the leadership of Moses?
B058C003V017	58	3	17	And with whom was God so greatly grieved for forty years? Was it not with those who had sinned, and whose dead bodies fell in the Desert?
B058C003V018	58	3	18	And to whom did He swear that they should not be admitted to His rest, if it was not to those who were disobedient?
B058C003V019	58	3	19	And so we see that it was owing to lack of faith that they could not be admitted.
B058C004V001	58	4	1	Therefore let us be on our guard lest perhaps, while He still leaves us a promise of being admitted to His rest, some one of you should be found to have fallen short of it.
B058C004V002	58	4	2	For Good News has been brought to us as truly as to them; but the message they heard failed to benefit them, because they were not one in faith with those who gave heed to it.
B058C004V003	58	4	3	We who have believed are soon to be admitted to the true rest; as He has said, 
B058C004V004	58	4	4	For, as we know, when speaking of the seventh day He has used the words, 
B058C004V005	58	4	5	and He has also declared, 
B058C004V006	58	4	6	Since, then, it is still true that some will be admitted to that rest, and that because of disobedience those who formerly had Good News proclaimed to them were not admitted,
B058C004V007	58	4	7	He again definitely mentions a certain day, »To-day,« saying long afterwards, by David's lips, in the words already quoted, 
B058C004V008	58	4	8	For if Joshua had given them the true rest, we should not afterwards hear God speaking of another still future day.
B058C004V009	58	4	9	It follows that there still remains a sabbath rest for the people of God.
B058C004V010	58	4	10	For He who has been admitted to His rest, has rested from His works as God did from His.
B058C004V011	58	4	11	Let it then be our earnest endeavour to be admitted to that rest, so that no one may perish through following the same example of unbelief.
B058C004V012	58	4	12	For God's Message is full of life and power, and is keener than the sharpest two-edged sword. It pierces even to the severance of soul from spirit, and penetrates between the joints and the marrow, and it can discern the secret thoughts and purposes of the heart.
B058C004V013	58	4	13	And no created thing is able to escape its scrutiny; but everything lies bare and completely exposed before the eyes of Him with whom we have to do.
B058C004V014	58	4	14	Inasmuch, then, as we have in Jesus, the Son of God, a great High Priest who has passed into Heaven itself, let us hold firmly to our profession of faith.
B058C004V015	58	4	15	For we have not a High Priest who is unable to feel for us in our weaknesses, but one who was tempted in every respect just as we are tempted, and yet did not sin.
B058C004V016	58	4	16	Therefore let us come boldly to the throne of grace, that we may receive mercy and find grace to help us in our times of need.
B058C005V001	58	5	1	For every High Priest is chosen from among men, and is appointed to act on behalf of men in matters relating to God, in order to offer both gifts and sin-offerings,
B058C005V002	58	5	2	and must be one who is able to bear patiently with the ignorant and erring, because he himself also is beset with infirmity.
B058C005V003	58	5	3	And for this reason he is required to offer sin-offerings not only for the people but also for himself.
B058C005V004	58	5	4	And no one takes this honourable office upon himself, but only accepts it when called to it by God, as Aaron was.
B058C005V005	58	5	5	So Christ also did not claim for Himself the honour of being made High Priest, but was appointed to it by Him who said to Him, 
B058C005V006	58	5	6	as also in another passage He says, 
B058C005V007	58	5	7	For Jesus during his earthly life offered up prayers and entreaties, crying aloud and weeping as He pleaded with Him who was able to bring Him in safety out of death, and He was delivered from the terror from which He shrank.
B058C005V008	58	5	8	Although He was God's Son, yet He learned obedience from the sufferings which He endured;
B058C005V009	58	5	9	and so, having been made perfect, He became to all who obey Him the source and giver of eternal salvation.
B058C005V010	58	5	10	For God Himself addresses Him as a High Priest for ever, belonging to the order of Melchizedek.
B058C005V011	58	5	11	Concerning Him we have much to say, and much that it would be difficult to make clear to you, since you have become so dull of apprehension.
B058C005V012	58	5	12	For although, considering the long time you have been believers, you ought now to be teachers of others, you really need some one to teach you over again the very rudiments of the truths of God, and you have come to require milk instead of solid food.
B058C005V013	58	5	13	By people who live on milk I mean those who are imperfectly acquainted with the teaching concerning righteousness.
B058C005V014	58	5	14	Such persons are mere babes. But solid food is for adults–that is, for those who through constant practice have their spiritual faculties carefully trained to distinguish good from evil.
B058C006V001	58	6	1	Therefore leaving elementary instruction about the Christ, let us advance to mature manhood and not be continually re-laying a foundation of repentance from lifeless works and of faith in God,
B058C006V002	58	6	2	or of teaching about ceremonial washings, the laying on of hands, the resurrection of the dead, and the last judgement.
B058C006V003	58	6	3	And advance we will, if God permits us to do so.
B058C006V004	58	6	4	For it is impossible, in the case of those who have once for all been enlightened, and have tasted the sweetness of the heavenly gift, and have been made partakers of the Holy Spirit,
B058C006V005	58	6	5	and have realized how good the word of God is and how mighty are the powers of the coming Age, and then fell away–
B058C006V006	58	6	6	it is impossible, I say, to keep bringing them back to a new repentance, for, to their own undoing, they are repeatedly crucifying the Son of God afresh and exposing Him to open shame.
B058C006V007	58	6	7	For land which has drunk in the rain that often falls upon it, and brings forth vegetation useful to those for whose sakes, indeed, it is tilled, has a share in God's blessing.
B058C006V008	58	6	8	But if it only yields a mass of thorns and briers, it is considered worthless, and is in danger of being cursed, and in the end will be destroyed by fire.
B058C006V009	58	6	9	But we, even while we speak in this tone, have a happier conviction concerning you, my dearly-loved friends–a conviction of things which point towards salvation.
B058C006V010	58	6	10	For God is not unjust so that He is unmindful of your labour and of the love which you have manifested towards Himself in having rendered services to His people and in still rendering them.
B058C006V011	58	6	11	But we long for each of you to continue to manifest the same earnestness, with a view to your enjoying fulness of hope to the very End;
B058C006V012	58	6	12	so that you may not become half-hearted, but be imitators of those who through faith and patient endurance are now heirs to the promises.
B058C006V013	58	6	13	For when God gave the promise to Abraham, since He had no one greater to swear by, He swore by Himself,
B058C006V014	58	6	14	saying, 
B058C006V015	58	6	15	And so, as the result of patient waiting, our forefather obtained what God had promised.
B058C006V016	58	6	16	For men swear by what is greater than themselves; and with them an oath in confirmation of a statement always puts an end to a dispute.
B058C006V017	58	6	17	In the same way, since it was God's desire to display more convincingly to the heirs of the promise how unchangeable His purpose was,
B058C006V018	58	6	18	He added an oath, in order that, through two unchangeable things, in which it is impossible for Him to prove false, we may possess mighty encouragement–we who, for safety, have hastened to lay hold of the hope set before us.
B058C006V019	58	6	19	That hope we have as an anchor of the soul–an anchor that can neither break nor drag. It passes in behind the veil,
B058C006V020	58	6	20	where Jesus has entered as a forerunner on our behalf, having become, like Melchizedek, a High Priest for ever.
B058C007V001	58	7	1	For this man, Melchizedek, King of Salem and priest of the Most High God –he who when Abraham was returning after defeating the kings met him and pronounced a blessing on him–
B058C007V002	58	7	2	to whom also Abraham presented a tenth part of all–being first, as his name signifies, King of righteousness, and secondly King of Salem, that is, King of peace:
B058C007V003	58	7	3	with no father or mother, and no record of ancestry: having neither beginning of days nor end of life, but made a type of the Son of God–this man Melchizedek remains a priest for ever.
B058C007V004	58	7	4	Now think how great this priest-king must have been to whom Abraham the patriarch gave a tenth part of the best of the spoil.
B058C007V005	58	7	5	And those of the descendants of Levi who receive the priesthood are authorized by the Law to take tithes from the people, that is, from their brethren, though these have sprung from Abraham.
B058C007V006	58	7	6	But, in this instance, one who does not trace his origin from them takes tithes from Abraham, and pronounces a blessing on him to whom the promises belong.
B058C007V007	58	7	7	And beyond all dispute it is always the inferior who is blessed by the superior.
B058C007V008	58	7	8	Moreover here frail mortal men receive tithes: there one receives them about whom there is evidence that he is alive.
B058C007V009	58	7	9	And Levi too –if I may so speak– pays tithes through Abraham:
B058C007V010	58	7	10	for Levi was yet in the loins of his forefather when Melchizedek met Abraham.
B058C007V011	58	7	11	Now if the crowning blessing was attainable by means of the Levitical priesthood –for as resting on this foundation the people received the Law, to which they are still subject– what further need was there for a Priest of a different kind to be raised up belonging to the order of Melchizedek instead of being said to belong to the order of Aaron?
B058C007V012	58	7	12	For when the priesthood changes, a change of Law also of necessity takes place.
B058C007V013	58	7	13	He, however, to whom that prophecy refers is associated with a different tribe, not one member of which has anything to do with the altar.
B058C007V014	58	7	14	For it is undeniable that our Lord sprang from Judah, a tribe of which Moses said nothing in connection with priests.
B058C007V015	58	7	15	And this is still more abundantly clear when we read that it is as belonging to the order of Melchizedek that a priest of a different kind is to arise,
B058C007V016	58	7	16	and hold His office not in obedience to any temporary Law, but by virtue of an indestructible Life.
B058C007V017	58	7	17	For the words are in evidence, 
B058C007V018	58	7	18	On the one hand we have here the abrogation of an earlier code because it was weak and ineffective–
B058C007V019	58	7	19	for the Law brought no perfect blessing–but on the other hand we have the bringing in of a new and better hope by means of which we draw near to God.
B058C007V020	58	7	20	And since it was not without an oath being taken–
B058C007V021	58	7	21	for these men hold office without any oath having been taken, but He holds it attested by an oath from Him who said to Him, »The Lord has sworn and will not recall His words, Thou art a Priest for ever« –
B058C007V022	58	7	22	so much the more also is the Covenant of which Jesus has become the guarantor, a better covenant.
B058C007V023	58	7	23	And they have been appointed priests many in number, because death prevents their continuance in office:
B058C007V024	58	7	24	but He, because He continues for ever, has a priesthood which does not pass to any successor.
B058C007V025	58	7	25	Hence too He is able to save to the uttermost those who come to God through Him, seeing that He ever lives to plead for them.
B058C007V026	58	7	26	Moreover we needed just such a High Priest as this–holy, guileless, undefiled, far removed from sinful men and exalted above the heavens;
B058C007V027	58	7	27	who, unlike other High Priests, is not under the necessity of offering up sacrifices day after day, first for His own sins, and afterwards for those of the people; for this latter thing He did once for all when He offered up Himself.
B058C007V028	58	7	28	For the Law constitutes men High Priests –men with all their infirmity– but the utterance of the oath, which came later than the Law, constitutes High Priest a Son who has been made for ever perfect.
